<title>Government Financial Assistance Programs</title><H1>Government Financial Assistance Programs</H1><dl><dt><b>VIRGINIA SMALL BUSINESS FINANCING AUTHORITY  (VSBFA)</b><p><dd>The VSBFA offers two financing programs for businesses in Virginia: a loan guaranty program for small businesses and industrial development bond (IDB) financing for manufacturing businesses . More than 98 percent of Virginia's businesses are considered eligible for these programs. To qualify, a business must have either 250 or fewer employees, or less than $10 million in annual gross revenues for each of the last three years, or less than $2 million in net worth. Fees are required with all applications. The approval process can be relatively quick once the applicant provides the required documents.<p><dd>LOAN GUARANTY PROGRAM.  This is specifically aimed at small businesses which need short term capital to expand or finance current operations. The VSBFA guarantees a portion of a loan made by a bank to an eligible borrower. The maximum guarantee is 50 percent of the loan amount or $150,000, whichever is less, with a term of one to three years, generally. The maximum interest rate is two points over the lender's prime rate. The program enables banks to make loans which they otherwise might not make or to increase the amount of the loan. Applicants for the loan guaranty must submit VSBFA's loan application to their bank. <p><dd>INDUSTRIAL DEVELOPMENT BONDS (IDB's).  The Authority issues tax-exempt IDB's for eligible manufacturing businesses to finance development of fixed assets, which includes land, building and capital equipment. IDB's, issued in compliance with federal regulations, provide effective annual financing costs at approximately 80 to 90 percent of the prime interest rate and terms of up to 30 years. The minimum feasible project size is $250,000.<p><dd>The VSBFA also has an "Umbrella IDB Program" which makes IDB financing available to manufacturing firms whose borrowing needs are too small to qualify for regular IDB financing. These tax exempt bonds also offer attractive interest rates and terms to finance fixed assets. This is done by pooling together the financing of many small businesses under one "umbrella" bond which is sold on the public capital market. <p><dd>To obtain application forms or additional information, contact:<dd>Virginia Small Business Financing Authority<dd>1021 E. Cary Street, P. O. Box 798, Richmond, VA 23206-0798<dd>(804) 371-8254<p><dt><b>SBA 504 LOAN GUARANTEE PROGRAM</b><p><dd>The SBA 504 program provides long term, fixed rate financing to small and medium sized businesses for financing construction, acquisition, and renovation of buildings and for purchasing major equipment.<p><dd>The program is generally intended to assist established, profitable, growing businesses by offering low down payment, long-term financing at a fixed interest rate. Working capital and refinancing are ineligible purposes.<p><dd>A borrower needs to provide no more than 10 percent equity in the project. The borrower's commercial lender provides up to 50 percent of the financing, usually in the form of a first trust or mortgage. The balance of the financing, which cannot exceed 40% or $750,000, is provided through an SBA guarantee of a subordinated loan. The maximum project size is approximately $1,900,000.<p><dd>The SBA's participation is in the form of a guarantee of a debenture (bond) which has an interest rate fixed at usually two points above treasury bonds of similar maturity and has a term of 10 or 20 years. Projects involving passive investment, speculation or extensive leased space are ineligible. The creation or preservation of jobs must be evidenced in the application.<p><dd>The program is administered in Arlington County and surrounding areas by the Virginia Asset Financing Corporation (VAFC). Staff of the VAFC and the Arlington County Economic Development Division will work closely with the business owner to determine eligibility and assist in the preparation of the loan application. For further information, contact either the Economic Development Division at (703) 358-3520 or:<p><dd>Virginia Asset Financing Corporation<dd>12020 Sunrise Valley Dr., Suite 260, Reston, VA  22091<dd>(703) 476-0504<p><dt><b>SBA 7A LOAN GUARANTEE PROGRAM</b><p><dd>The SBA 7A program guarantees loans made by commercial lenders to small businesses. Loans can be used for business or property acquisition, expansion, equipment purchase, working capital and debt consolidation. The SBA will guarantee up to 90 percent of a loan of $155,000 or less and up to 85% for loans over this amount. The maximum loan amount is $750,000. Loans up to $1 million can be guaranteed if used for the purchase of plant and equipment for the production of goods and services in international trade.<p><dd>To use the program, applicants must go through a bank or other lending institution, obtain and submit application forms to the bank. If the guarantee is approved by the SBA, the lender disburses the funds and services the loan. Note, however, that not all banks elect to use the program. Thus it may be helpful to talk to more than one lender.<p><dd>Good credit and a strong financial condition are important to qualify for a loan; the SBA's guarantee may enable a lender to make a loan where collateral is otherwise inadequate.<dd>The loan term depends on the purpose of the loan. Interest rates are set by the lender within SBA limits. <p><dd>The Virginia Asset Financing Corporation (see address above) will also help a qualified borrower to obtain financing through this program. In certain cases a SBA 7A Loan can be combined with the SBA 504 program (see above) to increase the financing available for a single project.<p><dt><b>OTHER SBA LOAN PROGRAMS</b><p><dd>Space does permit descriptions of other SBA programs to assist small business. The SBA operates loan guarantee programs to assist specific groups. These include:<p><ul><li>small general contractor loan guarantee<li>seasonal line of credit guarantee<li>contract line of credit<li>export revolving line of credit<li>international trade loan program<li>pollution control financing<li>surety bonds for small contractors</ul><p><dd>The SBA operates direct loan programs, when funds are available, for Vietnam-era veterans, disabled veterans and physically handicapped persons.<p><dd>Special provisions govern eligibility for each of these programs. For further information, contact the U.S. Small Business Administration either directly or through the:<p><dl><dd>Small Business Administration, Washington District Office<dd>1111 18th Street, N.W., Washington, D.C.  20036<dd>(202) 634-1500</dl><p><dt><b>SMALL BUSINESS INVESTMENT COMPANIES (SBIC)</b><p><dd>SBIC's provide equity capital and subordinated loans to small businesses. SBIC's are privately owned and capitalized companies that are licensed and regulated by the U. S. Small Business Administration. SBIC's invest in small businesses according to their own investment criteria.<p><dd>A specialized type of SBIC is the "Section 301(d) SBIC" (often called MESBIC for Minority Enterprise SBIC) which restricts its funding to businesses owned or operated by socially or economically disadvantaged persons. Women-owned and Vietnam veteran-owned firms may qualify. A MESBIC can also provide management assistance to companies that it finances.<p><dd>Contact the SBA office identified above for a current list of SBIC's and MESBIC's in the Washington area. Also, see Appendix I for resource information.<p><dt><b>SMALL BUSINESS INNOVATION RESEARCH PROGRAM (SBIR)</b><p><dd>The SBIR Program provides grants for research and development in order to stimulate technological innovation in the United States. Under the program, qualified U.S. small businesses propose innovative concepts which will meet the research and development needs of the federal government. Awards are granted through a three-phase evaluation, development and commercialization process. Eleven federal agencies participate in this program. The SBA publishes quarterly a pre-solicitation announcement (PSA) to inform businesses of the SBIR solicitations of the various federal agencies. For more information, contact:<p><dl><dd>Office of Innovation, Research & Technology<dd>Small Business Administration<dd>409 3rd Street, S.W., Washington, D.C. 20416<dd>(202) 205-7777</dl><p><dt><b>VIRGINIA NEIGHBORHOOD   ASSISTANCE ACT</b><p><dd>The Virginia Neighborhood Assistance Act offers a state income tax credit for businesses which invest in impoverished areas or people of the state. The tax credit equals 50 percent of the amount invested not to exceed $175,000 annually. Investment by a business may take the form of financial assistance, material, labor, job training, counseling, emergency assistance, medical care, and crime reduction activities. To participate in the program, businesses should contact:<p><dl><dd>Neighborhood Assistance Program<dd>Office of Executive Assistance, Department of Social Services<dd>8007 Discovery Drive, Richmond, VA  23229<dd>(804) 281-9204</dl></dl><p>

