<Title>Minority Business Programs</title><H1>Minority Business Programs</h1>Various programs and services for minority business owners, sponsored by the Federal Government, State of Virginia or non-profit organizations are available to Arlington businesses. The Federal Government uses the term "socially and economically disadvantaged persons" to include minorities and others eligible for certain programs. Note, however, that the definition of who qualifies as a minority person may differ among programs and governments in regard to gender, race, nationality or income level of the person.<p><dl><dt><b>VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF MINORITY BUSINESS ENTERPRISE (DMBE)</b><p><dd>The Virginia DMBE works with minority firms to increase contracting opportunities for minority businesses in both the public and private sector, with emphasis on the state government. DMBE maintains a statewide databank of minority-owned firms. The agency will help minority firms register as a vendor with Virginia, federal and local agencies, including certification and pre-qualification with the Virginia Department of Transportation.  DMBE publishes a marketing guide for doing business with the state called "Let Us Guide You."  For more information, contact:<p><dl><dd>Department of Minority Business Enterprise<dd>200-202 N. 9th St., 11th floor<dd>Richmond, VA  23219<dd>(804) 786-5560</dl><p><dt><b>VIRGINIA REGIONAL MINORITY SUPPLIER DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL  (VRMSDC)</b><p><dd>VRMSDC is a non-profit organization working to increase marketing opportunities for minority vendors. Services include vendor identification and certification, directories, training programs and buyer/seller liaison.<p><dl><dd>VRMSDC<dd>201 E. Franklin St<dd>Richmond, VA  23219<dd>(804) 780-2322</dl><p><dt><b>MINORITY ENTERPRISE SMALL BUSINESS INVESTMENT COMPANIES (MESBICs)</b><p><dd>See "Small Business Investment Companies" in the section on <a href="st-asst.htm"> Government Financial Assistance Programs</a> for financing information for minority businesses. <p><dt><b>SBA 8(a) and 7(j) PROGRAMS</b><p><dd>Businesses owned by "socially and economically disadvantaged persons" can take advantage of two programs managed by the U. S. Small Business Administration: the 8(a) Procurement Program and the 7(j) Management and Technical Assistance Program. <p><dd>The Section 8(a) program assists minority businesses to compete for contracts offered by federal agencies. Under the law federal agencies are required to procure a certain amount of goods and services from "disadvantaged" businesses. The Small Business Administration certifies firms for the 8(a) program, negotiates and awards contracts to the firms, and provides management assistance. The Management and Technical Assistance 7(j) program offers a range of assistance to 8(a) and non-8(a) firms who meet certain qualifications such as a business owned by a low income person. For further information contact:<p><dl><dd>U. S. Small Business Administration, Washington District Office<dd>1111 18th Street, N.W., Washington, D.C. 20416<dd>(202) 634-1500</dl><p><dt><b>MINORITY BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT AGENCY</b><p><dd>The MBDA is a federal agency created to foster the establishment and growth of minority-owned businesses. It provides services through Minority Business Development Centers under contract to the MBDA. The Centers provide management and technical assistance to minority entrepreneurs. Services include local and federal certifications, financial planning, loan packaging, bid estimating and bonding assistance, marketing analysis and seminars. <dd>The MBDA offers a service, called Profile, that matches minority firms with actual contract opportunities offered by government agencies and private industry. The nearest Minority Business Development Center serving Arlington is:<p><dl><dd>Washington D.C. MBDC<dd>1133  15th St., N.W., Suite 1120<dd>Washington, D.C. 20005<dd>(202) 785-2886</dl><p><dt><b>MINORITY BUSINESS OPPORTUNITY FAIR</b><p><dd>From time to time the Arlington Chamber of Commerce, in conjunction with the Arlington County Economic Development Division and various sponsors, conducts a trade show for the specific purposes of:<p><ul><li>providing information about free and low cost assistance to minority businesses<li>providing minority businesses an opportunity to showcase their goods and services<li>raising public awareness of these businesses<li>Call the Chamber of Commerce at (703) 525-2400 for additional information.</ul></dl><p>

