<title>BALLSTON</title><H1>Ballston</h1><img src="Blst-loc.gif"> Ballston, a major new real estate submarket in the Washington Metropolitan area, is located in Arlington at the western end of the Orange Line Metro corridor.  Within the central area of Ballston are the highest density mixed-use developments found within Arlington.<p>Since 1985, an impressive amount of office, residential, retail and hotel development has been completed.  With 3.9 million square feet of office development built, Ballston presently maintains a three percent vacancy rate, and its multi-family residential buildings exhibit strong market attraction with an average 85 percent occupancy.  Indeed, the Windsor Plaza luxury condominium project sold out the first phase of development within four months.  Presently under construction in Ballston is the new headquarters building for the National Rural Electric Cooperative Association (246,639 sq ft), phase two of Windsor Plaza condominiums (92 units), and Ballston Park apartments (145 units).  By late summer of 1994, it is anticipated that the Richmond Square residential project (324 units) will start construction.<p>The success of the Ballston Sector Plan in achieving "Arlington's New Downtown" character is noteworthy.  Today, approximately 54 percent of Ballston's site-plan-approved residential development is completed,  including townhouses, condominiums, and rental units. Fifty-two percent of office development is completed or under construction and 69 percent of retail space has or is being developed.<p>The retail focus of Ballston is the Ballston Common Mall, but other destination retail includes Rio Grande Cafe, Staples and American Service Center.  Private-sector corporations in Ballston include USLICO Corp., CACI International Inc., Eastman Kodak Company and SatoTravel.  Ballston's legal firms include Haley, Bader & Potts and Nixon & Vanderhye, P.C.  The National Rural Electric Cooperative Association (NRECA), the Shipbuilders Council of America and the American Anthropological Association are but several of the national associations that are located in Ballston.  The federal government presence is represented by the National Science Foundation, Advanced Research Projects Agency and the Office of Naval Research.  Ballston is flanked on the east by George Mason University's Arlington Campus and on the west by Marymount University's school of business.  In addition,  George Mason University's International Institute occupies space in the heart of Ballston.<p>Adding to the livability of Ballston are amenities such as the recently enlarged Arlington Central Library, the seven-acre Quincy Park, jogging and bicycle paths and the to-be-developed Stuart Park.  The Ellipse Art Center, the Ballston Pops/Arlington Symphony, the Arlington Arts Center and the 10,000-square-foot multi-purpose space being provided by NRECA all add to the quality of life in the "new" Ballston.
</DOC>
<DOC>
