<title>ROSSLYN</title>
<H1>Rosslyn</h1>

<img src=Rosslyn.gif> Rosslyn is entering its third period of redevelopment.  Until 1960 the area was the site of a motley collection of oil storage tanks, industrial buildings and pawn shops.  With the advent of Arlington's then new site plan process, a wave of intensive redevelopment began resulting in the construction of 27 new office buildings and hotels by 1970.  Rosslyn saw its second development boom in the early 1980's with the construction of such signature buildings as 1525 Wilson, Potomac Tower and the Arland Towers complex, most commonly known as the home of the Freedom Forum and USA Today.<p>

Now in the mid-90's Rosslyn is again on the verge of substantial change.  Although considerable construction and renovation activity will occur as outmoded buildings from Rosslyn's early years are either substantially renovated or redeveloped, the hallmark of this new era will be the creation a more user friendly Rosslyn.  This will occur as streetscape, public art and beautification projects either currently being developed or called for in the County's 1992 Rosslyn Station Area Plan Addendum are completed; with the construction of the Freedom Forum's Newseum; introduction of new retail development which expands Rosslyn's already considerable base of restaurants and shops; and by the architectural quality and sensitive urbanity of Rosslyn's next generation of buildings, as exemplified by the Commonwealth Tower project.  All of these activities will enable Rosslyn to further capitalize upon its strengths which include:<p>

<b>ROSSLYN FACTS AT A GLANCE</b><p>
<ul><li>8 million square feet of office space much of it with unparalleled views at very competitive lease rates
<li>One of the most accessible locations in the region whether by train, plane, bike, car or foot
<li>Close proximity to such National Landmarks as Roosevelt Island and the Iwo Jima Memorial
<li>6,000 housing units within a 10 minute walk of the Metro offering a wide variety of styles and prices
<li>50+ restaurants and 500,000 square feet of retail development including jewelers, grocery stores, furniture and a complete array of business support services</ul>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B38-14</DOCNO>
