<title>COURTHOUSE</title><h1>Courthouse</h1><img src="ctplaz2.gif">Convenience, compact development and outstanding views have attracted businesses and residents alike to Courthouse.  Since 1983, eight highrise residential buildings have been constructed in the area along with several new townhouse projects and the renovation of historical Colonial Village.  Nine office buildings have been built during the same period, as has the County's new court house and detention center.  The area is currently home to an estimated 7,500 people and has an employment base of 12,500.  Over the next 15 years, residential growth in Courthouse is projected to exceed 50 percent and employment is expected to increase by 32 percent.<p>Like most of the Rosslyn-Ballston corridor, the development pattern in Courthouse is highrise residential and office development around the Metro station with townhomes, garden apartments and single-family residences on the periphery.  The center of the neighborhood is Courthouse Plaza, a joint development between Arlington County and the Charles E. Smith Company.  Surrounding the outdoor plaza's fountains and landscaping are retail, restaurants and an eight-screen movie theater.  The development's office and apartment buildings frame the plaza on the north and south.  On the west end is a hotel site which the county is actively marketing.<p>Long the center of Arlington County government, Courthouse is home the county's administrative offices, its police headquarters and its court system.  It is also home to numerous high-technology businesses and associations, such as Bell Atlantic, SRA, LCC Communications and the Electronic Industries Association.  More information-based companies are expected to move to Courthouse when office development picks up, taking advantage of the area's synergy and the fiber optics running throughout the corridor.<p>The residential population of Courthouse is mostly young, single professionals.  Sixty-seven percent of the people are under 35 years old and 54 percent are single.  The median income is $38,100 and 74 percent of all people live in apartments.  Catering to these demographics are a number of successful retail and restaurant establishments, including Arlington's first brew pub, Bardo Rodeo, and the acclaimed Go! Compact Discs.<p>Filling the niche between the established residential neighborhoods and the new apartment buildings will be new townhouse developments.  Plans have been filed recently for a 126-unit townhome project one block from Metro and more plans may be on the way.<p>Office townhouses may also be on the horizon for Courthouse.  Several companies and associations have expressed interest in smaller buildings that could be built just outside the higher-density core of the area.
</DOC>
<DOC>
