<html><head><title>Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-1>LLP</font> Recruiting</head></title>
<h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-1>LLP</font><p>Recruiting</h3>
<h2 align=center>International Associates Program</h2>
<CENTER>
<strong>
Introduction</strong><P>

</CENTER><P>

		For many years, Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> has had an international associate program that allows an attorney from outside the United States to spend nine to twelve months as an associate of the firm.  The purpose of the program is to assist Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> in the preparation of cases with both international and domestic dimensions; to add to the firm's diversity; and to expose talented foreign lawyers to the practice of law at Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font>.  The firm's program so far has included international associates from Argentina, Australia, Austria, Belgium, England, Ethiopia, Germany, Greece, Ireland, Israel, Italy, Japan, Pakistan, Russia, Scotland, Sri Lanka and Switzerland.<P>

<P>



<CENTER>
<strong>
The International Associate's Role</strong><P>

</CENTER><P>

		During his or her period with the firm, the international associate is expected to perform a wide variety of legal tasks.  Like all associates, the international associate must carry out legal research and prepare drafts of memoranda, opinions, congressional testimony, articles, speeches, and the like.  Some work will be non-billable; most will be done on behalf of the firm's clients.  The international associate's early work is reviewed carefully and discussed with the associate to ease the transition to American legal practice.<P>

<P>

		The substantive legal experience of the international associate is not solely confined to international matters.  Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> believes that its international associates should be exposed to all facets of the typical Washington practice; therefore, they can expect to be involved in a full range of domestic issues.  Although legal research and the preparation of memoranda occupy a significant amount of the associate's schedule,  contact with clients, opposing counsel, government officials and outside experts is encouraged.  Special steps have also been taken to give the international associate exposure to a broad range of lawyers within the firm.<P>

<CENTER>
<STRONG>
Duration of the Program</STRONG><P>

</CENTER><P>

		The international associate program is designed for foreign lawyers who wish to experience American legal practice before returning to their countries of origin.  It is not designed for lawyers seeking a permanent position in the United States.  Accordingly, international associates are not expected to take a U.S. bar examination, and the period of the associateship will be limited to nine to twelve months; extensions of this period will not ordinarily be granted.<P>

<P>



<CENTER>
<STRONG>
Salary</STRONG><P>

</CENTER><P>

		The international associate salary is currently $51,100 a year.  Salaries are adjusted in January of each year.  In many cases, the foreign lawyer may be able to mitigate tax burdens significantly as a result of agreements entered into between the United States and other nations.<P>

<P>


<CENTER>
<strong>
Qualifications</strong><P>

</CENTER><P>

		Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> seeks foreign lawyers of the highest caliber.  Candidates should demonstrate a high level of academic achievement both at home and in the United States.  It is not necessary for candidates to be admitted to the bar of their home countries, but such a qualification will be viewed favorably.  All international associates must hold a law degree (typically an LL.M. or equivalent) from an American law school.  Grades achieved while studying for this degree will play a large role in the selection process.<P>

<P>

		Selection for the program will be carried out on the basis of merit.  A preexisting business or personal relationship with Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> is not a prerequisite.  Some special consideration will be given to candidates from countries that have not yet been represented in the firm's program.<P>

<P>

		Participants in the program must have a United States social security number when they begin work.  The firm is required to provide this number to the Internal Revenue Service for identification purposes when reporting an employee's income, although international associates may frequently pay reduced federal income and state taxes.<P>

<P>



<CENTER>
<STRONG>
Applications</STRONG><P>

</CENTER><P>

		Candidates should send a full personal resume detailing academic and career achievements to Rosemary Kelly Morgan, Director of Recruiting.  The application should include a transcript of grades achieved at the candidate's U.S. law school and the names of two professors at that same school  who can serve as references.  Candidates should also submit a writing sample in English.  The sample should demonstrate the candidate's legal analytical skills in the context of practical problems.  Law review articles or research papers produced over several weeks are helpful.  Class work and examination papers produced under tight deadlines are acceptable but are less likely to show the candidate in the best light.<P>

<P>

		Applications should be submitted by the end of February.  Highly qualified candidates will be selected for interviews in March with the expectation that the international associate program will begin in the fall.<P>

Spring 1996<P>







