<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>re: Environmental Cleanup Relief</TITLE>
</HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h2 align=center><FONT size=+4>re:</font> Environmental Cleanup Relief</h2>
<hr>
<CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER>
<hr>

<p><center>June 20, 1996</center>
<P>

<h2 align=center>Arizona turns Brownfields into Greenfields</h2>

<p>The sale and purchase of contaminated land in Arizona will soon become easier as a result of a recently enacted law.  The law (Senate Bill 1410; Chapter 177, Laws of 1996) contains provisions which, if carefully followed, mean that the following persons can <I>avoid</I> environmental cleanup liability:  (1) new purchasers of contaminated property; (2) lenders that hold a security interest in contaminated property; and (3) trustees who manage contaminated property.  When the law becomes effective in July 1996, contaminated property will become more marketable in Arizona.<P>
<P>



<B><font size=+1>THE PROBLEM</font></B>.<P>
The concern about environmental cleanup liability arises from two laws, one federal and one state.  Both the federal Superfund law (the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act or "CERCLA") and the Arizona Superfund law (the Water Quality Assurance Revolving Fund or "WQARF") impose cleanup liability on owners and operators of contaminated property without regard to whether they caused the contamination.  If property is contaminated, the owners and operators of the property must remediate it.  Liability extends to new purchasers of the property, to lenders who acquire possession of the property through default, and even to trustees who manage the property.  This liability has caused the value of even nominally contaminated property to plummet.  The resulting challenge is twofold:  to restore value to such property while still providing for its remediation.<P>
<P>

	
<B><font size=+1>THE FEDERAL SOLUTION</font></B>.
<P>On the national level, the Environmental Protection Agency ("EPA") has undertaken a "Brownfields" initiative under which it will issue "comfort letters" to potential buyers of contaminated property (commonly referred to as "Prospective Purchasers") specifying what liability, if any, the purchaser will have with respect to the property.  Under certain circumstances, EPA will even enter into a formal "Prospective Purchaser Agreement" with the new buyer.  Because the Brownfields initiative is relatively new, and because EPA is decentralized into ten administrative regions, obtaining liability clarifications from EPA is not an exact science and requires skill and experience.  The important fact, however, is that EPA has now acknowledged the existence of the problem and that it is both a cause of the problem as well as a vital part of its resolution.<P>
<P>


<B><FONT SIZE=+1>THE STATE SOLUTION</FONT></B><P>
After CERCLA was enacted in 1980, approximately 45 states adopted their own mini-Superfund laws.  Arizona adopted WQARF in 1986.  Within the last few years, however, more than 20 states have also adopted their own "Brownfields" initiatives to fix the glaring problem of having, unwittingly, devalued thousands of commercial and industrial properties.  States that have adopted Brownfields laws include:  Arkansas, California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Michigan, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Washington and Wisconsin.  And, in July, Arizona will join the list when Senate Bill 1410 becomes effective.<P>
<P>


<B><font size=+1>THE ARIZONA SOLUTION</font></B><P>
Senate Bill 1410 contains liability relief for three separate categories of persons: <P>
(1) prospective purchasers of contaminated property; (2) lenders that hold a security interest in contaminated property; and (3) trustees who manage contaminated property.  The primary focus of this article is on how SB 1410 affects prospective purchasers of contaminated property.<P>
<P>


<B><font size=+1>PROSPECTIVE PURCHASER LIABILITY; PROSPECTIVE PURCHASER AGREEMENTS</font></B><P>
A purchaser of contaminated property bargains for whatever information, representations, warranties and indemnifications it can obtain from the seller.  Sometimes, however, a seller will provide only information about its property and will require, without any further inducement (such as representations, warranties and indemnifications), that the purchaser do its own due diligence and use its own judgment as to whether to buy the property.  This is a matter of negotiation between the buyer and seller and differs from case to case.<P>
<P>

Under SB 1410, however, the buyer may obtain the following <I>written</I> protections from the <I>State of Arizona</I> against liability arising out of the ownership of contaminated property:<P>
<P>
<ul type=disk>
<li>	a release from the state so that the purchaser is not liable to the state for cleanup of the property;<P>
<P>
<li>	a covenant-not-to-sue from the state so that the state cannot sue the buyer for cleanup of the property; and <P>
<P>
<li>	a grant of immunity (i.e., "contribution protection") from the state so that third parties cannot sue the purchaser for cleanup of any hazardous substances on the property as of the date of closing.<P>
<P>
</ul>
To obtain the foregoing protections, a buyer must negotiate a <I>written</I> Prospective Purchaser Agreement ("PPA") with the Arizona Department of Environmental Quality ("ADEQ") <I>before</I> purchasing the property.  Senate Bill 1410 provides that <I>all</I> of the following conditions must be met before ADEQ can enter into a PPA:<P>
<P>
<ul type=disk>
<li>	The facility must either be identified on the WQARF priority list maintained by ADEQ <I>or</I> ADEQ must be provided sufficient information to reasonably identify the extent of contamination at the facility.<P>
<P>
<li>	The prospective purchaser cannot be actually liable for the contamination at the facility.<P>
<P>
<li>	The proposed redevelopment or reuse of the facility <I>must not:</I>  (a) contribute to or exacerbate existing known contamination; (b) unreasonably interfere with remedial measures necessary at the facility; or (c) cause the contamination to present a substantial health risk to the public.<P>
<P>
<li>	The PPA must provide a substantial public benefit.  [See discussion below about what constitutes a "substantial public benefit."]<P>
<P>
<li>	The department must consult with local planning and zoning authorities with jurisdiction over the facility and consider reasonably anticipated future land uses at the facility and surrounding properties.<P>
<P>
<li>	The prospective purchaser cannot be associated, through any familial relationship or any corporate or contractual relationship other than a contract to protect a security interest, with a person who is responsible for contamination on the property.<P>
<P>
</ul>
In addition to the foregoing, SB 1410 requires that a PPA must include all provisions "deemed necessary" by ADEQ such as the following:<P>
<P>
<ul type=disk>
<li>	The prospective purchaser must represent that it did not cause or contribute to the contamination on the property.<P>
<P>
<li>	If the prospective purchaser does not undertake remedial action, it must agree that it will not exacerbate or contribute to the existing contamination or create additional contamination by an act or omission.<P>
 <P>
<li>	The prospective purchaser must agree that any activity that it will conduct or direct on the contaminated property will not unreasonably interfere with any ongoing remedial actions that are being performed by a responsible party or ADEQ, and that the purchaser will cooperate with those activities.<P>
<P>
<li>	The prospective purchaser must agree to undertake measures that constitute a substantial public benefit.  A substantial public benefit is defined as including, but is not necessarily limited to, <I>any of</I> the following:  (a) an agreement by the prospective purchaser to provide substantial funding or other resources to perform or facilitate remedial measures at the facility; (b) an agreement by the prospective purchaser to perform substantial remedial measures at the facility; (c) <I>productive reuse of a vacant or abandoned industrial or commercial facility</I>; (d) development of a facility by a governmental entity or nonprofit organization to address an important public purpose; <I>or </I>(e) creation of conservation or recreation areas.<P>
<P>
<li>	If the prospective purchaser is to perform remedial measures under the PPA, it must agree to perform those measures in compliance with applicable statutes and rules under ADEQ's supervision.<P>
<P>
<li>	Unless the contamination was caused by the state, the prospective purchaser must waive any claim or cause of action against the state that arises from contamination that exists as of the date of purchase.<P>
<P>
<li>	The prospective purchaser must grant an easement to ADEQ and its authorized representatives for purposes of ensuring compliance with the agreement or for remedial measures in connection with contamination at the facility as of the date of purchase.<P>
<P>
<li>	ADEQ and the prospective purchase will reserve their rights as to any person who is not a party to the PPA.<P>
<P>
</ul>
If the purchaser fails to perform any of its PPA obligations, ADEQ may void the agreement.  In addition to the foregoing, the state may, as a condition of entering into a PPA, impose a lien on property on which it has conducted a remedial action for which it has not been reimbursed.<P>
<P>
Another significant benefit of the new law is that a landowner may assign a PPA by providing written notice to ADEQ of any sale, assignment or other transfer of the property at least fifteen (15) business days before the date of any transfer.  On assignment, the assignee assumes the obligations and the benefits of the PPA.  And unless the assignor has breached the agreement, it will retain the benefits conferred by the PPA.<P>
<P>
<B><font size=+1>LENDER LIABILITY</font></B>.<P>
Senate Bill 1410 also provides relief to lenders that hold a security interest in contaminated property.  Under the new law, holding a security interest does not, by itself, make the lender liable for cleaning up the property<I>
provided that</I> the lender does not participate in the management of the property and does not cause, contribute to or aggravate the contamination through intentional misconduct or gross negligence.  The lender can lose its exemption from liability, however, by failing to take certain actions spelled out in SB 1410.<p>
<P>

<B><font size=+1>TRUSTEE LIABILITY</font></B>.<P>
Senate Bill 1410 also provides that a trustee, as specifically defined in the bill, is not itself liable for cleanup costs. The immunity does not preclude claims against the trust assets themselves, and the trustee can lose its immunity <I>if:</I>  (a) the trustee, itself, actually caused the contamination; (b) the trustee, through intentional misconduct or gross negligence, aggravates or contributes to the contamination or permits others to do so; or (c) the trustee's appointment is for the purpose of avoiding liability.  With respect to the last exemption, it is <I>prima facie</I> evidence that a fiduciary was appointed to avoid liability if the facility is the only substantial asset in the fiduciary estate.  A person cannot qualify for the exemption from environmental liability if the person is both the grantor and the fiduciary of the same estate.<P>
<P>

<B><font size=+1>THE NET RESULT</font></B>.<P>
Environmental liability laws pose a severe economic threat to those who are involved with contaminated property, and the issues surrounding such liability are as complex, confusing and contentious as ever.  Regardless, the time has never been better to sell, buy, manage or finance such property.  A party can now determine <I>before</I> a decision is made to purchase a property exactly what remedial action, if any, will be required <I>and</I>, in addition, whether a particular state (or, in certain circumstances, EPA) will agree in writing that the new owner will not have any liability for such remediation.  Further, as a result of clearer liability provisions, it should become easier to finance and manage activities on contaminated property. q <P>
<P>

	<blockquote><I>
For additional information on this or other environmental issues, or to obtain a copy of Senate Bill 1410, please contact Jim Derouin in the Phoenix office at (602) 257-5237.</I><P>
<P>
 <P>
<P>
<P>




