<HEAD>
<TITLE>re: environmental regulation</TITLE>
</HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h2 align=center><FONT size=+4>re:</font> Environmental Regulation</h2>
<hr>
<CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER>
<hr>

<p><center>March 15, 1996</center>
<P>

<h2 align=center>New EPA Audit and Disclosure Policy</h2>

<p>The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has implemented a new "Policy on Discovery, Disclosure, Correction and Prevention of  Violations" effective January 22, 1996.  While restating the EPA's long-standing opposition to an evidentiary privilege for information generated by environmental audits, the policy creates new incentives for use of audits and voluntary disclosure of violations, particularly by companies concerned about a risk of criminal prosecution.<P>



<B><font size=+1>BACKGROUND</font></B>.  The new EPA policy recognizes that overly stringent enforcement against companies that report their own violations may actually discourage compliance with environmental regulations.  While companies frequently have no practical alternative to reporting a <I>
known</I> incident of noncompliance, they may decline to conduct voluntary audits that might reveal <I>
unknown</I> violations.<P>

	Industry has worked to eliminate such disincentives to voluntary reporting.  Numerous states have enacted statutes recognizing an evidentiary privilege for environmental audits.  Congress and several other states are currently considering audit legislation. The Arizona legislature is considering a bill that would provide a privilege against prosecution to those who conduct self-audits.  Governor Symington vetoed similar legislation last year, but he and the Arizona Department of Environmental Quality back this session's version.  <P>

	The EPA has consistently opposed legislation creating either an evidentiary audit privilege or formal immunity for violators who voluntarily report.  The agency's new policy, published at 60 Federal Register 66,706 (Dec. 22, 1995), reflects significant improvement of its position after extensive public comment.<P>



<B><font size=+1>INCENTIVES FOR DISCLOSURE</font></B>.  Qualifying organizations are eligible for several benefits under the new EPA policy.  First, the policy fully eliminates "gravity-based" penalties if the organization detected the violation through a formal environmental "audit" or an "objective, documented systematic practice or procedure" reflecting "due diligence" by the company.  The penalties are reduced 75 percent if the violation was detected by less exacting means that otherwise satisfy the policy's conditions.  The EPA reserves the right, however, to collect a fine in the amount of any economic benefit that the organization may have realized by noncompliance.<P>

	Second, the EPA commits not to recommend criminal prosecution of an organization that uncovers violations through an audit or due diligence, promptly discloses and expeditiously corrects those violations, and meets all other conditions of the EPA policy.<P>

	Third, the EPA commits not to request production of audit results, absent independent knowledge of a violation.<P>

	<P>

<B><FONT SIZE=+1>QUALIFYING FOR BENEFIT</FONT></B>S.  The EPA imposes a number of conditions on such benefits, including the following:<P>

  &#149;  The violation must be discovered through an "audit" or "due diligence," rather than through spontaneous employee confessions or other fortuities; <P>

  &#149;  The discovery of the violation must be "voluntary," and not the result of routine monitoring of emissions (as required in most NPDES permits) or an audit mandated under a prior consent order or settlement agreement;<P>

  &#149;  The violation must be disclosed promptly, i.e., no later than <I>
10 days</I> after the company "discovered" it;<P>

  &#149;  Discovery and disclosure must be independent of any government or third-party action, and not an attempt to ward off imminent government action;<P>

  &#149;  The company must promptly correct the violation;<P>

  &#149;  The violation must not have resulted in "serious actual harm" to human health or the environment; and <P>

  &#149;  The company must cooperate fully with any subsequent EPA investigation. <P>

<P>

<B><font size=+1>CAVEATS AND LIMITATIONS</font></B>.  The policy's benefits must be viewed in light of its limitations.  First, as the policy states, it "is intended as guidance," and does not legally bind the EPA.<P>

	The EPA's policy also does not bind the Department of Justice.  Although the EPA states that it will not refer qualifying cases to the DOJ for criminal prosecution, other agencies involved in environmental enforcement (including the FBI) may do so.  Moreover, the DOJ ultimately decides whether to file criminal charges, and it has published its own set of nonbinding and considerably less specific prosecutorial guidelines in this area.<P>

	In addition, the EPA policy applies only to the regulated "entity," not its employees.  Under the policy's "cooperation" condition, an entity seeking to qualify probably will be required to provide prosecutors with any available information regarding individuals.<P>

	The new policy also does not apply to cases resulting in "serious" harm.  Thus, companies suffering true environmental disasters (like the grounding of the <I>
Exxon Valdez</I>) will find no safe harbor.<P>

	Finally, the EPA policy applies primarily to reports generated by audits or due diligence.  A company that voluntarily reports violations detected by pure serendipity, anonymous reports, or similar means should not expect to benefit from the new policy.<P>

	<P>

<B><font size=+1>CONCLUSION</font></B>.  The new EPA policy will not fundamentally alter the balance of factors that a company should weigh in deciding whether to report a violation <I>
once knowledge of the violation exists</I>.  The new policy is so heavily qualified and vulnerable to subjective interpretation that few companies should report solely because of the policy.  <P>

	In fact, most companies <I>
already</I> have overwhelming incentives to report violations once known.  If a violation is subject to mandatory reporting requirements, such as those found in CERCLA and most permits, failure to report is itself a crime.  Moreover, under the federal sentencing guidelines, a company that elects not to report voluntarily may receive a stiffer sentence or probation.  Regardless of the guidelines, lenient treatment is unlikely if regulators detect the violation after the company chooses not to report it.  Finally, many companies consider voluntary reporting a necessary part of being a "good corporate citizen."<P>

	In certain cases, the new EPA policy may give a company comfort that it may conduct voluntary auditing or due diligence to acquire knowledge regarding a potential violation without exposing itself to an unnecessarily high risk of criminal prosecution.  Much will depend, however, on the EPA's actual practices in implementing its new policy. <P>

	<P>

	<blockquote><I>
For more information on this or other environmental law issues, contact James G. Derouin in the Phoenix office at (602) 257-5237 or William T. Hassler in the Washington, D.C. office at (202) 429-6469.</I></blockquote><P>

	<P>

	<P>





In certain cases, the new EPA policy may give a company comfort that it may conduct voluntary auditing or due diligence without exposing itself to an unnecessarily high risk of criminal prosecution.  <P>

