<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>re: Legislative Tax Alert</TITLE>
</HEAD><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<h2 align=center><FONT size=+4>re:</font> Legislative Tax Alert</h2>
<hr>
<CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER>
<hr>
<P><center>March 25, 1996</center>

<P>On March 19, 1996, as part of its budget proposal to Congress, the Administration proposed an amendment to the rules governing tax-free spinoffs that would largely eliminate so-called <I>
Morris Trust</I> spinoffs.  The Administration also proposed an amendment aimed, in part, at eliminating the disappearing basis problem that may arise in certain section 304 transactions.  <P>

<P>

<B>
MORRIS TRUST ELIMINATED.  </B>The <I>
Morris Trust</I> structure is generally used when an acquiring corporation seeks to acquire some but not all of a target corporation's business assets in a tax-free acquisition.  To facilitate the acquisition, the target corporation transfers the unwanted assets to a newly formed subsidiary and then distributes the stock of the controlled corporation to the target corporation's shareholders in a tax-free spinoff.  The target corporation continues to hold the assets wanted by the acquiring corporation and, immediately after the spinoff, either is merged into the acquiring corporation, or has its shareholders exchange their target corporation stock for stock of the acquiring corporation.  Since the repeal of the <I>
General Utilities</I> doctrine in 1986, the<I>
 Morris Trust</I> transaction has been one of the few ways in which a corporation can dispose of unwanted assets without imposition of corporate-level tax.<P>

	Under current law, there is no requirement that its shareholders remain in control of the target corporation after the spinoff.  <U>
See</U> <U>
Morris Trust v. Commissioner</U>, 367 F.2d 794 (4th Cir. 1966); Revenue Ruling 68-603, 1968-2 C.B. 148.  The Administration proposal targets <I>
Morris Trust</I> transactions by requiring a distributing corporation (the target) (but not its shareholders) to recognize gain in a spinoff if the distributing corporation's shareholders (as a group) do not hold a <U>
50 percent</U> interest in <U>
both</U> the distributing and controlled corporations for the two-year period preceding, and the two-year period following, the distribution.  Thus, the proposal precludes tax-free <I>
Morris Trust</I> transactions where the subsequent acquisition results in a loss of control of the target corporation by its historic shareholders.  <U>
The proposal generally would be effective for distributions after March 19, 1996</U>.<P>

<B>
REVENUE RULING 70-496 OVERRULED.</B> Under section 304, the sale of a subsidiary between nonconsolidated affiliated corporations will be treated as a redemption, and may be taxed as a dividend.  For example, assume <I>
P</I> directly owns two subsidiaries, <I>
S1</I> and <I>
S2</I>, and <I>
S1</I> owns all of the stock of <I>
X.  </I>If<I>
 S1 </I>sells all of<I>
 </I>the<I>
 X </I>stock to <I>
S2</I>, <I>
S1</I> will be deemed to have contributed the stock of </A><I>
X</I> to the capital of <I>
S2 </I>and <I>
S1</I> will be deemed to have received the proceeds of the sale in redemption of stock in <I>
S2</I>.  The proceeds will be taxed to <I>
S1</I> as a dividend to the extent of the earnings and profits of <I>
S2</I> and <I>
X</I> .  However, because <I>
S1</I> actually owns no stock in <I>
S2</I>, the I.R.S. has ruled that <I>
S1</I>'s basis in the <I>
X</I> stock disappears.  <U>
See</U> Revenue Ruling 70-496, 1970-2 C.B. 74.  Thus, if the amount of the distribution exceeds the earnings and profits of <I>
S2 </I>and <I>
X,</I> the excess<I>
 </I>will be taxed at capital gains rates, since basis recovery under section 301(c)(2) is unavailable.  <U>
See</U> section 301(c)(3).  <P>

	Arguably, however, if <I>
S1</I> actually owned even one share of <I>
S2 </I>stock,<I>
 S1</I>'s basis in the <I>
X</I> stock would be added to the one share of <I>
S2</I> stock owned by S1.  <U>
See</U> Revenue Ruling 71-527, 1971-2 C.B. 174.  As a result, section 301(c)(2) would apply to the extent the distribution exceeded available earnings and profits, and <I>
S1</I>'s excess basis, if any, in the <I>
S2</I> stock would remain with the <I>
S2</I> stock.<P>

	Under the Administration proposal, such a section 304 transaction will be treated as a contribution by <I>
S1</I> of the <I>
X</I> stock to the capital of <I>
S2</I> in exchange for <I>
S2</I> stock, followed immediately by a redemption of that <I>
S2</I> stock.  Therefore, <I>
S1</I>'s basis in the <I>
X</I> stock will be reflected in the hypothetical share of <I>
S2</I> stock it is deemed to receive.  In contrast to Revenue Ruling 70-496, <I>
S1</I>'s basis in the <I>
X</I> stock will not disappear, but instead will be reflected in <I>
S1</I>'s share of <I>
S2</I> stock.  To the extent the distribution exceeded available earnings and profits, <I>
S1</I>'s basis in the <I>
S2</I> stock will be recovered.  <U>
See</U> section 301(c)(2).  <I>
S1</I>'s excess basis, if any, in the <I>
S2</I> stock should attach to <I>
S2</I> stock owned by <I>
P</I>.  <U>
See</U> Reg. &#167;1.302-2(c), Example (2).  However, to the extent <I>
S1</I> receives a dividends-received deduction on the deemed distribution from <I>
S2</I>, the Administration proposal appears to require <I>
S1</I> to reduce its basis in the <I>
S2</I> stock under sections 1059(a) and (e)(1).<P>

<P>

<B>
OTHER SIGNIFICANT PROPOSALS. </B>The Administration also proposed a number of other significant changes, including (i) requiring taxpayers to determine their basis in substantially identical securities by averaging their basis in all such securities, (ii) amending the extraordinary dividend rules of section 1059 to target the use of options by corporate shareholders to obtain dividend treatment for certain non-pro rata distributions, and (iii) treating transactions designed to reduce the risk of loss on stock as dispositions of such stock in many circumstances (commonly referred to as the &quot;short sales against the box&quot; proposal).  <P>

<P>

	Anyone wishing to discuss the Administration proposals in more detail should contact Mark J. 

Silverman at (202) 429-6450. <P>


<hr>
