</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
	sbw
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and 
circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web 
page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  
Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely 
to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P><hr>


<H1><B>Legislation Limits Environmental Liability for Lenders and Trustees</B></H1>

<P>		One of the last acts of the 104th Congress was to limit the environmental liability of lenders and trustees
 under the Comprehensive Environmental Response Compensation and Liability Act (CERCLA)  (frequently called Superfund).  
The changes to the Superfund law are significant because they more clearly define the actions that lenders or trustees may
 undertake without risking CERCLA liability.  Courts have varied in their interpretations of the activities that create CERCLA liability
 and the amendment provides increased certainty and uniformity.    
<H4>
<P>Lender Liability Limited</H4>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<P>		The definition of owner or operator under CERCLA now explicitly excludes &quot;a person that is a lender
 that, without participating in the management of a vessel or facility, holds indicia of ownership primarily to protect the security
 interest of the person in the vessel or facility.&quot;  &quot;Participation in management&quot; has been defined to specifically
 exclude merely having the capacity to influence or the unexercised right to control.  This is significant because some courts
 previously held that having the right to exercise control was sufficient to create liability, even if the lender never exercised that
 control.
<P>Several other activities also are specifically excluded from the term &quot;participation in management.&quot;
  These include: inspecting the facility and providing financial or other advice in an effort to avoid default or a decrease in
 the value of the facility.  
<P>		In addition,  the law now specifically provides that a lender that has not participated in the management
 of a facility prior to foreclosure is not liable as an owner or operator after foreclosure where the lender maintains business activities
, winds up operations, or takes other measures to preserve or protect the facility.  However, the lender must attempt to divest the
 facility at the &quot;earliest practicable, commercially reasonable time, on commercially reasonable terms, taking into accoun
t market conditions and legal and regulatory requirements.&quot;    
<P>  
<P>		Under the new provision, a lender is considered to participate in manage- ment if, while the borrowe
r is still in possession, the lender exercises 
decision-making control over environmental compliance by the facility.  Such control is defined to include day-to-day dec
ision-making on environmental compliance, or substantial control over the operational, as opposed to financial and administrative, functions of the facility.  In summary, this recent amendment to CERCLA now provides guidance on how a lender can advise a borrower without risking CERCLA liability.
<H4>
<P>Trustee Liability Also Limited </H4>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<P>		The amendment also provides that fiduciaries will not be personally liable for the release
 or threatened release of a hazardous substance, by limiting the liability to the assets held in the fiducia
ry capacity.  However, the limitation does not apply if a fiduciary is liable under CERCLA, independent of its fid
uciary responsibilities.  Moreover, the limita- tion does not apply  if the release or threatened release of hazard
ous sub- stances is caused by the negligence of the fiduciary.
<P> 
<P>		The amendment also defines the term &quot;fiduciary&quot; and includes in the definition executor, adm
inistrator, receiver, and conservator.  Lenders are specifically excluded from the definition.
  The definition also excludes any party acting as a fiduciary for an estate organized for the primary purpose of actively car
rying out a trade or business.
<P>
<P>		Certain safe harbors have been created for fiduciaries, similar to those created for lenders.  For e
xample,  a fiduciary may inspect a facility and provide counseling or financial advice without incurring personal liability.
<P>
<P>		If you have questions about the impact of the amendments, please contact Sara Beth Wat
son at (202)429-6460 (e-mail address:  <a href="mailto:swatson@steptoe.com">swatson@steptoe.com</A>) or the attorney
 with whom you routinely work at Steptoe &amp; Johnson LLP.
</BODY>
