<HEAD>
<TITLE>Dida HTML Editor </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and 
circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web 
page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  
Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely 
to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<P>
<hr>
<Center><H3>INTERNET TELEPHONY</H3><P></P> 
Alfred M. Mamlet</Center><P></P>

<H4>INTRODUCTION</H4><P></P>
		This paper provides an introduction to some of the basic technological, economic,
 regulatory and policy considerations related to Internet telephony.  In the interests of brevity and 
reaching a general audience, some of these topics are necessarily over-simplified.<P></P>

		Estimates of the penetration of Internet voice software exceed 1 million copies
 in the United States as of mid-1996.  Most of this software has been bundled with other products such
 as Internet browser software and modems.<P></P>

		This paper begins by providing elementary background on the technological 
(Part 2), economic (Part 3) and regulatory (Part 4) considerations behind Internet telephony.  The 
paper then analyzes the petition filed by America Carriers Telecommunications Association ("ACTA") 
at the FCC in March 1996 (Part 5).  The paper concludes with a brief discussion of some of the Internet 
interconnection fees issues which pose a much bigger challenge to the Internet than the ACTA Petition 
(Part 6).  Finally, nascent international issues are examined (Part 7).<P></P>

<H4>TECHNOLOGY CONSIDERATIONS</H4><P></P>

	<H4>Traditional Voice Telephone Technology</H4><P></P>

		Traditional voice service on the public switched telephone network ("PSTN")
 relies on circuit-switching.  The network devotes a dedicated circuit for each conversation.  A long 
silence on a call between an awkward teenage boy asking a girl for a date consumes the same
 capacity as the intense negotiations between two attorneys.  <P></P>

<H4>Internet Voice Technology</H4><P></P>

<H4>Internet Voice Technology Today</H4><P></P>

		While traditional voice technology employs circuit-switching, all Internet
 transmissions, including data, voice and video use packet-switching.   To use the Internet for a 
voice conversation today, a typical "dial-up" Internet user speaks into a microphone connected to 
a personal computer that is equipped with a sound card.  Software and the sound card first convert
 the voice wave to an analog signal.  Next, additional software converts the analog signal to a digital
 form and then compresses the signal to reduce the necessary bandwidth.  <P></P>

		The Internet breaks all data (including voice and video) into packets, and uses
 routers (computers) to direct the path of the packets on the network. The individual packets of the
 message may be sent over different routes.  This routing technology allows many different messages
 to be sent over the same line, permitting efficient sharing of the same fixed costs.  At the receiving
 end of the call, the packets are reassembled in the original order.  When the call comes over the phone
line and through the PC the initial process is reversed, sending the call through the modem, sound card 
and out the speaker.<P></P>

		The voice quality depends on a number of factors.  If the network is congested, 
some of the packets in the telephone message may be delayed or lost ("dropped"), reducing the 
quality of the call.  Early Internet voice software operated only at half-duplex, which permits only
 one party to talk at a time.  More recently, some software offer full duplex operation, allowing both
 parties to talk simultaneously and reducing delay.<P></P>

		A major limiting factor of Internet telephony has been the requirement that both
 users be online at a prearranged time in order to initiate and receive a call.  This technical obstacle
 may also be eliminated shortly.  Vocaltec has recently unveiled a new product, called the Internet
 Phone Telephony Gateway that reportedly will automatically switch calls from the Internet to the 
traditional public switched telephone network by linking Internet calls to and from local exchange 
networks.  International Discount Telecommunications has also announced a similar product.<P></P>

<H4>Internet Voice Technology Tomorrow</H4><P></P>

		Greater bandwidth, as well as software and hardware innovations will increase
 the quality of Internet telephony.  The above description was for the typical "dial-up" user constrained 
by the local telephone company copper wire network.  Users with access to increased bandwidth
 through an ISDN line, high speed leased line connection or cable modem should have increased
 Internet telephony quality.<P></P>

		A number of companies, including Netscape, Microsoft, AT&T, Sprint, MCI, IBM
 and Intel are working on a variety of innovative products, standards and technologies to enhance the
 delivery of voice and video services over the Internet. The potential for using the Internet for voice 
communications was reportedly a driving factor in the recent $2 billion acquisition of UUNet  by
 MFS Communications.<P></P>

		One potentially promising developing technology is Multicast Backbone
 ("MBONE").  The MBONE is a virtual network that is layered on top of part of the Internet.  It may
 eventually provide Internet telephony comparable to the voice quality on the PSTN.  The MBONE
 also allows live audio and video transmission to be multicast to numerous destinations simultaneously
, permitting videoconferencing, distance learning and "personal broadcasting."  Today, the MBONE
 reportedly operates on about 1700 networks in 20 countries.  It can transmit video at about 3 frame
 per second (TV is 30 frames per second).  Video connections to the MBONE require a minimum
 connection of 128 Kbps (equivalent to a dual channel ISDN line), but a T-1 link is highly desirable. 
 Audio connections require less bandwidth.<P></P>

<H4>ECONOMIC CONSIDERATIONS</H4><P></P>

		Internet voice telephony has two potential cost advantages over traditional PSTN
 services.  First, packet-switching is inherently less expensive than circuit-switching.  Second, and
 more significantly, traditional interexchange and international voice traffic carry a number of
 interconnection charges that are not normally placed on Internet services in the United States.<P></P>
Potential Cost Advantages Of Internet Voice Services<P></P>

		Packet-switching is inherently less expensive than circuit-switching because it
 provides a more efficient method of transmitting calls.  As discussed above, conventional telephone
 service requires a dedicated end-to-end connection.  This connection dedicates more capacity than
 necessary for the call on an exclusive basis.  In contrast, the Internet message is split into packets to
 enable each circuit to be filled to capacity.  <P></P>

		This technological difference means that the circuit-switching PSTN
 uses a lot of lines (for dedicated connections) and economize on switching and routing.  The
 Internet uses a lot of switches (computers) and economizes on lines.<P></P>

		The original design of the PSTN provided significant efficiencies when
 lines were relatively cheap compared to switches.  However, the cost of switches (computers)
 has fallen much faster than the cost of lines.  As a result, the Internet is a highly efficient network 
and enjoys some potential comparative advantages over the PSTN for some services.  <P></P>

		In addition, the Internet offers further efficiencies because it compresses data,
 and uses bulk lines.  While both techniques are employed in the PSTN, they are not as prevalent.<P></P>

		These efficiencies must be placed in the proper perspective.  The marginal
 transmission cost of an incremental Internet telephone call has been estimated to be well under $.01
 per minute.  However, most estimates of the incremental transmission cost for a traditional U.S.
 coast-to-coast voice call range from $.01-$.02 per minute.  In addition, most long distance carriers
 incur marketing, billing and collection, and some fixed switching costs not paid by ISPs.<P></P>

		However, the principal, and substantial, incremental cost differences are 
attributable to regulatorily imposed interconnection costs and universal service contributions in
 PSTN service, most of which are avoided by Internet telephony.  <P></P>

<H4>Potential Regulatory Advantages Of Internet Voice Services</H4><P></P>

<H4>Local Access Charges</H4><P></P>

		Today, U.S. long distance carriers pay local access fees on both the originating
 and terminating end of a long distance call that range from approximately $.03-$.07 per minute on 
each end (or $.06-$.14 in total).  These interconnection fees are generally regarded as well above the
 incremental cost of the interconnection.  The fees are used to pay for development of the local
 telephone network.  They effectively subsidize users who do not make many (or any) long distance
 calls.  <P></P>

		Ever since the modern access charge regime was established in 1983, there 
has been a "temporary" exemption for enhanced services, including Internet services.  This exemption
 is analyzed below.  Since local access fees consume between 40% and 50% of long distance carrier
 revenues, this exemption provides a powerful price incentive to use Internet voice services, which have
 been presumed by most to be enhanced services (this presumption is also analyzed below).  <P></P>

		Entry of new companies into the local telephone market and new FCC rulemakings
 regarding interconnections, universal service and access charge reform may lead to significant
 reductions in access charges.  In addition, as discussed below, the Commission's upcoming
 rulemaking on access charge reform will provide another vehicle for considering the differential 
regulatory treatment of traditional and Internet voice services.  <P></P>

<H4>Universal Service</H4> <P></P>

		In addition to the implicit subsidies in above-cost access charges, traditional
 long distance carriers pay explicit subsidies for universal service that are currently based on the
 number of their subscribers.  The FCC is actively considering changing its methodology for assessing
 contributions to universal service, although it is unlikely to assess Internet Service Providers ("ISPs").<P></P>

<H4>International Accounting Rates</H4><P></P>

<H4>The International Accounting Rate System For Voice Traffic</H4><P></P>

		Traditional voice traffic relies on the "accounting rate system" to price the
 interconnections of most international calls.  This is best illustrated by an example.  AT&T and
 British Telephone ("BT") have negotiated an accounting rate for calls on the U.S.-U.K. route.  
If the accounting rate is $1.00 per minute, then the carriers will normally pay half that amount
 ($.50 per minute) as the settlement rate.  If an American in Orlando, Florida calls a person in
 London for ten minutes, then AT&T will pay BT $5.00 for that call.  In theory, these payments
 compensate BT for the costs of:  (1) providing half of the trans-Atlantic cable circuit used;
 and (2) terminating the call on its local London network.  In practice, these payments normally 
exceed the costs incurred.<P></P>

		Many more calls are billed in the United States, with settlement payments made
 to foreign carriers, than vice-versa for three reasons.  First, U.S. consumers and businesses are
 generally wealthier than their foreign counterparts.  Second, U.S. co<P></P>

		The FCC and many U.S. carriers contend that the settlement rates are well
 above the cost of providing these services.  They are looking for ways to reduce this
 telecommunications trade deficit.  Many foreign governments and foreign carriers maintain
 that these rates are necessary to support construction and improvement of the local telephone
 networks in their countries.<P></P>

<H4>Internet Voice Services Offer A Potential Mechanism To Bypass The International Accounting Rate
 System</H4><P></P>

		Today, one of the leading attractions of Internet voice services is the opportunity
 to bypass the settlement costs in the international accounting rate system.  This is one of the
 objections raised by ACTA, and others.<P></P>

		As part of its efforts to encourage lower accounting rates, the FCC has
 expressed a hope that new technologies may increase the downward pressure on accounting rates:

<UL>
<LI>new technologies offer new and improved forms of communication and should thus be encouraged.
  Development of these technologies would be advanced by a new, more flexible regulatory framework
 providing greater economic incentive to invest in and use the infrastructure necessary to support
 these technological innovations.  Such a framework should be able to accommodate fundamentally
 different ways of organizing the supply and pricing of services."<P></P>
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>		Internet telephony is potentially one such technology that the FCC may
 hope will increase pressure on foreign carriers to reduce their international accounting rates.
 Of course, many foreign governments and foreign carriers will not share any FCC enthusiasm
 for bypass of the international accounting system.<P></P>
</UL>

<H4>Internet Interconnections</H4><P></P>

		On the Internet, interconnection arrangements are largely unregulated.
  In the absence of regulation, the various Internet networks have essentially agreed that they will 
exchange traffic on a "no-charge" basis.  This "bill-and-keep" practice has worked because traffic
 flows have been perceived as relatively symmetrical, and because marginal transport costs are
 viewed as close to zero if there is sufficient capacity.<P></P>

<H4>Internet Pricing</H4><P></P>

		Unburdened with interconnection charges imposed by regulation or economics,
 most U.S. interconnection prices are flat capacity-based access fees.  Typical U.S. "dial-up" access
 users pay flat monthly Internet access fees.  This pricing mechanism has contributed significantly to
 the growth in the Internet's popularity.  And, along with the developing capability to transmit voice and
 video messages, this pricing leads to network congestion.  <P></P>

		U.S. end-users with leased lines and Internet Service Providers ("ISPs")
 generally pay a flat fee for unlimited throughput for their connection (e.g., 56k, T1, T3).  Internet
 users in some other countries pay metered prices based on their usage.<P></P>

<H4>Regulatory Background</H4><P></P>

<H4>Regulatory Jurisdiction</H4><P></P>

		There can be no real dispute that the Commission has jurisdiction over
 Internet communications because its authority encompasses all "interstate and foreign commerce
 in communication by wire and radio. . . ."  <P></P>

		However, ever since the Commission's 1980 Computer II decision, 
the FCC has forborne from imposing common carrier regulation on enhanced services. 
 The central rationale for not regulating the enhanced services market was that it did not have the
 concentrated market structure which justified economic regulation of traditional telephone services.
<P></P>

Under Section 64.702 of the Commission's Rules:<P></P>


<UL>
<LI>the term enhanced service shall refer to services, offered over common carrier transmission
 facilities used in interstate communications, which [1] employ computer processing applications
 that act on the format, content, code, protocol or similar aspects of the subscriber's transmitted
 information; [2] provide the subscriber additional, different, or restructured information; or [3] involve
 subscriber interaction with stored information.<P></P>
</UL>

		Internet data clearly meet this test.  First, computer processing is normally
 used to add packet header information and perform other functions.  Second, the Internet frequently 
provides the subscriber with "additional, different or restructured information.  Third, the Internet often
 "involve[s] subscriber interaction with stored information."<P></P>

		Application of this test to Internet telephony is less clear.  First, the voice
 wave is transmitted from end-to-end without change in content.  Second, the Internet telephony
 user does not receive any "additional, different, or restructured information.  Third,  the subscriber
 may not interact with stored information.   While some Internet telephony may be subject to minor
 store-forward procedures while the voice data temporarily resides on a server, developers of
 advanced Internet telephony applications claim to provide "real-time" communications and 
seamless computer-to-telephone services.<P></P>

<H4>Access Charge Regulation.</H4><P></P>

		In 1983, when the Commission established the modern access fee structure,
 the FCC created "temporary exemptions" for enhanced services to avoid "huge increases in their
 costs of operation which could affect their viability".   In 1988, the Commission proposed repealing
 the exemption.  However, the proposal was met with loud concerns about  ACTA INTERNET VOICE 
proceeding.<P></P>

<H4>ACTA's Petition</H4><P></P>

		In March 1996, ACTA, a trade association comprised mostly of long distance
 resellers, filed a Petition for Rulemaking (and a request for additional relief) with the FCC.  ACTA's
 Petition asked the FCC to:  (1) declare that the FCC has authority over the Internet; (2) institute a
 rulemaking for regulating the Internet; and (3) "immediately order" all software providers to stop
 providing software for Internet voice services until they file tariffs and receive FCC authorizations. 
</P></P>

		In its subsequent Comments, ACTA broadened its target from software publishers
 to include Internet Service Providers ("ISPs"), such as PSI, and Online Service Providers ("OSPs"), 
such as America Online, that offer software with Internet voice telephony features.<P></P>

<H4>Legal Analysis Of ACTA Petition</H4><P></P>

<H4>Software Publishers</H4><P></P>

		At a minimum, the ACTA Petition was misdirected at software publishers.
  Software publishers do not provide "telecommunications" services because they do not transmit 
information.  Further, software publishers do not offer "telecommunications for a fee directly to the
 public."  Instead, they sell software packages that permit the public to use the Internet to transmit
 voice messages over the Internet.  While Internet voice software providers often (but not always)
 market directly to the public, the software provides similar effective functionality as the software
 made by telephone equipment and switch providers used in the public switched telephone network
, who have never been regulated as common carriers.<P></P>

<H4>Internet Service Providers</H4><P></P>

<H4>Common Carriage Regulation</H4><P></P>

<H4>Arguments In Favor Of Common Carrier Regulation</H4><P></P>

		The best argument that Internet voice services qualify for common carriage
 under the statutory definitions is that it meets the three-pronged definition of "telecommunications"
 because (1) it is "the transmission, between or among points specified by the user, [2] of information
 of the user's choosing, [3] without change in the form or content of the information as sent and
 received."  Internet voice services may meet this test because:  (1) the Internet voice user specifies
 where the call originates and terminates; (2) the caller decides what to say; and (3) the recipient
 hears the same voice message that is delivered without change.<P></P>

		It is important to note that this argument would still not subject traditional Internet
 data services to common carriage treatment.  Internet data is changed by computer processing 
between the time it is sent and received by the addition of packet headers (and often by other
 information).  In addition, particular Internet applications and functions do not meet the statute's
 definition of telecommunications.<P></P>

<H4>Arguments Against Common Carrier Regulation</H4><P></P>

		The best arguments against subjecting Internet voice services to common
 carriage regulation are practical and technical ones.  The biggest obstacle is that it is impossible to
 differentiate Internet voice packets from data packets (although future standards may require 
differentiating information in the packet "headers").  For this reason, an ISP could not distinguish
 between regulated voice packets and unregulated data packets.  The ISP would not know when it is
 acting as a common carrier (or "telecommunications carrier" under the statute).<P></P>

		A second issue is that many ISPs are arguably not "telecommunications carriers
" because they do not "offer[ ] telecommunications for a fee directly to the public. . . ."  Instead, they offer 
Internet connections which the end-user combines with software (sometimes supplied by the user) to
 obtain the ability to use telecommunications.  However, other ISPs actively market Internet voice
 services, or at least Internet access software with Internet voice capabilities.<P></P>

		A third complication is that it is impossible to know who all the "carriers" of
 any given voice call are since each of the packets in the call take a circuitous and different route.
  Finally, it is virtually impossible to measure the length of a call.  In short, applying the statutory
 definitions to Internet voice services would be exceedingly difficult to implement today.<P></P>

		To fit Internet voice services into traditional common carrier regulation would 
require redesigning substantial technical (and economic) characteristics of the Internet.  While it is 
true that the PSTN has been designed in part around regulatory requirements, it is far from clear that
 there are substantial public benefits to be gained from common carrier regulation or redesign of the
 Internet.<P></P>

<H4>Forbearance</H4><P></P>

		Even if Internet telephony is a common carrier service, the Commission  may 
forbear from subjecting this service to common carrier regulation if:  (1) regulation is not necessary 
to ensure just and reasonable charges; (2) regulation is not required to protect consumers; and (3)
 it would be in the public interest to forebear from regulation.  <P></P>

		The Commission has forborne from economic regulation of enhanced 
services, including the Internet, since the 1980 Computer II decision for precisely these reasons. 
 Economic regulation of the Internet is hardly necessary to protect subscribers from being charged
 unreasonably high rates.  The Internet has flourished without common carrier regulation, and will 
continue to do so if not regulated.  In addition, the numerous technical and practical problems discussed
 above underline the need for forbearance from common carrier regulation.  <P></P>

		Therefore, the Commission could properly forbear from subjecting Internet 
voice services to common carrier regulation even if it determined that these services met the statutory 
definition of common carriage. Such forbearance would accord with the congressional policy "to
 preserve the vibrant and competitive free market that presently exists for the Internet and other
 interactive computer services, unfettered by Federal or State regulation."  <P></P>

<H4>Internet Services and Interconnection Charges </H4><P></P>

		The ACTA Petition marks, the first, but not the last attempt to impose economic 
regulation on the Internet.  The critical issue is not whether Internet telephony should be subject to
 common carrier regulation, but whether it should continue to enjoy the regulatory advantages 
related to interconnection charges and universal service over traditional voice telephone service
, with which it is increasingly competing.  Indeed, the Internet telephony issue will force the Commission
 to confront the question whether any Internet services (data, voice or video) should continue to be 
exempt from the interconnection charges regulatorily imposed on traditional voice services because 
all Internet services use portions of the local and international networks.<P></P>

		Some will point to the explosive growth of the Internet and concomitant increased 
use of the local network to justify imposition of access charges.  Published (but unsubstantiated)
 reports claim that non-voice (Internet, other data, fax) traffic now accounts for fully half of the traffic
 carried on the local network.<P></P>

		The process of rationalizing access charges may begin in the Commission's
 ongoing interconnection and universal service rulemakings.  However, the FCC is likely to initiate a
 rulemaking on access charge reform at the end of 1996 or early 1997.  This will be a difficult and
 contentious proceeding.  Currently, the access charges are well above incremental cost levels to 
subsidize local telephone service.<P></P>

		 New entrants into the local market will target this lucrative market, putting 
downward pressure on these charges.  Local telephone companies are likely to respond to this price
 pressure by reducing their access charges and trying to increase their subscriber line charges. 
 Increases in these subscriber line charges may be politically unpalatable to the Commission and 
Congress.  There will be significant pressure to find additional funds to ease these financial and 
political tensions.  The potential fees from Internet services -- data as well as voice -- will be extremely
 tempting targets to many.  <P></P>

		In addition, it is in the interests of both local exchange companies and most 
interexchange carriers to subject the Internet to the same interconnection charges currently paid 
by long distance carriers.  The local exchange companies view the rapidly expanding Internet traffic
 as a welcome source of new revenues.  Some local exchange companies will want to impose the 
regulation-based interconnection fees on Internet services.<P></P>

		The long distance companies that now pay 40%-50% of revenues for local access
 fees will urge that Internet services shoulder some of the obligations of supporting the local network.
  Even long distance companies that support, and profit from the Internet, will be tempted to use the
 regulatory disparity as a central argument for why they should be given cost-based interconnection
 charges.  Indeed, some long distance companies will strive to use the Internet's "free market"
 interconnection for traditional PSTN services.<P></P>
		To conclude, the potential imposition of access charges poses a far greater
 threat to Internet telephony, and to other Internet services, than the ACTA attempt to require common 
carrier regulation.<P></P>

<H4>INTERNATIONAL INTERNET VOICE ISSUES</H4><P></P>

<H4>International Issues</H4><P></P>

		While the growth of the Internet is explosive throughout the world, the Internet
 (much less discussion of Internet regulation) is generally much less developed in most other countries.
  Since the Internet is inherently an international service, there are many difficult issues to be resolved
 on an international scale.<P></P>

		In the United States, there are many alternatives to obtain leased lines for the
 Internet network.  However, in most foreign countries, these leased lines are available primarily
 (or solely) from the monopoly operator.  Eventually, there will be additional sources of leased lines
 for Internet service as competition is introduced in more countries throughout the world.<P></P>

		Collection rates (end-user rates) for traditional long distance telephone service
 are much higher in most foreign countries than in the United States.  Therefore, the incentives to use
 Internet voice service to bypass the public switched telephone network are substantially greater than
 in the United States.  <P></P>

		Many foreign carriers will be quite concerned if Internet telephony becomes a
 viable and prevalent means of bypass.  Carriers with monopolies on traditional voice services will
 probably try to stop the development of Internet telephony.  In addition, most foreign carriers will be
 quite concerned about any bypass of the international accounting rate system, since they have relied
 on these funds as a critical source of revenue.  <P></P>

<H4>Specific Countries</H4><P></P>

<H4>Switzerland</H4><P></P>

		In July 1995, the Swiss Office of Communications issued a decision stating
 that it saw no need at that time to regulate Internet voice services given its nascent nature.<P></P>
<H4>Canada</H4><P></P>

		The Internet telephony issue was recently raised in Canada
.  A telecommunications ruling officer with the Canadian Radio-television and 
Telecommunications Commission has reportedly indicated informally that an ISP
 providing Internet telephony service would be regulated by the Canadian Telecommunications
 Act, and would be subject to regulation-based interconnection charges.  <P></P>
<P></P>

<P></blockquote><P><hr><P>Copyright 1996 Steptoe & Johnson LLP <blockquote><P>
