<html><head><title>Steven Reed</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Steven Reed</h2>
<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/ferc.htm">Energy Regulation</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/transpt2.htm">Transportation Law</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/apellate.htm">Appellate Practice </a>
<br><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/taxprac.htm">State Business Taxation</a></center></blockquote>
<hr>


<P>Steve Reed's primary focus lies in the area of energy regulation,
especially on those aspects of the oil and gas industry regulated
by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.  In particular, he
has participated in representing major oil pipelines in matters
before the FERC and the courts of appeals and is co-author of an
article summarizing the effects of the FERC's recent oil pipeline
regulatory reform efforts.  He also has substantial experience
with various forms of alternative dispute resolution, including
arbitration and ADR mini trials.</P>

<P>Mr. Reed has represented a number of major companies in tax
disputes with various states, particularly those involving
federal constitutional or statutory dimensions.  He has
participated in three U.S. Supreme Court cases involving state
taxation of interstate business, has testified before a number of
state legislative committees on that subject, and recently co-
authored an article in The Tax Lawyer on the subject of equal
protection limitations on state taxation of interstate business.
</P>
<P>Mr. Reed worked as a reporter for the Nashville Banner, covering
state and local government, before attending law school.  Upon
graduation from law school, he was a law clerk to Judge Levin H.
Campbell, in the United States Court of Appeals for the First
Circuit.</P>

<P></p><ul><LI>Harvard University J.D. magna cum laude, 1979
Editor, Harvard Law Review
<LI>Harvard University A.B. magna cum laude, 1974
Phi Beta Kappa</ul><hr>
