<html><head><title>Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-1>LLP</font> Recruiting</head></title>
<h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-1>LLP</font><p>Recruiting</h3>
<h2 align=center>Firm Description</h2>

<h3 align=center>Overview</h3>

<P>

Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> is a Washington, D.C.-based law firm with an expanding office in Phoenix, Arizona and an affiliate in Moscow, Russia.  Although Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> is a diverse institution, with more than 200 attorneys from all regions of the country, its attorneys share a common firm culture that emphasizes two primary goals:  (1) the pursuit of excellence in the practice of law at the most challenging levels and (2)preservation of a cooperative, supportive atmosphere.<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>Practice Of The Firm</h3>

<P>

The distinctive characteristic of Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font>'s practice -- whether litigation, counseling or transactional matters -- is that it reflects the impact of policy and emerging economic, political and social trends on the law.  Our objective is to draw on the creativity of individual attorneys to solve particularly difficult legal problems.  Our attorneys regularly appear as counsel in cases of substantial national or industry importance, and Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> is widely recognized as one of the nation's leading firms in a number of highly visible legal specialties.  We have an active appellate practice, including frequent appearances before the Supreme Court of the United States.  We also have an extensive pro bono program.<P>

<P>

A short sampling of our attorneys' recent activities include:<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of witness in the Whitewater investigation<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of Burlington Northern Railroad Company on a variety of matters, including their recent application for merger which created the nation's largest railroad<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of a major foreign air carrier in a reciprocal investment arrangement with a U.S. airline<P>

<P>

&#183;	defense of the company operating the Trans Alaska Pipeline System in &quot;whistleblower&quot; litigation<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of major industry participants in criminal price-fixing suits and related class actions<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of Resolution Trust Corporation in its formation of two private/public sector partnerships and in the partnerships' acquisitions of portfolios of complex loan and real estate assets with an aggregate book value of $3.5 billion  <P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of numerous taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service and in the Federal courts with respect to a variety of tax issues, including the threatened revocation of exemption of a major non-profit organization<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of lenders and developers in a variety of transactional and litigation matters relating to real estate, financial restructurings and bankruptcy<P>

<P>

&#183;	negotiation of more than $1.5 billion in refinancings of government-backed debt<P>

<P>

&#183;	negotiation of joint ventures and other business arrangements with parties in the former Soviet Union<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of the Canadian Forest Industries Council in countervailing duty litigation before the Department of Commerce, the International Trade Commission and Bi-National Panels established under the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of the government of Bulgaria in its GATT accession sessions<P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of a major law firm threatened with disqualification of its retirement plan<P>

<P>

&#183;	defense of a wide range of defendants -- including lawyers, accountants, appraisers and others -- in professional malpractice litigation <P>

<P>

&#183;	representation of major defense contractors under civil and criminal investigation<P>

 <P>

&#183;	assisting multinational real estate conglomerate in connection with U.S. tax consequences of bankruptcy workout.<P>

<P>

Our representations frequently require originality because they involve issues not previously settled by the courts.  In addition, our cases often demand substantial analysis of public policy or economic issues.  <P>

<P>

The firm maintains an active practice before the Supreme Court, where our cases often make new law. The firm has been successful at the Court in defending an employer's affirmative action hiring plan against a challenge brought by a white plaintiff; in arguing that the Equal Protection Clause limits tax discrimination against out-of-state companies; and in defining the availability of punitive damages under ERISA.  We also handle a substantial number of certiorari petitions, oppositions, and briefs amicus curiae in the Supreme Court.<P>

<P>

As a Washington-based firm, we regularly advise our clients regarding the interpretation and impact of proposed or newly-promulgated federal regulations and new statutory provisions.  In addition, we encounter many novel legal issues first in nonjudicial settings -- in counseling, in legislative and in transactional contexts.  For example, we are counsel to corporations and others in a variety of congressional settings, and our white collar crime specialists find themselves conducting internal corporate investigations here and abroad.  Our employment lawyers counsel on AIDS testing and equal opportunity issues before those issues reach the courts.  <P>

<HR>
<P>Our representations frequently require originality because they involve issues not previously settled by the courts.<P>

<HR>
<P>

	We take a long-term strategic approach to the development of our practice.  A number of Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> attorneys counsel a wide variety of clients, both foreign and domestic, on major international trade and business issues.  We have a Moscow affiliate -- Steptoe &amp; Johnson International -- with a significant practice specializing in trade and corporate transactional work in the former Soviet Union and in Eastern Europe. <P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>Firm Organization</h3>

<P>

For administrative purposes, the firm's Washington-based practice is organized into eight broad practice groups which include:  (1) energy, environment; (2) transportation; (3) transactions, including corporate, securities, financial services, real estate, intellectual property and East/West investment; (4) tax and ERISA;
(5) international; (6) antitrust; (7) insurance, employment and commercial litigation; and (8) technology, contracts and crimes.<P>

 <P>

Attorneys frequently divide their time among several of the eight groups.  This loose structure fits our practice and philosophy better than would strict departmentalization.  Incoming associates initially are assigned to one of the eight practice groups, based on their interests and the firm's needs, with an option to spend a portion of their time in a second group.  Many new associates wish to gain exposure to a variety of practice experiences before beginning to specialize, and we think it is important to accommodate that desire.  The firm does not have a formal rotation system, but associates may periodically shift from one practice group to another.<P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>Associate Training and Evaluation</h3>

<P>

The introduction of new associates to the firm is not left to good intention and chance.  A new associate's first steps are guided by a more senior associate who serves as an advisor.  The advisor monitors work assignments, provides information about the firm's practice, and offers insight into the way the firm operates.  The advisor ensures that the new associate gets started on the right foot and begins to feel at home as quickly as possible.<P>

<P>

The group system is designed to allow associates to develop expertise and assume new responsibilities at a steady pace.  It is our objective to give associates as much responsibility as they can handle at as early a stage as possible.  This includes dealing directly with clients, conducting oral and document discovery, drafting pleadings and appearing before courts and agencies.<P>

<P>

	To foster professional growth, we conduct a comprehensive in-house training program covering a full range of lawyering skills.  The program includes seminars and workshops designed specifically for new attorneys, as well as training activities open to all Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> lawyers.  The training program includes in-depth workshops coordinated by outside experts on topics such as negotiating techniques, deposition skills and trial advocacy, as well as seminars on client relations, legal ethics, legal writing, business development and similar topics.  Use of the firm's videotaping equipment and extensive library of video training tapes enhances many of these programs.<P>

<P>

<HR><P>
The group system is designed to allow associates to develop expertise and assume new responsibilities at a steady pace.<P>

<HR>

<P>

	In addition to this firm-wide training program, each practice group sponsors training programs relevant to its areas of expertise.  An associate may supplement these in-house practice group programs by attending outside Continuing Legal Education seminars.  Each associate meets semi-annually with the Deputy Manager of his or her group and the Chair or Vice Chair of the Associates Committee, to focus on career development issues that are relevant to that individual associate.<P>

<P>

Each associate annually receives a formal written evaluation of his or her professional progress; in addition, the firm gives each new associate an informal review a few months after arrival.  These evaluations are based on the assessments of all the lawyers for whom the associate has performed significant work during the year; the results are communicated directly to the associate both orally and in writing.  Through the evaluation process, the firm makes a conscious effort to identify and fill gaps in professional experience and to respond to associates' changes in interest and developing expertise.  Evaluations in the sixth and seventh years include a careful and candid assessment of each associate's partnership prospects.  Decisions regarding election to partnership ordinarily are made in the eighth year after law school graduation.<P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>Fostering Diversity</h3>

<P>

It has always been Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font>'s goal to hire a diverse group of interesting individuals who are excellent attorneys.  Our attorneys hail from more than fifty different law schools, both U.S. and foreign, and many have had significant careers before joining the firm -- as journalists, business executives, and academics, including professors of English, political science, foreign languages and philosophy. <P>

<P>

	Being a good lawyer is hard work, and we work hard at it.  Nonetheless, many of our lawyers continue to pursue varied interests outside the law.  Our firm includes a playwright with hit productions on Broadway.  Our lawyers also play leading roles in civic, charitable and professional organizations.<P>

<P>

	We are as proud of our accomplishments outside the office as of our victories in the legal arena.  Sharing the rich diversity of our experiences -- both at work and outside the office environment -- increases substantially the rewards associated with the practice of law and contributes to the collegial and informal atmosphere that characterizes Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font>.<P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>Commitment to Equal Opportunity</h3>

<P>

Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> strives to make a reality of its strong philosophical commitment to equal opportunity.  The firm is a charter signatory to the Policy Statement Regarding Minority Hiring and Retention of the District of Columbia Conference on Opportunities for Minorities in the Legal Profession; the firm participates in several minority clerkship programs and engages in a variety of outreach programs in an effort to attract minority candidates. The firm has a high percentage of women partners. <P>

<P>
<h3 align=center>Pro Bono and Community Activities</h3>

<P>

Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> has a strong tradition of pro bono representation and takes seriously the obligation in the Code of Professional Responsibility to provide free legal services to those in need.  <P>

<P>

Our organizational structure includes a Public Service Counsel -- an attorney whose full time responsibility is to oversee our Public Service Program, including the development and staffing of pro bono matters within the firm.  Our Public Service Counsel also represents Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> in the pro bono legal community, actively working with the District of Columbia Bar Association and various providers of legal services to broaden the scope of pro bono participation by the legal community.<P>

<P>

Our Public Service Counsel, together with our Public Service Committee, develops policy for our pro bono practice and reviews and evaluates proposed and ongoing pro bono activities.  Participation in the Public Service Program by Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> attorneys is broad-based, and cases are staffed by partners and associates from all of our practice groups.  Many of our attorneys initiate projects in areas in which they have a personal or professional interest.  Our program is also enriched by the fact that attorneys from differing practice areas often work collectively on pro bono matters, bringing their varying perspectives and expertise to the case.  In addition, the firm offers a series of speaker forums and arranges for training covering a wide spectrum of pro bono activities.<P>

<P>

	Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> is a charter signatory to the American Bar Association Law Firm Challenge, designed to enhance the public service commitment among the nation's largest law firms.  As a charter signatory to this initiative, Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> has pledged to devote five percent of the firm's billable hours to pro bono representations; to enlist the majority of both partners and associates in the firm's Public Service Program; and to continue to direct the majority of our pro bono efforts toward providing legal services to persons of limited means or on behalf of organizations in matters primarily designed to assist persons of limited means.  In addition, Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> is fully involved in the public service activities of the District of Columbia Bar Association.<P>

<P>

	Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font>'s efforts have been recognized by numerous public service organizations.  The District of Columbia Bar Association awarded the firm its Annual Pro Bono Award for 1993, the highest honor given to a law firm for its public service commitment.  In addition, Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font>, either as an institution or through its individual attorneys, has been recognized in recent years by the International Human Rights Law Group, the Washington Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights and Urban Affairs, the Washington Area Lawyers for the Arts and the Service Members Legal Defense Network. <P>

<P>The types of pro bono cases handled at the firm are varied, and have included representation of:<P>

<P>

&#183;	several law school graduates previously involved in criminal activity, in an effort to show current moral suitability for admission to the Bar<P>

<P>

&#183;	a parents' advocacy group in an action to remedy rampant fire code violations throughout the local public school system<P>

<P>

&#183;	political refugees from a number of countries in their applications for political asylum<P>

<P>

&#183;	a number of individuals and classes of individuals in sex and race discrimination claims.<P>

<P>

Many Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> attorneys and staff are participating in an adopt-a-school program through which the firm is assisting local school children and their families with legal, social service and educational services.<P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>Summer Associate Program</h3>

<P>

The summer associate program is one of the most important elements of the firm's recruitment effort.  If you receive an offer to join us as a summer associate, we have made an initial judgment that you can make a valuable contribution to the firm's work.  A significant portion of our associate hiring each year comes from the summer associate group of previous years, and a high percentage of our former summer associates who enter private practice in Washington return to the firm.<P>

<P>

	We make every effort to give our summer associates a rounded view of Washington law practice.  Summer associate assignments are designed to provide a variety of substantive work and the broadest possible exposure to our lawyers.  In order to help ensure that these assignments match the work preferences of our summer associates, we have adopted an &quot;open book&quot; system, a notebook of assignments from which summer associates may, with a minimum of guidance, choose their own projects.  <P>

<P>

	In addition, over the summer we keep a special calendar of trials, arguments, depositions, negotiations and other legal activities in which the firm is involved, and we encourage summer associates to attend as many of these events as possible.  We host weekly seminars which cover the firm's organization, its practice, and other matters of topical interest, with presentations by speakers both inside and outside of the firm.  We also try to give our summer associates direct exposure to those institutions that make Washington unique -- the Supreme Court, the Congress and the executive agencies.  <P>

<P>

	It is important to us that we get to know our summer associates not just within the office environment, but also in more informal settings.  To that end, we sponsor a varied program of events, ranging from sailing to theater parties, at which summer associates have the chance to get acquainted with firm attorneys as well as with one another.<P>

<P>

The firm offers a program which provides a number of our summer associates the opportunity to spend a portion of their summer working for public interest organizations in Washington, D.C.  As part of the Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> Summer Public Service Program, second-year law students are sponsored by the firm to spend four weeks with a public service group in an area of interest to them after completing eight weeks as a summer associate at the firm.<P>

<P>

How well our summer associate program succeeds is best judged by those who have been in it, and we strongly encourage you to talk with former program participants.<P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>Firm Management</h3>

<P>

The firm has an exceptionally democratic governance structure.  Membership on major firm committees rotates regularly so that important policy questions are decided on a broadly representative basis.  In addition, associates at all levels play an active role in many aspects of the firm's administration through membership on firm committees.  Approximately thirty associates currently serve on key firm committees, including the Hiring, Associates, and Professional Training Committees.<P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>The Phoenix Office</h3>

<P>

Since opening in 1987, Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font>'s Phoenix office has expanded its practice significantly and currently has 25 attorneys serving clients in the Southwest.  The Phoenix office has a broad-based practice, including business transactions, commercial and employment litigation, media and communications law, water rights and environmental law and real estate development and finance.  In addition to Arizona matters, Phoenix office attorneys are involved in regional and national cases as well, often working closely with their Washington colleagues in areas in which the firm has established a national reputation, such as government contracts law and sophisticated insurance coverage disputes.<P>

<P>

	Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> in Phoenix is neither a free-standing branch operation nor merely an extension of the firm's original Washington base.  The office manages its own representations and staffing requirements but also is intimately involved in the work of the firm as a whole.  Phoenix partners serve on the firm's Executive Committee and on the committee which recommends the selection of new partners.  Phoenix partners and associates serve on the firm's Associates Committee and Professional Training Committee.  Associates joining the firm in Phoenix can expect to deal with a variety of transactional, counseling and litigation matters.  Given the office's relatively small size, associates have the opportunity to work on a wide range of matters and rapidly assume substantial responsibilities.  Like their colleagues in Washington, Phoenix associates have access to the firm's extensive research and in-house training resources, and receive detailed annual evaluations to assist them in understanding their strengths as well as areas that require additional attention.<P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>The Moscow Affiliate</h3>

<P>

In early 1990, Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> became the first U.S. law firm to form a joint venture with a group of private Russian attorneys to provide legal services in the former Soviet Union.  Subsequently reorganized as &quot;Steptoe &amp; Johnson International,&quot; this affiliate represents U.S. and other clients engaged in business in the republics constituting the former Soviet Union and in Eastern Europe.  The affiliate has both Russian and American attorneys in Moscow.<P>

<P>

Supported by the firm's strong international trade and investment practice in Washington, Steptoe &amp; Johnson International assists clients in activities ranging from sales of goods or technology to participation in sophisticated investment arrangements.   Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> attorneys negotiate investment and financing agreements, seek the development and  reform of both countries' investment and trade laws and guide clients through the maze of rapidly evolving U.S. and republic regulations applicable to investment in the former Soviet Union.<P>

<P>

	Using the Moscow affiliate as a springboard, the firm is expanding its services throughout Central and Eastern Europe.<P>

<P>

<P>

<h3 align=center>General Information and Benefits</h3>

<P>

The firm interviews applicants at approximately twenty law school campuses and conducts regional interviews throughout the country.  In addition, we solicit resumes from interested students through the placement directors at dozens of other law schools. <P>

<P>

Letters of inquiry are answered within two or three weeks.  After initial interviews at law schools, the Hiring Committee extends invitations to visit Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> at the firm's expense.  We prefer not to make a hiring decision until we have had a chance to review an applicant's law school transcript, and we therefore request an unofficial copy of the transcript from all candidates as a routine matter.<P>

<P>

Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> seeks to maintain salaries and benefits for both associates and summer associates that are competitive with those offered by other major Washington-based firms.  Summer associates receive an allowance for travel expenses.  Incoming attorneys are reimbursed for household moving and travel expenses in accordance with a policy that is available on request.  Incoming attorneys just graduating from law school who will be starting work shortly after completion of the District of Columbia bar exam, or of another bar exam on which an application for waiver into the D.C. Bar may be based, also receive a stipend to assist with bar review, living and other expenses while preparing for the exam.<P>

<P>

We welcome your applications and inquiries.  Please address them to our Director of Associate Services and Recruiting, Rosemary Kelly Morgan.  <P>

Spring 1996<P>






