<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/FERC Regulatory Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>FERC Regulatory Practice</CENTER>
</H2>


<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have participated in a wide variety of regulatory
proceedings before the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission
(FERC) since the creation of that agency in 1977, as well as
before the FERC's predecessors, the Federal Power Commission
(FPC) and the Interstate Commerce Commission (ICC).

<h4><CENTER>Oil Pipeline Proceedings </CENTER></h4>

<P>Beginning with the ICC's rulemaking and adjudicatory proceedings
that ultimately led to the issuance of the FERC's Opinion 154-B
ratemaking guidelines, Steptoe & Johnson LLP has been an active
participant in the rapidly evolving area of oil pipeline
regulation.  This has included key roles in the major
proceedings involving pipelines both in Alaska and in the
lower-48 states.  In addition to counseling numerous pipeline
companies with respect to applicable law and FERC policies, the
firm has participated in such litigated matters as the
following:  

<H4><CENTER>Trans Alaska Pipeline System (TAPS)</CENTER></H4>
Steptoe & Johnson LLP has
participated in virtually all phases of the legal disputes
involving the construction of TAPS and the litigation over the
TAPS rates, including, for numerous specific aspects of the case,
as lead counsel on behalf of all of the TAPS owners.  In
particular, Steptoe & Johnson LLP served as lead counsel in the
cost-of-service phase of the TAPS case before the FERC, and in
the related portion of the Alaska Public Utilities Commission
(APUC) proceeding.  Once the TAPS settlement was announced,
Steptoe & Johnson LLP took a primary role in securing its approval,
both before the FERC and before the APUC.

<P>More recently, the firm has represented the TAPS owners in
defending against the prudency challenge relating to the
inclusion in rates of the costs to repair the significant
corrosion experienced on the pipeline.  That matter involved the
use of an innovative <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/alternat.htm">Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR)</a> procedure, designed to avoid what would otherwise be a lengthy
and expensive FERC hearing on the merits.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP is
also currently representing a group of TAPS owners in contesting
a proposed connection to the TAPS system, and is representing
one of the owners with respect to the permissibility of a
surcharge imposed on oil shipped from certain fields serving the
pipeline.


<H4><CENTER>Lakehead Pipeline Company, Limited Partnership</CENTER></H4>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP is representing Lakehead, which is part of the
world's longest and most complex oil pipeline system, in the
defense of Lakehead's first rate increase in nine years.  The
proceeding appears likely to involve a number of highly
significant issues, including those raised by a group of
protesting Canadian oil producers.  The case was
heard in May, 1993.

<H4><CENTER>Tecumseh Pipe Line Company</CENTER></H4>

<P>The firm recently represented Tecumseh in its first-ever rate
proceeding.  The case involved cost of service, rate design, and
other important issues, several of which had not previously been
raised in any FERC oil pipeline matter.  The case was settled
just prior to going to hearing in June, 1992.

<H4><CENTER>Kuparuk Transportation Company (KTC)</CENTER></H4>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has
served as outside counsel for KTC throughout the more than seven
years that KTC's initial rate case was litigated before the FERC
and the APUC.  KTC, which is a partnership made up of
subsidiaries of ARCO, BP/Sohio and Unocal, operates a crude oil
pipeline on the North Slope of Alaska, connecting to TAPS. 
KTC's interstate rate case resulted in a Commission decision on
a range of significant issues under the Opinion 154-B
methodology.  Subsequently, the case was settled by KTC and the
contesting parties at the FERC and APUC (where approval of the
settlement remains pending).

<H4><CENTER>ARCO Pipe Line Company (APL)</CENTER></H4>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has served as
outside counsel for APL in the FERC proceedings involving APL's
lower-48 crude and petroleum products tariff rates.  The first
of these ended in Commission rulings that APL's rates for its
crude and products systems were just and reasonable under the
governing cost-based methodology.  The second, which involved
the threshold issue whether APL had market power regarding its
products system tariffs, was terminated in 1991 after the
challenging shippers withdrew from the case.  

<H4><CENTER>Four Corners Pipe Line Company</CENTER></H4>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP served as
outside counsel for Four Corners in a rate case before the FERC
that was initiated in late 1986.  The case ended in August 1987,
by a stipulated dismissal of the Commission's investigation
after the presentation of Four Corners' case-in-chief.

<H4><CENTER>Point Arguello Pipeline Company (PAPCO)</CENTER></H4>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP served as co-counsel for PAPCO in its initial rate case, which
was filed in early 1988.  PAPCO is a partnership of eleven
corporations, including affiliates of Chevron, Phillips, ARCO,
Texaco and others, that constructed an oil pipeline and related
facilities to transport oil from platforms off the coast of
California to a terminal near Santa Barbara.  

<h4><CENTER>Natural Gas and Other Proceedings</CENTER></h4>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP is regularly involved in a variety of FERC
matters covering all aspects of the Commission's jurisdiction. 
For example, the firm has been involved in simultaneous
certificate and abandonment applications in which a pipeline and
producer sought to revamp their long-standing contractual
relationship.  The firm also has represented a lender in
connection with the transfer of a permit to operate a
hydroelectric power facility, and the refinancing of the project.

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represented one of the major participants in
the FERC's "Northeast open season" proceeding in which a variety
of pipelines were seeking permission to expand natural gas
pipeline capacity in the Northeastern United States.  The firm's
activity covered both regulatory and antitrust aspects of this
complex matter.

<P>In addition to FERC representations, Steptoe & Johnson LLP's energy
regulatory work frequently involves matters outside the
Commission, including litigated proceedings -- both in federal
and state trial and appellate courts.  

<h4><CENTER>Partners With Substantial FERC Experience</CENTER></h4>

<P>The following Steptoe & Johnson LLP partners have had substantial
involvement in energy matters before the FERC and other
agencies: 

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/jordan.htm">Robert E. Jordan III</a> -- Mr. Jordan served as lead counsel for ARCO Pipe Line Company in Phase I of the TAPS proceeding, in the
ground-breaking Williams Pipe Line case, and in related
proceedings involving the FERC's overall oil pipeline ratemaking
methodology.  Mr. Jordan is past President of the District of
Columbia Bar.  He is a graduate of the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology and Harvard Law School.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/brose.htm">Steven H. Brose</a> -- Mr. Brose has served as lead counsel for the
pipeline in the Lakehead, ARCO Pipe Line, and Kuparuk cases, as
well as in a variety of TAPS matters.  He also has broad
experience in FERC proceedings involving natural gas regulation.
 Mr. Brose is on the Council of the Section on Public Utility,
Communications and Transportation Law of the American Bar
Association, and is the Chair of the Oil Pipelines Committee of
that section.  He is a past member of the Executive Committee of
the Federal Energy Bar Association, and has served on the
Editorial Board of the Energy Law Journal.  He is a frequent
speaker on oil pipeline and natural gas issues at
industry seminars and other programs.  Mr. Brose is a graduate of
Pennsylvania State University and Columbia Law School, and
served as a judicial law clerk at the United States Court of
Appeals for the Second Circuit.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/walsh.htm">Timothy M. Walsh</a> -- Mr. Walsh has served as lead counsel in the
Tecumseh and Four Corners rate proceedings.  He was also an
active participant in the TAPS rate proceeding before both the
FERC and the APUC, concentrating on economic regulation issues. 
Mr. Walsh has been involved in a number of other FERC matters on
behalf of ARCO Pipe Line Company and its affiliates, including
the Williams Pipe Line case and the Court of Appeals' review of
Opinion 154.  He is a graduate of Stanford University and Yale
Law School.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/reed.htm">Steven Reed</a> -- Mr. Reed has been a primary participant in all of
the oil pipeline and natural gas proceedings discussed above,
including playing an active role in the TAPS, Lakehead and
Kuparuk cases, and in both of the major proceedings involving
APL.  Mr. Reed is a graduate of Harvard College and Harvard Law
School, and served as a judicial law clerk at   the United
States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit. 
<p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>
