<html><head><title>Philip L. Malet Bio</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>
Philip L. Malet</h2>

<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/commprac.htm">Telecommunications</a></center></blockquote>





<P>Phil Malet has a broad regulatory and litigation practice, with a substantial focus on international telecommunications, high technology and satellites.

<P>Mr. Malet has represented domestic and international satellite operators, telephone companies, cellular radio operators and manufacturers, corporate telecommunications users, pay telephone companies, fiber optic cable licensees, broadcast licensees and electric utilities in matters before the Federal Communications Commission and in court.  He has advised cable companies and municipalities on regulatory matters affecting cable television, and has negotiated major construction contracts for cable systems and programmers.  In addition, he continues to advise foreign companies on U.S. telecommunications policy issues.  Mr. Malet's clients include Motorola, Inc. with regard to all regulatory
matters relating to its Iridium satellite system, and EchoStar Satellite Corp., a Direct Broadcast Satellite company.

<P>Mr. Malet also has a substantial litigation practice representing both plaintiffs and defendants in the federal and local courts and before regulatory agencies.  He has litigated cases involving a wide range of commercial disputes, including complex issues in the fields of antitrust, consumer protection,  telecommunications, franchise law and RICO.  

<P>Mr. Malet authored a treatise on state unfair and deceptive trade practices (Little FTC Acts) published by Matthew Bender in its Business Torts compendium. 

<P>Mr. Malet was an Attorney Advisor at the Federal Communications Commission, Review Board, 1979-80.  Between 1975-79, he served as its chief engineer advisor.

<P>Mr. Malet is a member of the Federal Communications Bar Association, the District of Columbia Bar, and several federal district and appellate courts.

