<html><head><title>COMPLIANCE WITH CALEA:THE COMMUNICATIONS ASSISTANCE FOR LAW ENFORCEMENT ACT OF 1994</title></head>

<body><H2 align=center>Compliance With Calea: The Communications Assistance For Law Enforcement Act of 1994</H2>



<blockquote><center>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> and <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/smithcli.htm">Clint Smith</a></center></blockquote>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>

<blockquote><center><a href="#exsum">Executive Summary</a>  |  <a href="#over">Overview of CALEA</a> </CENTER></blockquote>
<hr>
<H3><a name="exsum">Executive Summary</a></H3>

<h4>Who Is Affected</H4>

<P>While the Act applies principally to telecommunications carriers, defined broadly as any party "engaged in the transmission or switching of wire or electronic communications for hire," the Act will also have serious implications for vendors supplying these carriers with equipment and services.


<h4>Obligations of Telecommunications Carriers</H4>

<P>To comply with the Act's "capability" requirements, telecommunications carriers must ensure that, to the extent "reasonably achievable," their equipment and facilities:
<ol><LI>allow the government to intercept wire and electronic communications carried on their services;<P>
<LI>allow the government to collect reasonably available caller identification information;<P>
<LI>can deliver intercepted communications and caller identification information to the government in a form that allows the government to retransmit that information;<P>
<LI>can facilitate authorized surveillance unobtrusively and with minimum interference, so that the surveillance target is unaware of the surveillance.</ol><P>
<P>To comply with the Act's "capacity" requirements, telecommunications carriers must ensure that they make available sufficient capacity to satisfy government surveillance needs.  Guidance on the extent of the government's needs will be periodically published by the Attorney General, starting in October 1995.
To comply with the Act's "privacy" requirements, telecommunications carriers must adopt in-house controls to minimize the potential for unauthorized intercepts by employees or law enforcement.


<h4>Obligations of Equipment Manufacturers</H4>

<P>The Act also imposes obligations on "manufacturers of telecommunications transmission and switching equipment" and "support service providers," who must:
<ol><LI>consult with carriers to ensure that all current and proposed equipment will meet the government's surveillance requirements; and<P>
<LI>make available equipment, facilities, services, features, or modifications to carriers at a reasonable charge and on a reasonably timely basis, to facilitate carrier compliance with the government's requirements.</OL>

<P>In spite of these relatively modest obligations, equipment manufacturers will bear much of the burden of the Act because purchasers will demand equipment that ensures compliance with the Act's capability and capacity requirements.



<h4>Compliance Procedures</H4>

<P>The Act provides several avenues for companies to determine if their equipment, facilities, or services are in compliance with the government's requirements:<P>	
<ol><LI><I>Industry Standards</I>:  An industry association or standard-setting organization can issue standards for carrier compliance with the Act.  Compliance with these standards would be deemed to meet the statutory requirements, unless the standards are challenged.<P>
<LI><I>FCC Standards</I>:  A government official or private party can challenge industry standards as deficient.  If the industry standards are challenged, or if no such standards are issued for a given product or service, the FCC can establish compliance standards by rulemaking.<P>
<LI><I>Self-Assessment</I>:  A company could make a self-assessment of compliance, but assume the risk of a Justice Department enforcement action in federal court.<P>
<LI><I>FBI Approval</I>:  A company could also seek informal (or perhaps even formal) reassurance from the FBI.  Discussing compliance directly with the FBI would minimize the risk of a subsequent enforcement action and avoid a public FCC proceeding.</ol><P>

<h4>Government Reimbursement of Compliance Costs</H4>

<P>Subject to the availability of appropriations, the Attorney General may agree to pay carriers certain costs directly associated with modifications to retrofit existing equipment.  The Attorney General is generally not required to reimburse compliance costs for equipment, facilities, or services deployed after January 1, 1995.	

<p><hr><p>
<H3><a name="over">CALEA Overview</a></H3>

<h4>Policy Background</H4>

	<P>In passing the Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement Act of 1994 ("CALEA," also referred to as the "Digital Telephony Act"), Congress responded to what FBI Director Louis Freeh characterized as an urgent law enforcement demand:  the preservation of law enforcement's ability to carry out authorized interceptions of personal communications irrespective of future technological advances.  CALEA intends to achieve this by requiring that, to the extent "reasonably achievable," telecommunications companies must design, build, and deploy equipment, facilities, and services that meet the government's surveillance requirements.

	<P>Prior to the 1990s, law enforcement could satisfy its surveillance requirements by putting alligator clips on wire telephone lines.  This required only minimal assistance from telephone common carriers, which were required to help law enforcement by the 1968 Omnibus Crime Control and Safe Streets Act ("1968 Act," the general federal wiretap statute).  In the early 1990s, though, law enforcement encountered difficulties intercepting cellular communications and communications that employed enhanced services such as call forwarding, voice-mail transfer, speed-dial, and voice-dial.  Law enforcement officials asked Congress for help.  Their battle cry:  advances in telecommunications technology could have the practical effect of repealing the 1968 Act that authorized law enforcement wiretaps.

	<P>CALEA is perhaps best understood as a new development in the government's long-standing policy of requiring assistance from private parties in the conduct of electronic surveillance.  The duty of private parties to assist the government existed in the common law, and has been codified by Congress in the 1968 Act, the 1978 Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act ("FISA"), and the 1986 Electronic Communications Privacy Act ("ECPA").  But by imposing system design requirements, CALEA moves beyond the prior statutes that required only occasional operational assistance.

	<P>The final form of CALEA, as discussed in this memorandum, reflects a compromise among the interests of the three primary groups affected by the legislation:  <P>
<ul>
<LI>Law enforcement and intelligence agencies interested in continued access to private communications.  <P>
<LI>Privacy advocates, such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation, interested in limiting or at least imposing accountability on the government's interception of private communications.  <P>
<LI>Industries concerned that law enforcement demands could impede or add costs to the development and introduction of new communication technologies and services.	</ul><P>
	<P>The government's compromise with industry is reflected chiefly in two aspects of CALEA.  First, CALEA's requirements cannot be enforced against a given company unless that company's compliance is "reasonably achievable," and law enforcement has no other means to conduct the surveillance.  Second, CALEA provides a mechanism for the government to reimburse a company's compliance costs in certain circumstances, primarily for the cost of "retrofitting" equipment now in use.  The government placated privacy groups principally by making concessions unrelated to the core legislation concessions that increase the privacy rights of cordless telephone users and on-line network services subscribers.

<h4>Overview of Who Must Comply with CALEA</H4>

	<P>CALEA imposes different obligations on two groups:<P>
<OL><LI>CALEA imposes on telecommunications common carriers clear and potentially burdensome obligations to assist government electronic surveillance;  and<P>
<LI>CALEA imposes on manufacturers and support service providers only a vague duty to consult with the carriers and provide appropriate equipment to carriers at reasonable cost.  However, as discussed below, these categories should not be seen as unrelated -- carriers who must comply with CALEA will require equipment manufacturers to provide them equipment that ensures the carriers' compliance with CALEA's requirements. </OL><P>



<h4>Obligations of Telecommunications Carriers:  Definition of Telecommunications  Carriers</H4>
	<P>CALEA applies most directly to telecommunications common carriers.  The statute defines telecommunications common carrier as any entity "engaged in the transmission or switching of wire or electronic communications as a common carrier for hire." CALEA <I> 102(8)(a), codified at 47 U.S.C. </I> 1001(8)(a).  Legislative history suggests that the two key criteria in determining whether a company is considered a telecommunications common carrier under CALEA are:  (1) whether the company's service is made available directly to end-users; and (2) whether the company's service accesses the public switched network. <a href="#note1">[Footnote 1]</a>  <a name="back1"></a>Legislative history further suggests that CALEA's definition of telecommunications common carrier includes a broad spectrum of communications services available to consumers and connected to the public switch network.<a href="#note2">[Footnote 2]</a><a name="back2"></a>

	<P>The statute itself specifies two entities that are to be treated as telecommunication common carriers.  First, any entity "engaged in providing commercial mobile service" is a telecommunications common carrier.<a href="#note3">[Footnote 3]</a>  <a name="back3"></a>Second, any entity that provides a switching or transmission service that the FCC considers "a replacement for a substantial portion of the local telephone exchange service" can be considered a telecommunications common carrier for purposes of CALEA if the FCC decides that it is in the public interest to do so.  CALEA <I>102(8)(a), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1001(8)(a).  This second provision, at least, would appear to go beyond the commonly understood definition of a communications common carrier.

	<P>Certain telecommunications service providers are specifically excluded from CALEA's definition of telecommunications common carriers.  Entities "insofar as they are engaged in providing information services," are not telecommunications common carriers.  CALEA <I> 102(8)(c)(i), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1001(8)(c)(i).<a href="#note4">[Footnote 4]</a>  <a name="back4"></a>Also, entities whose equipment, facilities, or services either "support the transport or switching of communications for private networks or for the sole purpose of interconnecting telecommunications carriers," are exempted from the most onerous requirements of CALEA.<a href="#note5">[Footnote 5]</a>  <a name="back5"></a>Furthermore, "any class or category of telecommunications carriers that the [FCC] exempts by rule after consultation with the Attorney General" will not be considered telecommunications common carriers for purposes of CALEA.  CALEA <I> 102(8)(c)(ii), codified at 47 U.S.C. </I> 1001(8)(c)(ii).
 
<h4>Obligations of  Telecommunications Common Carriers</H4>
	<P>CALEA imposes three types of obligation on telecommunications carriers:  capability requirements, capacity requirements, and privacy requirements.  The capability requirements are the most significant.  

<h4>Capability Requirements In General</H4>
<P>	CALEA generally requires telecommunications carriers to ensure that by October 25, 1998, the government is capable of intercepting communications and obtaining call-identifying information from their customers ("capability requirements").  CALEA  <I>103(a), codified at 47 U.S.C. </I> 1002(a).<a href="#note6">[Footnote 6]</a>  <a name="back6"></a>Specifically, to comply with the capability requirements, a telecommunication common carrier must ensure that any equipment, facilities, or services that provide a customer or subscriber the ability to originate, terminate, or direct a communication allow the government, when authorized, to:

<P>(a) intercept all wire and electronic communications to and from a customer, either concurrently with the communication or at such later time as may be acceptable to the government;

<P>(b) record call-identifying information "reasonably available" to the carrier in a manner that allows the information to be associated with a specific communication, either before, during, or immediately after the communication or at such later time as may be acceptable to the government.<a href="#note7">[Footnote 7]</a><a name="back7"></a>  

<P>(c) deliver intercepted communications and call identifying information to the government in a format such that the government can retransmit that information to a location other than the premises of the carrier;

<P>(d) facilitate the interception of communications and collection of call identifying information unobtrusively and with a minimum of interference with a subscriber's service.

	<P>These requirements require carriers to assist in the decryption of communications only if two specific conditions are met.  CALEA provides:  "A telecommunications carrier shall not be responsible for decrypting, or ensuring the government's ability to decrypt, any communication encrypted by a subscriber or customer, unless the encryption was provided by the carrier and the carrier possesses the information necessary to decrypt the communication." CALEA  <I>103(b)(3), codified at 47 U.S.C. </I> 1002(c)(3) (emphasis added).

<h4>Mobile Services</H4>
	<P>CALEA's capability requirements are modified slightly when applied to providers of mobile commercial services, as defined in Section 332(d) of the Communications Act of 1934, as amended, codified at <I>47 U.S.C. 332(d)</I>.  In addition to the obligations discussed above, carriers offering customers the ability to redirect, hand-off, or assign communications to another service area or another service provider must ensure that if the carrier loses access to a customer's communication or identifying information, the carrier can nonetheless identify the service provider that has acquired access to same.  CALEA  <I>103(d), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1002(d).

<h4>Capacity Requirements</H4>
	<P>A telecommunications common carrier must also ensure that it has available sufficient capacity to accommodate the government's law enforcement surveillance needs.  CALEA <I> 104, codified at 47 U.S.C. </I> 1003.  Legislative history suggests that these capacity requirements respond to law enforcement's concern that certain cellular systems with limited capacity were unable to accommodate a large number of intercepts simultaneously.  House Report at 14.  

	<P>No later than October 4, 1995, the Attorney General will publish an estimate of the maximum capacity required to accommodate all anticipated government interceptions, pen registers, and trap and trace devices.  CALEA requires that, to the extent practicable, the Attorney General identify the capacity required at specific geographic locations, and the capacity required based upon the type of equipment or service, the number of subscribers, the type or size of the carrier, and the nature of the service area.  CALEA  <I>104(a)(2), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1003(a)(2).  Thereafter, the Attorney General will periodically publish notices of any increased capacity requirements that the government anticipates.  Id. 

	<P>A telecommunications carrier subject to CALEA must respond to the Attorney General's notices within six months of their publication in the Federal Register to identify any of its systems or services that do not have the capacity the government may require.  CALEA <I> 104(d), codified at 47 U.S.C. </I> 1003(d).  Telecommunications carriers subject to CALEA must also ensure that, after October 1998, they can expeditiously accommodate the government's maximum capacity requirements, as estimated by the Attorney General.  CALEA  <I>104(b)(2), codified at 47 U.S.C. </I> 1003(b)(2).

	<P>Unlike the capability requirements, which are mandatory except when specific conditions are met, the capacity requirements are dependent on the availability of government reimbursement.  CALEA provides that until the Attorney General agrees to reimburse a carrier for the expansion of its capacity to meet the government's requirements, the carrier shall be considered in compliance with the capacity requirements.  CALEA <I>104(e), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1003(e).  This suggests that a carrier would have no obligation to comply with the capability requirements until the government agreed to pay the costs of compliance.

<h4>Privacy Requirements</H4>
	<P>CALEA requires telecommunications common carriers to adopt in-house controls to limit the potential for either law enforcement or the carrier's employees to conduct unauthorized intercepts.  CALEA <I> 105, codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1004.  Specifically, CALEA requires that in accordance with regulations to be issued by the FCC, a carrier must implement procedures to ensure that interceptions of communications or access to call-identifying information effected within the carrier's switching premises can only be obtained (1) in accordance with a court order or other lawful authorization, and, (2) with the affirmative intervention of an employee of the carrier.  CALEA at  <I>301, codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 229.  The purpose of this provision was to preclude the government from conducting automated remote surveillance.

<h4>Obligations of Equipment Manufacturers and Support Service Suppliers </H4>

	<P>Companies that supply support services or equipment to telecommunications common carriers also have obligations under CALEA.  CALEA imposes limited obligations on "manufacturers of telecommunications transmission and switching equipment," as well as "providers of telecommunication support services."<a href="#note8">[Footnote 8]</a><a name="back8"></a>

	<P>Manufacturers and support services providers must:   (a) consult with carriers to ensure that all current and proposed equipment, facilities, and services will meet the government's capability and capacity requirements; and (b) make available equipment, facilities, services, features, or modifications to carriers at a reasonable charge and on a reasonably timely basis, as necessary for the carrier to comply with CALEA's capability requirements.  CALEA <I>106, 107, codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1005, 1006.

	<P>The Attorney General can enforce these requirements through an order of a federal district court.  CALEA <I> 201(a), codified at 18 U.S.C.</I> 2522.  CALEA provides that the court "may direct that a provider of support services to the carrier or the manufacturer of the carrier's transmission or switching equipment furnish forthwith modifications necessary for the carrier to comply [with CALEA.]"  Id.  Failure to comply with the order could result in civil penalties of $10,000 per day.  Id.

	<P>While the direct statutory requirements imposed by CALEA on equipment manufacturers and support service providers are not great, the practical impact of CALEA is nonetheless significant to them.  CALEA's requirements are designed to flow from the retail telecommunications service providers through to other components of telecommunications systems, including equipment manufacturers.  Given the size of investments in telecommunications systems, neither equipment manufacturers nor carriers can afford to assume the risk that the common carrier will be found in violation of CALEA because of the underlying system's design.  Accordingly, the limited direct statutory obligations of equipment manufacturers should not lead an equipment manufacturer to disregard the requirements of the Act.

<h4>Procedures for Compliance with CALEA</H4>  

	<P>Providers of telecommunications services, especially new services, will have a pressing need to determine how they can comply with CALEA.  A company that is uncertain of the extent to which CALEA applies to its proposed service has at least three and possibly four options.  Under the statute,  the company can (1)  participate in industry-wide standards setting;  (2)  ask the FCC to decide how much compliance is "reasonably achievable;"  (3)  make an independent assessment of what is reasonably achievable, and live with the risk of a subsequent Justice Department enforcement action.  At least one further option seems likely to emerge as companies struggle to define their obligations under CALEA:  (4)  negotiate compliance directly with the Justice Department (and perhaps the FCC), leading to either a formal or informal settlement.  The appropriate avenue for achieving compliance will vary from company to company and industry to industry.

<h4>Industry or FCC Established Standards</H4>  
	<P>Industry associations and standard setting organizations, in consultation with law enforcement officials, are authorized to publish standards that they believe meet CALEA's requirements.  These standards constitute a "safe harbor" if carriers, manufacturers, or support service providers comply with the standards, they are deemed to have met the statutory requirements, at least until the standards are challenged and changed by the FCC.  CALEA <I>107(a), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I>  1006(a).

	<P>Any government agency or any private party can by petition to the FCC challenge the industry association's or standard-setting organization's standards as deficient.  If the industry standards are challenged, or if the private sector does not issue standards, the FCC can establish technical requirements or standards by rulemaking after consultation with the Attorney General.  CALEA <I>107(b), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1006(b).<a href="#note9">[Footnote 9]</a>    <a name="back9"></a>Compliance with standards established by the FCC would constitute compliance with CALEA.  Id.   

<h4>Company Specific FCC Standards</H4>
	<P>An individual company can petition the FCC to determine the extent to which the company must comply with CALEA's capability requirements.  With respect to equipment, facilities, and services deployed after January 1, 1995,<a href="#note10">[Footnote 10]</a> <a name="back10"></a>CALEA provides that, on petition from a company, the FCC will determine whether the company's compliance with CALEA's capability requirements is "reasonably achievable."  CALEA  <I>109(b), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1008(b).  The FCC should reach a determination of what is "reasonably achievable" within one year.  Id.   

	<P>The FCC's central inquiry in such a proceeding would be "whether compliance would impose significant difficulty or expense on the carrier or on the users of the carrier's systems."  Id.  The FCC will have discretion about how to weigh the following ten factors identified by Congress as relevant:<P>


<ol><LI>The effect on public safety and national security.<P>
<LI>The effect on rates for basic residential telephone service.<P>
<LI>The need to protect the privacy and security of  communications not authorized to be intercepted.<P>
<LI>The need to achieve the capability assistance requirements by cost-effective methods.<P>
<LI>The effect on the nature and cost of the equipment, facilities, or service at issue.<P>
<LI>The policy of the United States to encourage the provision of new technologies and services to the public.<P>
<LI>The financial resources of the telecommunications carrier.<P>
<LI>The effect on competition in the provision of telecommunications services.<P>
<LI>The extent to which the design and development of the equipment, facility, or service was initiated before January 1, 1995.<P>
<LI>Such other factors as the FCC deems appropriate.</ol><P>

	<P>If the FCC determines that compliance is not "reasonably achievable," the company may request the Attorney General to reimburse a portion of the company's anticipated costs of compliance.  If the Justice Department agrees to reimburse the company, it may not be required to pay the entire costs of compliance only the costs of getting the company to the "reasonably achievable" threshold, from which the company must pay its own way.  If the Justice Department does not agree to reimburse the company, the company is deemed to be in compliance with CALEA's capability requirements.    

<h4>Self-Assessment and Federal Court Enforcement</H4>
	<P>A company could also conduct a self-assessment of how much compliance with CALEA is "reasonably achievable."  But the company would remain exposed indefinitely to a Justice Department enforcement action, either an action for a court order authorizing government surveillance in a specific law enforcement investigation, or an enforcement action in district court unrelated to a specific surveillance need.  CALEA <I> 201(a), codified at 18 U.S.C.</I>  2522.  In either case, the court could only order compliance if the court found that:<p>
<ul><LI>alternative technologies or capabilities, or the facilities of another carrier, are not reasonably available to law enforcement; and<p>
<LI>compliance is reasonably achievable through the application of available technology to the equipment, facility, or service at issue, or would have been reasonably achievable if timely action had been taken.</ul><P>
	<P>This standard provides a defense to companies that believe their systems cannot be modified at a reasonable cost.  But a company's reliance on these defenses carries a high risk.  If the company invests in technology that does not comply with CALEA, and an alternative technology that the company did not use is later found to meet the "reasonably achievable" standard, the court could order the company to replace its equipment without reimbursement; the court might also order the company to suspend service until its system complied with CALEA. 
 
<h4>Company Specific Negotiated Settlements</H4>
	<P>Given the complexity of many new telecommunications services, a negotiated, company-specific compliance plan may well prove necessary in many cases.  Most companies will want a binding assurance in advance that their system or product's design is adequate for law enforcement's purposes.  The Federal Bureau of Investigation ("FBI"), the part of the Justice Department charged with enforcement of CALEA, has recently established a telecommunications industry liaison unit to assist industry compliance with CALEA.  But it remains to be seen whether the FBI will be authorized or willing to certify or otherwise approve a company's compliance with CALEA.  No such authority is conferred by the statute. On the other hand, recognizing the need for greater certainty, FBI officials have indicated a willingness to consider issuing a certification letter upon request of a company that has demonstrated its compliance to the FBI's satisfaction.  

	<P>As an alternative, it seems likely that a company will be able to reach some kind of formal agreement with the FBI and Justice Department as to what constitutes acceptable compliance.  Since the Attorney General can enforce CALEA through a civil action in district court, it follows that the Attorney General could also settle the issue of a company's compliance through entry of a settlement in district court.  Such a settlement might prove preferable to a public FCC proceeding on whether a company's compliance with CALEA is "reasonably achievable."  Though not specifically provided for in CALEA, this process may be feasible to pursue when both the government and the private company share a common interest in not publicizing the technical details of how the government will intercept communications on the company's telecommunications system.

<h4>Recovery of Compliance Costs</H4>

	<P>Government reimbursement to companies for certain costs associated with compliance was a central reason for industry acquiescence in this legislation.  CALEA authorized, but did not appropriate, a total of $500 million to cover reimbursement costs to be paid by the Justice Department in fiscal years 1995 to 1998.  CALEA at <I>110, 47 U.S.C.</I> 1009.  (The Justice Department is seeking $100 million in appropriations for the 1996 fiscal year.)  Different procedures apply to reimbursement for compliance with (a) the capability requirements; and (b) the capacity requirements. 

<h4>Capability Requirements</H4>
		<P>For equipment, facilities, or services deployed after January 1, 1995, the private sector must pay for compliance so long as compliance is reasonably achievable.  Government reimbursement is only available at the discretion of the Attorney General after an FCC finding that a company's compliance with CALEA is not "reasonably achievable."  CALEA  <I>108(c)(2), 109(b), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 107(c)(2), 1008(b).  As discussed above, if the Attorney General fails to reimburse the company in such a situation, the company is considered to be in compliance with CALEA's capability requirements.  Id.<a href="#note11">[Footnote 11]</a><name="back11"></a>


<h4>Capacity Requirements</H4>
<P>	As noted in the discussion of capacity requirements, a telecommunications carrier subject to CALEA must respond to the Attorney General's notices within six months of their publication in the Federal Register.  In its response, the company must identify any of its systems or services that do not have the capacity the Attorney General requires.  CALEA <I>104(d), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1003(d).  

	<P>Subject to the availability of appropriations, the Attorney General may agree to reimburse a carrier for reasonable costs directly associated with meeting the government's capacity requirements.  Until the Attorney General agrees to reimburse the carrier, the carrier shall be considered in compliance with the capacity requirements of CALEA.  CALEA  <I>104(e), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1003(e).
<hr><blockquote>
<h3 align=center>Footnotes</h3>

<H4><a name="note1"><B>Footnote 1</B></a></H4>  The House Judiciary Committee Report on CALEA provides that CALEA's requirements apply to "a carrier providing a customer with a service or facility that allows the customer access to a publicly switched network."  House Report at 23.  <a href="#back1">[Return to text at Footnote 1]</a>

<H4><a name="note2"><B>Footnote 2</B></a></H4>
<P>The Senate Judiciary Committee Report on CALEA provides that the definition of telecommunications common carrier "encompasses such service providers as local exchange carriers, interexchange carriers, competitive access providers (CAPS), cellular carriers, providers of personal communications services (PCS), satellite-based service providers, cable operators, and electric or other utilities that provide telecommunication services for hire to the public, and any other common carrier that offers wireline or wireless service for hire to the public."  Senate Report at 20.   <a href="#back2">[Return to text at Footnote 2]</a>

<H4><a name="note3"><B>Footnote 3</B></a></H4>  Commercial mobile radio services is defined in the Communications Act of 1934, as amended, as any mobile service that is provided for profit and makes interconnected service available to the public, or to such a class of users as to be effectively available to a substantial portion of the public.  <I>47 U.S.C.</I> 332(d).
  <a href="#back3">[Return to text at Footnote 3]</a>

<H4><a name="note4"><B>Footnote 4</B></a></H4>  This broadly defined exception was lobbied for by the on-line services industry:  the term information services "means the offering of a capability for generating, acquiring, storing, transforming, processing, retrieving, utilizing, or making available information via telecommunications."  CALEA <I>102(6), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1001(6).  The term includes "(i) a service that permits a customer to retrieve stored information from, or file information for storage in, information storage facilities; (ii) electronic publishing; and (iii) electronic messaging services."  Id.  <a href="#back4">[Return to text at Footnote 4]</a>

<H4><a name="note5"><B>Footnote 5</B></a></H4>  While this exemption applies only to CALEA's capability requirements, discussed in detail below, the capability requirements constitute the major substantive obligation of this legislation.  The House Report reiterates that any private service that does not connect to a public switched network, such as an ATM or PBX system, or a carrier that merely interconnects the systems of other service providers, need not comply with CALEA's capability requirements.  House Report at 18, 22-24.  <a href="#back5">[Return to text at Footnote5]</a>

<H4><a name="note6"><B>Footnote 6</B></a></H4>  Telecommunications carriers unable to comply with CALEA's capability requirements by October 25, 1998, may request an extension of the time to comply.  CALEA  <I>107(c), codified at 47 U.S.C. </I> 1006(c).  The FCC, after consultation with the Attorney General, may grant extensions of the compliance date if compliance is not reasonably achievable through the use of then-available technology.  Extensions are available for the length of time the FCC considers necessary for the carrier to comply, but no longer than two years.  Id.  <a href="#back6">[Return to text at Footnote 6]</a>

<H4><a name="note7"><B>Footnote 7</B></a></H4>  CALEA defines call-identifying information as "dialing or signaling information that identifies the origin, direction, destination, or termination of each communication generated or received by a subscriber."   <a href="#back7">[Return to text at Footnote 7]</a>

<H4><a name="note8"><B>Footnote 8</B></a></H4>  The definition of support services includes "any product, software, or service used by a telecommunications carrier for the internal signaling or switching functions of its telecommunications network."  CALEA  <I>102(7), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1001(7).  <a href="#back8">[Return to text at Footnote 8]</a>

<H4><a name="note9"><B>Footnote 9</B></a></H4>  By law, the FCC standards should:  meet the capability requirements by cost-effective methods; protect the privacy of communications not authorized to be intercepted; minimize the cost of compliance that is passed on to residential ratepayers; serve the policy of the U.S. to encourage the provision of new technologies and services to the public; and provide reasonable time and conditions for carrier compliance.  CALEA <I>107(b), codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 1006(b).
  <a href="#back9">[Return to text at Footnote 9]</a>

<H4><a name="note10"><B>Footnote 10</B></a></H4>  CALEA provides different procedures for equipment, facilities, or services deployed on or before January 1, 1995.  <a href="#back10">[Return to text at Footnote 10]</a>

<H4><a name="note11"><B>Footnote 11</B></a></H4>  Telecommunications carriers may also petition the FCC to adjust charges, practices, classifications, and regulations to enable the carrier to recover costs expended for making modifications to equipment, facilities or services pursuant to the capability requirements of CALEA.  CALEA  <I>301, codified at 47 U.S.C.</I> 229(e).  <a href="#back11">[Return to text at Footnote 11]</a></blockquote><P>
