<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Labor Relations and Employment Law
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>Labor Relations and Employment Law</CENTER></H2>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP offers a wide range of experience and expertise in all areas of labor
relations and employment law.  Between its Washington, D.C. and
<a href="http://www.steptoe.com/phoenix.htm">Phoenix, Arizona offices</a>, the firm has more than a dozen lawyers
whose practices are fully dedicated to this area of the law.

<h4><CENTER>Employment Discrimination</CENTER></h4>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has been prominent in the area of employment
discrimination law since the early 1970s when it represented
AT&T, at the time the nation's largest employer, in
administrative litigation and negotiations to resolve nationwide
claims of race and sex discrimination.  Since that time, our
lawyers have represented employers in civil rights litigation at
all levels of the state and federal system throughout the United
States.  These cases have included local jury trials, large
class actions, enforcement proceedings brought by government
agencies, and appellate proceedings, involving allegations of
bias due to race, sex, age, national origin, disability, and
religion.  Our lawyers have frequently participated in Supreme
Court cases in the equal employment area, representing parties
and amici.  For example,Tom Powers, former Executive Director of
the EEOC, successfully argued two of the most significant cases
to be decided by the Court in this area, <U>Weber v. Kaiser Alum. &
Chem. Corp.</U> and <U>Falcon v. General Telephone Co.</U>  In recent
years, we have litigated numerous cases involving claims of sex,
disability and age discrimination, sexual harassment, and
unlawful retaliation under the civil rights laws.  Our attorneys
frequently lecture and write on new developments in this field
around the country.

<h4><CENTER>Wrongful Discharge Cases</CENTER></h4>
<P>As state legislatures and courts throughout the country have
expanded individual employee rights and created new causes of
action for employees, Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have been in
the forefront of representing employers in wrongful termination
and related state court proceedings based on contract and tort
theories arising out of employment disputes.

<P>Our capabilities in this area were expanded significantly in
1992 with the addition to our Phoenix office of a group of
employment lawyers headed by <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/katz.htm">Larry Katz</a> and <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/selden.htm">Dave Selden</a>.  Larry
brought to the firm more than twenty-five years of  experience
representing management clients in traditional labor relations
matters, equal employment opportunity law, and all areas
of employment litigation.  Larry enjoys a national reputation in
this field, with broad experience in the litigation of
employment discrimination and wrongful termination claims.  He
has successfully litigated jury trials on behalf of such large
employers as Allied Signal, Motorola, Wyle Laboratories, and
America West Airlines.

<P>Dave Selden's specialties have included representation of
public employers, construction companies and employers with
disputes arising under the Americans With Disabilities Act.
Adding Larry, Dave and their colleagues to our team of
experienced Washington labor attorneys has given the firm an
extremely broad and talented base in this critical area of
practice.  We have remained on the cutting edge in several
developing areas of employment litigation, defending several
cases brought by alleged whistleblowers, plaintiffs asserting
unique coverage under the disability laws, and "glass ceiling"
challenges.

<h4><CENTER>Employer Counseling</CENTER></h4>

<P>In addition to litigation, our employment lawyers also provide
advice on the growing range of employment law issues affecting the day-to-day personnel
activities of corporations. These include, in particular,
questions involving force reductions and early retirement
programs, the development of sexual harassment and disability
policies, the drafting of personnel manuals, employment
contracts and severance agreements, and the resolution of
grievances through internal proceedings or arbitration.

<P>Our lawyers have particular expertise in issues involving the
Age Discrimination in Employment Act.  In addition, <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/cooper.htm">Ron Cooper</a>
of our Washington office was actively involved, on behalf of
management clients, in the legislative process that led to the
Older Workers Benefit Protection Act, which has a particular
impact on "window plans" and employee waivers.  Our attorneys
are also frequently called upon to advise clients regarding the
WARN Act, the Americans With Disabilities Act, and the Family
and Medical Leave Act.  Moreover, employment issues are often
inextricably related to benefit issues under ERISA, and our
employee benefit lawyers often work closely with our employment
lawyers in advising and representing clients.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP
attorneys have frequently been consulted with respect to labor
relations issues growing out of mergers, acquisitions and other
corporate reorganizations and restructuring, in both union and
non-union settings.

<h4><CENTER>Federal Contract Compliance</CENTER></h4>

<P>For employers who do business with the federal government, we
provide assistance in the development and implementation of
affirmative action plans.  We also represent clients in
connection with investigations and audits by federal agencies
such as the Office of Federal Contract Compliance Programs. 
Because the Executive Order programs are based on the federal
procurement process, our work in this area benefits
substantially from the expertise of our Government Contracts
Group. In turn, the firm's employment lawyers are often
consulted with respect to internal investigations conducted by
the Government Contracts Group, or reviews undertaken by
government contracting agencies, in order to minimize the
prospect of claims by adversely affected employees.  In recent
years, Steptoe & Johnson LLP has frequently been retained to defend
qui tam actions initiated by employees claiming that their
companies have violated government contracts.

<h4><CENTER>Whistleblower Law</CENTER></h4>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have been very active in
representing employers in litigation brought by "whistleblowers"
as well as client requests for advice in such matters. 

<P>We have extensive experience in litigating such cases under the
federal environmental statutes, and our firm has developed an
unparalleled private database of legal precedents in this arena.

<P>We also have represented clients in sensitive inquiries by
regulators and Congress.

<h4><CENTER>Traditional Labor Relations</CENTER></h4>
<P>We also represent clients in connection with union organizing
campaigns, representation elections, unfair labor practice
charges, and collective bargaining.  Our employment lawyers have
substantial experience in these areas, having successfully
assisted numerous companies in defeating union campaigns in the
last several years.  Furthermore, Larry Katz played a
significant role in establishing the employer's right to take
legal action against a union which makes defamatory statements
during an organizing campaign, when he successfully argued <U>NLRB
v. Bill Johnson LLP's Restaurants</U> in the U.S. Supreme Court a few
years ago.

<P>In conjunction with the firm's <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/transpt2.htm">Transportation Group</a>, we
represent both rail and air carriers in connection with Railway
Labor Act matters.  In addition, with the increased importance
of health benefits to labor relations, we benefit from our close
association with the firm's ERISA Group.

<h4><CENTER>Labor Standards</CENTER></h4>

<P>Our employment lawyers advise numerous clients with respect to
their obligations under various labor standards statutes,
including the Fair Labor Standards Act, the Service Contract
Act, and the Davis Bacon Act.  We have conducted several
successful appeals of wage determinations on large construction
projects under government contracts, and have frequently
represented employers in Department of Labor wage and hour
compliance reviews.

<P>Recent decisions under the Fair Labor Standards Act have called
into question the exempt status for large numbers of white
collar employees based on personnel policies that authorize
certain types of deductions from their compensation.  We have
represented both public and private employers facing such
claims, and are advising clients on how to minimize exposure to
this new litigation threat.

<h4><CENTER>International Issues</CENTER></h4>
<P>In consultation with our international lawyers, the firm's
employment lawyers have advised foreign concerns regarding the
employment law ramifications of undertaking business activities
in the United States.  We have also advised the governments of
newly independent and developing countries on labor relations
and employment standards issues that would be relevant in
encouraging foreign investment.

<p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>
</DOC>
