<html><head><title>Kevin M. Keyes Bio</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>
Kevin M. Keyes</h2>

<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/taxprac.htm">Federal Taxation</a></center></blockquote>




<P>Kevin Keyes practices in the area of federal income, gift and estate taxation.  His particular emphasis is on transactional tax planning, including such matters as structuring and financing corporate acquisitions and dispositions, preserving favorable tax attributes such as loss and credit carryovers, and using pass-through entities, such as partnerships and S corporations, as acquisition vehicles.

<P>Mr. Keyes is also a certified public accountant.  Before joining Steptoe & Johnson LLP, Mr. Keyes was with the international accounting firm of Arthur Young & Co., where he specialized in tax matters.

<P>Mr. Keyes is Chairman of the Bankruptcy Subcommittee of the American Bar Association's Corporate Tax Committee.  Previously, he was Co-Chair of the Interest Rate Agreements Subcommittee of the Financial Transactions Committee.  He is also an adjunct Professor of Law at Georgetown University Law Center, where he teaches Business Planning and Income Tax Accounting.

<P>Mr. Keyes serves as Editor for the Corporation and Shareholders Department of The Journal of Taxation, and is the former Corporations and Partnerships Columnist for Small Business Taxation.  He is the author of Tax Practice Series Alternative Minimum Tax on Non-Corporate Taxpayers and Alternative Minimum Tax on Corporate Taxpayers.  He has written extensively on a variety of tax matters for other professional publications and is a frequent speaker at tax institutes and programs.

<P><dir><li> Case Western Reserve University J.D. 1983 Order of the Coif
<li> Bowling Green State University B.S. 1979 Beta Alpha Psi
