<html><head><title>Blake D. Rubin</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Blake D. Rubin</h2>
<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/taxprac.htm">Federal Taxation</a></center></blockquote>
<hr>

<P>Blake Rubin practices in the area of Federal taxation, with particular emphasis on matters relating to real estate and partnership taxation.  His practice includes planning, policy and controversy matters.  He has extensive experience in structuring large partnership and real estate transactions, and represents several of the nation's largest real estate developers and owners in transactional matters.  He has also served as tax counsel in connection with the formation and operation of numerous corporate joint ventures.  In the policy area, he has represented clients before Congress, the Treasury Department and the Internal Revenue Service.  In the controversy area, he has handled major cases before the Internal Revenue Service and in the courts.

<P>Mr. Rubin is Chair of the 1600-member District of Columbia Bar Section of Taxation.  He previously served as Chair of both the Pass-Through Entities and Real Estate Committee of that organization and the Real Estate Taxation Committee of the American Bar Association Section of Taxation.  He serves as general counsel to the Real Estate Tax Institute, and is Chair of the Advisory Council of the National Institute on Real Estate Taxation.  He is a member of the Advisory Board of the Journal of Real Estate Taxation, the Washington Tax Review, the Tax Management Real Estate Journal and the Journal of Taxation of Investments.  He writes a column on real estate tax issues for the Journal of Taxation of Investments, and is the author of more than 30 professional articles.  He is also a frequent speaker on tax topics.

<P>From 1984 through 1987, Mr. Rubin served with the Office of Tax Legislative Counsel, U.S. Department of Treasury.  He was deeply involved in the development and implementation of the Tax Reform Act of 1986 provisions affecting real estate and tax shelters, including the passive loss rules, the non-business interest limitations, and the provisions limiting use of the installment method of accounting and extending the at-risk rules to real estate.  In addition, he had responsibility for matters relating to partnership taxation, including partnership allocations and the treatment of master limited partnerships.

<P>Before joining the Treasury Department, Mr. Rubin practiced in Philadelphia and was an Adjunct Professor in Villanova University's LL.M. program, where he taught courses on tax planning for real estate transactions.

<P></p><UL><LI>University of Pennsylvania J.D. cum laude, 1980
Order of the Coif<br>
<LI>Wharton School of Finance M.B.A. with distinction, 1980
Beta Gamma Sigma
Beta Alpha Psi<br>
<LI>Haverford College B.A. 1976</UL>
