<HTML> <HEAD><TITLE>Bernstein Litigation</TITLE></HEAD><body><hr><P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P><hr>
<CENTER><H3>Bernstein Litigation</H3><P>
</CENTER><P>
		There have been two recent court decisions addressing whether the First Amendment restricts the State Department's application of the International Traffic in Arms Regulations (&quot;ITARs&quot;) to encryption.  The first decision was issued by Judge Richey in litigation brought by privacy activist Phil Karn, and was widely hailed as a victory for the government.  The second decision was issued last week by Judge Patel in litigation brought by Daniel Bernstein, and has been taken as a major defeat for the government.  In fact, the approaches taken by the two courts are much closer than they at first appear.  Moreover, Judge Patel's decision is only a preliminary ruling, and it is possible that the government may yet emerge victorious.<P>
<P>
		The background of the Bernstein decision is as follows.  In July 1993, Bernstein submitted a commodity jurisdiction (&quot;CJ&quot;) request with regard to an encryption and decryption algorithm called &quot;Snuffle.&quot;  The State Department informed Bernstein that Snuffle was a defense article under the international Traffic in Arms Regulations (&quot;ITARs&quot;).  Bernstein filed suit, arguing principally that the ITARs violated the First Amendment in that they were a content-based infringement on speech and acted as a prior restraint on speech.  The Justice Department moved to dismiss, arguing that the Snuffle source code was not speech entitled to First Amendment projection, and that even if it was speech, the State Department's regulations satisfied the appropriate standard under the First Amendment.<P>
<P>
		On April 15, Judge Patel of the federal district court in San Francisco rejected the Justice Department's motion to dismiss Bernstein's challenge to the State Department's regulation of source code as a defense article.<P>
<P>
		The court first addressed whether Bernstein's challenge was barred by the provision of the Arms Export Control Act (&quot;AECA&quot;) precluding judicial review of the President's designation of items as defense articles.  See 22 U.S.C.  2778(h).  The court held that the AECA did not bar Bernstein's constitutional challenge as long as his claim was &quot;colorable.&quot;  This holding is consistent with Judge Richey's recent decision in the Karn litigation.<P>
<P>
		The court then addressed the standard for deciding whether Bernstein's constitutional challenge was &quot;colorable.&quot;  The court held that under Ninth Circuit precedent, the standard for allowing the claim to proceed was whether the claim was &quot;wholly insubstantial or frivolous&quot; or was &quot;clearly immaterial and made only for the purposes of jurisdiction.&quot;  This procedural issue is important to an understanding of the court's decision in Bernstein.  The court's decision that Bernstein had a colorable constitutional claim (and therefore could withstand the Justice Department's motion to dismiss) turned on the use of a low standard -- whether the claim was nonfrivolous -- to determine whether the claim was colorable.<P>
<P>
		Most of the court's decision focused on whether the Snuffle source code was speech protected by the First Amendment, as opposed to &quot;conduct,&quot; as argued by the Justice Department.  The court held that the source code was speech, for several reasons.  The court saw computer language as akin to any other languages (e.g., German or French), allowing the communication of &quot;understood meanings within specific communities.&quot;  The court said that it was irrelevant that the source code also was functional (i.e., the Snuffle algorithm was not only about encryption, but -- when compiled into object code -- could encrypt and decrypt).  The court analogized to technical information about hydrogen bomb construction, which has been held to be speech even though it serves a functional purpose.  Finally, the court noted that computer software is entitled to copyright protection, which is intended to protect original expression, supporting the conclusion that source code is a means of original expression and should be treated as speech.<P>
<P>
		Having found that the Snuffle source code was entitled to protection as speech, the court analyzed whether the ITAR control was consistent with the First Amendment. The court treated the ITAR control as a content-neutral regulation reviewable under the fairly lenient standard established in United States v. O'Brien, 391 U.S. 367 (1968).  While the court suggested that a higher standard might be appropriate (i.e., that the ITAR control might actually be content-based, and therefore presumptively invalid), the court declined to apply a higher standard without additional briefing from the parties.  The O'Brien standard was applied in the Karn decision as well, and the court there held that Karn did not have a colorable claim that the State Department's action did not meet the standard.<P>
<P>
		Here, however, the court found that Bernstein had a colorable claim that the ITAR control of Snuffle did not meet the O'Brien test for content-neutral regulation of speech.  The court's jurisdiction for this conclusion is only one sentence long, simply stating that the ITAR control appeared to &quot;relate to the 'suppression of free expression' and may reach farther than is justifiable.&quot;  The court said it could not find that Bernstein's contentions on these issues were &quot;frivolous.&quot;  (In contrast, the Karn court avoided deciding whether the ITAR regulation was broader than necessary, finding that to address this issue would involve the court in fundamentally political decisions.)<P>
<P>
		Finally, the court held that Bernstein had a colorable (i.e., non-frivolous) claim that the ITARs imposed a prior restraint on his speech, since the regulation prohibited him from publishing the Snuffle source code without first obtaining a license.  The court noted the &quot;heavy presumption&quot; against prior restraints on speech.  The Justice Department apparently did not contest the point that if the Snuffle program was speech, the ITARs imposed a prior restraint on Bernstein's speech.<P>
<P>
		Since the court denied the Justice Department's motion to dismiss, the case will now enter the fact-finding phase, including discovery of government officials and documents.  It is difficult at this stage to predict the eventual outcome, but I offer the following thoughts.  It appears very likely that Judge Patel will find that the ITARs impose an unconstitutional prior restraint on speech.  If this holding is upheld on appeal, it would bar the State Department from requiring licenses before publication of encryption.  However, State could still impose significant civil penalties for publishing controlled encryption, so it is unclear how much impact this change would have.  Indeed, it could be a pyrrhic victory, since exporters might no longer be able to obtain State Department confirmation that a particular activity was allowed.<P>
<P>
		With regard to Bernstein's broader claim that the ITARs unconstitutionally regulate his speech, the key issue will be Judge Patel's factual findings as to the State Department's purpose in regulating encryption and as to whether the ITARs are broader than necessary to achieve a legitimate purpose.  Judge Patel's holding that Bernstein's allegations on these issues were not &quot;frivolous&quot; does not necessarily mean she will end up agreeing with him on the facts.  However, the overall tone of Judge Patel's decision is fairly cool toward the government, and it seems likely that the factual findings will favor Bernstein.  If so, it would be difficult for the government to challenge these factual findings on appeal, given the deference given to lower courts' factual findings.  <P>
<P>
		However, if Judge Patel holds that the ITARs are an unconstitutional content-neutral regulation (or decides that the ITAR controls are content-based and therefore invalid), there would be opportunity for the government to obtain a reversal on appeal based on broader legal issues.  For instance, an appeals court might hold that the lower court's inquiry into whether the ITAR controls are broader than necessary resulted in an improper consideration of a political question (as the Karn court held).  If Judge Patel's decision is based on her view that the ITAR controls are content-based rather than content-neutral, this could also be the subject of an appeal. <P>
<P>
		In the end, it is interesting to note that the &quot;political question&quot; issue is where Judge Patel and Judge Richey parted company.  Until that point, the judges followed similar paths -- both holding that colorable constitutional claims were not precluded from review, that the State Department's regulation of encryption was subject to the First Amendment, and that the ITAR controls were content-neutral.  Judge Richey then refused to address Karn's argument that the controls were broader than necessary, based on the political question doctrine.  Judge Patel, in contrast, preliminarily reached Bernstein's argument on this point -- without even mentioning the political question doctrine.  As fact-finding proceeds, and Judge Patel confronts the need to make findings about what approach the State Department should have taken, it is possible that the political question doctrine may hold greater appeal to her.<P>
<P>

<P></blockquote><P><hr><P>Copyright 1996 Steptoe & Johnson LLP <blockquote><P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP grants permission for the  contents of this publication to be reproduced and distributed in full free of charge, provided that:  (i) such reproduction and distribution is limited to educational and professional non-profit use only (and not for advertising or other use); (ii) the reproductions or distributions make no edits or changes in this publication; and (iii) all reproductions and distributions include the name of the author(s) and the copyright notice(s) included in the original publication.<P>Requests for permission to copy portions of the document should be directed to:  <a href="mailto:wbatterton@steptoe.com">wbatterton@steptoe.com</A></blockquote><hr><P><blockquote><center><A HREF="http://www.steptoe.com/pubtoc.htm">Publications</A> | <A HREF="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Biographies</A> | <A HREF="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</A></BODY></HTML>
