</a></CENTER></BODY></HTML><HTML><TITLE><CENTER>Highlights of New Joint-Stock Company Law of the Russian Federation</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H2 ALIGN=center>Highlights of New Joint-Stock Company Law<BR> of the Russian Federation</H2>

<CENTER><I>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/carey.htm">Sarah C. Carey</a></I></CENTER>
<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>

<H4>The JSC Law should be read in conjunction with the RF Civil Code and RF Law on Foreign Investment.</H4>

<H4>All Joint-Stock Companies must re-register by July 1, 1996.</H4>

<H4>Charter is the only formation document that must be filed:</H4>

<UL><LI>it need not list shareholders and distribution of shares among shareholders
<LI>bare-bones format acceptable, see Article 11 for minimum requirements; additional provisions optional; affirmation of principle of freedom of contract-- charter may contain any provision that does not contradict law
<LI>founders should review JSC law for options that will be foreclosed if not dealt with in Charter
<LI>must be open company if more than 50 shareholders
<LI>founders agreement required only for new companies, but no longer a formation document subject to registration</UL>

<H4>More flexibility in capital structure:</H4>

<ul><LI>minimum charter capital for closed company is 100 times the minimum wage ($1400); minimum charter capital for open company is 1000 times the minimum wage ($14,000).
<LI>Charter may provide for authorized, but unissued shares; authorized shares may be issued by decision of the Board of Directors
<LI>only one class of common stock permitted, but wide flexibility for classes of preferred which can be voting or non-voting, with cumulative or non-cumulative dividends, convertible into common or non-convertible
<LI>bonds, debentures, other convertible securities also permitted
<LI>stock splits and reverse splits permitted
<LI>restrictions concerning dilution of government-owned share remain
<LI>reserve fund requirement increased to 15%, with mandatory annual contributions of 5% of net profit
<LI></ul>

<H4>Valuation of Shares, Preferential and Pre-emptive Rights:</H4>

<UL><LI>founders free to value initial contributions to Charter Fund

<LI>thereafter, payment in-kind still permissible, but appraisal is required in case of purchase of additional shares in excess of 200 times the minimum wage (roughly $2800).

<LI>price of shares at foundation is par value; price of additional shares fair market value, but not less than par value.  Fair market value = the price a willing and informed buyer would pay a willing and informed seller

<LI>right of first refusal re-transfer of issued and outstanding shares required in closed joint stock company, prohibited for open JSCs.

<LI>pre-emptive right for new issues of stock, which may be at up to 10% discount, permissible in open joint stock company</UL>

<H4>More flexibility in governance:</H4>
 
<UL><LI>JSC with fewer than 50 shareholders may be two-tiered (General Shareholders Meeting, Management)
<LI>JSC with 50 or more shareholders must be three-tiered (General Shareholders Meeting, Board of Directors, Management)
<LI>GSM can be by proxy or balloting by mail  (No proxy for Board Meeting)
<LI>No minimum number of Board members, except that companies with more than 1000 shareholders must have at least 7, and those with 10,000 shareholders must have at least 9
<LI>Board does not need to hold monthly meetings; no automatic tie breaker for Chair of Board
<LI>GSM has more clearly defined powers.  Most decisions by a majority or, greater, if provided by Charter
<LI>Five fundamental matters require 3/4 vote of GSM -- amendment, reorganization, liquidation, change in authorized shares, approval of major transactions; many matters require previous approval by Board of Directors</UL>

<H4>Clarification of Limited Liability:</H4>

<UL>
<LI>Directors, officers, shareholders liable only if they knowingly cause insolvency
<LI>Parent company liable only if it controls its subsidiary and uses that control to knowingly cause insolvency
<LI>Law makes it difficult to "pierce the corporate veil"
</UL>

<H4>Clarification of Directors' and Officers' Roles Fiduciary Duties:</H4>

<UL><LI>Duties of Loyalty and Care: obligation to act reasonably, in good faith, and in the interest of the company
<LI>Duty to disclose and avoid conflicts of interest where interested transactions are involved (extends to family members)
<LI>Directors and officers can be terminated at any time
<LI>Same person cannot be both Chair of Board and General Manager if management is by individual executive; officers may not constitute a majority of the Board of Directors </UL>

<H4>Stronger Shareholders' Rights:</H4>

<UL><LI>right to obtain copy of charter and information about the company
<LI>approval of major transaction -- greater than 25% of net assets by unanimous Board vote, greater than 50% by three-fourth vote by GSM
<LI>dissenters' put rights in case of major transaction, reorganization or limitation on shareholders rights
acquirer of more than 30% interest must offer buy out other shareholders unless waived in the Charter or by GSM resolution
<LI>10% shareholder(s) have right to call extraordinary meeting
<LI>2% shareholder has right to propose agenda items for GSM, nominate board members, auditing committee members (no specification who bears cost of publication, dissemination of notices)
<LI>1% shareholder has right to bring derivative case for mismanagement
<LI>certain other actual and/or optional preemptive rights
<LI>increased disclosures/filing re actions by major shareholders (self-dealing, major transactions, increasing stock position)
<LI>strengthened rights re share registrar (buttressed by new law on stock registers - registration is the future, not certificates
<LI>right of redemption of shares through self-tender by shareholders
<LI>cumulative voting permitted in all JSCs, required in open JSCs with more than 1000 shareholders </UL>

<H4>Clarification of  Types of Reorganization:</H4>

<UL>
<LI>merger
<LI>consolidation
<LI>split-up
<LI>spin-off
<LI>transformation into limited liability company
</UL> 

<H4><I>LLC</I> vs. <I>JSC</I>:</H4>

<P>With the new law, the joint stock company maintains its lead as the best defined business form under Russian Federation law.  Being well defined has its pros and cons.  With advent of more stringent securities regulation, JSC can be cumbersome, especially for closed companies with a small number of shareholders.   Limited Liability Company Law is pending.  If issued before the July 1, 1996 deadline for re-registration of joint stock companies, this may be a good option for certain closed companies depending up tax consequences and other considerations.  

<P><I>January 23, 1996</I>

