<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
	342660
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and 
circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web 
page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  
Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely 
to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<P>
<hr>
<P></P>
<Center><H3> Hearing of the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations</H3></Center>
<P>
	On July 16, the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigation held a hearing 
on computer network security.  Sens. Bill Cohen (R-Me.), Sam Nunn (D-Ga.), and Carl Levin (D-Mich.) 
attended the hearing.  Subcommittee staffers, Harold Damelin (Chief Counsel, Staff Director) and 
Daniel Gelber (Chief counsel, Minority Staff Director), were also present.  The witnesses were Sens. 
Patrick Leahy (D-Vt.) and Jon Kyl (R-Ariz.), Deputy Attorney General Jamie Gorelick, and Deputy 
Secretary of Defense John White. 
<P>
<H4>1.	<U>Senate Computer Security Developments</U></H4>

<P>		There was a consensus among the Senators that a catastrophic attack on 
Cyberspace was imminent and that there was an urgent need for a comprehensive strategy to deal 
such an attack. 
<P>
<P>	The National Information Infrastructure Protection Act (S. 982):  The Act was introduced by 
Sens. Kyl, Leahy, and Charles Grassley (R-Iowa) in June, 1995 and was reported favorably by the 
Judiciary Committee last month.  The Senate is expected to consider the Act before the August 
break.
<P>
 <BLOCKQUOTE>
The goal of the Act is to increase the protection for both government and private computer 
systems from the growing threat of computer crimes.  The Act (a) adds a new provision to ensure 
prosecution of computer-age blackmailers, who threaten to harm or shut down computer networks 
unless their extortionate demands are met; (b) penalizes those who, without authorization, access 
information on private computers that are used in interstate or foreign commerce or communications; 
(c) extends federal protection from intentionally damaging viruses to computers of the government 
and financial institutions, including those that are not used in interstate communications; and (d) 
consolidates computer crimes in Section 1030 of Title 18.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<H4>2.	<U>Administration Computer Security Developments</U></H4>

<P>		Both Gorelick and White testified that they considered computer 
security as one of the most important issues for the government.  Sen. Kyl, however, criticized 
the lack of leadership by the President in this area. 
<P>
<P>Critical Infrastructures:  The Critical Infrastructure Working Group, which was formed 
by Attorney General Janet Reno in response to Presidential Decision Directive 39, has identified 
eight categories of Critical Infrastructures:  telecommunications, electrical power systems, gas 
and oil storage and transportation, banking and finance, transportation, water supply systems, 
emergency services (including medical, police, fire, and rescue), and government operations.
<P>The Executive Order No. 13010 on Critical Infrastructure Protection: The Order was signed 
by the President on July 15, 1996.  Gorelick described the Order as the &quot;Manhattan 
Project&quot; for infrastructure protection.  Sen. Nunn commented that unlike the &quot;Manhattan 
Project&quot;, any successful measure would require extensive public education and participation.  
<P>
<P><B>The Order creates the following two organizations:</B>
<P> 
<P>The President's Commission on Critical Infrastructure Protection:  The Commission will 
formulate measures to protect the nation's Critical Infrastructures.  The Commission will issue 
its final report within one year. It will be chaired by a presidential appointee from the private sector, 
and will have representatives from the public and private sectors.
<P>
<P>Infrastructure Protection Task Force:  This will be an interim interagency task force, 
chaired by the FBI, which will coordinate existing infrastructure protection efforts. 
<P>
<H4>3.	<U>Single Cyberspace Security Center</U></H4>

<P>		Sens. Nunn and Kyl expressed their support for establishing one organization 
that would handle all computer security matters.  Sen. Nunn seemed to favor giving such an 
organization an authority to handle both law enforcement and intelligence matters.  Because the 
private sector owns most of Critical Infrastructures, there was a consensus among participants 
that further efforts should be made to solicit cooperation from the private sector.   
<P>
<H4>4.   <U>Industry-wide Cooperation</U></H4>

<P>		Gorelick testified that there should be an organization like National Security 
Telecommunications Advisory Committee for each one of eight Critical Infrastructures.  
<P>
<H4>5.	<U>Encryption Policy</U></H4>

<P>		The panel devoted about half an hour out of its three hour session to encryption 
policy.  Much of what was said is familiar by now.  Sen. Leahy called for the loosening of export 
restrictions on encryption and expressed his support for the widespread use of strong encryption 
to improve computer security.  Gorelick emphasized the importance of preserving the capability 
for the law enforcement to access data and cautioned against the unregulated use of encryption.  
Sen. Levin also seemed to want more liberalization, recommending a reexamination of current policy 
to strike a better balance between security and privacy interests and interests of the law enforcement 
in accessing data.
<P>
</P>
