<html><head><title>Facilitating Government-Private Sector Cooperation in the Development of Commercial Key Escrow:  Alternatives to Legislation</title></head><body>
<H2 align=center>Facilitating Government-Private Sector Cooperation in the Development of Commercial Key Escrow:  Alternatives to Legislation</H2>
<br><CENTER>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart A. Baker</a></CENTER>
<br><CENTER>September 7, 1995</CENTER>
<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>


<P>Legislation providing clear rules governing the certification and liability of key escrow agents would be the preferred outcome of these discussions.  But we must bear in mind two real-world considerations:  (1) in light of the crowded Congressional agenda this fall, the prospects for enacting key escrow legislation are uncertain at best; and (2) industry will not offer key escrow services on a commercially significant scale until industry can make a reasonably informed assessment of the obligations and risks associated with entering the market.  The convergence of these two considerations has led me to consider how the Administration could take immediate action in response to industry concerns -- without resort to legislation. 

<P>Below I outline four possibilities for how government and industry might reach an agreement on key escrow policy through existing statutes and procedures.  Each approach is analyzed on the basis of how it meets the two fundamental interests driving these discussions:  (1) government's interest in assuring that responsible and responsive key escrow agents will provide assistance upon lawful request; and (2) industry's interest in knowing the risks of the business in advance of entering the market.

<P>My hope in offering this proposal is that if legislation is not feasible in the near-term, one or more of the approaches discussed below may provide an acceptable basis for defining the terms under which government and industry will cooperate to develop globally available and commercially successful private key escrow. <hr>
<P>A.  NIST STANDARDS
<OL><LI>NIST standards have the potential to serve as the de facto standard of care applied for purposes of determining key escrow agent liability to customers and third parties.  <P>
<LI>But there is no guarantee that a NIST standard, even if applied correctly by a court, would shield key escrow agents from unjustified liability. <P>
<blockquote>Key escrow agents might be slightly more reassured if the government agreed to intervene, at the request of a certified key escrow agent, in litigation to argue that the NIST standards constituted the appropriate standard of care.  </blockquote>
<LI>But NIST standards alone cannot establish the binding terms and conditions by which the government can ensure that all escrow agents are responsible and responsive.<P>
<LI>Because of the shortcomings of NIST standards in meeting the fundamental interests of both industry and government, it will be necessary to consider other arrangements to supplement any standard of care to be established by NIST.</OL>

<P>B.  COMMON LAW RULES RELATING TO ASSISTING GOVERNMENT
<OL><LI>	Even absent any statutory authorization, federal common law provides a basis for law enforcement to request assistance from private parties.<P>
<LI>The rule that a private citizen must assist law enforcement originated in the English common law, which required all able-bodied men (a posse comitatus) to pursue a felon at the request of a sheriff.<P>
<LI>Most states have codified the common law rule.  Statutory assistance requirements are not limited to the pursuit of felons, but instead generally apply to any assistance required in the execution of state law.  According to one survey, all but twelve states have statutes that require private parties to assist law enforcement.  Jon C. Blue, High Noon Revisited:  Commands of Assistance by Peace Officers in the Age of the Fourth Amendment, 101 Yale L.J. 1475 (1992).  <P>
<LI>When private parties are required to assist the government, the private parties enjoy immunity from claims that arise in connection with providing the assistance.  <I>Fowler</I> v. <I>Southern Bell Telephone & Telegraph Company</I>, 343 F.2d 150 (5th Cir. 1965) provides a clear expression of the rationale for common law immunity.  
<blockquote>In Fowler, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal held that if a telephone company acted "for and at the request" of the federal agents in placing a wiretap, and the federal agents had acted within the bounds of their authority, the telephone company would be immune from a private party's suit.  <P>
The Fowler court reasoned that:  "to deny the privilege [of immunity] to those who assist federal officers would conflict with the underlying policy of the privilege itself, to remove inhibition against the fearless, vigorous, and effective administration of policies of government."  Id. at 157.	</blockquote>
<LI>In the key escrow context, the government might have inherent authority to require assistance from escrow agents.  But the possible availability of some ill-defined common law immunity might not motivate industry to cooperate.  Some of this uncertainty could be eased by an agreement between the government and the escrow agent, setting forth responsiveness standards and stating that:  
<blockquote>The government will intervene in court cases brought against key escrow agents who have met the standards.<P>
The Justice Department has confirmed the availability of common law immunity in the key escrow context. 		</blockquote> </ol>


<P>C.  TITLE III WIRETAP LAW
<OL><LI>	The Omnibus Crime Control and Safe Streets Act of 1968 and the Electronic Communications Privacy Act of 1986 ("Title III") provide the government mechanisms for obtaining assistance from private parties in the interception of electronic communications.  <P>
<LI>A threshold issue is whether Title III could be applied to key escrow -- an initial reading of Title III suggests that such a reading would not be implausible.  <P>
<ul><LI>Under Title III, any government officer authorized by law to intercept wire, oral, or electronic communications can, when required, obtain "technical assistance" from communications service providers, landlords, custodians, or "other persons."  18 U.S.C.  2511(2)(a)(ii).<P>
<LI>An escrow agent providing the government a customer's private key could be considered providing "technical assistance" required by government to read encrypted wire, oral, or electronic communications.</ul><P>
<LI>In the most plausible scenario, government and industry could negotiate terms and conditions to govern government requests for keys (i.e., responsiveness).  Then, when the government required a key, it could obtain it by presenting the escrow agent with one of the forms of authority specified in Title III:  <P>
<ul><LI>Court orders:  which are used by the government in most circumstances where "technical assistance" is required executing a wiretap.  <P>
<LI>Attorney General certifications:  which are typically valid for only forty-eight hours, and generally are used in emergencies when a court order is not immediately available.  </ul><P>
<LI>Parties providing assistance under Title III can avail themselves of two statutory liability limitation:  <P>
<ul><LI>The statutory immunity in Title III provides that "no cause of action shall lie in any court against any provider of wire or electronic communications service, its officers, employers or agents, landlord, custodian or other specified person for providing information, facilities, or assistance in accordance with the terms of a court order or certification under this chapter."  18 U.S.C.  2511(2)(a)(ii) (emphasis added). 
<LI>The good faith defense of Title III further provides:  "Good faith reliance on a court warrant or order, a grand jury subpoena, a legislative authorization, or a statutory authorization . . . is a complete defense against any civil or criminal action brought under this chapter or any other law."  18 U.S.C.  2520(d) (emphasis added).  </ul><P>
	<LI>These immunity and good faith defense provisions have been widely applied by the courts to telephone companies, banks, and other private parties assisting the government's electronic surveillance for law enforcement purposes.  See, e.g., Camacho v. Autoridad de Telefonos de Puerto Rico, 868 F.2d 482 (1st Cir. 1989); Jacobson v. Rose, 592 F.2d 515 (9th Cir. 1978); Manufacturas International v. Mfrs. Hanover Trust, 792 F. Supp. 180 (E.D.N.Y. 1992).  <P>
<LI>Title III and FISA cover only a portion of authorized government intercepts.  Agents will have to rely on common law immunity in the absence of a statute.</ol>

<P>D.  GOVERNMENT PROCUREMENT LAW
<OL><LI>	Since the government in its commercial key escrow initiative is in effect agreeing to permit exportable key escrow in return for key escrow agents' agreement to provide a service to both its customers and the government, key escrow policy could logically take the form of a government procurement contract.<P>
<ul><li>The basic agreement would be for the government to reimburse key escrow agents for operating their businesses according to certain government- specified standards and providing the government certain services on an on-going basis.  Note that since the government has an interest in the responsibility as well as the responsiveness of escrow agents, the agreement could set standards forth both.</ul><P>
	<li>This approach could prove attractive to industry from a liability standpoint because it might make available the government contractor defense.  <P>
<ul><li>Under the federal common law's government contractor defense, as elaborated by the Supreme Court's Boyle decision, a contractor is immune from tort liability in connection with products built to the government's specifications.  Boyle v. United Technologies Corp., 487 U.S. 500 (1988) (helicopter manufacturer not liable under Virginia tort law for death of Marine pilot allegedly attributable to defectively designed emergency escape system).<P>
<li>In Boyle, the Supreme Court set out a three-part test for when the defense is available:  (1) the government approves reasonably precise specifications for product design; (2) a contractor's equipment conforms to those specifications; (3) the contractor warned the government regarding all dangers known to the contractor.<P>
<li>The Boyle Court held that when these three criteria are met, procurement falls within the Federal Tort Claims Act (FTCA) exception for government performance of "discretionary functions,"  28 U.S.C. 2680(a), and that the FTCA immunity available to the government is likewise available to the government's supplier.  </ul><P> 
	<li>The Court's reasoning in Boyle would appear equally applicable in the key escrow context.  In Boyle, the Court reasoned that if government contractors were held liable in tort to third parties, the government contract terms would be adversely affected:  either the contractor would refuse to manufacture for the government or the contractor would raise its prices -- either outcome would disadvantage the government.  <P>
	<li>The government contractor defense, because it exists only as federal common law and has not been codified in legislation, is subject to unpredictable interpretation and application by the courts.  Accordingly: <P>
<ul><li>There is no certainty that the defense would apply in the key escrow context.  For instance, Federal Courts of Appeal are split on the issue of whether the government contractor defense applies to non-military contractors or non-military equipment.<P>
<ul><li>In Carley v. Wheeled Coach, 991 F.2d 1117 (3d Cir. 1993), cert. denied, 114 S. Ct. 191 (1993), the Third Circuit held that the government contractor defense conferred immunity on the manufacturer of an ambulance procured by the General Services Administration.  See also Stout v. Borg-Warner Corp., 933 F.2d 331 (5th Cir. 1991), cert. denied, 112 S. Ct. 584 (1991). <P> 
<li>However, in two cases involving tort claims for exposure to asbestos products, the government contractor defense was found inapplicable.  Nielsen v. George Diamond Vogel Paint Co., 892 F.2d 1450 (9th Cir. 1990); In re Hawaii Federal Asbestos Cases, 960 F.2d 806 (9th Cir. 1992).   </ul><p>
<li>Nor is the exact scope of the government contractor defense well-defined, even if it were found applicable to key escrow agents.<P>
<ul><li>First, the defense applies only to immunity for design defects, not defects in manufacture.  Therefore, key escrow agents would remain liable to customers and third-parties for performance failures unrelated to the government-sanctioned design.  <P>
<li>Second, dicta in Boyle and Federal Circuit Court cases suggest that the government contractor defense may not be applicable to "stock products sold in the commercial market," even if procured by the government. To the extent that key escrow services are considered "stock products," the defense might not be available.<P>
<li>Finally, and perhaps most significantly, the contract between the key escrow service provider and the government would not be a typical government procurement contract -- it is not certain that a contract to provide the government an occasional escrowed key upon request should justify insulating a key escrow agent from liability for running the key escrow service on a day-to-day basis. </ul>  <P>
<li>Moreover, setting key escrow policy via government procurement could be unattractive to industry because of the compliance costs and risks associated with government procurement:<P>
<ul><li>Cost data which government contractors must maintain under the complex Federal Acquisition Regulations.<P>
<li>Uncertainty as to potential liability arising from acting as a partner with government (state action).</ul></ul>

<hr>
