<html><head><title>Newsletter:  Pesticides Regulation Update Volume 6</title><CENTER><IMG SRC="http://www.steptoe.com/logo62.gif" ALT="Steptoe & Johnson LLP Pesticides Regulation Update"></CENTER></head><body>
<h4 align=center>December 1995, Volume 6</h4>
<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>					

<H2 align=center><a name="toc">Articles in this Issue</a></H2>

<blockquote><a href="#dev">Developments in Adverse Effects Reporting</a><P>

<a href="#bar">Barolo to Start OPP Reorganization in 1996</a><P>

<a href="#fif">FIFRA Reform Bills Still Pending</a><P>

<a href="#pes">Pesticide Export Changes Offered for Public Input</a><P>

<a href="#epa">EPA Releases Revised Test Guidelines</a><P>

<a href="#upd">Updated Data Submitters List Available</a><P>

<a href="#epa2">EPA Issues More Registration Eligibility Decisions</a><P>

<a href="#reg">Regulatory Actions and Restrictions for Methyl Bromide Announced</a></blockquote>

<hr>
<H4 align=center><a name="dev">New Developments in Adverse Effects Reporting</a></H4>
			
	<P>For several months, EPA has stated that it will shortly issue new guidance on reporting adverse effects from pesticides under section 6(a)(2) of FIFRA.  The new regulations were scheduled to be in OMB's hands for review by mid-October, but apparently have not yet been sent.  Personnel from EPA have been speaking about the new policy since late this summer.  As they describe it, the new policy will refine, but not significantly alter, the current reporting requirements. 
	<P>Reporting of pesticide adverse effects currently is governed by EPA's 1979 policy, 44 Fed. Reg. 40718 (July 12, 1979).  This guidance is not published in the Code of Federal Regulations (C.F.R.).  Although EPA has begun action to amend or update it several times, the 1979 Guidance remains the only interpretation of the statute currently in effect.  Generally, it requires reporting of known health effects, incidents involving nontarget organisms and series of incidents.  The reporting requirements are broader for products in reregistration. 		
<P>Remarks by EPA personnel indicate that reporting requirements under the policy being developed by EPA will be at least as broad as those under the 1979 policy.  In particular, EPA speakers have said that the new policy will: (1) require reporting many events   registrants   do   not  generally consider adverse effects; (2) require reporting perpetually on registrations that  have  been  canceled; (3)  include
an overly broad definition of pesticide and of information in the possession of registrants; and, (4) require the results of virtually all toxicology studies to be reported. 
	<P>In addition to speaking on revisions to the adverse effects reporting policy, EPA personnel also have been speaking on the adverse effects settlement it reached with DowElanco.  This enforcement action grew out of 6(a)(2) reports filed by DowElanco after media inquiries concerning claims made in personal injury litigation.  Following extensive negotiations and a settlement that was rejected by the Environmental Appeals Board, EPA and DowElanco settled for a penalty of $876,000.  EPA views this settlement as an illustration of its renewed commitment to 6(a)(2) enforcement. The high penalty amount also evidences EPA's position that reporting violations are continuing.  
	<P>The penalty paid by DowElanco was calculated under EPA's Enforcement Response Policy (ERP) (July 2, 1990).  This policy contemplates penalty reductions of up to 40 percent for voluntary disclosure of information, and a reduction of up to another 20 percent for "good faith."  The penalty paid by DowElanco reflected the 20 percent good faith reduction and a 30 percent reduction for incomplete voluntary disclosure.   		
<P>In light of the DowElanco action and EPA's stated intent to pursue 6(a)(2) reporting violations, registrants should consider whether to embark on an audit of their 6(a)(2) compliance.  By undertaking a compliance audit, registrants should be in a position to bring their compliance up to date and minimize any penalties for prior arguable violations.  In addition to the penalty reductions available under the 1990 ERP, registrants conducting compliance audits may be in a position to take advantage of the Interim Policy on Voluntary Environmental Self-Policing and Self disclosure issued by ERP on April 3, 1995. 60 Fed. Reg. 16875.
	<P>This policy is intended to encourage self policing and reporting among regulated entities.  For qualifying audits or self-evaluations, EPA will reduce significantly or might even eliminate the "gravity" component of any penalty that would otherwise apply.  Because adverse effects reports generally have only a gravity component, this can result in the complete elimination of penalties for non-reporting.  Accordingly, registrants may want to seriously consider a self-evaluation of adverse effect reporting compliance to minimize penalties for preexisting failures to report.<P>
<a href="#toc"><CENTER>Return to table of contents</CENTER></a>
<hr>

<H4 align=center><a name="bar">Barolo Intends to Start Opp Reorganization in 1996, Despite Budget Problems, and Provides Suggestions for Helping EPA</a></H4>

	<P>Daniel Barolo, Director of the Office of Pesticide Programs, recently said that OPP intends to go forward with reorganization plans in 1996, but the level of appropriations finally approved for EPA will have an impact on OPP's plans.  The reorganization is in response to the Clinton Administration's mandate to "reinvent" government, first announced in September 1993.
	<P>Federal agencies at that time were ordered to develop plans to reorganize and revamp the federal bureaucracy.  One of the requirements is the elimination of one layer of middle managers.  To implement this, OPP has to reduce the ratio of supervisors to staff to a minimum of one-to-twelve up to  one-to-twenty.  The target date for completing this phase of reinvention is the end of fiscal year 1998.  The Office also is scheduled to reduce the number of employees in senior grades (GS-14, GS-15 and Senior Executive Service) by about five to ten percent at the end of this year.
	<P>Barolo, speaking at the fall meeting of the American Crop Protection Association, said that in addition to removing a layer of management, OPP also intends to create an Antimicrobial Division, to integrate registration and reregistration   activities,   and  to  pair   science review functions with administrative functions in multidisciplinary divisions.  A first step in the reorganization was the October 13, 1995 announcement that the pilot Biopesticides and Pollution Prevention Division had been granted permanent status.
	<P>Barolo also offered suggestions to registrants on ways to help EPA enhance its ability to do its job.  These include:
	<UL><LI>Provide training opportunities for OPP staff.  This is particularly important in the face of EPA travel budget reductions.<P>
	<LI>Assist OPP staff on opportunities for automation, especially by providing OPP with the benefit of registrants' experiences with automation projects.<P>
	<LI>Submit complete registration packages, the first time.<P>
	<LI>Contribute to harmonization efforts with Canada, California and others "by jumping the CBI hurdle."  	</ul>
	<P>Claims that data are confidential business information are perceived as a significant impediment to sharing data reviews and corollary information.
	<P>Barolo also said that OPP will continue its work on "Living REDs."  This project is aimed at continuing the process, established when creating a Reregistration Eligibility Document (RED), to capture all decisions made on a pesticide active ingredient and its formulations (for example, special labeling provisions and decisions on uses and use restrictions) in a single data file.  He also said that a notice will be published in the next several months on an options paper on registrant self-certification to the acceptability of acute toxicity data submitted in support of registrations.<P>



<a href="#toc"><CENTER>Return to table of contents</CENTER></a>
<hr>
<H4 align=center><a name="fif">FIFRA Reform Bills Still Pending</a></H4>

<P>Both the House and Senate have introduced bills to reform FIFRA and the Delaney Clause (Section 409 of FFDCA), but neither bill has been reported to the floor at this time.  

<H4 align=center>H.R. 1627</H4>

	<P>The FIFRA portion of the House bill, H.R. 1627, was reported by the House Agriculture Committee in June, but the House Commerce Committee, which has jurisdiction over food safety issues, is currently marking up the FFDCA portion of the bill.  H.R. 1627 would make the following reforms to FIFRA, among others:
	<uL><LI>streamlining the pesticide cancellation process,<P>
	<LI>allowing EPA to issue an emergency suspension of a pesticide before processing cancellation of a pesticide,<P>
	<LI>expedited registration of reduced risk pesticides,<P>
	<LI>a ban on local government regulation of pesticides,<P>
	<LI>expedited reviews of antimicrobials and public health pesticides, and<P>
	<LI>providing incentives for registration of minor use pesticides.</ul>
	<P>The FFDCA section of H.R. 1627 would reform the Delaney Clause to delete its zero-risk standard and set a "negligible risk" standard for pesticides in both raw and processed foods. 
		
<H4 align=center>S. 1166</H4>

<P>	Senator Richard Lugar (R-Ind.) introduced on August 10 the proposed Food Quality Protection Act of 1995 (S. 1166), which has been referred to the Senate Agriculture Committee that Lugar chairs.  Lugar's bill is similar to H.R. 1627 in its treatment of the Delaney clause -setting a "negligible risk" standard for pesticides in  both raw and processed foods.  Under the bill, EPA would be able to consider benefits of pesticide use when setting both raw and processed food tolerances.  In the interest of promoting harmonization, the bill requires EPA, in setting tolerances, to consider whether a maximum residue level has been estimated for the pesticide by the Codex Alimentarius Commission.
<P>	Lugar's bill  also would revise FIFRA to provide relief to growers of minor use crops.  Manufacturers would be given incentives in the bill to develop new minor use pesticides and maintain minor use registrations.  Such incentives included establishing minor use offices in EPA and the USDA, extending the period during which minor use pesticide manufacturers have exclusive use of their registration data, and allowing EPA to waive minor use data requirements in some circumstances.  A separate Senate bill has been introduced on the issue of minor use (S 794).

<H4 align=center>Reregistration</H4>

	<P>According to Rep. Pat Roberts (R-Kan), Chairman of the House Agriculture Committee, H.R. 1627 may be revised to include language regarding maintenance fees.  Reregistration is funded through the $14 million in annual maintenance fees assessed on the regulated industry, but EPA's authority to assess such fees expires in 1997.  EPA has predicted it will take until 2005 to complete the reregistration process, and that another $105 million will be needed.  EPA has requested an increase in fees to cover that shortfall.
	<P>Pesticide manufacturers support a 3-year extension of the maintenance fees but do not want an increase in the $14 million annual cap on such fees, according to an August 7 letter sent to Roberts by industry groups.  The letter stated that EPA has provided no substantiation for its proposed fee increase.

<H4 align=center>GAO Report on EPA's Accountability for Reregistration Funds</H4>

	<P>The U.S. General Accounting Office (GAO) recently issued a report to Rep. Roberts outlining suggestions for revising HR 1627 in order to improve the EPA's accountability for funds spent on reregistration.  In the October 26 report to the Committee, GAO suggested means for improving both the financial reporting and the performance reporting for the EPA's reregistration effort.
	<P>GAO noted that all FIFRA reregistration and expedited processing activities are reported as part of the FIFRA Revolving Fund.  GAO suggested expanding the financial auditing of the FIFRA Fund to examine overhead allocations and performance measures.  GAO recommended that the bill before Congress be amended to require a fiscal 1996 full scope audit of the FIFRA Fund, including a requirement that the audit review "the reasonableness of the overhead allocation and the adequacy of disclosures of direct and indirect costs."
<P>The GAO report also recommended two measures for enhancing performance reporting.  The first would require EPA to prepare a schedule that covers the remainder of the reregistration process and indicates how many reregistration eligibility decisions (REDs) will be completed each year.  The second would require the agency to prepare a list of which specific chemical cases will have REDs completed during fiscal 1996, which began Oct. 1, and fiscal 1997.  The list of specific REDs would be updated every two years.  Such a schedule would help Congress assess whether EPA is properly prioritizing its reregistration efforts by working first on REDs for high-risk and high-use pesticides, known as List A chemicals, rather than working first on the lower-risk Lists B, C, and D.<P>
 <a href="#toc"><CENTER>Return to table of contents</CENTER></a>
<hr> 
<H4 align=center><a name="pes">Changes for Pesticide Exports Offered for Public Input</a></H4>

<P>	As part of its reinventing government effort U.S. EPA Office of Pesticide Programs  issued proposed changes in the regulations governing the export of registered and unregistered pesticides.  According to a publicly available option paper, the proposed program would reduce the number of pesticides for which export notices are required. EPA is proposing a "risk-based approach"  that would require export notices only "for those pesticides of greatest concern to countries:  pesticides on the international PIC [Prior Informed Consent] list, pesticides which have been nominated by the U.S. for inclusion in PIC procedures, and pesticides with active ingredients that have never been registered in the U.S."  See 60 Fed. Reg. 50,582 (Notice of Availability).
	<P>The major changes include: (1)  exempting certain unregistered products from the foreign purchaser acknowledgment statement requirements; (2) requiring exporters of registered pesticides on the U.S. and international PIC lists to submit export notices; and (3)  changing the content of the notices and the manner and frequency of the transmission, including consideration of electronic transmission of Foreign Purchaser Acknowledgment Statements.  In proposing these changes EPA has recognized what industry predicted when the current policy was announced: that the policy would create too many notices thus diluting the value of the notices.  In addition, EPA is considering steps to harmonize the pesticide export system with EPA's chemical export system under the Toxic Substances Control Act and the European Union's export policy.

<H4 align=center>EPA Exemptions Expanded</H4>

	<P>Section 17(a)(2)  of FIFRA requires that prior to export, exporters of unregistered pesticides obtain a signed statement from the foreign purchaser acknowledging that the purchaser understands that the pesticide is not registered for use in the U.S. and cannot legally be sold in the U.S.  In addition, the statute requires that a copy of the acknowledgment statement be sent to the appropriate official of the importing government. EPA is considering exempting  certain unregistered pesticide products from the requirements of Section 17(a)(2) through a rule promulgated under FIFRA section 25(b).  The exemption would include: (1)  a product not listed on the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)/ United Nations Environments Programme (UNEP) PIC procedures for banned or severely restricted  pesticides ("international PIC list); (2) a product not a U.S. candidate for inclusion on the PIC list ("U.S. PIC List"); and (3) a pesticide that does not contain an active ingredient that has never been registered in the U.S.   
	<P>The exemption from the foreign purchaser acknowledgment statement would not exempt the product from the labeling requirements for exported pesticides.  For example the label or labeling of any unregistered exported pesticide would be required to have the statement "Not Registered for Use in the United Sates of America."   The labeling requirements of EPA's 1993 Export Policy would apply, including the requirement for multi-lingual labels.  See 40 C.F.R. Part 168.
	<P>In addition, EPA would withdraw the exemption from the unregistered labeling requirements for formulations with minor composition modifications from registered pesticides.   Under the proposal, pesticides formulations with minor composition changes would be required to be labeled as unregistered pesticides in accordance with 40 C.F.R. 168.65. 

<H4 align=center>Proposal Would Increase PIC List Notifications</H4>

	<P>EPA also is considering requiring exporters of registered pesticides on the international PIC list or U.S. PIC list to file export notices with EPA.  This is a change from current law which does not require the filing of these notices for registered pesticides.   The notice would include information necessary to identify the exporter, the purchaser, the pesticide's product name and chemical identity and the country or countries of final destination. 

<H4 align=center>Reporting Changes Suggested</H4>

	<P>Currently EPA sends copies of the foreign purchaser acknowledgment statement to the person named as the recipient for pesticide notification in the international PIC program or for countries that are not participants in PIC to the appropriate embassy.  In the current proposal EPA is considering having the pesticide producers send the notice directly to the official of the importing company.  EPA recognizes the limitations of this proposal in light of the difficulty in verifying compliance and the significant reduction in EPA's ability to track information about exports. EPA also is considering requiring exporters to electronically transmit the foreign purchaser acknowledgment statement directly to the foreign government and to provide electronic or paper copies to EPA.  In neither of these approaches does EPA indicate how the pesticide producers will obtain information on the proper contact person.  Clearly EPA must provide a mechanism for identifying the proper individuals in each country to receive the notice.   In addition, EPA should set forth criteria for acceptance of the notice by the importing country. 
	<P>EPA also may require additional information on  the foreign purchaser acknowledgment statement.  EPA has proposed adding the following: information on available health and safety data for the pesticide or a point of contact for such information; the pesticide's EPA regulatory status such as any EPA tolerances; hazard classification; origin of shipment; exporter information; safety procedures; international PIC status; exporter information; and safety procedures.  
	<P>In 1993 EPA changed from requiring the foreign purchaser acknowledgment statement on an annual basis to a per shipment basis.  Pesticide   producers  have  the  option 
of obtaining a foreign purchaser acknowledgment statement prior to the first shipment to a particular purchaser and to submit to EPA an annual summary of all shipments of that product to that purchaser.  EPA plans to continue this practice. 
	<P>EPA has solicited comments from the regulated community on the proposed changes and is now reviewing the comments received.  EPA hopes to address these issues in 1996.  According to EPA, the speed with which these issues are addressed will depend in part on whether the Agency determines that formal rulemaking is required.<P>
<a href="#toc"><CENTER>Return to table of contents</CENTER></a>
<hr>

<H4><a name="epa">EPA Releases Revised Test Guidelines</a></H4>

	<P>EPA has proposed updates to pesticide test guidelines for product properties, residue chemistry, and metabolism and pharmacokinetics.  (40 CFR Part 158, Pesticide Registration Data Requirements).  The proposed guidelines are the result of a harmonization  project begun in 1990  (60 Fed. Reg. 44,343).
	<P>The goal of the multi-year project, co-chaired by the Office of Pesticide Programs and the Office of Prevention, Pesticides, and Toxic Substances, was to develop guidelines which incorporate those from OPP, OPPTS and the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.  OECD's guidelines are commonly used by other countries in registering pesticides, and EPA hopes that by incorporating those guidelines, industry can move towards completing one set of tests which would be applicable for different countries.
	<P>Some of the EPA guidelines harmonized with OECD guidelines include melting point/melting range, boiling point, vapor pressure, water solubility, partition coefficient (n-octanol/water, shake flask method), density, surface tension of aqueous solutions, partition coefficient for octanol/water--estimation by liquid chromatography.  Other guidelines were given reference updating and general editorial revision.
	<P>Other specific changes include guidelines related to color which summarizes the Munsell Color Method for opaque substances and stability which summarizes a CIPAC general method.  The guideline for oxidizing or reducing action incorporates the EPA method previously published in the Federal Register and adds a European Community Method as an option.  The flammability guideline is divided into separate tests for liquids and aerosols and adds three European Community tests as options.  A test for thermal explodability and a summary of a European Community test has been added to the guideline for explodability.  For the corrosion characteristics, EPA has deleted the ASTM method and suggested an alternate test employing visual observations.  Data reporting guidance has been added to all guidelines unique to pesticides.
	<P>The FIFRA Scientific Advisory Panel held a public meeting on September 27 to review the proposed guidelines.  At the meeting EPA provided brief presentations of the guidelines for the SAP members.  Questions were taken from the panel as well as the audience.  Some questions involved Good Laboratory Practices and which tests must be run under strict GLPs.  EPA indicated that GLPs apply to all tests.  In response to a question concerning the possible need for specificity, EPA replied that it preferred flexibility in generating data to allow for changes in the state of the art.  
	<P>After analyzing the meeting presentations, questions from the public and the proposed guidelines, the Advisory Panel issued its final report in late October.  Overall, the Panel considered the guidelines a vast improvement over those established in 1980 and cited the appropriateness of EPA's effort at harmonization.
	<P>In reference to product chemistry the Panel noted that a good balance had been developed between guidance and flexibility.  However, the guidelines need a clearer indication of which tests should be run under GLP and the Panel indicated that such information could be provided in the Preamble.  Further, the Panel indicated that the data and analytical methods generated by the tests should be made available to interested parties as quickly as possible.
	<P>Written comments on the proposed guidelines were due to EPA on or before October 31, 1995.  The comments are still being analyzed by EPA staff and further action is not expected for at least thirty days.<P>
<a href="#toc"><CENTER>Return to table of contents</CENTER></a>
<hr>

<H4 align=center><a name="upd">Updated Data Submitters List Available</a></H4>

	<P>An updated Pesticide Data Submitters List (DSL) was released by EPA on September 30, 1995.  This version adds information on data submissions since 1990, when the DSL was last updated.  However, it continues to contain outdated information and does not reflect all data submissions.  Another update is scheduled for March 1996.  A completely reissued DSL will not be available for at least another year.  
	<P>The updated DSL is available via the Internet and the Special Review and Reregistration Division's Electronic Bulletin Board. Microfiche copies can be ordered from the National Technical Information Service.  A Federal Register notice published September 27, 1995, provides additional information on availability of the DSL. 
	<P>The DSL has been periodically updated, but updates have never addressed transfers of data ownership; registrant name changes and relocations; or typographical and other information errors.  It also may be incomplete because its preparation is based on correspondence from registrants explicitly requesting inclusion.  However, the DSL reportedly does not include registrants that submitted registration data using EPA's recommended "data matrix" form, despite the form's inclusion of a section in which registrants may request placement on the DSL.  
	<P>The Office of Pesticide Programs plans to create a completely new DSL following conversion to Oracle, an interactive computer network.  The DSL will be created from OPP's Document Management System.  Registrants will have an opportunity to review and provide corrections and updates to the information before the system becomes operational.  Given the interactive structure of all OPP systems following conversion to Oracle, OPP officials anticipate that changes in data ownership, registrant names and office locations, corrections of errors and updated information on data and submitters will be routinely reflected in the DSL when the new version is available.  <P>
<a href="#toc"><CENTER>Return to table of contents</CENTER></a>
<hr>
<H4 align=center><a name="epa2">EPA Issues More Reregistration Eligibility Decisions</a></H4>

	<P>EPA in reregistering pesticides initially registered prior to November 1, 1984, must reexamine whether the pesticides meet current scientific and regulatory standards.  If not, use patterns and application methods must be modified to reduce risks to appropriate levels.  As required by FIFRA, EPA issues a Reregistration Eligibility Decision (RED) upon completion of its investigation of each chemical.  The RED summarizes the scientific assessment of the human health and environmental data bases for the chemical.  The Agency recently released REDs for the following chemicals:
	<ul><LI>Chloro-m-xylenol<br>
	<LI>Dowicil CTAC<br>
	<LI>Fosamine Ammonium<br>
	<LI>Piperalin<br>
	<LI>Polybutene<br>
	<LI>Terbuthylazine<br>
	<LI>(z)-9-Tricosene</ul>

<P>Approximately 15 additional REDs have been completed, but notice has not yet been given in the Federal Register and copies are not yet available.
	<P>In fiscal 1995 EPA completed 40 REDs.  This is an historic high, but EPA is concerned that this pace will not be sustained if budget cuts written into fiscal 1996 EPA appropriations are maintained.  The proposed cuts range between 23 and 34 percent.  Without sufficient funding, Agency staff argue that the current output will not continue and will certainly fall to 35 or 36 REDs completed next year.
	<P>The General Accounting Office submitted a report to the House Agriculture Committee relative to pending FIFRA legislation.  The report suggests that EPA develop a schedule for completion of the remaining REDs.  In addition, the schedule should prioritize the REDs so that Congress can readily determine that high-risk pesticides from List A were being completed before those on Lists B, C, and D.  (See previous article in this newsletter for details on pending FIFRA legislation.)     
	<P>Copies of the newly completed REDs or RED Fact Sheets are available from the OPP Pesticide Docket, Public Response and Program Resources Branch, Rm. 1132, 1921 Jefferson Davis Hwy., Arlington, VA; or call (703) 305-5805.<P>
<a href="#toc"><CENTER>Return to table of contents</CENTER></a>
<hr>
<H4 align=center><a name="reg">PR Notice Addresses Regulation of Methyl Bromide, Industrialized Nations Agree to Phase Out By 2010</H4>

	<P>EPA has issued a Pesticide Regulation (PR) Notice regarding the production and importation of methyl bromide.  PR Notice 95-4 also discusses the Agency's activity relative to alternatives for methyl bromide.  The future use of methyl bromide is controlled by two separate statutes and one international agreement.  First, it is a pesticide under the jurisdiction of FIFRA.  It currently is in reregistration with the last data due in late 1997.
	<P>Second, methyl bromide is subject to the Clean Air Act.   Under the CAA, EPA determines a chemical's "ozone depletion potential" (ODP).  Any chemical with an ODP greater than 0.2 is listed as a "class I ozone depleting chemical."  Methyl bromide's ODP is 0.6, requiring that it be phased out.  Beginning in 1994 production levels were frozen at 1991 levels.  Final cessation of production and importation is scheduled to occur in 2001.
	<P>Third, methyl bromide is subject to the Montreal Protocol.  In 1992 the signatories to the Protocol agreed to freeze production at 1991 levels beginning in 1995 (except for quarantine and preshipment applications) and to reduce emissions.  On December 7, following a conference of parties to the Montreal Protocol, it was agreed that industrialized nations will phase out methyl bromide use by 2010, with reductions by 25 percent and 50 percent scheduled for 2001 and 2005, respectively.  The issue of exemptions for critical agricultural use, along with a decision on phase out by developing nations, were deferred to 1997.
	<P>EPA has established the Methyl Bromide Alternatives Task Force with members from the Office of Pesticide Programs and participation from the Office of Air and Radiation and EPA Region 9.  The Task Force will coordinate FIFRA, CAA and Montreal Protocol activities, and work with USDA, commodity groups and others to develop alternatives to  methyl   bromide.  In the near term, EPA expects that already registered  pesticides  will  be replacements for methyl bromide.  However, some of these also may face regulatory difficulties.  To aid the replacement process, the Agency will expedite review of potential alternatives, especially those which may be reduced risk alternatives.
 	As    an    additional   inducement to the development of alternatives,   on   January 13,    1995, EPA  notified  state  pesticide agencies and federal agencies that future emergency exemption requests for methyl bromide made under section 18 of FIFRA must include documentation on the steps taken to find an alternative and also include a commitment to continue pursuit of alternatives. 





