<html><head><title>SUMMARY REPORT ON THE OECD AD HOC MEETING
OF EXPERTS ON CRYPTOGRAPHY</title></head>
<body><H2 align=center>Summary Report on the OECD Ad Hoc Meeting of Experts on Cryptography</H2>
<P><CENTER><I>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart A. Baker</a></I></CENTER>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>

<H4 align=center>Summary</H4>

		<P>The OECD's ad hoc meeting of experts on cryptography was the brainchild of U.S.  policymakers.  Export controls on encryption have increasingly been attacked as unworkable by U.S. software and hardware producers, who see a major market for security on the global information infrastructure.  This need, they argue, will be met by foreign producers if U.S. export controls are kept in place.  Many companies in the software business have also attacked the latest Administration proposal allowing the export of strong encryption only if it incorporates some form of key escrow.  These companies question the international demand for key escrow.
<P>The likely U.S. purpose in calling for the OECD meeting was to show that other nations are or soon will be inclined to favor key escrow in order to avoid the problems that criminal use of encryption will pose.  From the U.S. point of view, the meeting was an opportunity to raise the consciousness of other governments about the problem of uncontrolled encryption while at the same time demonstrating to U.S. industry that defeating U.S. export controls would not open the door to a vast market for unescrowed encryption but would instead spark new and perhaps inconsistent local regulation of encryption.

		<P>If that was the purpose of the meeting, it was a qualified success.  It was not a complete success, because several governments expressed grave doubts about the U.S. effort to control encryption technology.  Most prominent among the doubters were the Scandinavian countries.  Japan also showed little interest in controlling encryption;  it seemed more concerned about catching up in this former defense technology now that its commercial possibilities were growing.  

		<P>Other governments, in contrast, were supportive of some kind of escrow, though they disliked that term and preferred to speak of "trusted third party" approaches to key storage and recovery.  The European Union, the United Kingdom, and France clearly favor the development of trusted third party encryption systems.  Other countries also said favorable things about trusted third parties.  But that term is deliberately ambiguous.  It mixes together a wide variety of "trust" services for users of computer networks.  Some services, such as maintaining a register of digital signatures or providing digital timestamps, do indeed require trust but are quite uncontroversial.  At its most minimalist, support for "trusted third party" encryption might simply mean that governments will set standards that allow companies performing uncontroversial  "trust" services to also perform private key escrow when asked to do so by users of encryption systems.  Such an approach is unlikely to make escrowed encryption the dominant form of secure computer network communication.

		<P>But at least some European governments plainly mean to do more than that under the heading of trusted third party encryption.  Both Italy and the Netherlands have recently considered legislation to regulate encryption directly in the fashion of the French.  The UK is also disinclined to see the spread of uncontrolled encryption within its borders.  While these governments now seem unlikely to adopt French-style encryption regimes, they are clearly intrigued at the thought that, with government's thumb on the scale, European telecom and computer companies might be willing to adopt trusted third party encryption even without a direct government mandate.

		<P>The good news for U.S. policymakers is that many European governments are clearly interested in doing something to encourage key escrow encryption, and Australia and Canada are likely to follow if a consensus in favor of key escrow emerges.  This proposal for international concensus is bound to cause some of the most vocally anti-escrow U.S. companies at least a moment of self-doubt.  

		<P>The bad news for U.S. policymakers is that there is little appetite in Europe (let alone Japan) for direct regulation of the encryption market (even the French are showing more flexibility in enforcing their law).  And some European governments' commitment to trusted third party encryption may not go beyond saying nice things about it while waiting to see what the market does.

<P>For a variety of reasons, the OECD is likely to be drawn into the process of making international encryption policy.  The U.S. was generally pleased with the warmth -- if not the ambiguity -- of the international praise for trusted third party encryption, and it hopes to build a stronger international consensus for such encryption.  Industry, particularly U.S. industry, would rather see policy made in the OECD than in a (presumptively more protectionist) European forum.  And the other OECD nations see that forum as a good place to moderate unilateral U.S. policies, such as the current requirement that keys be escrowed in the United States.  Thus all of the participants have something to gain from continuing the dialogue in the OECD.
<H4 align=center>The Meeting In Detail</H4>

		<P>The meeting was opened by the head of the OECD's science, technology and communications division.

		<P>In a carefully orchestrated set of nominations and seconds, Mike Nelson of the United States was elected Chairman of the meeting.

<P>The U.S. then opened with a description of its cryptographic policy and initiatives.  The U.S. delegation was rounded out by representatives of the Business Software Alliance and representatives of the National Research Council panel on cryptography, which is due to finish its report within a few months and was trying to get a better handle on international aspects of encryption policy.  Also attending from the U.S. were several private representatives named to the Business-Industry Advisory Committee (BIAC).

</OL>

		<ol><LI><B><I>United States</I></B>

		<P>The opening statements on U.S. policy were unsurprising for anyone who has followed developments here.  The U.S. said that the growth of the GII has meant growing demand and supply in the security field.  Key escrow appeals to the U.S. government as a "third way."  The U.S. expressed keen interest in the approaches of other countries, particularly toward "trusted third party" concepts.

		<P>The floor was then opened to a series of (mostly skeptical) questions from other nations.  Japan led off, asking how effective an key escrow system could be.  "Won't criminals simply use their own systems?" Japan asked.  In addition, in a question that suggested the Japanese had not closely followed recent developments in U.S. policy, the Japanese delegate questioned the wisdom of using a classified algorithm for international security solutions.  The U.S. noted that the spread of escrow would make it harder but not impossible for crooks to develop alternative systems.  And the U.S. explained that Clipper used a classified algorithm but that the latest initiative was algorithm-neutral. 

		<P>The Dutch asked for an explanation of who could be an escrow agent and who would make that decision.  The U.S. referred generally to the criteria recently released on this topic.  None of the other governments made an issue of the U.S. criteria that disqualify foreign-owned firms from being escrow agents (at least for products sold in the U.S.) and require a security clearance for escrow agents.	

		<P>Finland returned to the idea of criminals making their own encryption.  Finland also noted that all cryptosystems have been broken in the long run and that introducing a weakness like key escrow was risky.

		<P>The UK representative noted that the rest of the world has been behind the U.S. in struggling with this issue.  "What's the next step from the U.S. point of view?" he asked.  The U.S. said that implementing the 64-bit escrowed encryption policy is the next step.

		<P>The European Commission asked for a timetable, and the U.S. said that the policy should be formally adopted by February 1996.  The U.S. also acknowledged that the 64-bit limit has been widely attacked.  The U.S. defended it on two grounds.  "As a practical matter, it will protect our data for the rest of our lives.  And we are taking a risk in allowing software exports when the problem of binding the algorithm to the escrow is so difficult in software."

		<P>Denmark expressed the view that it could get the contents of encrypted communications between crooks and their bank by going to the bank for the data.  It thought that key escrow would likely be redundant for interceptions that require a court order.  (It also hinted at a suspicion that the real plan was to use escrow to facilitate intercepts that don't use court orders, such as foreign intelligence-gathering.)  The U.S. countered by pointing out that the bank might be in Panama or the Caymans.<P>

		<LI><B><I>European Community</I></B>

		<P>The next presentation was the European Commission (EC).  The EC began by laying out the Commission's responsibilities in the field.  This is by no means uncontroversial.  While there are a number of law enforcement initiatives within the European Union, the bureaucrats of the Commission have been excluded from them.  Instead, the bureaucracies of member states work out the arrangements themselves.  On the other hand, the Commission has been active in information security, telecom, and even export controls.  On the whole, the Commission is in charge of industries and issues that are benefited by the spread of encryption and not in charge of interests that are hurt by the spread of encryption.  This makes it less enthusiastic about controlling encryption than member states like the UK and France.  (In an odd way, the division of responsibilities and resulting conflicts are reminiscent of the conflicting duties and views of NIST and NSA.)

		<P>The second slide laid out the Commission's organization,  including the infosec calling of DG XIII.  DG XV is also mentioned.  It is a rival organization.  It is in charge of ensuring a genuine common market, and as such is perhaps even more responsive to business than DG XIII.  Hallway speculation suggested that DG XIII was losing the turf battle with DG XV over the encryption issue and that this would be good for business interests and bad for those who wanted to control encryption.  As an example, the DG XV rules on privacy of telecommunications evidently require -- or nearly require -- that encryption be installed on telecom lines within three years.

		<P>The EC next laid out the fundamental principles that a government encryption "solution" must meet.  It must be secure and trusted.  It must be tested by neutral parties (presumably in the government or through peer review).  Downloaded software, the Commission emphasized, would never provide trusted security.  The EC stressed voluntary use, saying that mandates would fail.  The EC explained the international perspective as requiring regional "sovereignty sharing" arrangements because the alternative was to lose sovereignty entirely.  To make the product work, the EC said, it would have to be legally as well as technically effective.  By this the Commission meant that governments would have to create a legal framework for digital signatures and escrow agents.  And the EC put expansion of the 64-bit limit under the category of "future enhancement" that would be needed eventually but perhaps not now.

		<P>Finally,  the EC offered what it described as an informal consensus of European Union countries on their preferred solution.  The solution would be to create a collection of Trusted Third Party (TTP) services -- certification of digital signatures, revocation of same, notarization, timestamping, and key escrowing.  The TTPs would be several and would be independent of each other and probably of governments.  This idea will be proposed by the Commission in January or February for adoption by the European Council.  Procedurally, any such step must first go to the European Parliament for its opinion and then to the Council.  If accepted there, a total of eighteen countries would be behind the idea.

		<P>Implementation of the TTP notion will require political consensus, trials of pilot services, and passage of laws to create the necessary framework for TTPs.  The Commission plans to finance trials of some of the technology.  It expects governments and industry to do most of the work in developing specific proposals.  And it foresees a need for international action that would create a framework for trusted transactions.  The Commission's sketch of such a framework envisioned trusted parties negotiating across borders with each other and then "sponsoring" their users for trusted transactions.   			
		<P>There were relatively few questions in response to the Commission presentation.  Finland noted that testing the strength of an encryption system meant more than looking at key length.  Norway asked whether the TTP concept included key escrow.  The Commission said that it did but that the term key escrow was not used because it had been tainted by Clipper.  The U.S. asked whether the U.S. approach was compatible with the European TTP approach.  At a technical level, The Commission declared, it was too early to tell, because the EC approach wasn't mature as a technical matter.  On a policy level, it thought the EC approach was more focused on providing security than on guaranteeing law enforcement access and that it was more focused on meeting market demand than the U.S. proposal.<P>

		<LI><B><I>Canada</I></B>

		<P>By way of background, Canada described the unenthusiastic reaction given to Clipper by a blue ribbon commission of Canadians.  The advisory council, established in 1994, set forth several principles for data security.  First, a basic level of security is essential for the data highway.  The precise amount of security should be matched to the value of the data protected.  Second, there must be balance between security and law enforcement interests.  Again, how to achieve balance was not spelled out, but Clipper and similar key escrow approaches were rejected on grounds of Canadian sovereignty (presumably because of U.S. government access to keys).  Third, standards should by open, corporations should be free to adopt their own solutions, and algorithms should be freely available (another slam at Clipper).  Fourth, the security infrastructure would require standards and a government oversight body to foster the public key infrastructure (PKI).  Fifth, and finally, the group called for review and revision of Canadian law to give effect to digital signatures and the like.

		<P>On the critical question of whether encryption should use escrow, Canada clarified, the report made no recommendation.  Escrow was not ruled out, but allowing one government to hold the keys was not acceptable.  The Canadian government has not yet responded formally to the report, but it is expected to accept it soon and to begin implementing the recommendations.

		<P>The Canadian government's plans for PKI were then presented.  The presentation was impressive in terms of the extent of implementation already undertaken by Canada.  But the extent to which it actually addresses the concept of encryption for privacy is open to question.

		<P>The Canadian PKI scheme envisions a single public management authority (PMA) that would approve a wide variety of certification authorities, such as major corporations.  (The PMA will be the oversight body.) There will not be a single Canadian root.  The PKI will require interoperability.  And it appears that Nortel will be at the center of the Canadian plan.  It will apparently be part of the first implementation, which will take place over the next two years and will involve 175,000 users.

		<P>The French immediately asked how all this would control encryption.  The Canadian answer was unclear.  Data recovery services will be possible in the Canadian scheme, but there is no sign that the government will encourage such services.

		<P>The Dutch asked about whether Canada planned privacy legislation.  Canada said that it would probably enact "light" rules following the OECD guidelines.  The Dutch also asked about an Ontario study touching on anonymous signatures, and Canada said that the Ontario recommendation was being taken seriously but that no decision had been made about when anonymous signatures would be recognized or enabled.

		<P>The EC expressed admiration for the extent of Canada's progress but suggested that the solution was quite nationally focused.  "How do you plan to interoperate with the U.S.?"  The response, a bit vague, was that issues would no doubt arise and had not been answered yet.  Canada believes its system is compatible with European TTP proposals.

		<P>The UK asked whether Canada was rejecting the idea of escrowing keys or just Clipper.  Canada said the concern was sovereignty and the idea of a U.S.-centered escrow system.  The report's endorsement of balance would suggest some kind of escrow system, Canada thought, but law enforcement had not yet clearly stated what it required.<P>

		<LI><B><I>United Kingdom</I></B>

		<P>The UK presentation picked up several earlier themes, starting with the invocation of a need for "balance" in data security between security needs and law enforcement needs.  "We can't dodge the issue or solve it using export controls," the UK said.  The balance requirement had been adopted in an interim report of a departmental committee to Ministers, and the Ministers have approved the report.  The report also recommends implementation of a TTP network with key escrow.  The report envisions TTPs responding to government intercept orders or warrants by providing encryption keys.

		<P>UK Ministers asked for more specificity on the TTP/escrow approach.  Lots of industry consultation is planned.  Royal Holloway College in London has also developed a new architecture for a possible escrow-TTP approach.  Any TTP approach would no doubt include timestamping, digital signatures and other services in addition to key retrieval.

		<P>The Dutch noted that the UK had foreseen a need to answer legal questions.  What legal questions?  The UK answered that there was some doubt whether UK law, which refers specifically to intercepting communications, could be applied without amendment to key retrieval.  Further, some new authority may be needed to license TTPs.  Ditto for the process of verifying signatures.

		<P>What about liability? asked the U.S.  The UK agreed that this was another unanswered question.

		<P>Finland asked how the UK would evaluate encryption strength.  The UK representative said that the government will not mandate crypto systems. Finland also asked whether a TTP, which is clearly useful for some purposes, was really needed for key retrieval.  The UK said that the government hoped TTPs would be used for key storage.

		<P>Austria and Denmark asked a series of questions:  "What happens when TTPs go out of business?  Will unlicensed TTPs be permitted?  What about TTPs that refuse to obey court orders or warn the user when they receive court orders?"  The UK said keys would have to be transferred if the TTP failed.  The question of licensing TTPs is not yet decided, but it will probably be necessary for TTPs that want to provide digital signature services.  All TTPs will be required to surrender keys if they want to get and keep such licenses.  The Danish representative observed that this wasn't much of a threat for a small TTP that was willing to give up its license, perhaps because it was originally established to serve a criminal enterprise.  Austria raised the prospect of the Mafia buying up a TTP.  The UK noted that under UK law anyone who hinders the police in doing their duty has committed a prosecutable offense, so the threat of license withdrawal is not the only enforcement mechanism.<P>

		<LI><B><I>Japan</I></B>

		<P>Japan's presentation is the subject of a separate paper.  Briefly summarized,  the Japanese brought by far the largest delegation, yet they included no police or national security representatives.  The presentations all suggested that Japan is taking seriously the publicity stressing the importance of good security for networked digital commerce.  It apparently has not taken seriously the threat to law enforcement's capabilities.  Unless the OECD conference leads to some rethinking of Japan's position,  it will not provide much encouragement to TTP or escrow solutions. (Concerns about tax evasion -- probably more focused on digital cash than encryption for privacy -- offer the only faint sign that Japan will rethink its position.)  The Japanese representative even offered the view that encryption systems not designed for government use should not be subject to export controls.

		<P>The U.S. delegation asked whether Japan now controls exports of encryption products and was told that it does, under the remnants of CoCom.  The decision about what's exportable is now made on an individual basis.<P>

		<LI><B><I>Australia</I></B>

		<P>Australia's position shadowed earlier European views.  Australia has generated two new reports on encryption this year.  So far, all the focus has been on using encryption to enhance privacy.  New privacy legislation is likely to drive companies toward greater use of encryption.  The Prime Minister has evidently asked for more study of the law enforcement impact of encryption.  But the Australian status report is unsympathetic to large-scale modification of encryption technology for law enforcement.  Instead, it suggests relying on warrants requiring decryption, a solution that will likely require a review of the rules against self incrimination.  Australia expressed little interest in intervening in the market to encourage greater use of TTPs for key retrieval, although it expects TTPs in general to be an important institution in electronic commerce.  TTPs will mostly regulate themselves, although some government oversight (perhaps including liability rules) is likely, and an antitrust exemption may be needed so that TTPs can work together.

		<P>In questions after the presentation, the UK asked how Australia's approach would allow the government to get keys from crooks, and Australia acknowledged that it would not.  Denmark offered the observation that in some circumstances the Danish courts will shift the burden of proof to the defendant if he does not provide certain kinds of evidence that is within his control.  The U.S. asked whether Australia has any TTPs now and whether Australians will embrace the use of TTPs for data retrieval.  Australia's representative could not say.<P>

		<LI><B><I>Italy</I></B>

		 <P>The Italian Interior Ministry recently made two proposals for legislation restricting encryption.  Neither passed, and passage now seems unlikely.  In other respects, Italy is typical of Europe.  It has controls on encryption exports, both under a 1990 (military devices) and a 1992 law (high technology) as well as under the new EU-wide export control regime. A 1994 decree defines encryption for export control purposes.

		<P>Italy also has authority over informatics policy and security policy.  It apparently has not pursued the idea of linking TTPs to key escrow.  The "technical" presentation by the Italian telecom company, STET, addressed policy issues in only a limited way, expressing a preference for a single international approach to encryption, expressing doubts about whether TTPs will hold keys if that makes the system seem weaker, and pointing out that monitoring communications to interdict unescrowed encryption is very difficult.

		<P>In response to a U.S. question, the Italian representative said he was unaware of any criminal probes defeated by use of encryption, but he reported that the Mafia was thought to be seeking access to strong U.S. encryption for its communications.

		<P>This led Austria to ask whether anyone knew of cases of crooks using encryption.  Denmark reported one case.  Holland reported a case of suspected terrorists using high-grade encryption; when pressed for information about how the case turned out, the Dutch representative simply said, "The encryption gave us a lot of trouble."  The U.S. reported that out of 350 computer evidence investigations last year, encryption turned up in 2% of the cases (that's seven matters by my count).<P>

		<LI><B><I>Switzerland</I></B>

		<P>Switzerland is concerned about computer intrusions and has strong privacy rules.  So far, it has not encouraged TTPs for key storage because of security concerns.  It has no answers to the law enforcement problem.  That's why it is participating in the experts' meeting.<P>

		<LI><B><I>The Netherlands</I></B>

		<P>The Dutch delegation indicated that domestic encryption controls are under consideration.  (A draft bill to restrict encryption was released prematurely in 1994 and produced such controversy that it was withdrawn, according to the hallway discussions.)  The restrictions might act like gun control, giving licenses for strong encryption to good citizens who show a need for it.  Other possibilities include a requirement that telecom companies offering encryption services provide decryption to the police when necessary and a requirement that citizens decrypt information that they have encrypted when that is necessary for purposes of a criminal investigation.   None of this has reached the level of legislation or even a formal proposal.<P>

		<LI><B><I>Norway</I></B>

		<P>Norway is planning to deploy a hardware-based security system for government and private use that will not be escrowed and will not use a public algorithm.<P>

		<LI><B><I>General Discussion</I></B>

		<P>The EC offered some principles that should illuminate the question of liability for TTPs.  First, strict government licensing is likely and will reduce liability concerns.  Second, security solutions will be reviewed and formally certified.  Third, TTPs will use strong crypto.  Fourth, key-splitting is an important safety/security feature.  Fifth, it is possible that compliance with law enforcement warrants will be required for TTPs that get the benefit of the government's liability-reducing initiatives.

		<P>Italy expressed the view that key-escrow systems will not work unless the public is persuaded that they offer good security.

		<P>Sweden stated that it was not clear whether government had a role in shaping encryption technology, and that establishing international rules will be much harder than establishing national rules.  At a national level, government can set an information technology framework, set standards, evaluate security, and encourage TTPs. Sweden sees the need for a balanced solution, but it has no national legislation on the point.  It is engaged in a plan for large-scale electronic procurement using smart cards.

		<P>Norway's representative expressed doubts about the wisdom of focusing on the use of TTPs for key escrow.  He thought this might be counterproductive.  TTPs are needed with or without key retrieval functions.  The biggest need is just to get good encryption on the market.

		<P>The UK, which was among the more supportive governments toward U.S. policy, nonetheless expressed the view that using U.S. export control laws to require that keys be escrowed in the U.S. would be a problem for the UK government.

		<P>Finland said that it was still in the process of developing policy in the encryption field, but it expressed considerable coolness toward escrow proposals.

		<P>Scott Charney of the U.S. delegation presented detailed data about the extent of computer intrusions in the U.S., laid out the need for encryption, and then pointed out the practical risks.  He indicated that the threat of encrypting or otherwise destroying computerized data was being used today in the U.S. and gave examples.  One small U.S. city, for example, had all of its data encrypted by an unknown hacker.

		<P>Australia stressed that any international solution must allow for interoperability and must keep data secure while it crosses borders.  Escrow systems will have difficulty working in an international context.</OL>

<H4 align=center>Conclusions</H4>

		<P>At the meeting's close, the Chair sought and obtained the agreement of the group to a variety of steps aimed at building on the dialogue of the past day and a half.

		<P>First, he noted the principles suggested by the European Commission representative as necessary for any escrow or TTP encryption system.  He suggested that they be formalized and distributed to the member governments.  These may form the basis of further refinement if the OECD process moves forward on encryption.

		<P>Next, the Chair distributed questions for each government to bear in mind and perhaps answer at any follow-up meeting.  The  OECD was at pains to emphasize that this was not to be an official OECD questionnaire as that term is ordinarily understood in the organization.

		<P>Third, the Chair and the OECD staff proposed a path forward for continued OECD action on encryption.  A February 9 meeting in Canberra will allow an hour or two of discussion by the experts group formed to consider such issues as intellectual property, data protection, and security on information networks.  This is time enough to consider a proposal for further work on the issue by a more official group.  The likely result of the February 9 meeting is approval of a work plan on encryption that could be considered and approved in March.
<P>

<hr>
