<html><head><title>Richard H. Porter</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Richard H. Porter</h2>
<blockquote><center>Civil Litigation | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/insuranc.htm">Insurance/Reinsurance</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/antitrst.htm">Trade Regulation and Antitrust</a><br>Administrative Law | Internal Investigations | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/govtcont.htm">Government Contracts</a></center></blockquote>
<hr>


<P>
Mr. Porter specializes in complex litigation and arbitration, corporate governance and internal corporate investigations.  His work on behalf of insurers and reinsurers involves matters ranging from coverage issues to fraud.  He has conducted numerous internal investigations for corporations concerned with fraud, employee misconduct and other issues.<P>
<P>
With other members of the firm, he represented Alyeska Pipeline Service Company in environmental litigation relating to the construction of the Trans Alaska Pipeline.  He represented Atlantic Richfield Company in <U>In Re Exxon Corp., et al.</U>, a complex administrative antitrust proceeding before the Federal Trade Commission.  He represented Burlington Northern in a monopolization case before the United States District Court for the District of Wyoming.  In addition, Mr. Porter has represented clients in commercial and contract litigation, as well as in litigation arising out of federal price control regulation.<P>
<P>
He came to Steptoe &amp; Johnson in 1971 after serving as a legislative staff assistant to Senator Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts and completing a three year military assignment as Assistant to the General Counsel of the Army.  He has been a partner of the firm since 1976.<P>
<P>
Mr. Porter is a member of the Bars of the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia, the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, the United States Claims Court, and the Supreme Court of the United States.<P>
<P>
His publications include:  &quot;Voluntary Disclosure to Federal Agencies - Their Impact on The Ability of Corporations to Protect From Discovery Materials Developed During the Course of Internal Investigations&quot;, 39 <U>Catholic U.L. Rev.</U> (1990); &quot;Minimizing the Cost of Complex Litigation,&quot; 28 <U>Law Office Econ. &amp; Mgmt.</U> 83 (1987); &quot;The Federal Trade Commission v. The Oil Industry:  An Autopsy on the Commission's Shared Monopoly Case Against the Nation's Eight Largest Oil Companies,&quot; 27 <U>Antitrust Bulletin</U> 753 (1982); &quot;Agreements In Restraint of Trade - The Sherman Act&quot;, Chap. 48A, <U>Williston On Contracts</U>, (3d ed.); &quot;Analysis of the Comptroller of The Currency's Approval of a Merger Involving the Security Trust Company and the Mercantile Trust Company National Association of St. Louis, Missouri&quot;, 54 <U>Geo. L.J.</U> 686 (1966).<P>
<P>
Mr. Porter is active in a large number of civic and charitable organizations.  He has served on the Board of Governors of the Georgetown University Alumni Association, as President and Chairman of the Board of the Langley School in McLean, Virginia, and is a Coordinator for So Others Might Eat, a not-for-profit organization that provides meals and other services to the homeless in the District of Columbia.<P>
<P>
<P></p><ul><LI>Georgetown University J.D. 1967 magna cum laude
<LI>Georgetown Law Review B.S.B.A. cum laude, 1964</ul>
