<html>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>1995 ENCRYPTION POLICY DEVELOPMENTS
</HEAD>
</TITLE>
<body><H3 align=center>1995 ENCRYPTION POLICY DEVELOPMENTS</H3>

<CENTER><I>By <a href="http://www.us.net/~steptoe/baker.htm">Stewart A. Baker</a></I></CENTER>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>

<h4>The Gore Letter</h4>
<blockquote><P>In his July 20, 1994 letter to Congresswoman Cantwell, Vice President Gore expressed considerable interest in private key escrow alternatives to the Clipper chip:  "The Administration understands the concerns the industry has regarding the Clipper chip.  We welcome the opportunity to work with industry to design a more versatile, less-expensive system.  Such a key escrow scheme would be implementable in software, firmware or hardware, or any combination thereof, would not rely on a classified algorithm, would be voluntary and would be exportable.  While there are many severe challenges to developing such a system, we are committed to a diligent effort with industry and academics to achieve such a system . . . .  We also recognize that a new key escrow encryption system must permit the use of private sector key escrow agents as one option."
<P>Gore's letter promised immediate action:  "We agree that we need to take action this year to insure that over time American companies are able to include information security features in their program in order to maintain their international competitiveness.  We can achieve this by entering into a new phase of cooperation among government, industry representatives and privacy advocates with a goal of trying to develop a key escrow encryption system that will provide strong encryption, be acceptable to computer users worldwide, and address our national security needs as well."
<P>Fifteen months later, where are we?  
<P><OL><LI>On August 17, 1995 White House aide Mike Nelson announced the Administration's private key escrow policy:  encryption software with a 64-bit key length, an adequate key escrow function, and escrow with a government-approved key escrow agents will be exportable.  <P>
<LI>Nelson called for a series of public and private meetings between government and industry in September 1995 to determine the criteria by which the exportability of key escrow encryption will be decided.  NIST also requested public input on a possible key escrow Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS). 
</OL></blockquote>


<h4>Grassley Legislation</h4>
<blockquote><P>Senator Grassley (Republican - Iowa), introduced S. 974, the Anti-Electronic Racketeering Act of 1995 on June 27, 1995.  The bill has raised controversy because it would impose criminal liability for the dissemination of any encryption software to foreign nationals, irrespective of the software's exportability.  
<P>The legislation is intended to close the Zimmerman loophole -- the legislation would impose criminal liability or a person if he knew or reasonably should have known that the computer network on which an encryption program was posted is "accessible to foreign nationals and foreign governments."  
<P>Grassley's bill incorporates, albeit crudely, the key escrow concept:  the bill would provide a defense to criminal liability if the person prosecuted established that "the software at issue used a universal decoding devise or program that was provided to the Department of Justice prior to the distribution."
<P>Grassley's bill, apparently drafted without Administration input (or for that matter, crypto-expert input), will not likely be a priority on the crowded legislative agenda in the Fall of 1995.</blockquote>

<h4>Terrorism Legislation</h4>
<P>In response to the bombing of the federal building in Oklahoma City, some members of the Administration advocated, but did not specify in concrete public proposals, restraints on the use of encryption in the United States.  
<blockquote>	<P>FBI Director Louis Freeh repeatedly stated that Congress must "deal" with encryption.  Freeh testified to Congress:  "Encryption capabilities available to criminals and terrorists endanger the future usefulness of court-authorized wiretaps.  We must continue working to address this problem."  Statement before the House Judiciary Committee's Subcommittee on Crime, May 3, 1995.  In internal Administration debates over the past several years, law enforcement is known to have advocated mandatory key escrow in the U.S.   See generally, Electronic Privacy Information Center, August 16 Press Release (analyzing fruits of its FOIA request for encryption policy documents).  
<P>Deputy Attorney General Jamie Gorelick spoke favorably of mandatory key escrow even for domestic users of encryption at public debates on the topic, but Justice made no public proposal for mandatory key escrow.
<P>No action:  The Administration kept domestic encryption controls out of the terrorism bill.  According to Director Freeh, the Administration needed more time to reach a consensus:  "We need a lot of help [with encrypted communications], and we need it very quickly.  As I said, we are working hard on the Administration to resolve this problem, but if not resolved, we will not have an effective counter-terrorism strategy, nor will we have an effective counter-criminal strategy is a very short time . . . I think right now what we need to do is resolve within the Administration some issues and have a consensus as to what we need.  The question of whether legislation is needed is a question which is not resolved yet.  Perhaps down the road there will be issues for the Congress to take up."  Transcript of May 3, 1995 Hearing of the House Judiciary Committee's Crime Subcommittee.</blockquote>

<h4>Gore Task Force Report</h4>
<blockquote><P>Vice President Gore's National Information Infrastructure Task Force's report on NII security issues, released in June 1995, was quite favorable to key escrow.  The report suggested that "private sector approaches being developed to meet the needs of corporate key escrow may also benefit government, both as a user and in its law enforcement responsibilities."  Report at 22.
<P>The Report recommended government promotion of private key escrow:  the government should "continue to work with industry to develop alternative key escrow technologies, to make available standards and technology for public use, to develop methods for providing compatibility among different key escrow technologies, and to consider ways to promote use of such technologies overseas."  Report at 28. </blockquote>

<h4>OTA Report to Congress</h4>
<blockquote>	<P>In its June 1995 report to Congress, the Office of Technology Assessment also lauded the prospects of commercial key escrow.  "Being able to export key escrow encryption products would presumably make escrowed encryption products more attractive to commercial developers and users.  Therefore, the Clinton Administration could ease export requirements for products with integrated key escrowing as an incentive for the commercial development and adoption of such products."  
<P>The OTA Report included favorable descriptions of proposed private key escrow systems, including those of Trusted Information Systems and Bankers Trust.</blockquote>

<h4>Private Industry Turns Up The Heat</h4>
<blockquote><P>Computer Systems Policy Project:  CSPP met with senior Administration officials and urged serious consideration of commercial key escrow as an acceptable answer to U.S. industry and government.  
<P>Trusted Information Systems:  TIS has proposed a software system that would embed a data recovery field (DRF) in every encrypted file.  The private key is automatically stored in a data recovery center (DRC), which law enforcement can access with a valid search warrant.  Data Recovery Centers can be maintained within a company or with an outside escrow agent.  In an effort to improve the prospects for export authorization, TIS has included in the software check-sums to defeat user efforts to disable the Data Recovery Field function.  TIS reportedly has sought export authorization for escrowed software containing 56-bit DES.
<P>National Semiconductor:  National Semiconductor, in coordination with Trusted Information Systems, has designed a hardware-based system:  Commercial Automated Key Escrow (CAKE).  The hardware solution, because it is tamper-proof, counterfeit-proof and difficult to disable could prove more attractive to law enforcement than software alternatives.  Similar to the TIS software system, the National Semiconductor CAKE system involves a data recovery field in each message and a data recovery center maintained within a corporation or with an outside agent.  The proposed hardware is a PersonaCard, a tamper-resistant PCMCIA token.  
<P>Bankers Trust:  Bankers Trust has proposed a hardware-based key escrow system that will allow customers wide choice among algorithms and escrow agents.  User-generated private keys will be escrowed automatically and can be "split" between one or more escrow agent designated by the user.  Central to the system is the user's ability to store key fragments with multiple escrow agents, thereby reducing the risk of private key compromise.  Bankers Trust intends to qualify as a key escrow agent.
Hewlett Packard:  Hewlett Packard's key escrow architecture is designed to accommodate developments in cryptographic algorithms and government policies.  The Hewlett Packard system would involve three components:  a tamper-resistant cryptographic unit to which algorithms could be uploaded and in which private keys would be stored; a policy card needed to enable the cryptographic unit and programmable to comply with any applicable government restrictions (i.e., the policy card could only enable algorithms in the cryptographic unit which were approved by the government); and a network security driver.</blockquote>

<h4>Leading Academics</h4>
<blockquote><P>According to Lance Hoffman of George Washington University's Institute for Computer and Telecommunications Policy, "key escrow systems can provide escrowed encryption that is more sensitive to the balance between the citizen and government than the flawed clipper initiative."  Balanced Key Escrow (August 4, 1995).  
<P>Georgetown Professor Dorothy Denning has also been a strong advocate of commercial key escrow, and has written on the important but rarely discussed international aspects of key escrow.</blockquote>

<h4>White House Announces Administration Policy</h4>
<blockquote><P>At the August 17, 1995 cryptography policy workshop sponsored by the Software Publishers Association and the American Electronics Association, the Administration announced a new export authorization policy for commercial key escrow encryption products:  strong encryption software with an acceptable key escrow function will be exportable.  Software (and probably hardware) eligible for export could contain 64-bit key encryption, including DES.
<P>The Administration scheduled two public meetings in September to develop criteria and guidelines for determining when the escrow function is acceptable and to determine what the criteria should be for key escrow agent eligibility.  Government use of key escrow encryption is also under discussion.
<P>NIST and NSA will determine if a given key escrow system is properly designed and contains a adequate key escrow function.  Central to this determination will be the binding procedure.   NIST, NSA and other agencies will have input on the issue of escrow agent certification.
<P>If a key escrow software product qualifies for exportability after a one-time NSA review, export authorization jurisdiction will be shifted from the State Department to the Commerce Department.  As a result, exporters will not require individual validated licenses, but will merely be required to file quarterly reports with Commerce regarding the dollar value exported to each country.  (This is the same procedure as currently required for exports of mass-market software containing 40-bit RC-4.)
<P>Government officials making the announcement emphasized the need for the U.S. government to support U.S. exports of key escrow encryption products.  Those countries with strict controls on domestic use of encryption will be encouraged to approve for domestic use all key escrow products exported from the U.S.</blockquote>
<P>

<hr>
<P>Copyright 1996 Steptoe & Johnson LLP 
<blockquote><P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP grants permission for the  contents of this publication to be reproduced and distributed in full free of charge, provided that:  (i) such reproduction and distribution is limited to educational and professional non-profit use only (and not for advertising or other use); (ii) the reproductions or distributions make no edits or changes in this publication; and (iii) all reproductions and distributions include the name of the author(s) and the copyright notice(s) included in the original publication.
<P>Requests for permission to copy portions of the document should be directed to:  <a href="mailto:wbatterton@steptoe.com">wbatterton@steptoe.com</A></blockquote>

<hr>
