<html><head><title>Robert E. Jordan III Bio</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>
Robert E. Jordan III</h2>

<blockquote><center>Major Litigation | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/ferc.htm">Energy Law</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/antitrst.htm">Antitrust Law</a><br>Ethics and Professional Responsibility </center></blockquote>

<P>Bob Jordan has been a partner at Steptoe & Johnson LLP since resigning as General Counsel of the Department of the Army in 1971.  In 1987-88 he served as President of The District of Columbia Bar, a position to which he was elected by the members of that Bar.

<P>Since joining Steptoe & Johnson LLP, Mr. Jordan has managed a number of major litigation matters in state and federal courts and before federal and state administrative agencies.  He led the litigation team in the major environmental suit regarding construction of the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System, led the litigation team for Atlantic Richfield Company in the FTC antitrust challenge to the structure of the petroleum industry in 1973-81, served as lead counsel for ARCO Pipe Line Company in a series of major proceedings involving oil pipeline rates in 1977-81, and has served as lead counsel in a variety of other major cases involving the valuation of oil from the North Slope of Alaska and DOE regulation of energy pricing.  In 1989-90, he has represented ARCO Chemical Company in a major acquisition challenged by the Federal Trade Commission.

<P>Since 1991, he has represented Alyeska Pipeline Service Company and the owners of the Trans Alaska Pipeline System in a series of Congressional investigations, whistleblower litigation and major
court actions. 

<P>Mr. Jordan is a confirmed computer buff, and has since 1974 pioneered in the application of computer technology to the organization and management of complex litigation matters.

<P>Mr. Jordan has also become a specialist in the law regarding federal conflicts of interest and legal ethics involving lawyers. He served as Chair of the Legal Ethics Committee of The District of Columbia Bar in 1978-81, and has served since 1983 as Chair of the Bar's Special Committee on the Model Rules of Professional Conduct.  He also counsels lawyers and law firms and other clients on federal conflict of interest law and ethics issues, and litigates such matters.

<P><DIR><LI> Harvard University J.D. 1961, magna cum laude, Editor, Harvard Law Review
<LI> Massachusetts Institute of Technology S.B. 1958</DIR>
<p><blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Area Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></center></body></html>
