<html><head><title>Stephen L. Sulzer Bio</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Stephen L. Sulzer</h2>
<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/intellip.htm">Intellectual Property</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/antitrst.htm">Antitrust</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/intltrad.htm">International Trade
</a></center></blockquote>
<hr>




<P>Stephen Sulzer's practice focuses on intellectual property,
particularly enforcement and licensing of patents and other
intellectual property rights in a wide range of technologies,
related antitrust litigation and counseling, Section 337
proceedings before the U.S. International Trade Commission, and
alternative dispute resolution, including mediation and
arbitration.  Mr. Sulzer has been trial counsel in numerous
federal court and ITC proceedings, including several of the ITC's
most significant Section 337 investigations.  He has represented
clients in enforcement and licensing of intellectual property in
all areas of optical disc technology, and in such diverse
technical areas as color electronic pre-press equipment,
satellite technology, machine tools, automotive components, power
generation equipment, paper products and packaging, and
pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>Mr. Sulzer has written extensively on intellectual property and
antitrust issues, and he is an instructor for Patent Resources
Group, Inc. in its patent litigation and appellate practice
courses.  
</P>
<P>Mr. Sulzer was a Senior Investigative Attorney from 1985 to 1988
at the U.S. International Trade Commission, and was a partner at
Cushman Darby & Cushman, LLP, until October 1995.  He is a member
of the Bar of the District of Columbia and is admitted to
practice before the United States Supreme Court, the U.S. Court
of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, and several other federal
trial and appellate court bars.  
</P>
<p></p><dir><l1>Emory University School of Law
  J.D., 1980
  Member, Board of Editors,
  Emory Law Journal
<br>
<l1>Northwestern University
  B.A., 1977
  History</DIR>
