<html><head><title>Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-1>LLP</font> Recruiting</head></title>
<h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-1>LLP</font><p>Recruiting</h3>
<h2 align=center>Summer Public Service Program</h2>


<P>

In 1990, Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> inaugurated a program to allow a number of its summer associates to spend a portion of their summer in public interest placements in Washington, D.C.  The S&amp;J Summer Public Service Program is intended to enhance the firm's already substantial pro bono commitment, while serving to expand opportunities for second-year law students who might not otherwise be in a position to work for a public-interest organization during the summer.<P>

<P>

The program is designed to accommodate up to seven Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> summer associates who would otherwise spend the entire summer with Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> and who wish to pursue public service work during the latter part of their summer associate stay in D.C.  Summer associates must spend at least the first eight weeks of their summer working at the firm, and are then eligible to spend the balance of the summer (up to four weeks) working with a public service group in an area of interest to them.  Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> will contribute to each organization an amount earmarked to make up the difference between the regular weekly summer associate salary at the firm and the salary otherwise offered by the public-interest organization.  In this way, the firm hopes that law students whose financial obligations might otherwise preclude them from exploring public interest opportunities will be encouraged to participate.  <P>

<P>

Each organization will employ the participants in this program on the same terms and conditions as the organization's usual summer law clerks.  This should ensure that the participants will experience a realistic sample of life in a public interest organization with respect to workload, supervision, evaluation and the type of projects offered.  The firm encourages the participants in this program to continue their association with the firm during the public interest placement by attending firm social events, seminars and the like.  <P>

<P>

The <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/ps2.htm">list of organizations</a> that will take part in the program this summer covers a broad spectrum of public needs and approaches to public service.  If, however, a student desires a placement at an organization not on the list, the firm will be happy to discuss whether appropriate arrangements can be made with that organization to participate in the program.<P>

<P>

During the past five summers, Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> summer associates have worked at the offices of AYUDA, Counsel for Child Abuse and Neglect, the D.C. Public Defender Service, Human Rights Watch, International Human Rights Law Group, Judge David L. Bazelon Center for Mental Health Law, Legal Counsel for the Elderly, National Women's Law Center, Neighborhood Legal Services, Sierra Club Legal Defense Fund, The State and Local Legal Center, Washington Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights and Urban Affairs, Washington Legal Clinic for the Homeless, and Women's Legal Defense Fund.<P>

<P>

Participants in the program are selected in January.  In the event the number of summer associates interested in participating exceeds the program's capacity, the participants will be selected by lottery.  Once the participants are selected, the firm will assist in pairing up students with compatible placements.<P>

<P>This program will not take the place of the usual pro bono work assignments available to summer associates during the summer, nor will it decrease in any way the firm's commitment throughout the year to providing legal services to individuals and organizations that cannot afford to pay.  The firm's goal is to facilitate the participation of summer associates in public-interest work on an organized basis, while encouraging students with an ongoing interest in public-interest law to spend part of their summer at Steptoe &amp; Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font>.  <P>

<P>

Inquiries regarding the details of the program should be addressed to the firm's Director of Associate Services and Recruiting, Rosemary Kelly Morgan, at (202) 429-8036.<P>

<P>

<P>

<FONT size=-2>JANUARY  1996</FONT>






