<h3 align="center">Steptoe &amp; Johnson LLP <a name="begin">Publications
&amp; Memos </a></h3>

<p align="center"><Blockqoute><a name="begin"> </a><a href="#net">Law and The
Net</a> <a href="#new"><font size="1">(WHAT'S NEW!) </font></a>| <a
href="#tele">Telecommunications Law</a> | <a href="#russia">Russian
Law</a> <br>
<a href="#environ">Environmental Law</a> | <a href="#tax">Tax Law</a>
</p>

<p align="center"></Blockqoute> </p>

<hr>

<h3 align="center"><a name="net">Law And The Net </a></h3>

<p><a name="net"><b><u>What's New: </u></b></a></p>

<p>On January 14, 1997, the FBI, pursuant to CALEA, published in
the Federal Register its <a
href="waisgate.txt">Second Notice and request
for comments on its proposed capacity requirements for electronic
intercepts</a>. The FBI proposed actual and maximum capacity
requirements for communication interceptions, pen register and
trap and trace device-based interceptions. In developing its
proposed capacity requirements, the FBI examined historical
interception activity in geographic areas to determine peak
surveillance activity. The FBI then applied growth factors to
this information to project future capacity requirements.
Comments on the FBI's Second Notice are due on or before February
13, 1996. </p>

<p>The Commerce Department has formally published its<a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/Revcomm.txt"> encryption export
control regulations</a>. They are in &quot;interim final&quot;
form, which means that they will take effect immediately but will
be subject to revision in response to comments from the public. </p>

<p><a href="compsec.htm">Recent Developments in Computer Security</a>:
An article appearing in the November/December issue of
&quot;Electronic Banking Law and Commerce Report&quot; written by
<a href="baker.htm">Stewart A. Baker</a> and <a href="selter.htm">Monica
L. Selter.</a> </p>

<p>The Administration has released a draft of the new <a
href="commerce.htm">Commerce Department regulations on encryption
exports</a>. The new regulations create a new category of
controls -- &quot;EI&quot; (which stands for &quot;encryption
items&quot;). The regulations divide these encryption items into
5 categories and create different licensing schemes for each. </p>

<p>Latest Developments in Administration's Encryption Policy: On
November 15, 1996, the Administration released an Executive Order
in preparation for the transfer of most encryption jurisdiction
to the Commerce Department. The Administration also announced the
appointment of a &quot;Special Envoy for Cryptography&quot; to
discuss encryption policy with other governments. The text of the
<a href="http://www.steptoe.com/Ex_ord.htm">Executive Order</a>, <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/Ltr2con.htm">President Clinton's
letter to Congress</a>, his <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/Mem2pol.htm">memorandum to relevant
policymakers</a>, and <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/goreann.htm">Vice
President Gore's announcement of the &quot;Crypto
Ambassador&quot;</a> follows. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/Crypta.htm">The new encryption
policy</a>: &quot;There seems to be an iron law of Washington
policy-making: If you solve a tough policy problem on Monday,
when you come into work on Tuesday, you won't find one solved
problem on your desk. You'll find a new problem that arises out
of Monday's solution.&quot; <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/oped.htm">A modified version of the
op-ed</a> by <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart
Baker</a> and <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/lichtenb.htm">Peter
Lichtenbaum</a> which appeared in the November 18, 1996, Journal
of Commerce.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/gore.htm">Statement of Vice
President Gore</a>: On October 1, 1996, Vice President Gore
announced the Clinton Administration's proposal to liberalize
export controls on encryption. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.hotwired.com/wired/4.09/es.crypto.html">&quot;Japan
Enters the Crypto Wars&quot;</a> : <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> argues
that the decisive battle over crypto will take place in the
international, rather than the domestic arena -- and that the
player to watch is Japan. Read his article from the September
issue of Wired magazine. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/342660.htm"><i>July 16, 1996,
Hearing of the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations:</i></a>
<a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a>
reports on the most recent Senate hearing held on &quot;Security
in Cyberspace.&quot; This hearing focused on possible responses
to cyber-based attacks. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/337683a.htm"><i>June 25, 1996,
Hearing of the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations:</i></a>
<a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker's</a>
summary of a recent hearing held on &quot;Security in
Cyberspace.&quot; This hearing addressed the vulnerability of
both government and private sector networks. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/enc_pol.htm"><i>July 12, 1996
Gore Statements on Encryption Policy</i></a>: Vice President Gore
announced the Administration's latest encryption policy
initiative, indicating a continuing commitment to some form of
escrow or key recovery system, while also signaling additional
flexibility on export controls on encryption. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/ukcrypto.htm"><i>UK Encryption
Policy</i> Summary</a> : <a
href="Http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a>
analyzes British encryption policy and emerging plans to
encourage but not mandate the use of trusted third party (key
escrow) encryption.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/infowar.htm"><i>Information
Warfare</i> Summary</a> : &quot;December 2002: As Iraqi troops
mass once again on the border with Kuwait, the President
mobilizes U.S. forces. But as the crisis grows, civilians find
themselves suffering home-front hardships unprecedented in this
century. . . .&quot; A modified version of the op-ed by Stewart
Baker which appeared in the April 22, 1996, Journal of Commerce. </p>

<p>France's proposed telecommunications law includes a provision
(Article 12) regulating encryption and encouraging the use of
trusted third party encryption systems. Our <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/france.htm"><i>analysis and
translation</i> </a>of that provision follows. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/bernt.htm"><i>Bernstein
Litigation</i> Summary</a> : On April 15, 1996, the U.S. District
Court for the Northern District of California denied the
government's motion to dismiss an action brought by Daniel
Bernstein. Our summary of that decision follows. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/crypt.htm"><i>Personal Use
Exemption for Cryptography</i> :</a> On February 16, 1996, the
State Department issued a final rule providing for a personal use
exemption to the International Traffic in Arms Regulations. This
rule permits the temporary export of cryptographic products for
personal use.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/cyber.htm"><i>Russia Restricts
Encryption</i> </a>: The following analysis was prepared by
Steptoe &amp; Johnson Company's Russian Law experts in Moscow.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/calea.htm"><i>Compliance With
CALEA: The Communications Assistance for Law Enforcement Act of
1994</i> </a>: A memo prepared by <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> and <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/smithcli.htm">Clint Smith</a> .</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/276908.htm"><i>Summary Report
on the OECD Ad Hoc Meeting of Experts on Cryptography</i> </a>:
In December, the OECD convened an ad hoc working group of
government experts on encryption. Also attending the meeting were
a few private-sector representatives, including <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> . These
are his notes and conclusions about the conference. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/276915.htm"><i>Emerging
Japanese Encryption Policy</i> </a>: <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker's</a>
assessment of the direction of Japanese encryption policy
(January 1996).</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/230113.htm"><i>Information
Superhighway Trust Fund</i> </a>: By <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a>
(Originally published as an op-ed in the Los Angeles Times,
October 1995) - State governments are anxious to collect taxes
from on-line merchants who are conducting sales to buyers within
their jurisdictions. The limits of a state government's authority
to do so, however, are unclear. The result is likely to be great
uncertainty and possible litigation. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/231336.htm"><i>1995 Encryption
Policy Developments</i> </a>: By <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> 1995
was an active year for the development of encryption policy --
from private key-escrow alternatives to the Clipper chip to
legislation that would restrict the domestic use of encryption.
In response to such developments, private industry stepped up its
efforts to influence these policies. First posted October 1995.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/225636.htm"><i>Legal Aspects
of Network Security</i> </a>: By <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> This
August 1995 outline provides an overview of three legal means to
promote computer network security: (1) the imposition of civil
liability on those hired to provide network security; (2) the
imposition of civil liability on those who violate network
security; and (3) the criminal prosecution of those who violate
network security. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/221277.htm"><i>State Taxation
of On-Line Transactions</i> </a>: By <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> This
July 1995 outline sets out the types of on-line transactions that
could be subject to state taxation and the legal basis for the
assertion of taxation authority over them.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/237557.htm"><i>Facilitating
Government-Private Sector Cooperation in the Development of
Commercial Key Escrow: Alternatives to Legislation</i> </a>: By <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> Stewart
Baker's testimony before the National Institute of Standards and
Technology (NIST), September 7, 1995. The administration should
take several steps in cooperation with industry to assure the
availability of responsible and responsive key escrow agents
while meeting industry's interest in knowing the risks of
business in advance of entering the market. This testimony sets
out four such possibilities.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/282836.htm"><i>Privacy and
Security Issues on The Internet</i> </a>: By <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker</a> This
November 1995 article provides an overview of the law relating to
the privacy and security of Internet e-mail communications,
focusing specifically on communications between attorneys and
clients.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/am3.htm"><i>Internet Telephony</i></a>
By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/mamlet.htm">Alfred Mamlet:</a>
An analysis of legal, policy, economic and technical issues
related to provision of internet voice services. </p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/overload.htm"><i>Overloading
the FCC</i> </a>: By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/mamlet.htm">Alfred
Mamlet</a> . An analysis of the regulatory role of the FCC under
the Telecommunications Act of 1996, modified from an article
published in Legal Times.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/290546.htm"><i>Electric
Utilities And The Telecommunications Act Of 1996</i> </a>: By <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/mamlet.htm">Alfred Mamlet</a> and <a
href="http://www.steptoe.com/paul.htm">Marc Paul</a> . An
analysis of the provisions of the Telecommunications Act of 1996
that impact electric utilities, focusing on the local competition
and pole attachment provisions.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/summary.htm"><i>Karn Decision</i>
Summary</a> : A federal district court in Washington, D.C. on
March 22, 1996, dismissed a case brought by privacy activist Phil
Karn challenging the State Department's refusal to allow him to
export cryptography. </p>

<p align="center"><a href="#begin">Return to top of document</a></p>

