<body>
<!-- WebElite Preview File --><p align=center>Recent Developments in Computer Security </p>
<p align=center>by </p>
<p align=center>Stewart A. Baker and Monica L. Selter </p>
<p>The computer revolution has brought miraculous change to the way that American companies do 
business. Thanks to technological breakthroughs, our civil infrastructure has become more efficient. 
Our transportation, utilities, telephone companies, and financial institutions now all rely heavily on 
computer networks in providing their services to customers. Dependence on technology, however, 
has its risks. Systems can fail, leaving the company and its private and corporate customers unable 
to perform routine tasks. Moreover, computer networks may be vulnerable to intruders. Infiltration 
of the computer systems of a major railroad, or of our telephone or utilities companies could be 
crippling -- hampering business and private communications, delaying the delivery of food and fuel, 
or even leaving entire cities in the dark.<a href="#1./" name="e1"><sup><font size=1><u>1/</u></font></sup></a></p>
<p>Unfortunately, the development of computer security systems to help prevent such occurrences and 
to efficiently react if they do occur has been slow. Many companies do not yet have adequate 
computer security safeguards to protect their systems from failure or infiltration. Nor do 
industry-wide standards of care for information technology systems exist. This situation begs the 
question, what happens if something does go wrong? Who will be expected to pay? How will 
liability be determined? </p>
<p>The lawyerly answer is that liability is likely to depend on whether a company has exercised due 
care in protecting its systems. But defining due care could be difficult for both companies and for 
those who must allocate liability, such as courts and insurance providers. This is especially true if 
private industry has not agreed on computer security guidelines. </p>
<p>In the absence of industry-wide computer security guidelines, courts and insurers may decide to 
look for guidance to the government. After all, the government also faces computer security 
dilemmas as it becomes more reliant on information technology. </p>
<p>Indeed, inadequate security procedures have caused serious problems for government agencies. In 
1995, for example, according to a recent GAO report,<a href="#2./" name="e2"><sup><font size=1><u>2/</u></font></sup></a> the Defense Department's unclassified 
computer systems and networks, which contain sensitive data, suffered as many as 250,000 
attacks; some attacks actually corrupted data or paralyze systems. Attack incidents are doubling 
each year and cost the government millions of dollars. The GAO report also cites to problems at 
the Internal Revenue Service. The IRS' computer system currently is not secure enough to ensure 
the confidentiality of taxpayer data or to protect such data from manipulation by unauthorized 
persons for personal gain. </p>
<p>Perhaps because government computer breaches come to the attention of the public more 
frequently than do private breaches (which are rarely reported), the government is at the forefront 
of establishing computer security guidelines. At the behest of Congress, the civilian sector federal 
agencies have been working on securing their computer networks for several years.<a href="#3./" name="e3"><sup><font size=1><u>3/</u></font></sup></a> Although 
progress is slow, 1996 has seen a big step toward comprehensive guidelines for government 
entities. The most recent developments are summarized below.	</p>
<p>In February the Office of Management and Budget (&quot;OMB&quot;) published a revision of Appendix III 
of its circular A-130, &quot;Management of Federal Automated Information Resources.&quot;<a href="#4./" name="e4"><sup><font size=1>4/</font></sup></a> This 
document &quot;establishes a minimum set of controls to be included in Federal automated information 
security programs.&quot;<a href="#5./" name="e5"><sup><font size=1><u>5/</u></font></sup></a> The policy set forth in the OMB Circular is mandatory for federal authorities. 
It emphasizes: </p>
<ul>
<li><ul>
<li>individual responsibility </li>
<li>system specific development of security rules </li>
<li>flexibility in necessity for formal risk assessments of specific systems </li>
<li>personnel controls </li>
<li>ability to detect and react quickly and efficiently to security threats </li>
<li>network security training </li>
<li>awareness of network interconnectivity </li>
<li>contingency planning in case of security breach </li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>The OMB circular also assigns various responsibilities to specific agencies. Among them, the 
National Institute for Standards and Technology (&quot;NIST&quot;) is responsible for providing guidance to 
agencies in security planning, interconnectivity, incident handling, training, and information sharing. 
In this role, this September, NIST issued its General Accepted Principles and Practices for 
Security Information Technology Systems,<a href="#6./" name="e6"><sup><font size=1><u>6/</u></font></sup></a> which supplements a 1995 handbook on computer 
security.<a href="#7./" name="e7"><sup><font size=1><u>7/</u></font></sup></a> This document sets forth eight basic principles necessary for developing computer 
security systems.<a href="#8./" name="e8"><sup><font size=1><u>8/</u></font></sup></a> In addition, it provides a check list of information technology security practices 
that NIST believes &quot;provide a common ground for determining the security of an organization and 
build confidence when conducting multi-organizational business.&quot;<a href="#9./" name="e9"><sup><font size=1><u>9/</u></font></sup></a> Included on this checklist are 
program and risk management practices, as well as sections on computer security incident handling 
and preparation for contingencies and disasters. NIST notes in its circular discussing the principles 
and practices that they provide a standard of care in the area of computer security. </p>
<p>Another government initiative is the Federal Computer Incident Response Capability (FedCIRC), 
which will assist federal agencies in &quot;their incident handling efforts by providing proactive and 
reactive computer security related services.&quot;<a href="#10./" name="e10"><sup><font size=1><u>10/</u></font></sup></a> The operational incident handling capability is 
subcontracted out by NIST to the Defense Advanced Research Project Agency's CERT (SM) 
Coordination Center (CERT/CC) and the Department of Energy's Computer Incident Advisory 
Capability (CIAC). NIST will analyze the vulnerability data provided by FedCIRC to develop 
incident handling standards and guidelines. The service will provide summaries of security breach 
incidents, a web site with information computer security, such as tools, information about
</DOC>
