</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META Name="Generator" Content="Lotus Word Pro">
<TITLE>Body</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<B><CENTER>
Privacy and Security Issues on the Internet</B><P>

</CENTER>
<CENTER>By <a href="http://www.us.net/~steptoe/baker.htm"><I>Stewart A. Baker</a></I></CENTER>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>


<P>

<P>

<P>

<B>
I.	Introduction</B><P>

No means of communicating is completely free from security risks.  Private rooms can be bugged.  Conventional mail can be intercepted and read.  Attorneys' offices can be burglarized.  Telephone lines can be tapped.<P>

The law has made great progress in providing criminal and civil redress for interception of electronic communications.  The courts, statutes, and ethical rules appear to be farther behind in addressing how attorneys should adapt to new technologies in their practice of law.  Security risks pose interesting and largely unanswered questions regarding lawyers' ability to protect client confidences.  Although the law is still developing to address the status of Internet e-mail communications between attorneys and clients, evaluation of current attorney-client privilege law, confidentiality rulings, and federal statutes on electronic communications and electronic surveillance can provide guidance on this issue. <P>

<B>
II.	The Risks of Internet E-mail</B><P>

	<B>
A.	Interception:</B>  In the journey of an e-mail message, interception can conceivably occur at any unprotected point along the way, such as the user's terminal, the network server, the transmission lines, electronic storage, etc.<P>

		1.	<B>
Passive Monitoring:</B>  Passive monitoring is essentially equivalent to eavesdropping.  The risk is that an unauthorized party will intercept and read the message either in transmission or in storage, thus compromising confidentiality.<P>

		2.	<B>
Active Interception:</B>  This is the feared &quot;hacking.&quot;  Variations of hacking include re-routing an e-mail transmission, modifying the transmission, interfering with authenticity, and even accessing the sender's LAN or WAN.  Here, not only is confidentiality compromised, but accuracy as well.  Another hacking risk is the potential theft of the sender's or receiver's password.<P>

		3.	<B>
Authentication:</B>  The risk here is that the message is actually from someone other than the designated sender.  Risks for lawyers in this context include receiving false information or phantom instructions. <P>

		4.	<B>
Reliability:</B>  Many transmission reliability problems are not inherent in the Internet.  Instead they are likely to be at one of the end points in message transmission.  For example, a software problem in a network server could prevent accurate messaging.<P>

		5.	<B>
Misrouting:</B>  The transmission can be misdirected through either human or computer error.<P>

<B>
III.	Internet E-mail and Confidentiality</B><P>

		Is the attorney-client privilege waived for communications sent via Internet e-mail due to lack of security?  <P>

		Is mere transmission of Internet e-mail a waiver of the privilege even if there is no breach of security?  <P>

		Is the ethical obligation of confidentiality breached if an attorney communicates with a client about confidential matters over the Internet?<P>

		This section will introduce the attorney client privilege and the ethical obligation of confidentiality and discuss each in the context of Internet e-mail security.<P>

	<B>
A.	Attorney-Client Privilege:</B>  While one state case has directly stated that an e-mail communication was privileged, the issue has not been fully litigated.  In <U>
State v. Canady</U>, 460 S.E. 2d 677, 689 (W. Va. 1995), the court decided that an e-mail message was protected by the privilege.  The opinion does not appear to treat the privileged communication differently due to its status as an electronic communication.  The e-mail message is from a corporation employee to the corporation's inside counsel regarding legal advice contained in a letter from the corporation's outside counsel.  Nevertheless, in a footnote the court states that the issue of waiver of attorney client privilege remains open to the circuit court below on reconsideration. <P>

		Communications between an attorney and client covered by the attorney-client privilege are protected from compelled disclosure.  In general, state and federal privilege is similar.  While the language delineating the elements of privilege varies, most jurisdictions privilege law can be broken into the following components.<P>

		1.	<B>
Elements of the privilege:</B><P>

			a.	a communication,<P>

			b.	between privileged persons (attorney, client, or agents of either),<P>

			c.	made in confidence,<P>

			d.	to seek, obtain, or provide legal advice,<P>

			e.	where the privilege is affirmatively raised, and<P>

			f.	not waived.<P>

			<U>
See</U> <U>
United States v. Noriega</U>, 917 F.2d 1543 (11th Cir. 1990); <U>
United States v. Machine Shoe</U>, 89 F. Supp. 357, 358-59 (1950); Edna Selan Epstein &amp; Michael M. Martin, <U>
The Attorney-Client Privilege and the Work-Product Doctrine</U> 14 (1989); Wigmore, <U>
Evidence</U> e 2292, at 554 (McNaughton rev. ed. 1961).<P>

			g.	<B>
Policy:</B>  The basic policy behind the privilege can be summarized as promoting client truthfulness and encouraging a client's full, free disclosure.  <U>
E.g.</U>, <U>
Upjohn Co. v. United States</U>, 449 U.S. 383, 389 (1981); <U>
Cox v. Administrator U.S. Steel &amp; Carnegie</U>, 17 F.3d 1386 (11th Cir. 1994); <U>
United States v. Noriega</U>, 917 F.2d 1543, 1550 (11th Cir. 1990).<P>

			h.	<B>
Choice of Law:</B>  Federal Rule Evidence 501 states that privileges are to be governed by federal common law unless state law supplies the rule of decision for an element or defense in a civil action, in which case state law will apply.  While a full choice of law analysis is outside the scope of this outline, in general, state privilege law is applied in state courts and federal privilege law is applied in federal courts in federal questions cases.  For diversity cases in federal courts, state privilege law is likely to be applied.<P>

		2.	<B>
Privileged Persons:</B>  In order to be covered by the attorney-client privilege, a communication must be between privileged persons, including the attorney, the client, agents or &quot;communicating agents&quot; of either necessary to the provision of legal services.  <U>
City of Worchester v. HCA Management Co., Inc.</U>, 839 F. Supp. (D. Mass. 1993).  Traditionally, those considered privileged persons other than the attorney and the client have been associates, law clerks, paralegals, secretaries, and other assistants who assist the attorney in rendering legal services.  <U>
Zenith Radio Corp. v. Radio Corp. of America</U>, 121 F. Supp. 792, 794 (D. Del. 1954).  In addition, accountants and other professionals have been considered privileged, but only to the extent they assist in legal, not business or other professional services.  <U>
United States v. Schwimmer</U>, 892 F.2d 237 (2d Cir. 1989).  The privilege has been extended to communicating agents (insurance agents, translators, secretaries, etc.) of either the client or attorney who facilitate the attorney-client communications, thus assisting in providing legal advice.  <U>
Golden Trade, S.r.L. v. Jordache</U>, 143 F.R.D. 514, 518 (S.D.N.Y. 1992).<P>

			a.	<B>
Extension to E-mail:</B>  Service providers have access to e-mail to the extent necessary to perform their services and protect their rights and property.  Electronic Communications Privacy Act of 1986, 18 U.S.C. e2511(2)(a)(i) (Supp. 1995).  Whether service providers can be considered privileged persons or communicating agents of the attorney has not been addressed by any court.  To the extent the service providers' role in facilitating communication between attorney and client is recognized, then they would be categorized as communicating agents and the privilege would be retained.  Of course, the confidentiality requirement must still be met.<P>

		3.	<B>
Confidentiality:</B>  If communications are not made in confidence, the attorney-client privilege is not effective.  Traditionally, courts have held that if a client intends a communication with his or her attorney to be confidential, then the privilege will attach.  <U>
E.g.</U>, <U>
United States v. Rockwell, Int'l</U>, 897 F.2d 1255, 1265 (3d Cir. 1990); <U>
Gottlieb v. Wiles</U>, 143 F.R.D. 241 (D. Colo. 1992).  Many courts go beyond the focus on intention to require that the intention be reasonable.  <U>
In re Auclair</U>, 961 F.2d 65, 70 (5th Cir. 1992); <U>
United States v. Noriega</U>, 917 F.2d 1543, 1551 (11th Cir. 1990); <U>
EDO Corporation v. Newark Ins. Co.</U>, 145 F.R.D. 18 (D. Conn. 1992).<P>

			a.	<B>
Extension to E-mail:</B>  If courts consider e-mail to be confidential, then use of e-mail to communicate privileged matters will not pose a threat to the attorney-client privilege.  Proving the <U>
intention</U> of confidentiality in an e-mail transmission would seem to be no more difficult than with any other type of communication.  Less clear is whether the intention to keep an e-mail confidential is <U>
reasonable</U>.  Certainly, it is possible to breach the confidentiality of attorney-client e-mail transmissions, but perhaps, no more likely than with voice mail, which has not been seriously questioned.  Cellular telephone communications have, on the other hand, been found notoriously lacking in confidentiality.  Lawyers may have been slow to join the Internet e-mail revolution, but courts have not been deluged with cases claiming lack of privilege or failure of confidentiality due to the use of e-mail. <P>

				Two state courts have viewed internal e-mail communications as protected by the privilege.  <U>
National Employment Service Corporation v. Liberty Mutual Insurance Company</U>, Suffolk Co. Sup. Ct. No. 93-2528-G (Mass. Sup. Ct. Dec. 21, 1994); <U>
State v. Canady</U>, 460 S.E. 2d 677, 689 (W. Va Sup. Ct. 1995) (noting that sufficient facts were found by the trial court, then waiver of attorney-client privilege may still be found under these circumstances).<P>

				California has passed legislation providing that confidential communications do not lose their confidential status simply because they take place on a &quot;facsimile, cellular telephone, or other electronic means.&quot;  Cal. Evid. Code e952.  If the privilege is withdrawn for Internet e-mail in other jurisdictions, we can expect to see more legislation of this sort.<P>

			b.	<B>
Title III of the Omnibus Crime Control and Safe Streets Act of 1968</B>:  18 U.S.C. e2517(4) provides that &quot;no otherwise privileged wire, oral, or electronic communication intercepted in accordance with, or in violation of, the provisions of this chapter shall lose its privileged character.&quot;  The effect of this provision on intercepted e-mails is uncertain, but is discussed more fully below in the section on federal statutes relating to electronic surveillance and electronic communications.  Depending on how choice of law and preemption issues are resolved, this provision could provide significant protection for privileged and confidential e-mails.<P>

			c.	<B>
Reasonable Expectation of Privacy for Technologies Other Than E-mail:</B>  Courts taking the view that the intention of confidentiality must be reasonable are likely to inform their judgment with cases addressing the reasonable expectation of privacy in various technologies.  (The ethics rulings on confidentiality have referred often to the reasonable expectation of privacy cases in analyzing technology related confidentiality questions.)  Courts have held there is no reasonable expectation of privacy in cellular, portable, or cordless telephone conversations, and pagers.  <U>
Tyler v. Berodt</U>, 877 F.2d 705, 706-07 (8th Cir. 1989) (no reasonable expectation of privacy in cordless phone); <U>
Edwards v. State Farm Ins. Co.</U>, 833 F.2d 535, 541 (5th Cir. 1987) (no reasonable expectation of privacy in cellular telephone conversations); <U>
Edwards v. Bardwell</U>, 632 F. Supp. 584, 589 (M.D. La. 1986) (no reasonable expectation of privacy in radio transmitted telephone calls); <U>
State v. Washington</U>, 855 P.2d 315, 317-18 (Wash. Ct. App. 1993) (person leaving message on pager has no reasonable expectation of privacy in message left); <U>
People v. Wilson</U>, 554 N.E.2d 545, 552 (Ill. App. 1 Dist. 1990) (no reasonable expectation of privacy in radio transmitted telephone calls); <U>
State v. Howard</U>, 679 P.2d 197, 206 (Kan. 1984) (no reasonable expectation of privacy in cellular telephone conversation by person placing call).  <U>
But see</U> <U>
People v. Bulllock</U>, 277 Cal. Reptr. 63, 66-67 (Cal. Ct. App. 1990) (reasonable expectation of privacy for data housed in pager).  Generally, courts have found wire transmissions to be more private than radio transmissions.  <U>
See</U> <U>
Dorsey v. State</U>, 402 So. 2d 1178, 1183-84 (Fla. 1981).<P>

			d.	<B>
Reasonable Expectation of Privacy for E-mail:</B>  One court has held (in the 4th Amendment search and seizure context) that there is a reasonable expectation of privacy in e-mail transmitted and stored by on-line service providers.  <U>
United States v. Maxwell</U>, 42 M.J. 568, 1995 CCA LEXIS 129, at *8-14 (U.S.A.F. Crim. Ct. App. 1995) (finding &quot;virtually no risk that appellant's computer transactions would be received by anyone other than the intended recipients&quot;) (emphasis added).  While one court's view certainly does not create a trend, this court seemed to place faith in the security of e-mail. <P>

			e.	<B>
Presence of Third Parties:</B>  The presence of nonessential third parties during the original confidential communication abrogates the privilege.  <U>
E.g.</U>, <U>
United States v. Gann</U>, 732 F.2d 714, 723 (9th Cir. 1984) (communication to attorney in front of police officers who were conducting a search of client's house).  <P>

				(1)	<B>
Presence of Third Parties Extended to E-mail:</B>    E-mail is unlike the traditional circumstance of having a third party physically present to undermine the confidentiality of the communication.  In the e-mail context, the third party would be remote, as in the case of a service provider.  As discussed above in the context of privileged persons, however, the service provider may be considered a communicating agent of the attorney or client necessary to the performance of legal services.  If so, the third party presence would not destroy the privilege. <P>

			f.	<B>
Inadvertent Disclosure:</B>  There is a certain amount of overlap between inadvertent disclosure pertaining to the original communication and inadvertent disclosure treated as an implied waiver (discussed directly below). In the context of confidentiality, inadvertent disclosure most clearly applies to the case of the eavesdropper.  The traditional view is that if confidentiality was intended, then, absent negligence the privilege is maintained even if a communication is overheard or intercepted.  <U>
People v. Decina</U>, 138 N.E.2d 799, 807 (N.Y. 1956) (explaining test is whether it was <U>
reasonable</U> to intend that communication not be overheard).  <P>

				(1)	<B>
Inadvertent Disclosure Extended to E-mail:</B>  The negligence approach above supports the position that e-mail communications can retain their privileged nature even if intercepted as long as the interception is not foreseeable.  The question remains, is it foreseeable?  As discussed above, while e-mail is at least as secure as voice mail, and has not had the well-publicized security problems of cellular phone transmissions, courts have not answered this question.<P>

		4.	<B>
Implied Waiver</B><P>

			a.	<B>
Implied Waiver by Inadvertent Disclosure Generally:</B>  Courts and commentators have taken three views on the effect of an inadvertent disclosure on the attorney client privilege.  The inadvertent disclosure cases most clearly applicable to e-mail are those cases in which a fax has been misdirected, often, but not only, to the adversary.<P>

				(1)	<B>
The Strict View:</B>  Under this view, promoted by Wigmore, the attorney-client privilege is waived by any inadvertent disclosure resulting from negligence.  <U>
In re Sealed Case</U>, 877 F.2d 976, 980 (D.C. Cir. 1989).  <U>
International Digital Sys. Corp. v. Digital Equip. Corp.</U>, 120 F.R.D. 445 (D. Mass. 1988); <U>
Underwater Storage Inc. v. United States Rubber Co.</U>, 314 F. Supp. 546 (D.D.C. 1970).<P>

				(2)	<B>
The Balancing View:</B>  The case-by-case approach uses several factors to determine whether it is fair considering all the circumstances to find inadvertent disclosure of confidential information to be a waiver of the attorney-client privilege.  One typical version of the factors (evaluating inadvertent disclosure in the context of document production) balances (1) the reasonableness of precautions taken to prevent inadvertent disclosure; (2) the number of inadvertent disclosures; (3) the extent of disclosure; (4) delay in curing and steps taken to rectify disclosures; and (5) the interests of justice in excusing the error.  <U>
Hartman v. El Paso Natural Gas Company</U>, 763 P.2d 1144, 1151-53 (N.M. 1988).  <U>
See also</U> <U>
Alldread v. City of Grenada</U>, 988 F.2d 1425, 1433 (5th Cir. 1993); <U>
United States v. Pepper's Steel &amp; Alloys</U>, 742 F. Supp. 641, 643 (S.D. Fla. 1990).<P>

				(3)	<B>
The No Waiver View:</B>  Under this approach, inadvertent disclosure alone will not waive the privilege under the theory that the right should not be unintentionally waived.  <U>
Transamerica Computer Corp. v. IBM Corp.</U>, 573 F.2d 646, 647 (9th Cir. 1978); <U>
Shriver v. Baskin-Robbins Ice Cream Co., Inc.</U>, 145 F.R.D. 112 (D. Colo. 1992); <U>
Mendenhall v. Barber-Greene</U>, 531 F. Supp. 951, 955 (N.D. Ill. 1982).<P>

			b.	<B>
Implied Waiver by Inadvertent Disclosure Extended to E-mail:</B>  Inadvertent disclosure of e-mail can occur in many ways.  An e-mail message can be sent to the wrong address, an e-mail address can be mistakenly included on an e-mail routing list, or a party can intercept the message without permission at any point along the way.<P>

				(1)	<B>
The Strict View:</B>  Although the strict view requires that the attorney-client privilege be guarded carefully, it is not absolute.  This view finds waiver when disclosure results from negligence.  With this in mind, is merely sending an e-mail to a client, which is later intercepted, likely to be considered negligent?  Probably not.  Less certain is whether failure to use encryption would be considered negligent.  Once communications reach a certain level of sensitivity, common sense dictates that a court could find negligence if an attorney fails to use encryption or switch to a safer means of communicating.<P>

				(2)	<B>
The Balancing View:</B>  As with any balancing approach, results are probably less certain in this category.  In jurisdictions adopting the case-by-case approach, it is likely that inadvertent disclosure of e-mail would not be considered a waiver of the attorney-client privilege unless the sender has repeatedly sent privileged information to the wrong parties, has unusual security problems, or some other facts in the case would create unfairness if waiver were not implied.<P>

				(3)	<B>
The No Waiver View:</B>  Jurisdictions following the approach that inadvertent disclosure does not alone constitute implied waiver are unlikely to find that the attorney-client privilege is waived if a third party is mistakenly sent an e-mail message or otherwise gains access to one.  The reason for this conclusion is that these jurisdictions find waiver only where it is intended.<P>

				(4)	<B>
Title III of the Omnibus Crime Control and Safe Streets Act of 1968</B>:  18 U.S.C. e2517(4) provides that &quot;no otherwise privileged wire, oral, or electronic communication intercepted in accordance with, or in violation of, the provisions of this chapter shall lose its privileged character.&quot;  The effect of this provision on intercepted e-mails is uncertain, but is discussed more fully below in the section on federal statutes relating to electronic surveillance and electronic communications.  Depending on how choice of law and preemption issues are resolved, this provision could provide substantial protection for the privileged status of e-mails and protect against claims that the privilege has been waived through interception.<P>

				(5)	<B>
The Confidential Legend:</B>  The use of a confidential legend on an e-mail is likely to have effect only in jurisdictions following the balancing approach, where it would be one of the precautions taken.  In &quot;strict view&quot; jurisdictions, a mis-sent fax is likely to be considered negligently sent, leading to waiver.  In &quot;no waiver&quot; jurisdictions, as discussed above, intent to waive would be missing, thus no waiver would be implied.<P>

	B.	<B>
Ethical Obligation of Confidentiality</B><P>

		1.	<B>
Generally:</B>  The ethical obligation of confidentiality is far broader than the attorney-client privilege.  Model Rule of Professional Responsibility 1.6 states that &quot;[a] lawyer shall not reveal information relating to representation of a client unless the client consents after consultation.&quot;  Thus, while the privilege protects from compelled disclosure those confidential attorney-client communications made for the purpose of obtaining legal advice, the duty of confidentiality protects information from other sources as well, and in situations other than judicial proceedings.  Essentially, more information is protected and in more circumstances.<P>

		2.	<B>
Application to Internet E-mail:</B>  Few ethics rulings address the relationship between e-mail and confidentiality directly.  In one interesting advisory opinion, a disabled attorney was investigating the possibility of setting up an on-line legal service.  The advisory committee expressed concern about service provider access to privileged information sent via e-mail.  The committee stated that &quot;unless certainty can be obtained regarding the confidentiality of communications via electronic media, that representation of a client or communication with a client via electronic media, may violate Rule 1.6, absent an express waiver by the client.&quot;  S.C. Bar Adv. Op. 94-27 (1995).  The committee came to this conclusion after choosing rulings on cellular telephone communications as an appropriate analogy.  Whether the analogy is apt will be discussed further below.  Although not directly stated, the language of this advisory opinion would appear to apply to voice mail as well as e-mail, as voice mail is merely another electronic medium.<P>

		3.	<B>
Cellular Telephone Analogy to E-mail:</B>   Multiple jurisdictions have decided or advised that attorneys should not have confidential discussions with clients without notifying their clients and getting informed consent.  N.Y.C. Eth. Op. 1994-11 (not requiring informed consent, but requiring the attorney to exercise reasonable caution, minimize exposure of client confidences, and take sufficient steps to insure security); Mass. Adv. Op. 94-5 (requiring informed consent to use of cellular telephone); N.H. Adv. Op. 1991-92/6 (1992) (informed consent required unless scrambling device is used); Iowa Ethics (p. No. 90-94 (1991) (advising lawyer to explain that communication is not confidential on cell phone). <P>

			a.	The New York City opinion has three elements worth contemplating in the e-mail context.  <P>

				(1)	The opinion explains that the lawyer should &quot;exercise caution.&quot;  The level of caution required for e-mail transmissions is probably less than for cellular phones.  These decisions came about as the result of well-publicized cellular telephone eavesdropping.  While there have been isolated cases of Internet hacking, the problem is not nearly as prevalent as cell phone eavesdropping.  One reason for this is the difference in difficulty involved.  Anyone with a scanning device capable of intercepting the FM radio signals of cellular telephones can easily accomplish the interception.  Computer hacking takes substantially more know how.  <P>

				(2)	The opinion advises the attorney to warn the client that the conversation is occurring on a cellular phone.  The logical basis for this position is that unless the lawyer warns the client, the client may not know that the lawyer is on a cordless or cellular phone.  In contrast, an e-mail recipient knows by observation that the means of transmission is electronic mail.  Perhaps, however, lawyers should be responsible for warning their clients of e-mail security risks?  If so, when?  At the beginning of a representation?  Every time an e-mail is sent?  The first communication by e-mail?  <P>

				(3)	The committee stated that the lawyer &quot;should consider taking measures sufficient to ensure, with a reasonable degree of certainty, that communications are no more susceptible to interception than standard land-line telephone calls.&quot;  In the e-mail context, this would be an invitation to encryption.  The language of this opinion suggests that lawyers have discretion regarding the need for extra security measures, a logical for e-mail as well.  If e-mail is the only practical means of communicating and highly confidential information must be transmitted, then encryption may be part of exercising reasonable caution.  <P>

			b.	A Colorado Opinion took the position that for all technologies &quot;a lawyer must exercise reasonable care when selecting and using communications devices in order to protect the client's confidences or secrets from unauthorized disclosure.&quot;  Colo Ethics Op., No. 90 (1992).  This opinion also cited court cases addressing reasonable expectation of privacy of various technologies as a means of determining what is &quot;reasonable,&quot; but cautioned attorneys to do their own research into the security of individual technologies.<P>

		4.	<B>
Inadvertent Disclosure of Confidential Information:</B>  As in the materials addressing privilege, the ethics rulings speak to the problem of inadvertent disclosure.  Aside from the cases where materials were inadvertently disclosed in a document production, the cases seem to result most often from a mis-sent facsimile.  Several state bars have decided that adverse counsel receiving such a fax have no obligation to return or refrain from using the confidential material.  This posture is analogous to the strict view of attorney-client privilege waiver discussed above where the privilege is waived if negligently disclosed by mistake.  The ABA, on the other hand, has issued two formal opinions supporting the position that adverse counsel receiving inadvertent confidential or privileged faxes should refrain from reading them, notify the sending attorney, follow the sending attorney's instructions regarding document disposition, and refrain from using the information until a court provides definitive direction.  ABA Formal Op. 94-382; ABA Formal Op. 92-368.<P>

			a.	<B>
Inadvertent Disclosure of Confidential Information Extended to E-mail:</B>  While the mis-sent e-mail may be rarer occurrence than the mis-sent facsimile, the possibility is not that remote.  For example, e-mail address lists can be easily prepared for mass mailings.  Sending to the wrong mailing list could result in sending an e-mail to the wrong place.  It has become common practice to include a warning legend on facsimiles to alert recipients of the confidential nature of a document.  Thus, in the fax context there is at least the possibility of adverse counsel returning an e-mail unread.   <P>

				With e-mail, however, it seems less practical to use a warning legend because there is no front page covering the confidential message.  The e-mail alternatives to the cover sheet warning legend seem to be a note in the subject heading or an introductory sentence or two proclaiming the warning before the message begins.  Unless the legend is merely a short &quot;Privileged and Confidential&quot; at the top the legend would become a likely source of irritation to intended recipients (clients) who would have to scroll through the warning.  Another problem is that of deciding which transmissions get the warning.  Attaching the warning to all transmissions may be safest, but unnecessary and annoying.  One solution might entail attaching the warning only for sensitive, privileged communications.  But if you forget, does your previous practice make a finding of breach of the confidentiality obligation (or waiver of the attorney-client privilege more likely?<P>

<B>
IV.	Federal Privacy Protection -- The Illegality of Intercepting E-mail</B><P>

	<B>
A.	Title III of the Omnibus Crime Control and Safe Streets Act of 1968 (&quot;Title III&quot;) and The Electronic Communications Privacy Act of 1986 (&quot;ECPA&quot;)</B>:  The intent of Title III, 18 U.S.C. ee 2510-2520, was to balance the needs of privacy of wire and oral communications, on the one hand, and to provide for and control the ability of law enforcement to engage in electronic surveillance.  <U>
See</U> <U>
Gelbard v. United States</U>, 408 U.S. 41, 48 (1972).  The ECPA significantly amended Title III to include electronic communications and to add sections regulating stored wire and electronic communications.  Taken together Title III, as amended by ECPA and other acts, 18U.S.C. ee 2510-2711, regulate electronic communications and electronic surveillance.<P>

		1.	<B>
Interception of Electronic Communications:</B>  Interception and disclosure of electronic communications is prohibited.  18 U.S.C. e2511(1).  Persons violating this statute are subject to fines or imprisonment, e2511(4) or civil suits, e2511(5).<P>

		2.	<B>
Access to Stored Electronic Communications:</B>  Obtaining, altering or preventing authorized access to stored electronic communications is prohibited.  18 U.S.C. e2701(b).  This violation is punishable by fines or imprisonment, e2701(b), or civil suits, e2707.<P>

		3.	<B>
Service Provider Exceptions:</B>  Electronic communications service providers can access electronic communications as long as the access is in the ordinary course of business and is either necessary for rendering the service or to protect the service provider's rights or property.  This access is available to service providers whether the electronic communication is in transmission, e2511(3), or stored, e2701(c).  <P>

		4.	<B>
Illegally Intercepted Communications Excluded as Evidence</B>:  Illegally intercepted communications cannot be used as evidence in court or other formal government proceedings.  In addition, evidence derived from illegally intercepted communications is also excluded.  18 U.S.C. e2515.  Thus, at least where information is <U>
illegally</U> intercepted, the attorney-client privilege seems to be secure.  <P>

		5.	<B>
Intercepted Privileged Communications:</B>  18 U.S.C. e 2517(4) provides that &quot;[n]o otherwise privileged wire, oral, or electronic communication intercepted in accordance with, or in violation of, the provisions of this chapter shall lose its privileged character.&quot; <P>

			This language could conceivably provide sweeping protection for the attorney-client privilege for communications sent via Internet e-mail (or any electronic medium).  Several issues arise, however, in considering this provision in the context of state privilege law. <P>

			a.	<B>
Preemption</B>:  Many cases have stated that Title III and ECPA preempt the field of electronic surveillance to the extent that state regulation is more permissive than the federal laws.  <U>
See, e.g.</U>, <U>
United States v. Marion</U>, 535 F.2d 697 (2d Cir. 1976); <U>
State v. Aurilio</U>, 366 So. 2d 71 (Fl. App. 1979).  Thus state laws can provide for more safeguards in controlling law enforcement wiretapping, but they cannot allow law enforcement more leeway in gathering evidence than does the federal law.<P>

				Section 2517(4) was passed as part of Title III in 1968 in a criminal context relating to the control of law enforcement surveillance.  It is unclear how the provision applies to civil intercepts of privileged communications by persons not engaged in law enforcement.  Thus, the scope of preemption remains unclear in the context of attorney-client privilege law.<P>

				Multiple cases also state that federal evidence law applies in federal courts, including the evidentiary provisions of Title III should apply to federal prosecutions.  <U>
See e.g.</U>, <U>
United States v. Testa</U>, 548 F.2d 847 (1977); <U>
United States v. Marion</U>, 35 F.2d 697 (2d Cir. 1976); <U>
United States v. Feiste</U>, 792 F. Supp. 1153 (D. Neb. 1991).  These cases do not refer specifically to the provision on privileged communications, however, they support the position that intercepted communications remain privileged at least in federal prosecutions.<P>

			b.	<B>
Applicability of State Law</B>:  The &quot;otherwise privileged&quot; language does suggest that common law waiver or confidentiality principles may still apply.  As discussed above, Rule 501 of the Federal Rules of Evidence, provides for the application of state privilege law where substantive state law is applied in a case.  The safety of the attorney-client privilege may then depend on choice-of-law or federal preemption issues.<P>

				One of the few cases addressing e 2517(4) states that &quot;[t]he sections's use of the language 'otherwise privileged' to us means privileged other than by virtue of their character as private telephone conversations.&quot;  <U>
United States v. Turner</U>, 528 F.2d 143 (9th Cir. 1975).  The case goes on to discuss the legislative history to conclude that the communications remain privileged in the event that they were privileged under traditional privilege law.  Nevertheless, this case does not address the preemption issue, so it is unclear whether waiver or other privilege elements may still come into play in the analysis.<P>

		6.	<B>
Interception of Privileged Communications By Service Providers:</B>  While e2517 provides at least some privilege protection in federal cases, service providers are given limited permission to disclose intercepted communications in a manner that may effectively destroy the privilege. Although service providers cannot generally divulge intercepted or accessed stored communication, they can turn over to law enforcement officials any such communications that &quot;appear to pertain to the commission of a crime.&quot;  e2511(3)(a)(iv).  The law does not directly address how this affects the privileged status of an e-mail.  Confidentiality of the communication is, however, clearly compromised.<P>

			a.	<B>
Confidentiality:</B>  The service provider exception raises serious concerns regarding the ethical obligation of confidentiality.  If service providers have the discretion to turn materials over to law enforcement officials, attorneys and clients communicating via e-mail risk that their communications will be divulged.  For example, if a criminal defendant client and his or her attorney were communicating by e-mail about the facts of the case (probably inadvisable), a service provider who randomly came across that information could turn it over to law enforcement officials.  <P>

			b.	<B>
Privilege:</B>  Whether information turned over to law enforcement officials may also be introduced as evidence in court is unclear.  The privilege does not appear to be lost merely because the interception is by a service provider.  <U>
Compare</U> e2517 <U>
with</U> e2511(3)(a)(iv).  However, if the privilege is found to be waived, under the analysis in section III.A above, then the intercepted information given to law enforcement officials could be used as evidence as well.<P>

		7.	<B>
Illegally Obtained Electronic Communications:</B>  If a burglar breaks into your office and steals your files, it seems unlikely that a court would find the attorney-client privilege waived under any of the theories described above.  Similarly, it seems that the attorney would not be found in violation of ethical obligations unless there was a known security risk, such as a faulty lock, an open window, or maybe even a particularly sensitive document not left in a safety deposit box.  On the other hand, it is illegal to intercept cellular telephone calls as well, but the materials discussed above, in the sections on privilege and confidentiality, suggest that the use of a cellular phone to discuss confidential information is an ethical violation, and that it may constitute waiver of the attorney-client privilege depending on the jurisdiction deciding the issue.  Where e-mail falls in this spectrum is uncertain.  Common sense might suggest that because it is generally simpler either to burglarize an office or intercept cellular telephone calls than it is to intercept e-mail messages that e-mail messaging would be safe from the treatment given to cellular telephones.<P>

	<B>
B.	State Privacy Tort Law and Statutes May Also Apply to the Extent Not Preempted by Federal Law</B><P>

<B>
V.	Available Security</B><P>

	<B>
A.</B>	<B>
Firewalls:</B>  Acts as a barrier to limit incoming and outgoing communications to particular locations on the server, to or from particular addresses, etc.<P>

<B>
	B.</B>	<B>
Intrusion Detection:</B>  Network level security to detect intrusion.  An example is the three try only entering of a password.<P>

<B>
	C.</B>	<B>
Encryption:</B>  Use of an algorithm to change text into unreadable form.<P>

		1.	<B>
Private Keys</B><P>

		2.	<B>
Key Escrow</B><P>

			a.	<B>
Commercial</B><P>

			b.	<B>
Public</B><P>

	<B>
D.	Digital Signature:</B>  Ensures that messages come from stated source.<P>

<B>
VI.	What Lawyers Should Do to Preserve the Attorney-Client Privilege and Confidentiality:</B>  Establishing an e-mail confidentiality policy and making attorneys in a firm aware of it is likely to improve e-mail security.  In situations where reasonable care must be shown, the existence of such a policy may be a key factor.<P>

	<B>
A.	Use the Communication Medium Appropriate to the Level of Confidentiality</B><P>

	<B>
B.</B>	<B>
Consider Encryption When Sending Highly Sensitive Materials Cannot Be Avoided</B><P>

	<B>
C.	Warn Clients of Risks of Communicating Via E-mail</B><P>

	<B>
D.	Protect E-mail at the Terminal</B><P>

		1.	Password protect time-outs at unattended terminals.<P>

		2.	Provide Password Protection for E-mail inbox access.<P>

<B>
	E.	Protect E-mail at the Network Server Level</B><P>

		1. Restrict access to the server.<P>

		2. Encryption<P>

<B>
	F.	Consider the Use of Warning Legends Where Feasible or When Necessary to Send Extremely Confidential Documents</b>
<hr>
