<html><head><title>LEGAL ASPECTS OF NETWORK SECURITY</title></head>
<H2 align=center>Legal Aspects of Network Security</H2>
<CENTER><I>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart A. Baker</a></I></CENTER>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>

<P>Summary:  This outline provides an overview of three legal means to promote computer network security: 
<OL><LI>The imposition of civil liability on those hired to provide network security; <P>
<LI> Imposition of civil liability on those who violate network security; and<P>
<LI>The criminal prosecution of those who violate network security.  </OL><P>
<P>Of course, none of the three assures secure networks.  In practice, network security vendors seek to contract out of the liability that could arise from failures in network security.  Computer hackers, notoriously antiauthoritarian, are imperfectly deterred by the threat of criminal prosecution.  And hackers will not have the deep pockets that make attractive targets for civil suits.  Laws are only part of the development of safe and secure computer networks.  Technical advances fueled by the prospect of income from corporations that demand the best available security in the age of open networks -- to a much greater degree than legal incentives -- will drive the development of computer security.

<h3>I.   Standard of Care for System Security</h3>
<blockquote><H4>A.   Common Law Standard of Care</H4>
<P>The customer has the right to expect a reasonable level of network security in light of the vendor's special knowledge, skills, and ability.  <I>Diversified Graphics v. Groves</I>, 868 F.2d 293 (8th Cir. 1989) (holding computer specialist to professional's standard of care). <I>But</I> <I>see</I><I> Hospital Computer Sys. Ltd</I>., 788 F. Supp. 1351 (D. N.J. 1992) (computer consultants not held to professional's standard of care).  A vendor's use of industry standard security technology may serve as evidence of reasonableness, but will not always relieve the vendor of liability -- industry practice may be unreasonable.  T.J. Hooper, 60 F.2d 737 (2d. Cir.), cert. denied, 287 U.S. 662 (1932).

<P>Liability for unreasonable security could arise when:

<ol><LI><B>Loss of Data Due to Security Breach</B>:  because a customer hires a security vendor to protect data, the loss or disclosure of data resulting from security failure could give rise to liability.  Ed Fine Oldsmobile v. Diamond State Tel. Co., 494 A.2d 636 (Del. 1985) (telecommunications company liable for negligent loss of data).  <P>
<LI><B>Loss or malfunction of encryption keys</B>:  a security vendor or key escrow agent who cannot decrypt a customer's files or retrieve a customer's private key from escrow could face substantial liability.<P>
<LI><B>Failure to Detect System Intruders</B>:  irrespective of damage, a network's inability to detect intruders could give rise to liability.  Ostalkiewicz v. Guardian Alarm, 520 A.2d 563 (R.I. 1987) (residential security company was held negligent for its failure to have an installed alarm system contact the local police). <P>
<LI><B>Unauthorized Copying</B>:  failure to prevent or detect unauthorized copying, even though the underlying data is still available to the customer, could also give rise to vendor liability.</OL>

<H4>B.   Government Standard of Care</H4>
<OL><LI><B>Computer Security Act</B>:  in coordination with NIST, each government agency must establish a computer security policy "commensurate with the risk and magnitude of the harm resulting from the loss, misuse, or unauthorized access to or modification of the information contained in such system."  Pub. L. No. 100-235, 101 Stat. 1724, 1729-30 (1988) (codified at 40 U.S.C. 759 note); 15 U.S.C.  278g-3 (1988 & Supp. 1994).<P>
<LI><B>National Archives and Records Administration</B>:  NARA has elaborated security procedures and standards of care for stored electronic records, including measures to restrict unauthorized access and to require backup and recovery procedures for electronic records.  36 C.F.R.  1234 (1994).  A high standard of care is applied to "official" file copies of text documents on electronic media.  Id. at 1234.22. <P> 
<LI><B>NIST</B>:  forthcoming publication, "Federal Computer Security Principles and Practices," will serve as a benchmark for judging the adequacy of computer security and determining what constitutes "reasonable" security.</OL>

<H4>C.  Model Contract Standards of Carez</H4>
<P>Various organizations have proposed standards of care to incorporate into commercial contracts, frequently in the realm of financial transactions.
<OL><LI><B>UCC Article 4A</B>:  provides an "ordinary care" standard for security of electronic funds transfer transactions, subject to modification in light of any specific security procedures agreed to between customer and bank.  U.C.C.  4A-201 (1991).  <P>
<LI><B>UNCITRAL EDI Uniform Rules of Conduct</B>:  requires security that is commercially reasonable in the circumstances, with reference to trade-data interchange protocols.<P>
<LI><B>ABA Model EDI Agreement</B>:  provides a standard of care linked both to technical standards chosen by the parties and published industry guidelines used within the particular industry.  Model Electronic Data Interchange Agreement and Commentary, reprinted in 45 Bus. Lawyer 1717 (1990).</ol>

<H4>D.  Commercial Contract Standard of Care</H4>
<P>Standard contracts used by vendors providing computer system security often contain the following clauses intended to replace the common law standard of care and minimize the vendor's liability for system security failures.<P>
<OL><LI><B>Disclaimers of Warranties</B>:  disclaim all express warranties as well as implied warranty of merchantability and implied warranty of fitness for a particular purpose (U.C.C. 2-314, 2-315 (1991)).  Also vendors may expressly disclaim warranty to any third party who might rely on the security of a customer's computer system. <P>
<LI><B>Waiver of Liability for All Negligent and Grossly Negligent System Security Failures</B>:  standard contracts waive liability for negligence to the extent permitted by law.  Most standard contracts also include a waiver of consequential and incidental damages.  Transport Corp. of Am. v. IBM, 30 F.3d 953 (8th Cir. 1994) (no consequential damages for disc drive failure).  The potentially enormous consequential damages that may result from breaches in security should cause vendor's concern.  See Evra Corp. v. Swiss Bank Corp., 673 F.2d 951 (7th Cir.) (finding bank would be liable for consequential damages for failure to transfer funds as directed by customer if bank were aware of special circumstances related to the transfer) cert. denied, 459 U.S. 1017 (1982).  <P>
<LI><B>Burden of Proof</B>:  vendors may place the burden of proof on the customer to establish that the security failure was the fault of the vendor.  If the source of the security failure cannot be proven, as may often be the case, the vendor would not be liable.<P>
<LI><B>Force Majeure</B>:  most standard contracts include a broad force majeure clause that would extend to equipment malfunction and other events that are arguably within the vendor's control.<P>
<LI><B>Indemnification from Suppliers Who are Responsible for Security Failure</B>:  vendors, through contracts with suppliers, can require indemnification and hold accountable the party responsible for the security failure.  <P>
<LI><B>Liquidated Damages</B>:  contracts can limit total damages for which the vendor could be liable to either a sum certain or an externally determined amount, such as the amount to date paid by plaintiff-customer to the vendor.  Ritchie Enter. v. Honeywell Bull, Inc., 730 F. Supp. 1041 (D. Kan. 1990) (damages for computer system failure limited by contract to purchase price of system).  But a remedy so inadequate that it fails the "essential purpose" of the contract might not be given effect.  Milgard Tempering, Inc. v. Selas Corp., 902 F.2d 703 (9th Cir. 1990) (refusing to give effect to a contract's "repair or replace" clause when the vendor proved unable to provide a product that met customer's requirements).<P>
<LI><B>Integration Clause</B>:  such a clause is sought by vendors to preclude a customer from arguing that the vendor's statements prior to or contemporaneous with the contract constituted an express warranty regarding system security.  Pennsylvania Gas Co. v. Secord, 357 N.Y.S.2d 702 (1974).  But see Glovatorium v. NCR Corp., 684 F.2d 658 (9th Cir. 1982) (liability for salesmen's misrepresentations of computer system's capabilities);  Sierra Diesel Injection Serv. v. Burroughs Corp., 874 F.2d 653 (9th Cir. 1989) (integration clause in standard form contract not given effect).<P>
<LI><B>Insurance</B>:  computer insurance policies available to both vendor and customer can cover losses attributable to fraudulent modification, damage, disappearance, or destruction of electronic data.  Parties could agree to a contract provision requiring one party to obtain such insurance.</OL>

<H4>E. Clinton Administration's Liability Proposals</H4>
<P>The National Information Infrastructure (NII) commission established by Vice President Gore, in its June 1995 report on security of the NII, noted that "civil liability is likely to create incentives for improving the security of information systems. . . .  However, consensus about what constitutes reasonable standards for information security will be difficult to achieve."  NII Security: The Federal Role (June 5, 1995) (attached to OMB Press Release re National Information Infrastructure Security Issues Forum Releases "NII Security:  The Federal Role" (June 14, 1995)).  The report suggested:  <P>
<OL><LI>Adoption of performance or technical standards for computer security, which might constitute de facto liability standards.<P>
<LI>Testing by independent nationally recognized "security certification" laboratories, which might also constitute de facto liability standards.<P>
<LI><B>Sector-Specific Liability Standards</B>:  "Because security requirements greatly vary in different contexts, such as finance, law enforcement, medicine, national security, research, and education, there may be a need for context-specific standards that can evolve as requirements change."  This arguably reflects the context-specific common law standard of care.  </OL>

<H4>F.  Other statutory standards of care</H4>
<P>The government has imposed heightened and relaxed standards of care on service providers for the following sectors:
<OL><LI><B>Telecommunications Common Carriers</B>:  both the standard of care and potential liability of telecommunications carriers are limited in the tariffs approved by the FCC.  47 U.S.C.  203 (1988 & Supp. V 1993);  Lebowitz Jewelers Ltd. v. New England Telephone & Telegraph, 508 N.E.2d 125 (Mass. App. Ct. 1987) (telephone carrier not liable for losses from jewelry store robbery even though burglars disconnected alarm from an easily accessible carrier's box).   <P>
<LI><B>Bonded Warehousemen</B>:  a higher standard of care applies to certain regulated storage facilities.  Warehousemen must exercise care "commensurate with the task;" warehousemen may not disclaim or waive this standard of care, but may by contract with the customer limit damages to a sum certain.  U.C.C.  7-204(1) (1991).</OL></blockquote><P>

<h3>II.  Civil Actions Against Those Who Violate Network Security</h3>

<blockquote><H4>A.  State tort law</H4>
<P>Tort law provides various causes of action against perpetrators of computer crime, including:
<OL><LI><B>Invasion of privacy</B>:  although the scope of this tort claim and, in some states, statutory cause of action, varies, invasion of privacy in all likelihood would be applicable to unauthorized access to private computer data.<P>
<LI><B>Conversion</B>:  the tort of conversion involves the intentional wrongful taking or interference with the personal property of another.  Since the essence of the tort is the deprivation of an owner's right to use or possess property, it could be applicable to data damage or theft.  As conversion can apply to the taking of either tangible or intangible property, there is likely some overlap among conversion, trade secrets misappropriation, and intellectual property right violations.<P>
<LI><B>Misappropriation of trade secrets</B>:  most states provide a private cause of action for the theft and disclosure of trade secrets, but not all electronic information qualifies as a trade secret -- only that information which is non-public, commercially advantageous and protected.  Kewannee Oil Co. v. Bicron Corp., 416 U.S. 470 (1974).  Federal intellectual property law may preempt certain trade secret actions, including those related to copyrighted software.  Joseph D. Zamore, Business Torts  17.08(3) (1991).  But see Warkington Assoc., Inc. v. Rel-Time Eng. Sys., Inc., 522 F. Supp. 367, 368 (N.D. Ill. 1981) ("[N]either Congress nor the courts have viewed the Federal Copyright Act as preempting the common law of trade secret misappropriation.")<P>

<LI><B>Interference with Contract</B>:  the tort of interference with contract provides for recovery against a party who intentionally induces another party not to perform a contract.  Stofer v. First Nat'l Bank, 571 N.E.2d 157, 166 (Ill. 1991).  Computer sabotage conducted for commercial advantage could give rise to this cause of action. <P>

<LI><B>Interference with Prospective Advantage</B>:  the tort of interference with prospective advantage involves a party who intentionally deprives another of a business opportunity.  O'Brien v. State Street Bank & Trust Co., 401 N.E.2d 1356, 1357 (Ill. 1980).  Computer sabotage conducted for commercial advantage could also give rise to this cause of action. </OL>

<H4>B.  Civil Copyright Action</H4>
<P>Unauthorized use of copyright material without the copyright owner's permission can give rise to an infringement action.  17 U.S.C.  106, 501(a).  Plaintiff is not required to prove defendant's intent to infringe.  Playboy Enterprises Inc. v. Frena, 839 F. Supp. 1552, 1558 (M.D. Fla. 1993).  Therefore, inadvertent theft of copyright material from a computer network could give rise to an infringement action.

<H4>C.   Section 605 of the Communications Act</H4>
<P>Civil cause of action against any person who intercepts and discloses unauthorized wire or radio communication, or who receives unauthorized wire or radio communication for his benefit.  47 U.S.C. 605(e)(3) (1988 & Supp. V 1993);  California Satellite Sys. v. Seimon, 767 F.2d 1364 (9th Cir. 1985). Remedy can include actual damages, statutory damages, and litigation costs -- statutory damages may be multiplied if repeated violations are found. There is no liability for the inadvertent interception of data.  Snider Communications Corp. v. Cue Paging Corp., 840 F. Supp. 664 (E.D. Ark. 1994) (no cause of action against paging company which had received data stream that included data from another paging service's subscribers).

<H4>D.  Electronic Communications Privacy Act of 1986 (ECPA)</H4>
<OL><LI><B>Unlawful Interception of Communications</B>:  civil cause of action against any person engaged in unauthorized interception and disclosure of electronic communications.  18 U.S.C.  2520 (1988);  Boddie v. American Broadcasting Co., 731 F.2d 333 (6th Cir. 1984) (civil actions against television network that broadcast an unauthorized recording of plaintiff).  Electronic communication is broadly defined to include all types of data communications.  Remedy can include statutory damages, punitive damages, and litigation costs -- statutory damages may be multiplied if repeated violations are found.  Biton v. Menda, 812 F. Supp. 283 (D.P.R. 1993) (each intercepted conversation justified a $10,000 civil penalty).  <P>
<LI><B>Unlawful Access to Stored Communications</B>:  a provider of electronic communication service, subscriber, or customer aggrieved by a unauthorized access to stored electronic communications may bring a civil action against any person which engaged in that violation.  18 U.S.C.A. 2707 (Supp. 1995);  Steve Jackson Games, Inc. v. United States Secret Service, 816 F. Supp. 432 (W.D. Tex. 1993), aff'd, 36 F.3d 457 (5th Cir. 1994).  Damages can include actual damages, defendant's profits, minimum statutory damages of $1,000, and litigation costs.  18 U.S.C.A.  2707(c).</OL> </blockquote><P>

<h3>III.   Computer Crime</h3>
<blockquote><P>The following statutes provide a basis for the prosecution of virtually every imaginable computer crime.  Although state and national legislators are justifiably alarmed by the potential damage which could result from computer crime, additional criminal provisions are not required.
<H4>A.   Computer Fraud and Abuse Act of 1986</H4>
<OL><LI><B>Fraudulent Use of Access Device</B>:  criminal penalties for use of an unauthorized "access device," such as computer password, PIN code, or smart-card, to obtain something of value, including electronic funds transfers and credit card charges.  18 U.S.C. 1029(a)(Supp. 1995);  United States v. McNutt, 908 F.2d 561 (10th Cir. 1990), cert. denied, 498 U.S. 1084 (1991);  United States v. Blackmon, 839 F.2d 900 (2d Cir. 1988).<P>
<LI><B>Alter, Damage, or Destroy Information on a "Federal Interest" Computer</B>:  extends not only to systems used by the U.S. government and systems operated by government-regulated financial institutions, but also to any other system that links two or more computers in different states.  18 U.S.C.A.  1030(a)(5)(Supp. 1995).  Requisite "intent" is intent to obtain access to the system, not an intent to cause damage.  United States v. Morris, 928 F.2d 504 (2d. Cir.) (conviction of Robert Morris for releasing the Internet "worm" that crippled 6,000 computer systems worldwide), cert. denied, 502 U.S. 817 (1991). <P>
<LI><B>Commit Fraud for Financial Gain on a "Federal Interest" Computer</B>:  criminal penalties for those who use a federal interest computer to defraud victims of property or anything of value.  18 U.S.C.A.  1030(a)(4)(Supp. 1995).<P>
<LI><B>Access to Classified Government Information</B>: criminal penalties for unauthorized access to classified government information with the intent to injure the United States or benefit a foreign nation.  Id.  1030(a)(1).<P>
<LI><B>Fraudulent Access to Financial Records</B>:  criminal misdemeanor penalties for unauthorized access to computer records of financial institution, credit card issuer, or consumer credit reporting agency.  Id. 1030(a)(2).</ol>

<H4>B.   State Computer Crime Laws</H4>
<OL><LI><B>Unauthorized Tampering</B>:  New York law imposes criminal liability for the unauthorized alteration of a computer program or computer data.  N.Y. Penal Law  156.20 (Supp. 1995); People v. Versaggi, 629 N.E.2d 1034 (1994) (Kodak computer technician convicted for shutting down phone service of company chemical plant).<P>
<LI><B>Trade Secret Violations</B>:  most states criminalize the theft and disclosure of trade secrets.  Not all information qualifies as a trade secret -- only that information which is non-public, commercially advantageous and protected.  Kewannee Oil, 416 U.S. 470. </OL> 

<H4>C.  Electronic Communications Privacy Act of 1986 (ECPA)</H4>
<OL><LI>Unlawful Interception of Communications:  criminal penalties for interception of electronic communications without the consent of at least one party to the communication.  18 U.S.C.A. 2510,  2511 (1970 & Supp. 1995).  Electronic communication is broadly defined to include all types of data communications.<P>
<LI><B>Unlawful Access to Stored Communications</B>:  criminal penalties for unauthorized access to electronic communications stored on a network or personal computer.  18 U.S.C.A. 2701 (Supp. 1995).</OL>

<H4>D.  Garden Variety Criminal Statutes</H4>
<OL><LI><B>Wire Fraud</B>:  criminal liability for fraudulent attempt to obtain money or property by means of a wire communication.  18 U.S.C.A.  1343 (Supp. 1995).  Wire communication includes computer messages sent via the public switch network.  The broad definition of property extends to property interest in the non-disclosure of proprietary information.  Carpenter v. United States, 484 U.S. 19 (1987) (wire fraud conviction of Wall Street Journal reporter's disclosure of column contents).  But see United States v. LaMacchia, 871 F. Supp. 535 (D. Mass. 1994) (wire fraud statute did not provide basis for criminal copyright prosecution of bulletin board operator). <P>
<LI><B>Copyright Infringement</B>:  criminal liability for intentional infringement of copyright for commercial advantage or financial gain.   Copyright Act 506(a); 18 U.S.C.A.  2319 (Supp. 1995).  Downloading alone might constitute infringement.  MAI Sys. Corp. v. Peak Computer, Inc., 991 F.2d 511, 517 (9th Cir. 1993) (civil infringement liability), cert. dismissed, 114 S. Ct. 671 (1994).<P>
<LI><B>Racketeering (RICO)</B>:  Criminal liability for engaging in a pattern of racketeering activity, including fraud, interference with commerce, or money laundering.  18 U.S.C.A.  1961 (Supp. 1995).  <P>
<LI><B>Interstate Transportation of Stolen Property</B>: criminal liability only applicable to transport of "goods, wares, merchandise, securities or money, of the value of $5,000 or more." 18 U.S.C.A.  2314 (Supp. 1995).  The transport of stolen intellectual property may not qualify as "goods, wares, [or] merchandise" for purposes of this statute.  United States v. Brown, 925 F.2d 1301 (10th Cir. 1991) (ITSP not applicable to transport of source code); Dowling v. United States, 473 U.S. 207 (1985) (ITSP not applicable to interstate shipments of pirated Elvis recordings).<P>
<LI><B>Interference with Commerce</B>:  criminal liability for interference with interstate commerce by means of extortion or threat of violence.  18 U.S.C.A.  1951 (1970 & Supp. 1995).<P>
<LI><B>Interference with Communications Systems</B>:  criminal liability for intentional interference with the function of a communications "line, system, or station."  18 U.S.C.A. 1362 (Supp. 1995). <P>
<LI><B>Vandalism to Government Property</B>:  criminal liability for intentional depredation against property of the United States.  Id.  1361.  This provision served as the basis for destruction of a governmental computer.  United States v. Komisaruk, 885 F.2d 490 (9th Cir. 1989).<P>
<LI><B>Vandalism to Public Records</B>:  criminal liability for intentional damage to public records and documents maintained by the government.  18 U.S.C.A.  2071 (Supp. 1995).    </OL>

<H4>E.   Pending Federal Legislation (August, 1995)</H4>
<OL><LI><B>Exon's Communications Decency Act</B>:  Senator Exon's (Republican-Nebraska) amendment to S. 652 targeted on-line porn, and those who transmit objectionable materials through the Internet or commercial on-line services -- but it may also impose liability on operators of the telecommunications systems and on-line services used to transmit that material.  Status:  approved by the Senate;  opposed by Speaker Gingrich and as yet not brought before the House for a vote.  <P>
<LI><B>Grassley Electronic Racketeering Bill</B>:  Senator Grassley's (Republican-Iowa) bill, S. 974, was introduced as the "Elliot Ness meets the Internet" legislation.  S. 974, 104th Cong., 1st Sess. 1995.  Status:  referred to Senate Judiciary Committee, no immediate action anticipated.  In addition to the controversial encryption measures, Grassley's bill would:<P>
<UL><LI>Amend definition of racketeering activity to criminalize acts which "damage or threaten to damage electronically or digitally stored data."<P>
<LI>Specify that any person who uses a computer or computer network in furtherance of racketeering activity is subject to prosecution under RICO.  <P>
<LI>Provide law enforcement authority to obtain Title III electronic surveillance orders for any RICO violation, including the computer-related RICO violations in the Grassley bill.  </UL></ol></blockquote><P>


<hr>
