<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B38-174</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA079-000540-B029-340</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.steptoe.com:80/290546.htm 198.240.72.75 19970124171640 text/html 31014
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Fri, 24 Jan 1997 17:16:25 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.2
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Tue, 10 Dec 1996 08:03:53 GMT
Content-length: 30837
</DOCHDR>
<html><HEAD>
<TITLE>Executive Summary</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body><H2 align=center>Executive Summary</H2><P>
<CENTER><I>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/mamlet.htm">Alfred Mamlet</a></I><p> </CENTER>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>


<P>

	Congress has just enacted the most significant telecommunications legislation in more than sixty years.  The Telecommunications Act of 1996 (the &quot;1996Act&quot; or &quot;S.652&quot;) eliminates and reduces numerous barriers to entry in the local telephone, long distance and video markets.  There are a number of other provisions that will significantly change all aspects of telecommunications law from Television to the Internet.  <P>

<P>

	This analysis of the 1996 Act focuses on the changes to the Communications Act with the greatest impact upon electric utilities.  The electric utilities are directly affected by the legislation in two principal ways.  <P><P><B>
First</B>, the 1996 Act opens up the local exchange market to competition.  This will significantly enhance the value of the existing communications assets of utilities.  For virtually any new entrant in the local telephone market, an electric utility's extensive fiber optic network, other communications facilities and access to poles, conduits, ducts and rights-of-way would be treasured assets.  Many electric utilities are likely to participate in the newly competitive telephone market by:  (1)selling capacity in their fiber optic cable system to new entrants; (2)participating in joint ventures with experienced telecommunications providers; or (3)even entering the local market directly.  Regardless of the form of participation, an understanding of the new structure of the local telephone market will be valuable.  In addition, participation in the local telephone market may subject utilities to obligations ranging from interconnection responsibilities to Universal Service Fund contributions.  <P>

<P>

	<B>
Second</B>, the 1996 Act dramatically expands the new pole attachment requirements for electric utilities.  Pole attachments for all telecommunications carriers, not just cable operators, are now subject to federal regulation.  The 1996Act also provides a new rate formula for attachments given to these telecommunications carriers which, while more generous than the old formula, does not allow a utility to recover its fully allocated costs, much less the market rate.  Finally, the 1996Act may impose, for the first time, a mandatory requirement on an utility to provide pole attachments.  <P>

<H4 align=center>Local Competition<P>

Preemption</H4>

<UL>

<LI></CENTER>The 1996 Act broadly preempts all state and local government barriers to entry.  The FCC is given authority to determine which state and local statutes and regulations are preempted.

</UL>
<H4 align=center>Interconnection Obligations</H4>

<UL>

<LI></CENTER>The 1996 Act creates three tiers of interconnection obligations.  <B>
First</B>, the legislation includes a new statutory definition of common carriage that will impose basic interconnection obligations on all telecommunications carriers that directly or indirectly serve the public.  Electric utilities that provide telecommunications services directly to the public, or indirectly to the public by providing capacity to other carriers, may have these basic interconnection obligations:

<UL>

<LI>interconnect directly or indirectly with other carriers; and

<LI>conform to network interconnection standards established by the FCC and handicapped accessibility standards.

</UL>
<LI><B>
Second</B>, all local exchange carriers (&quot;LECs&quot;) (including new entrants) will have four additional interconnection obligations intended to enable multiple carriers to provide competing services in the same area:

<UL>

<LI>permit resale of their services;

<LI>provide number portability and dialing parity to the extent technically feasible;

<LI>offer access to poles, ducts, conduits, and rights-of-way; and

<LI>establish reciprocal compensation agreements for origination and termination of telecommunications.

</UL>
<LI><B>
Third</B>, incumbent local exchange carriers have the most stringent set of interconnection requirements:

<UL>

<LI>duty to comply with the interconnection obligations of all LECs

<LI>duty to negotiate in good faith interconnection agreements with new entrants covering the following subjects;

<LI>duty to provide nondiscriminatory, unbundled interconnections at any technically feasible point of incumbent LEC network at reasonable rates;

<LI>duty to provide services at wholesale rates to competitors for resale at rates that do not include retail marketing and billing and collection charges;

<LI>duty to provide reasonable public notice of changes in the network; and 

<LI>duty to provide actual collocation of equipment on incumbent LEC premises at reasonable rates and nondiscriminatory conditions.

</UL></UL>
<H4 align=center>Interconnection Agreements</H4>

<UL>

<LI></CENTER>The heart of the statutory plan to facilitate competitive entry into the local exchange market is the interconnection agreement to be negotiated between an incumbent LEC and a new entrant.  

<LI>If an agreement cannot be negotiated, either party can request the State Commission to conduct compulsory arbitration.

<LI>Interconnection agreements are subject to State Commission approval.  Judicial review of State Commission decisions will be in federal district courts.

</UL>
<H4 align=center>Universal Service</H4>

<UL>

<LI></CENTER>The 1996 Act lays the groundwork for changing the Universal Service system.

<LI>The difficult task of devising a new Universal Service plan has been delegated to a Joint Board of FCC and State Utility Commissioners.

<LI>The legislation expands the class of carriers required to contribute to the Universal Service Fund to all telecommunications carriers providing interstate communications.  This expanded class will include some electric utilities.

</UL>
<H4 align=center>Pole Attachment Regulation<br>



Expanding Scope of Regulation</H4>

<UL>

<LI></CENTER>The 1996 Act expands pole attachment regulation to cover attachments given to all telecommunications carriers (except for incumbent local exchange carriers) in addition to cable TV system operators.

<LI>Existing pole attachment agreements with telecommunications carriers remain in force with their rate provisions intact.

</UL>
<H4 align=center>

Rate Regulation</H4>

<UL>

<LI></CENTER>The formula used previously for cable TV system operators will continue to apply to them as long as they do not expand to telecommunications.  This formula limits rates to the cost of the proportionate amount of usable space occupied, and does not permit any recovery of costs allocable to unusable space.  The old formula will also be used for telecommunications carriers for two years.

<LI>The FCC is required to establish a new formula by regulation within two years.  The new formula will permit utilities to recover the same cost of the proportionate amount of usable space occupied under the old formula, plus two-thirds of the proportionate cost of the unusable space.  Moreover, rate increases arising from the new formula must be phased-in over five years from the effective date of the FCC regulation.  In summary, while the new formula is more generous than the old, it will not be effective for seven years and will prevent utilities from recovering their fully allocated costs, much less market rates.

</UL>
<H4 align=center>Mandatory Pole Attachments</H4>

<UL>

<LI></CENTER>The 1996 Act also contains a <B>
mandatory</B> pole attachment provision, stating that &quot;[a] utility <B>
shall</B> provide a cable television system or any telecommunications carrier with nondiscriminatory access to any pole, duct, conduit, or right-of-way owned or controlled by it.&quot;

<LI>The precise scope of this mandatory duty is unclear.  It could be:

<UL>

<LI>a requirement to provide attachment to any requesting carrier or cable TV operator;

<LI>a requirement to provide attachment to any requesting carrier or cable TV operator if an attachment has already been given to a competing carrier or cable TV operator; or

<LI>a requirement that a utility providing telecommunications or cable TV provide nondiscriminatory access to competitors.

</UL>
<LI>Since the previous pole attachment provisions withstood a Fifth Amendment challenge precisely because there was no mandatory obligation, the current statute may be vulnerable to a Fifth Amendment challenge.

</UL>
local telephone competition
	Many electric utilities are considering participation in the local telephone market in one form or another.  Most electric utilities have extensive fiber optic networks and other assets that would be quite valuable for any competitive entry into the local telephone market.  The 1996Act increases the value of these assets by breaking down barriers to entry into the local exchange market.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Preemption of State and Local Entry Barriers</h4>

	The 1996 Act broadly preempts all state and local statutes and regulations that create barriers to entry in the local exchange and interstate markets.  This blanket removal of entry barriers opens the way for utilities, long distance companies, cable television companies, competitive access providers, and others to enter the local exchange market.  This preemption provision is also likely to curtail the ability of a state or local government to impose substantive franchising regulations on carriers attempting to enter the telecommunications market.  However, a state or local government might be able to require a franchise if the grant were a ministerial action.  <P>

<P>

	Under the preemption provision, a State retains authority to &quot;protect the public safety and welfare, ensure the continued quality of telecommunications services, and safeguard the rights of consumers.&quot;  However, a State's attempt to restrict entry unduly is not likely to prevail since the FCC has the authority to determine that such regulation is preempted.  This FCC power will probably be used to invalidate most attempts to restrict entry.  <P>

  <P>

	The 1996 Act includes an explicit provision preserving the right of local governments to impose such fees.  State or local governments can &quot;require fair and reasonable compensation from telecommunications providers, on a competitively neutral and nondiscriminatory basis, for use of public rights-of-way on a nondiscriminatory basis.&quot;  The key requirement is that the fee must be &quot;competitively neutral.&quot;  If a Regional Bell Operating Company (&quot;RBOC&quot;) is not charged a fee, then an electric utility offering telecommunications services should not have to pay one.  <P>

	<h4 align=center>Interconnection Requirements</h4>

	<p>The 1996 Act establishes interconnection requirements that allow requesting carriers to interconnect with the network of an existing telecommunications carrier.  The 1996 Act imposes these interconnection obligations in two ways:  (1) through a generalized interconnection obligation required of all telecommunications carriers; and (2) through interconnection obligations that are specifically required of all local exchange carriers.  Within six months of enactment, the FCC is responsible for developing regulations to implement both categories of interconnection obligations.  To the extent that they are consistent with Federal law, State access and interconnection obligations are not preempted.<P>

<P>

	The first category of interconnection requirements will require an electric utility providing telecommunications services to allow competing carriers to interconnect with the utility's communications network.  The second category of interconnection requirements will be instrumental in allowing new entrants seeking to provide telecommunications to take advantage of the vast communications network of the incumbent local exchange carrier (&quot;LEC&quot;).  <P>

<h4 align=center>Interconnection Requirements For All Telecommunications Carriers</h4>

	The 1996 Act contains a generalized interconnection duty that is imposed on all &quot;telecommunications carriers.&quot;  <P>

<h4 align=center>Expansion of Common Carriage</h4>

	Under the 1996 Act, a &quot;telecommunications carrier&quot; is a &quot;provider of telecommunications services....&quot;  In turn, &quot;telecommunications service&quot; means the &quot;offering of telecommunications for a fee directly to the public, or to such classes of users as to be effectively available directly to the public, regardless of the facilities used to transmit the telecommunications service.&quot;<P>

<P>

	The definition of &quot;telecommunications carrier&quot; is potentially a significant expansion of the interconnection obligations currently required of all common carriers because under the 1996 Act a 
telecommunications carrier shall be treated as a <B>
common carrier</B> under this Act only to the extent that it is engaged in providing telecommunications services.... <P>

<P>

	Previously, it was possible for an utility to provide &quot;private carriage&quot; by negotiating individualized agreements with common carriers such as competitive access providers.  However, these provisions could potentially reclassify the same utility activity as common carriage.  Common carriers are subject to a number of requirements including: (1) filing interstate tariffs with the FCC; (2) charging just and reasonable rates; (3) serving all customers in a non-discriminatory manner; and (4)providing interconnections as described below.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Interconnection Obligations</h4>

	The 1996 Act requires each telecommunications carrier:  <P>

<P>

(1) to interconnect directly or indirectly with the facilities and equipment of other telecommunications carriers; and<P>

(2) not to install network features, functions, or capabilities that do not comply with the standards established pursuant to section 255 or256.<P>

<P>

Therefore, electric utilities providing &quot;telecommunications services&quot; have potential interconnection obligations.  However, the interconnection obligations of LECs are much greater.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Local Exchange Carrier Interconnection Obligations</h4>

	LEC interconnection requirements are further divided into two categories:  (1)interconnection obligations required of all LECs (including new entrants); and (2)additional obligations required of only incumbent LECs.  A LEC is a provider of telephone exchange service or exchange access service.  A company that completes a local call between customers provides telephone exchange services, while a company that connects a customer with a long distance telephone carrier provides exchange access service.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Interconnection Requirements of All LECs</h4>

	Under the first category, the 1996 Act specifies that all LECs (including new entrants) have the following duties:  <P>



<UL>

<LI>A duty not to prohibit or impose unreasonable or discriminatory conditions or limitations on the resale of the LEC's telecommunications services.

<LI>A duty to provide number portability (to the extent technically feasible) and dialing parity.  Number portability permits consumers to retain the same local phone number regardless of which LEC they are using.  Local dialing parity permits consumers to dial the same number of digits regardless of which carrier they use.

<LI>A duty to offer access to the poles, ducts, conduits, and rights-of-way of such carrier to competing providers of telecommunications services on rates, terms, and conditions that are consistent with the 1996 Act's pole attachment regulations.

<LI>A duty to establish reciprocal compensation arrangements for the origination and termination of telecommunications.

</UL>

These requirements are intended by Congress to encourage competition by knocking down entry barriers, opening networks and requiring cooperation between LECs.  A new entrant in the local exchange market will be required to comply with this list of local exchange carrier obligations.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Interconnection Requirements of Incumbent LECs</h4>

	&quot;Incumbent local exchange carriers&quot; must satisfy a much more stringent set of interconnection requirements, designed to reduce barriers for new entrants.  An &quot;incumbent LEC&quot; is a carrier offering local service in the area at the time of enactment, or one classified by the Commission as having a market position comparable to an &quot;incumbent LEC.&quot;  <P>

<P>

	Incumbent LECs have the following duties:<P>



<UL>

<LI>A duty to negotiate, in good faith, agreements that incorporate the duties that are required of all LECs, and the following duties:

<LI>A duty to provide interconnection to any requesting carrier.  An interconnection agreement must contain rates, terms, and conditions that are &quot;just, reasonable, and nondiscriminatory....&quot;  Further, it must provide for interconnection at any technically feasible point within the incumbent LEC's network, and the agreement must be at least equal in quality to that provided by the local exchange carrier to itself or &quot;to any subsidiary, affiliate, or any other party to which the carrier provides interconnection....&quot;

<LI>A duty to provide, on an unbundled basis and at rates, terms, and conditions that are just, reasonable and nondiscriminatory, nondiscriminatory access to network elements at any technically feasible point.

<LI>A duty to offer any telecommunications service that it offers at retail to subscribers for resale at wholesale rates.  The wholesale rates shall be determined by the state commission on the basis of the retail rates minus the marketing, billing and collection costs avoided by the LEC.  The reasonableness of these rates will be an issue that creates substantial administrative litigation.  

<LI>Duty to provide reasonable public notice of changes in the information necessary for the transmission and routing of services using that LECs facilities and network.

<LI>A duty to provide, at rates, terms, and conditions that are just, reasonable, and nondiscriminatory, for actual collocation of equipment necessary for interconnection or access to unbundled network elements at the premises of the LEC.

</UL>

	The additional interconnection requirements and obligations imposed upon incumbent LECs are intended to promote competition by reducing barriers to entry and by preventing LECs with established market power from using their monopoly power in the local exchange markets to prevent the development of competition.<P>

<h4 align=center>Waivers of Interconnection Requirements</h4>

	In an effort to alleviate any adverse economic burdens that any of the LEC interconnection requirements may cause, the 1996 Act includes certain exemptions. The most significant of these exemptions is that LECs with less than 2percent of the subscribed access lines nationwide are permitted to petition the relevant State commission for a modification or suspension of interconnection requirements required of all LECs, and the requirements required only of incumbent LECs.  To the extent the State believes that imposing interconnection obligations upon these carriers would create an adverse economic impact on consumers or carriers, or would be technically infeasible, the State is permitted to suspend the interconnection obligations.  <P>

<P>

	In addition, rural telephone companies are exempt from the interconnection requirements for incumbent LECs until they receive an interconnection request that the State determines is not unduly economically burdensome, is technically feasible, and is consistent with the universal service provisions of the 1996Act.<P>

	<h4 align=center>Procedures for Negotiation of Interconnection Agreements</h4>

	The heart of the statutory plan to facilitate competitive entry into the local exchange market is the interconnection agreement to be negotiated between an incumbent LEC and a new entrant.  An incumbent LEC must agree to negotiate over each of the interconnection obligations discussed above.<P>

  <P>

	The new entrant (or the incumbent LEC) can ask the State commission to conduct compulsory arbitration.  The request must be made during the 25-day window between the 135th and 160th day after the new entrant initially requested negotiation of an interconnection agreement.  The State commission has only about six months to complete the arbitration.  <P>

<P>

	Regardless of whether the State commission is requested to take part in the negotiations, all negotiated interconnection agreements are subject to final approval from the State commission.  The standard by which the State commission reviews these interconnection agreements for approval depends upon the State commission's involvement in the negotiation process.  <P>

<P>

	In reviewing an interconnection agreement in which the State has not intervened, the State has broad discretion to reject the agreement if it would not be consistent with &quot;the public interest, convenience, and necessity....  In reviewing an interconnection agreement that was achieved through arbitration by the State commission, however, the State can reject the agreement only if it determines that it does not satisfy the interconnection standards mandated by Congress.  Appeals from State commission interconnection determinations will be heard by federal district courts.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Universal Service Contributions</h4>

	The 1996 Act lays the groundwork for changing the system of Universal Service.  The 1996 Act delegates to a Joint Board of FCC and State Utility Commissioners the task of creating a new Universal Service plan for a competitive environment.  <P>

<P>

	The 1996 Act also expands the class of carriers required to contribute to the Universal Service Fund:  <P>

<P>

Every telecommunications carrier that provides interstate telecommunications services shall contribute, on an equitable and nondiscriminatory basis, to the specific, predictable, and sufficient mechanisms established by the Commission to preserve and advance universal service.<P>

<P>

Thus, electric utilities providing interstate telecommunications services will be required to contribute funds to the Universal Service Fund.  As mentioned above, an electric utility will be considered a telecommunications carrier depending upon the degree to which it offers telecommunications services to the public.  Any other provider of interstate telecommunications may also be required to make a contribution if the Commission decides the public interest warrants.  <P>

<P>

	As for telecommunications carriers that provide intrastate telecommunications services, the 1996 Act does not preempt state regulations that mandate particular universal service contributions for that state.  <P>

<h4 align=center>POLE Attachment Regulation</h4>

	The 1996Act makes three critical revisions to the pole attachment provisions in the Communications Act, which cover poles, ducts, conduits and rights-of-way.  <B>
First</B>, the 1996Act broadens the scope of pole attachments subject to regulation.  <B>
Second</B>, the 1996Act establishes a new formula for the additional pole attachments subject to regulation which provides for increases over the old rate formula.  However, these increases will occur very gradually, and still will not allow utilities to recover their fully allocated cost, much less market rates.  <B>
Third</B>, the 1996Act may be construed to require utilities to furnish pole attachments in some circumstances.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Expansion of Pole Attachment Regulation</h4>

	The 1996 Act greatly expands the coverage of federal pole attachment regulation.  Previously, federal law only regulated pole attachments for cable television providers.  However, under the 1996 Act, federal regulation extends to pole attachments for virtually all telecommunications carriers.  <P>

<P>

	There is only one exception.  Pole attachments provided to an &quot;incumbent local exchange carrier,&quot; such as an RBOC, are not covered by the 1996 Act.   Presumably, incumbent LECs have, or can readily obtain, comparable pole attachments.  Incumbent LECs that want attachments from an electric utility can be charged market rates.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Pole Attachment Rates For Telecommunications Carriers </h4>

	Pole attachment rates for a cable system that will be used solely for provision of cable services will continue to be subject to the old formula.  Pole attachments for telecommunications carriers will be set at rates that will increase gradually over the old formula.  Very gradually.  <P>

<P>

	Under the formula that will continue to apply for cable television providers, an electric utility can only charge for the cost related to the proportion of usable space that is occupied on the pole.  By only considering the percentage of the usable space occupied, the old rate formula does not reflect any of the utility's costs for the unusable space on the pole.  Accordingly, a utility is prohibited from recovering its fully allocated costs under the formula that will continue to apply to cable TV operators.  <P>

<P>

	For the next two years, the rates for telecommunications carriers' new pole attachments will also be subject to the same formula previously applied only to cable TV operator attachments.   Fortunately, current pole attachment agreements will remain in force with their rate provisions intact.  However, new pole attachment agreements with any telecommunications carrier will be subject to the old rate formula immediately.  As under existing law, the new federal pole attachment regulations will not apply in states where pole attachment regulation meets the federal standards.  <P>

<P>

	The FCC is required to adopt new rate regulations for pole attachments provided to telecommunications carriers within two years.  These regulations must permit utilities to recover the full proportionate cost of the usable space (as under the current formula) plus two-thirds of the proportionate cost of the non-usable space (which was not permitted previously).  Clearly, utilities will still be prevented from recovering their fully allocated costs.  <P>

<P>

	While the new rate formula will permit rate increases, these increases must be phased in through equal annual increments over a five-year period commencing when the FCC's rate regulations become effective.  In contrast to the 1996Act's prompt implementation of most provisions, it will take seven years before these rate provisions are fully effective.  <P>

<h4 align=center>Mandatory Pole Attachments</h4>

	The 1996 Act may impose a new <B>
requirement</B> that utilities provide pole  attachments to requesting carriers.  While the previous pole attachment provisions did not require a utility to provide or renew a pole attachment,  the new legislation states that:  <P>

<P>

A utility <B>
shall</B> provide a cable television system or any telecommunications carrier with nondiscriminatory access to any pole, duct, conduit, or right-of-way owned or controlled by it.  <P>

<P>

	This mandatory access provision will lead to litigation over two critical issues.  <B>
First</B>, it is not clear from this language whether this provision:  (1)requires a utility to provide attachments to any requesting cable television system or telecommunications carrier; (2)requires a utility providing attachments to one cable system or one telecommunications carrier to provide them to all competing carriers (subject to space limitations); or (3)requires a utility providing telecommunications or cable TV service to provide nondiscriminatory access to competitors.  <P>

<P>

	<B>
Second</B>, there is a good argument that the mandatory access provision, particularly if construed broadly, is a taking under the Fifth Amendment.  In <I>
Loretto v. Teleprompter Manhattan CATV Corp.</I>, 458U.S. 419 (1982), the Supreme Court found that a New York statute requiring landlords to give cable television operators access to their property for cables and switches was a taking.  <P>

<P>

	Relying on <I>
Loretto</I>, the Eleventh Circuit invalidated the previous pole attachment provision because it found that the FCC effectively required a utility to maintain a pole attachment.  The Supreme Court, however, reversed.  It construed the Pole Attachment Act not to require a utility to provide a pole attachment.  <P>

<P>

	Nevertheless, the Supreme Court specifically left open the application of <I>
Loretto</I> if utilities were required &quot;to enter into, renew, or refrain from terminating pole attachment agreements.&quot;  The new statutory provision poses precisely this question.  Utilities will be able to challenge the mandatory access provisions on constitutional grounds.  
