<h4 align=center>

<a name="1">EPA ACTS TO INVOLVE PUBLIC IN NEGOTIATED REGISTRATION ACTIONS</a></h4>

<P>

	EPA has announced that it plans to begin seeking input from public interest groups and other members of the &quot;public&quot; in registration decisions that previously had been negotiated between the Agency and registrants.  This new policy, published in the Federal Register on August 10, 1994, may have an important effect on negotiated registration actions to reduce risks.<P>

	For several years, EPA has tried to avoid formal action to suspend or cancel registrations, believing these procedures are too time and resource consuming.  Instead, EPA has acted by negotiating with registrants.  Generally, EPA informs registrants what restrictions it wants, ranging from hazard warning changes to deletion of label uses to cancellations, and the negotiates with the registrant(s) to a level of restriction both sides find acceptable.  Then, the registrant submits a &quot;voluntary&quot; request that EPA take the action agreed upon, and EPA implements the decision.<P>

	The decision as to what level of restriction is acceptable to EPA and the negotiations that lead up to the voluntary action to date have taken place in private, with just the registrant and EPA participating.  This was thought by both sides to preserve any settlement or attorney work product privileges, and, of course, to avoid a burdensome public suspension or cancellation hearing, with potential adverse publicity.  Among recent examples are the Alar withdrawal and the withdrawal of mercurial biocides from the marketplace.<P>

	Now, EPA is indicating that it plans to open to members of the public the thus-far closed process of negotiating product withdrawal or restriction.  The Federal Register notice dated August 10 indicates that EPA will be providing notice of negotiations concerning these &quot;voluntary&quot; actions to public interest groups and others to involve them in the decision making.  This action is likely to have a serious disturbing influence on the negotiation process.<P>

	In the future, registrants must be especially careful to have clearly articulated ground rules before undertaking any negotiations with EPA.  If it is not possible to agree upon a role for non-parties that is satisfactory to the registrant, the registrant may be compelled to consider the alternative of having EPA begin formal suspension or cancellation action.<P>

	Under current law, these proceedings generally move very slowly, and any resolution that could have been reached with EPA through pre-complaint negotiation also can be attained in negotiations to resolve a suspension or cancellation hearing.  However, EPA has been aggressive in threatening to publicize any formal hearing, and making the registrant appear to be a malefactor.<P>

<center><a href="#begin">Return to Articles List</a></center>
<P>

<hr>


<h4 align=center><a name="2">DOT FINALIZES NEW HAZMAT STANDARDS, PROPOSES OTHERS</a></h4>

<P>

	The Department of Transportation's Research and Special Programs Administration (RSPA) recently updated regulations for hazardous materials transportation.  59 Fed. Reg. 67390 (Dec. 29, 1994).  The changes bring the regulations into conformity with international standards, specifically those in the United Nations Recommendations on the Transport of Dangerous Goods.<P>

	The new regulations amend approximately one-third of the hazardous materials rules.  Many of the changes are editorial; however, some are more substantive, e.g., the addition of new categories to the hazardous materials classification tables and reclassification of certain other materials.  The rules are effective October 1, 1996, with voluntary compliance beginning immediately.<P>

	RSPA has issued a notice of proposed rulemaking relative to hazardous materials transportation registration and fee assessment.  60 Fed. Reg. 5822 (Jan. 30, 1995).  Comments on the new fee proposal are due by April 3, 1995.  Because the current annual fee of $300 does not generate adequate revenues to fund the nationwide emergency response training program, RSPA is proposing a graduated fee scale ranging from $300 to $5050, depending on material type.<P>

	Radioactive materials would be at the high end with a $5,050 fee ($50 for processing).  Fees for explosives and certain materials poisonous by inhalation would range from $300 to $5,050, depending on quantity.  Hazardous materials in bulk quantities would be assessed fees between $300 and $5050, depending on the number of different bulk packagings used during a registration year.  Anyone transporting registrable hazardous materials in non-bulk packaging or anyone not transporting in one year, but planning to do so in the next year, would pay a $300 fee.<P>

	Only one change would be made in the definition of materials.  The regulation would be expanded to include every &quot;material poisonous by inhalation.&quot;  The proposed rules would make permanent the exemption from registration for foreign-domiciled parties offering registrable quantities of hazardous materials only from outside the United States.  This exemption applies only if the other country does not impose a registration requirement or fee on United States companies.<P>

	In other activity, RSPA terminated a rulemaking proceeding begun in 1987 which questioned the need for shippers to obtain proof of insurance from each hazardous material carrier.  Since adequate enforcement mechanisms regarding insurance already exist, RSPA considered a rule burdensome and unnecessary.<P>
<center><a href="#begin">Return to Articles List</a></center>
<P>

<hr>

<h4 align=center><a name="3">CHEMICAL WEAPONS CONVENTION (CWC) LIKELY  TO IMPACT MANY U.S. CHEMICAL MANUFACTURERS  AND  SUPPLIERS</a></h4>

<P>

	The U.S. Department of Commerce is developing  regulations to implement the Chemicals Weapons Convention (&quot;CWC&quot;).  This international agreement will have a broad impact on the U.S. chemical industry, affecting approximately 6,000 U.S. facilities that produce, ship or consume a wide range of commercial chemicals and related products.  They will be subject to reporting obligations and possibly even inspections under this new program.  59 Fed. Reg. 66291, 66292.<P>

	The CWC is a multi-lateral treaty that prohibits the development, production, acquisition, transfer or use of chemical weapons.  It also establishes an ambitious program for monitoring production and trade in chemicals that have &quot;dual uses;&quot; <U>
i.e.</U>, chemicals which are used in commercial applications but also are ingredients for various military chemical agents.  The United States and 130 other countries signed the CWC on January 13, 1993.  President Clinton has submitted the treaty and implementing legislation to Congress.  The treaty will not enter into force until 180 days after the 65th nation ratifies the convention.  The Preparatory Commission, the body of signatory states currently working out implementation matters, assumes an effective date as early as July 1995.<P>

	Chemicals covered by the CWC are divided into three schedules based on their possible utility in developing chemical weapons.  Schedule 1 covers known warfare agents and their immediate precursors.  These chemicals have limited commercial applications.  Schedule 2 covers toxic chemicals and precursors that have some industrial uses.  Schedule 3 covers chemicals with broader commercial applications.  The CWC also covers &quot;other relevant facilities&quot; that produce unscheduled discrete organic chemicals or discrete organic chemicals containing phosphorus, sulfur and chlorine above specified thresholds.<P>

	Because many of the chemicals covered by the CWC have legitimate commercial applications, the Commerce Department predicts that the Convention will have a far-reaching impact on U.S. industry.  For example, thidiglycol (&quot;TDG&quot;), which is commonly used to manufacture ink for ballpoint pins, also is a precursor for the blistering agent mustard.  Similarly, trimethyl phosphite, which is used in insecticides, also is a precursor for some nerve agents.<P>

	The CWC requires an extensive reporting and international inspection regime for facilities, including civilian industries, that produce and in some cases process or consume chemicals that could be used in a weapons' program.  The Bureau of Export Administration (&quot;BXA&quot;), estimates that the reporting requirements may apply to thousands of commercial chemical facilities.  In addition, the facilities that produce and in some cases process or consume specified quantities of CWC related chemicals willbe subject to routine on-site inspection conducted by international inspectors.  CWC also provides for &quot;challenge&quot; on-site inspections, which may be conducted at any public or private location at the request of another country when there is legitimate concern about activities.<P>

	The CWC includes provisions to protect the confidential business information of companies that are subject to the reporting and inspection requirements.  These provisions were developed in consultation with chemical trade associations from the U.S., Europe and Japan.<P>

	The CWC requires that upon its entry into force each country that ratifies the convention adopt the necessary measures to implement its obligations.  The BXA announced December 23, 1994, that it will begin drafting regulations to implement the CWC.  59 Fed. Reg. 66291 (1994)  If you would like a copy of the chemicals on Schedules 1, 2 and 3 or have questions regarding the CWC or its likely impact, please contact us.
<p><center><a href="#begin">Return to Articles List</a></center>

<P>

<A name="DDE_BOOKMARK1">
</A><P>
<hr>
<h4 align=center><a name="4">INTEREST GROUPS SUE TO OBTAIN CONFIDENTIAL STATEMENTS OF FORMULA</a></h4>

<P>

	In a case that potentially could impact all pesticide registrants, the Northwest Coalition for Alternatives to Pesticides (NCAP) and the National Coalition Against the Misuse of Pesticides (NCAMP) have brought suit against EPA seeking the release of Confidential Statements of Formula, including the identities and quantities of inert ingredients, for six registered pesticides.  The American Crop Protection Association (ACPA) has intervened in the lawsuit on the side of EPA. <P>

	Federal pesticide law has embodied a policy of confidential treatment for product formulas since the original enactment of FIFRA in 1947, and manufacturers have relied on the assurance of confidentiality in submitting their formulas for registration and reregistration.  Section 10 of FIFRA protects confidentiality of formulas submitted to EPA in connection with pesticide registration and reregistration.  Significantly, section 10(d)(1)(B) protects from disclosure the identities and quantities of inert ingredients utilized in pesticide formulations. 7 U.S.C. e136h(d)(1)(B).  In addition, Exemption 4 of the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) protects from disclosure pursuant to FOIA, trade secrets and confidential commercial information submitted by regulated entities.  5 U.S.C. e552(b)(4).  EPA has promulgated specific procedures at Title 40, Part 2 of the Code of Federal Regulations, for preserving the confidentiality of proprietary business information pursuant to Exemption 4 of FOIA. <P>

	In April 1991, NCAP and NCAMP sent EPA a formal FOIA request seeking the Confidential Statements of Formula, including the identities and quantities of inert ingredients, for Aatrex 80W (atrazine), Weedone LV4 (2,4-D), Roundup (glyphosate), Velpar (hexazinone), Garlon 3A (triclopyr), and Tordon 101 (picloram and 2,4-D). EPA denied  the FOIA  request on the grounds that the request sought confidential information exempt from disclosure pursuant to Exemption 4 of FOIA.  NCAP and NCAMP filed suit seeking a declaratory judgment that EPA's withholding of the Confidential Statements of Formula and EPA's failure to segregate confidential and non-confidential portions of the Confidential Statements violate FOIA, and an injunction ordering release of the requested information.  The requests of NCAP and NCAMP, if granted, could set a precedent subjecting the Confidential Statements of Formula submitted by all pesticide registrants to disclosure through FOIA.<P>

	ACPA  intervened in the suit on the side of EPA to protect the rights of its members, particularly the registrants of the  pesticides at issue.  Much of the  information at issue has been submitted under seal to the Court pursuant to a protective order.  Plaintiffs, ACPA and EPA each have filed motions for summary judgment.<P>

	The summary judgment motions of ACPA and EPA focus primarily on section 10(d) of FIFRA and on the exemptions to FOIA for information protected from disclosure by another statute (Exemption 3) and for trade secrets and confidential commercial information (Exemption 4).  ACPA takes the position that the Confidential Statements of Formula are protected pursuant to section 10 of FIFRA in combination with Exemption 3 of FOIA, which protects from disclosure information specifically exempted by statute.  5 U.S.C. e552(b)(3).  In the alternative, ACPA argues that the Confidential Statements of Formula are protected trade secrets and commercial information under Exemption 4 of FOIA.  ACPA's motion also develops the commercial harm that could arise from indiscriminate disclosure of pesticide formulations.<P>

	In its motion, EPA defends its decision on both procedural and substantive grounds.  EPA points out that the regulations do not require it to incorporate a discussion of the criteria set out at 40 C.F.R. e2.208 in its determination.  EPA also argues that release of full or partial lists of ingredients by some of the registrants of pesticides at issue did not waive confidentiality claims to unreleased information, such as sources and percentages of ingredients in the formulation.  Finally, like ACPA, EPA argues that the withheld information qualifies for protection as both trade secrets and confidential information.<P>

	In their motion, NCAP and NCAMP argue that their FOIA request should be granted because (1) EPA failed to follow its own regulations by not making specific findings with respect to the criteria set forth in its regulations for determining trade secret or confidential commercial information; (2) EPA did not make an independent determination that the information sought was confidential, but rather rubber-stamped the registrants' claims; (3) EPA failed to segregate satisfactorily confidential from non-confidential information, for example, in three cases EPA declined to disclose the identity of the active ingredient even though the registrant must disclose the identity of the active ingredient on its label; and (4) the information sought does not qualify as trade secrets or confidential commercial information because the identities of inert ingredients in particular formulations can be obtained through reverse engineering and are available in public documents such as patents, MSDSs, and published documents.  Plaintiffs also emphasize that, with respect to three of the pesticides, the registrants made available lists of the inert ingredients.<P>

	Significantly, in their summary judgment motion, NCAP and NCAMP appear to back away from their original FOIA request.  Their complaint clearly seeks release of the Confidential Statements of Formula, which would include not only the identities of inert ingredients, but also percentages of ingredients utilized in the formulations and sources of all ingredients, including the actives.  Plaintiffs' motion, however, focuses solely on the identities of the inerts, a distinction which is buried in a footnote.  If in fact NCAP and NCAMP are interested only in the identities of the inert ingredients, the court, if it grants their demand for the Confidential Statements of Formula, could give them much more information than they actually are seeking in the lawsuit and could set a dangerous precedent regarding disclosure of Confidential Statements of Formula.<P>

	The parties are scheduled to submit opposing briefs in the near future.
<p><center><a href="#begin">Return to Articles List</a></center>

<hr>
<a name="5">TREND IN RECENT COURT DECISIONS CONFIRMS THAT FIFRA SECTION 24(b) PREEMPTS COMMON LAW DAMAGES CLAIMS AGAINST PESTICIDE MANUFACTURERS</a><P>

<P>

		A number of well reasoned cases have solidified the trend in the case law holding that FIFRA &#167;24(b) preempts state common law tort claims against pesticides based on inadequate labeling, failure to warn, breach of warranty, and other related causes of action since the Supreme Court's decision in <I>
Cipollone v. Liggett Group, Inc.</I>, 112 S. Ct. 2608 (1992) (plurality).  <I>
Cipollone</I> addressed the preemptive scope of a provision of the Public Health Cigarette Smoking Act of 1969 analogous to &#167;24(b) of FIFRA.  <P>

		Section 24(b) of FIFRA precludes states from imposing labeling requirements on registrants, even those <I>
in addition to</I> FIFRA standards:  &quot;[A] State shall not impose or continue in effect any requirement for labeling or packaging in addition to or different from those required under the Act.&quot;  7 U.S.C. &#167;136v(b).  Prior to <I>
Cipollone</I>, the federal Courts of Appeals were divided on whether the language of<B>
 </B>&#167;<B>
</B>24(b) preempted claims for mislabeling and failure-to-warn brought by plaintiffs allegedly harmed by a pesticide registered under FIFRA.  Some courts found that 24(b) did not preempt common law claims, following the line of reasoning in <I>
Ferebee v. Chevron Chemical Co.</I>, 736 F.2d 1529 (D.C. Cir.), <I>
cert</I>. <I>
denied</I>, 469 U.S. 1062 (1984).  The court in <I>
Ferebee</I> held that for purposes of FIFRA preemption, state tort damage actions were distinguishable from state regulation through legislation and administrative regulation.  The Supreme Court in <I>
Cipollone</I>, confronted with language virtually indistinguishable from that of FIFRA &#167;24(b), rejected <I>
Ferebee</I>'s distinction between regulations and tort suits, instead adopting the rationale of numerous other decisions preempting state tort claims on the ground that damage actions have the same effect as legislative regulation.  Either in response to administrative regulation or to avoid tort liability, the registrant must change its label.<P>


		Following the Supreme Court's ruling in <I>
Cipollone</I>, virtually every court to consider the issue has held that claims relating to pesticide labeling or packaging, including particularly claims that the label failed to include certain warnings, are preempted by FIFRA.  The courts have differed, however, on what kinds of claims other than express inadequate labeling claims are also preempted.  Review of these cases is instructive in terms of (a) avoiding, where possible, conduct that may give rise to potential claims that plaintiffs will argue are outside FIFRA preemption; and (b) framing the issues in response to any such claim in away that increases the likelihood that a court will apply the broad effect of <I>
Cipollone</I>'s mandate in a given case.<P>


<B>
Duty-to-Warn Claims</B><P>

<P>

		Recent cases decided by a number of federal and state courts virtually all have held that a variety of claims relating to pesticide labeling are preempted, whether or not specially identified as labeling claims.  Such claims seek to impose state law liability on a registrant for doing exactly what federal law authorizes:  distribution of a federally registered pesticide with warning labels required and approved by EPA.  Such claims, therefore would impose state law duties different from and in addition to the FIFRA labeling requirements, and are therefore preempted by FIFRA.<P>



<B>
Breach Of Warranty Claims and Other Claims Based on Warnings Outside the Label</B><P>



		A number of courts have similarly held that, in addition to labeling claims, breach of warranty claims are preempted.  Clearly, with respect to allegations relating to warranties expressed or implied by the label, these claims are based on, or derived from, FIFRA-approved labeling and therefore are preempted.  <P>



		A leading case taking a broad view of the preemptive effect of FIFRA &#167;24(b) is the Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals' decision in <I>
Papas v. Upjohn Co.</I>, known as &quot;<I>
Papas II</I>.&quot;  <I>
Papas II</I> involved personal injury claims arising from exposure to a pesticide.  The Eleventh Circuit held that FIFRA &#167;24(b) preempted not only plaintiffs' claims based directly on inadequate label warnings, but also plaintiffs' claims based on negligent testing and disclosure to EPA, inadequate point-of-sale and other non-label warnings, and implied warranty.  <P>



		The court in <I>
Papas II</I> also extended the preemptive effect of FIFRA &#167;24(b) to failure-to-warn claims that go beyond the actual language of the labels and to claims for breach of implied warranty.  The court held that FIFRA &#167;24(b) preempted claims asserting that Upjohn Co. breached a duty to warn by failing to utilize adequate point-of-sale or other non-label warnings.  In addition, the court held that claims based on breach of implied warranties were preempted.  The court reasoned that implied warranties are imposed by state contract law and run afoul of FIFRA &#167;24(b)'s prohibition against state regulation of labeling.<P>



		The year after the Eleventh Circuit decided <I>
Papas II</I>, a Florida state appeals court, in <I>
ISK Biotech Corp. v. Douberly</I>, likewise held that FIFRA &#167;24(b) preempts claims for inadequate labeling and failure to warn outside the label.  In that case, which involved crop damage associated with use of a particular pesticide, plaintiffs argued that ISK Biotech had a duty to disseminate warning information once it became aware that its pesticide damaged watermelon crops and the label was no longer accurate.  The Florida court, citing <I>
Papas II</I>, held that this claim arose from a theory of inadequate labeling and, therefore, was preempted by FIFRA &#167;24(b).<P>

<B>
Claims Related To Testing And Placement In The Stream Of Commerce</B><P>



		Allegations relating to monitoring, testing, inspection and placement in and removal from the stream of commerce also come within the ambit of FIFRA's preemption of pesticide labeling and packaging.  <P>



		FIFRA's labeling regulations are inextricably linked to monitoring, testing, and inspection of pesticides.  Before registering a pesticide under FIFRA, EPA requires submission of substantial test data so that EPA can make its risk-benefit determination.  7 U.S.C. &#167;136a(c)(2).  The regulations set forth in detail the types of data that must be submitted in support of a registration application.  <I>
See</I> <I>
generally</I> 40 C.F.R. Part 158.  By granting a registration under FIFRA, EPA has determined that the product will perform its intended function without unreasonable adverse effects in the environment, including any unreasonable health risks to humans.  7 U.S.C. &#167;36(bb); 40 C.F.R. &#167;52.112(e).  Thus, approval under federal law constitutes a finding, based on EPA's expert review of extensive evidence and testing, that the product bearing the labeling required by EPA does not pose any unreasonable risk.   In <I>
Papas II</I>, plaintiffs attempted to circumvent FIFRA &#167;4(b) by arguing that their claims were not based on the inaccuracy or inadequacy of the EPA-approved label, but on the fact that the manufacturer, Upjohn Co., caused the labeling inadequacy by failing to disclose to EPA information that should have been on the label.  The court responded that it was up to EPA and not a jury to determine whether the labels were incomplete and, if so, what changes were necessary.<P>

<B>
Recent Attempts to Circumvent FIFRA Preemption</B><P>



		Other cases have extended FIFRA preemption to alleged duties to warn not specifically encompassed by the label.  In a few recent decisions, however, lower federal and some state courts have tried to limit the application of <I>
Cipollone</I> in the FIFRA context.<P>



		For example, a California state appeals court recently considered FIFRA &#167;24(b) in connection with California's program to eradicate the medfly.  In that case, <I>
Macias v. State of California</I>, plaintiff sued pesticide manufacturers after he was blinded allegedly due to exposure to aerial spraying of malathion mixed with bait.  The State of California failed to provide the general public with the warnings set forth on malathion's EPA-approved label.  Plaintiff sued the manufacturers of malathion, alleging they had a duty to warn the downstream bystanders once they became aware that the State, the direct user, had failed to do so.  The California Court of Appeals took a narrow view of the preemptive effect of &#167;24(b) and stated:  &quot;'FIFRA does not occupy the whole field of pesticide regulation,' merely 'the entire field of pesticide labeling.'&quot;  The court did not cite <I>
Cipollone</I>, but relied instead on <I>
Wisconsin Public Intervenor v. Mortier</I>, in which the Supreme Court held that FIFRA &#167;24(b) does not prohibit government units below the state level from imposing ordinances requiring posted placards to warn about pesticide use .  The California Supreme Court has accepted review of the <I>
Macias</I> case.  <P>

		A couple of other recent decisions also have refused to apply preemption to state tort claims not expressly based on a failure-to-warn theory.  For example, in <I>
Papas II</I>, the Eleventh Circuit drew the line at claims for breach of express warranties.  The court reasoned that express warranties made outside the label are voluntary and governed by state law.  Consequently, the court held, FIFRA &#167;24(b) does not preempt claims for breach of express warranty.<P>


		Similarly, a Florida intermediate appellate court in <I>
ISK Biotech Corp. v. Douberly</I>, held that FIFRA &#167;24(b) preempts claims for inadequate labeling and failure to warn outside the label, and limited that rule by also stating that &#167;24(b) did not preempt plaintiff's claim for a defective product.  The court held that the strict liability claim was based solely on the product's defective condition, and, therefore, was independent from any theory pertaining to inadequate labeling.  While the court did not cite to it, the decision in <I>
ISK Biotech</I> adopted the same rationale as <I>
Kennan v. Dow Chemical Co.</I>, a pre-Cipollone decision from the Middle District of Florida which likewise held that FIFRA &#167;24(b) did not preempt claims based on strict liability for defective design or manufacturing flaw.  <P>



		We believe the logic in the <I>
Macias</I>, <I>
ISK Biotech</I> and <I>
Macrie</I> decisions is fundamentally flawed, based on the language of FIFRA and the explicit findings EPA (and the states) make in granting a registration.  The limitations should be subject to attack in an appropriate follow-on case.<P>



		Like the California court in <I>
Macias</I>, a New Jersey appellate court has held that state courts are not preempted by FIFRA &#167;24(b) from imposing a duty on pesticide manufacturers to warn persons likely to be exposed to pesticides downstream, <I>
i.e.</I>, those persons who would not have access to the label.  In <I>
Macrie v. SDS Biotech Corp.</I>, the court considered claims brought by employees of a produce broker who were injured when they were exposed to a pesticide sprayed directly on produce by a farmer in contravention of the label instructions.  While the court did not hold that a duty existed to warn individuals downstream from the direct user, the court held that the claim was not preempted and could go to the jury.<P>



<CENTER>
*   *   *<P>

</CENTER>		In sum, recent court decisions have clearly established that in most U.S. jurisdictions, state tort law claims based on pesticide labeling are preempted by FIFRA &#167;24(b).  However, recent cases in a few jurisdictions have somewhat narrowed the full preemptive scope of FIFRA &#167;24(b).  In responding to common law claims based on exposure to pesticides, a registrant should work to maximize the preemptive value of its registration by characterizing a case as involving the FIFRA-approved label to the extent practicable, and relying upon all available case law, statutory and regulatory support.<P>
<p><center><a href="#begin">Return to Articles List</a></center>

