<html><HEAD>
<TITLE>State Taxation of On-Line Transactions</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body><H2 align=center>State Taxation of On-Line Transactions</H2>
<CENTER><I>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart A. Baker</a></I></CENTER>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>

<H3>I.  Basics Of On-Line Commerce</H3>
<blockquote><H4>A.  Using On-Line Service Providers</H4>
<OL><LI>Merchants pay fees and abide by the on-line service provider's rules in exchange for space in the on-line service provider's "electronic mall."  <P>
<LI>Subscribers to the on-line service can browse the mall, view merchant products, and purchase the merchant's goods or services by means of:<P>
<UL><LI>Credit Card<P>
<LI>Electronic Cash<P>
<LI>Charge to subscriber's account with the on-line service (Microsoft Network). </uL><P>
<LI> America On Line:  As an Example<P>
<UL><LI>Benefits to merchants:  AOL has more than several million subscribers.  AOL helps the merchant design publicity, promotions, etc. to reach AOL subscribers.<P>
<LI>Fees:  Merchants pay AOL a store set-up fee, an annual maintenance fee, and a commission on all sales made via AOL.<P>
<LI>Terms and Conditions of Sale:  Merchants must offer AOL subscribers a "100% satisfaction guarantee," agree to on-line product complaint procedures, and provide a discount to first-time shoppers.  The merchant must also abide by AOL condition's, such as a restriction of the merchant's right to sell or reuse AOL customer names.  Merchants must indemnify and hold harmless AOL in a variety of circumstances</UL></OL></blockquote>

<H4>B.  Using the Internet</H4>
<OL><LI>Merchant uses a node on the Internet to create a "World Wide Web" page.<P>
<LI>Users find the Web page using software browsers (e.g., Netscape) that may have commercial features (encryption for credit cards).</OL></blockquote>

<H3>II.  Overview Of Tax Issues</H3>
<blockquote><H4>A.  Sales Via An Internet Web Site</H4>
<P>Will Merchants Be Required to Collect Use Tax?

<H4>B.  Will Service-Providing Companies like CompuServe be Required to Collect the Use Tax for On-Line Purchases?</H4>
<OL><LI>May service providers be required to collect tax?<P>
<LI>May such service providers be deemed agents of the out-of-town merchant, and as such, be required to collect tax?</OL>
<H4>C.  Use Tax Collected On Sale of Information</H4>.
<H4>D.  Tax of Issuers of Electronic Cash.</H4></blockquote>

<H3>III.  Sales Via An Internet Web Site:  Will Merchants Be Required to Collect Use Tax? </H3>

<blockquote><H4>A.  Test for Commerce Clause challenge to state tax</H4>
<OL><LI>Tax does not violate Commerce Clause if it "[1] is applied to an activity with a substantial nexus with the taxing State, [2] is fairly apportioned, [3] does not discriminate against interstate commerce, and [4] is fairly related to  the services provided by the State." Complete Auto Transit, Inc. v. Brady, 430 U.S. 274 (1977).<P>
<LI>To meet requirement of "substantial nexus" to impose sales and use tax, the seller must have a physical presence in the taxing jurisdiction greater than just the "slightest presence."  National Geographic Soc'y v. California Board of Equalization, 430 U.S. 551, 556 (1977).  But the physical presence may not be required to be "substantial." Orvis Co v. Commissioner of Taxation and Finance, 64 U.S.L.W. 2012, 1995 WL 354196 (N.Y.  June 14, 1995).</OL>
<H4>B.  The test represents balancing of interests</H4>
<P>"The view that interstate commerce enjoys a free trade immunity from state taxation; and the view that businesses engaged in interstate commerce may be required to pay their own way."  Goldberg v. Sweet, 488 U.S. 252, 259 (1989). 
<H4>C.  What are the 'nexus' boundaries set forth by the Courts so far?</H4>
<OL><LI>"[A] vendor whose only contacts with the taxing State are by mail or common carrier lacks the 'substantial nexus' required by the Commerce Clause."  Quill Corp. v. North Dakota, 112 S.Ct. 1904, 1912 (1992). <P>
<LI>In summary, courts review a number of factors to determine whether a sufficient nexus exists.  See e.g. Quill, 112 S.Ct. at 1907-08; National Bellas Hess, 386 U.S. at 754; Pledger v. Troll Book Clubs, 871 S.W.2d 389, 390 (Ark. 1994); Geoffrey, Inc. v. South Carolina Tax Comm'n, 437 S.E.2d 13 (S.C.), cert. denied, 114 S.Ct. 550 (1993); SFA Folio Collections v. Bannon, 585 A.2d 666 (Conn.), cert. denied, 501 U.S. 1223 (1991); Bloomingdale's By Mail v. Pennsylvania, 567 A.2d 773 (Pa.Cmwlth. 1989), aff'd without op., 591 A.2d 1047, and cert. denied, 504 U.S. 955 (1992); L.L. Bean v. Pennsylvania, 516 A.2d 820 (Pa.Cmwlth. 1986). <P>
<UL><LI>Whether the seller maintains offices or other places of business in the taxing state.  Generally, the continuous presence of an office or other place of business will create sufficient nexus for taxation.  See D.H. Holmes v. McNamara, 486 U.S. 24 (1988)(finding nexus for taxation of out-of-state mail order business of Louisiana Corporation with, among other things, 13 department stores in-state); National Geographic Soc'y, 430 U.S. 551 (finding nexus where company had two in-state offices, even where the operations of those offices was unrelated to the out-of-state mail-order business).<P>
<LI>Whether the seller places sales people or other representatives in the taxing state.  See Quill, 112 S.Ct at 1914. ("the presence in the taxing state of a small sales force, plant or office" of an out-of-state company will likely create a sufficient nexus). <P>
<LI>Whether the seller owns property within the taxing state.  A small amount of property has been held not to create a sufficient nexus for taxation.  Quill, 112 S.Ct. at 1914 & n.8. (company's licensing of small amounts of software to clients in the state).  See also Cally Curtis v. Groppo, 572 A.2d 302, 306 (Conn. 1990) (leasing of films by out-of-state company did not create a sufficient nexus), cert. denied, 111 S.Ct. 77 (1990).<P>
<LI>Whether the seller maintains a local telephone listing within the taxing state.  (1) Fact that telephone call was initiated or terminated in a state and either charged to a service address in the state or billed or paid for within the state supported nexus for purposes of excise tax on interstate telephone calls.  Goldberg v. Sweet, 488 U.S. 252, 263 (1989).  However, Court doubted that "States through which [a] telephone call's electronic signals pass have a sufficient nexus" and that "the termination of an interstate call [in a state] by itself, provides a substantial enough nexus for a state to tax a call."  Id.
(2) Use of "800" telephone number held not to create nexus.  SFA Folio Collections, 585 A.2d at 671; L.L. Bean, 516 A.2d at 825.<P>
<LI>Whether the seller advertises in local media; whether the seller prints or publishes catalogs in the taxing state; whether the seller is licensed to do business in the taxing state; whether the seller has a bank account in the taxing state; whether the seller has enlisted the aid of a collection agency in the taxing state.  These factors have not been dispositive, but when they are absent, they usually are cited as support for the fact that no nexus exists.  SFA Folio Collections, 585 A.2d 666; L.L. Bean, 516 A.2d 820.</UL><P>
<LI>Still unclear as to the exact extent of the physical presence required.<P>
<UL><LI>See Orvis Co., 1995 WL 354196 at *1. (holding that use tax may be applied where out-of-state company sends sales agents into the taxing jurisdiction only "sporadically.")  See also Standard Pressed Steel v. Washington Dep't of Revenue, 419 U.S. 560 (1975) (finding nexus where one employee, who worked out of his home, was present in the taxing jurisdiction). </UL></OL>

<H4>D.  Arguments for Taxing Authorities that Merchants of On-Line Sales Can Be Required to Collect Use Tax</H4>
<OL><LI>The Supreme Court's "bright-line, physical- presence requirement" set forth in Quill does not provide a safe harbor for Internet transactions.  <P>
<UL><LI>The bright-line rule originally exempted only the mail and common carriers. <P>
<LI>The rationale given in Quill for maintaining the physical presence rule was partly the long-term reliance of existing mail-order businesses on the existing rule.  But the on-line business is too young to claim long-term reliance on such a rule.<P>
<LI>Another factor considered by the courts to determine state taxation is whether the out-of-state merchant derived benefits from the state.  Internet sales are facilitated by local computer networks and servers, often operated by state university or other government computers, which may be maintained with state money.<P>
<LI>"Cached" Web software is physically present in user's computer memory.<P>
<LI>"Transactional Nexus."</UL></OL>

<H4>E.  Arguments that Merchants of On-Line Sales Will Not Be Required To Collect Use Tax </H4>
<OL><LI>Other than use of common-carrier phone lines, the Internet does not create any physical presence by sellers in the taxing state.  It certainly is less of a physical presence than that created by out-of-state mail-order companies that physically send their materials into the state. <P>  
<LI>The question of whether a merchant receives benefits from a taxing state is associated with the Due Process limits on state taxation, not with Commerce Clause. <P>
<UL><LI>Until the Supreme Court's 1992 decision in Quill, 112 S.Ct. 1904, both Due Process concerns and Commerce Clause concerns precluded state taxation of out-of-state mail-order transactions where the seller did not have sufficient contact with the taxing state.  See National Bellas Hess, 386 U.S. at 756.  In Quill, the Court found that Due Process concerns no longer stood in the way of such taxation.  112 S.Ct. at 1911.      <P>
<LI>The Due Process rationale for allowing states to tax out-of-state merchants is different from that of the Commerce Clause.  The Due Process rationale is based on whether the merchant derived some benefit from the state, while the Commerce Clause rationale centered on protection of interstate commerce from undue state interference.  Id.</UL></OL></blockquote>

<H3>IV.  Will Service-Providing Companies like CompuServe be Required to Collect the Use Tax for On-Line Purchases?</H3>
<blockquote><H4>A.  May Service Providers be Required to Collect Use Tax?</H4>
<OL><LI>Service providers could be required to collect use tax if they have a sufficient nexus to the taxing state, either by virtue of computer equipment in the state or sales offices and personnel. <P> 
<UL><LI>State courts have used Goldberg v. Sweet, 488 U.S. 252, to uphold the imposition of use taxes on the sale of telephone exchange network access services.  AT & T v. Department of Revenue, 778 P.2d 677, 681 (Colo. 1989); GTE Sprint v. Department of Treasury, 445 N.W.2d 476, 481 (1989).  <P>     
<LI>One case seems particularly on point: The Ohio Supreme Court upheld the imposition of use tax on "automatic data processing and computer services" which included provision of "access to computer equipment for the purpose of processing data or examining or acquiring data stored in or accessible to such computer equipment."  Quotron Sys. v. Limbach, 584 N.E.2d 658, 659 (Ohio 1992).  
Quotron was required to collect the tax from subscribers for fees collected by it for terminal charges, access fee and charges for data.  The court found "a definite link exists" between Quotron and the taxing state; "Quotron owns equipment that it delivers to subscribers in Ohio, constructed two communication concentrators in Ohio, and employs personnel in Ohio to install and maintain equipment."  Id. at 659-60.  Furthermore, the "information travels on telephone lines in Ohio to equipment situated in Ohio to subscribers located in Ohio."  Id. at 660. </UL><P>
<LI>Arguments for State Taxing Authorities that Service Providers Must Collect Tax<P>
<UL><LI>Purchase of merchandise over Internet carries the same nexus as the purchase of telephone services; both initially involve a local telephone call.</UL><P>
<LI>Arguments that Service Providers Do Not Have to Collect Tax<P>
<UL><LI>States have never tried to tax the U.S. Mail or other common carriers for facilitating interstate purchases.<P>
<LI>Upholding service provider's requirement to collect tax on telephone call is not the same as requiring service provider to collect tax on purchase.  The later is one step removed.  Furthermore, Sprint is a telephone "retailer;" maybe closer to a merchant than a service provider. </UL></OL>

<H4>B.  Agency Argument</H4>
<OL><LI>Companies such as CompuServe may be required to collect a use tax on out-of-state purchases if they are deemed agents or representatives of the out-of-state merchants assisting in the solicitation of business.<P>
<UL><LI>Individual employees as agents or representatives:  (1) Can be an independent contractor; if independent, it is important that the person receive a commission.  Scripto, Inc. v Carson, 362 U.S. 207 (1960);  (2)Test in a case involving gross receipts tax was "whether the activities performed in th[e] state on behalf of the taxpayer are significantly associated with the taxpayer's ability to establish and maintain a market in this State for sales." Tyler Pipe Industries v. Washington Dep't of Revenue, 483 U.S. 232, 249-51 (1987).  Unclear whether analysis for gross receipts tax can apply here.  See Geoffrey, 437 S.E.2d 13, 18 (S.C. 1993) (Quill rule limited to sales and use tax); (3) The employee might not have to be positioned full-time in the taxing state.  Orvis, 1995 WL 354196.   <P>
<LI>Other companies as agents or representatives.  Courts will usually not find that corporate affiliation alone creates an agency relationship.  SFA Folio Collections, 585 A.2d 666 (finding insufficient nexus where out-of-state company was part of "larger enterprise of affiliated corporations" including some corporations subject to state tax); L.L. Bean, 516 A.2d 820 (finding insufficient nexus where out-of-state corporation sold returned items and seconds to in-state corporation).<P>
<LI>Finding agency or representative relationship may depend on state law. (1) Court held that two "essential elements for a showing of agency relationship were authorization and control." Pledger, 871 S.W.2d at 392 (finding no agency relationship where teachers acted as go-between between book seller and students; deriving its test from the Restatement (Second) of Agency and 2 Am.Jur. 13, Agency,  2).
The agent must have authority to act for the principal and its acts must be subject to the principal's control.  Pledger, 871 S.W.2d at 392. (2) Court also distinguished factually similar California case on the basis of different state laws regarding agency.  Id. (citing Scholastic Book Clubs v. State Board of Equalization, 207 Cal.App.3d 734 (1989) (holding teachers were agents of an out-of-state book seller)).</UL><P>
<LI>Arguments for State Taxing Authorities<P>
<UL><LI>Under Tyler Pipe Industries test, service providers such as CompuServe may "significantly" assist the out-of-state merchant in maintaining a market in the taxing state.  483 U.S. at 250.  If CompuServe provides potential customers with access to on-line catalogs, it may meet this test.<P>
<LI>CompuServe could have a relationship of "authorization and control" with the out-of-state merchant.  This would depend on the details of the contract.   </UL><P>
<LI>Arguments for Service Providers<P>
<UL><LI>Unclear whether Tyler Pipe Industries analysis can apply here.  That case involved nexus to apply gross receipts tax, while it is possible the Quill case is limited to sales and use tax. See Geoffrey, 437 S.E.2d at 18.<P>
<LI>Depending on terms of the contract and state law, service provider will argue that no agency relationship exists.</UL></OL></blockquote>

<H3>V.  Use Tax Collected on Sale of Information</H3>
<blockquote>A.  The Ohio Supreme Court upheld imposition of use tax on "automatic data processing and computer services" which included provision of "access to computer equipment for the purpose of processing data or examining or acquiring data stored in or accessible to such computer equipment."  Quotron, 584 N.E.2d at 659. </blockquote><P>

<hr>
