<html><head><title>EMERGING JAPANESE ENCRYPTION POLICY</title></head>
<H3 align=center>Emerging Japanese Encryption Policy</H3>
<P><CENTER><I>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart A. Baker</a></I></CENTER>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>


<H4>Summary:  The emerging Japanese consensus on cryptography</H4>

		<P>Japan's encryption policymaking is in its early stages, but there are strong signs that encryption is increasingly seen as a key technology for improving Japan's penetration of the Global Information Infrastructure.  A highly selective (and possibly biased) sampling of informed Japanese opinion on cryptography suggests a growing determination to treat cryptography as a national Japanese economic priority.  

		<P>In the United States and Europe, encryption policy is formed by a mix of interests.  Advocates of business, national security agencies, and more recently the police -- all play a large role in the policy debate.  This policy triumvirate is difficult to see in Japan.  For a variety of reasons, commercial interests are predominant in Japanese government thinking about encryption.  Time after time during my interviews, I was reminded that Japan was an island nation that has not had to defend itself for fifty years and so has not had to confront the national security concerns associated with encryption.  And Japanese police face severe political and constitutional constraints on wiretapping, so the prospect of losing this criminal investigative tool seems not to be as troubling to the Japanese government as to the United States and many European nations.

		<P>That leaves business interests in command of encryption policy inside Japan.  And business interests increasingly see encryption as an enabling technology that is critical for Japanese success in a world suffused with information networks.  Cryptography is seen as a key technology for a variety of network payment problems, from ensuring the identity of each party to the transaction to providing an electronic receipt without creating a risk to the privacy of electronic transactions.

		<P>Just below the surface of Japanese government comments on encryption policy there seems to lie a suspicion that U.S. government concerns about national security and law enforcement are an excuse to perpetuate what is increasingly seen as U.S. domination of a strategic industrial technology.  Some officials insisted that all encryptionsystems can be broken, suggesting that the solution was to fund better police decryption technology.  Others suggested that the solution was to have two levels of encryption -- reserving the most powerful for government and national security while encouraging commercial encryption standards that are less strong.  This approach, however, has proven to be a dead end in the United States, where any cryptographic strength deemed exportable has immediately been condemned as insufficient by business and cryptography experts.

		<P>All in all, the emerging Japanese consensus on cryptography could pose a major challenge to U.S. (and perhaps European) government hopes of striking a compromise between commercial and governmental interests with respect to cryptographic policy.  If Japan puts the weight of its government and industry behind strong, unescrowed encryption, competitive pressure will quickly doom any attempt to influence this technology through export controls and standard-making.  Governments will be forced to choose between overt regulation in the Russian and French manner or laissez-faire policies of the sort that now prevail in the domestic markets of countries like the United States, Great Britain, and Germany.

		<P>Whether Japanese policy will in fact coalesce around a purely commercial approach to cryptography remains to be seen.  In response to the analysis above, one senior MPT official stated that the U.S. and European concerns had not been well understood in Japan until the OECD meeting and that the MPT's study group would be giving special importance to the issue in its review of electronic payment systems.  Thus, it is apparently still possible that Japan will join with the U.S. and European governments in seeking to shape a more accessible encryption standard.

<H4>Details of Japanese Encryption Studies</H4>

		<ol><B><LI><I>The Ministry of Post and Telecommunications</I></B>

		<P>The powerful Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications (MPT) is hoping to take the lead in driving this area of policy.  (Likely competitors for control of cryptography policy include the Ministry for International Trade and Investment and the Bank of Japan -- also agencies with a predominantly commercial focus).  <P>

			<ul><LI><I>Network study group</I>.  In early 1995, the MPT set up a "Research and Study Group on the Use of Electronic Information and Networks."  The Research Group's report is hardly surprising to students of the Global Information Infrastructure.  It emphasizes the need for privacy protection on networks to encourage use of the infrastructure, and it proposes some concrete measures to protect the safety and reliability of electronic information.  

		<P>The group recommends use of public key encryption for a variety of network-enhancing purposes -- authentication of identity (both for digital signatures and access control), hashing (antiforgery and antitampering), and confirmed receipt of intact messages.  

		<P>To encourage such uses, the group endorses legislation with the vague goal of "promoting" EDI and electronic commerce.  More concretely, the report calls for international measures to combat consumer fraud on international networks.  

		<P>Finally, the report opens what will surely be among the most controversial issues for international negotiations over the Internet, calling for international "rules to govern contents circulating on networks" -- rules that "make it a prerequisite for nations to respect and comprehend each other's social and cultural backgrounds."

		<p>This report is one of three study group reports sponsored by Japan's MPT.  The others also treat cryptography as a central enabling technology for digital commerce.  <P>

			<LI><I>Security technology study group</I>.  A group focused on security technology seems to have been established to encourage concentrated government research aimed at assessing the strength of cryptographic systems and at promoting standardization of cryptographic techniques.  The government recognizes that cryptographic standardization has pros and cons, but its summary is remarkable for what it does not say.  Unlike the U.S. and Europe, Japan shows little concern for criminal misuse of standardized encryption, even though the terror group that gassed Tokyo's subways -- Aum Supreme Truth -- apparently had encrypted some of its computer files.  The downside of standardization from the Japanese point of view is the practical difficulty of agreeing on standards, particularly in the face of export controls on the technology, and (apparently) a sense that standardization will increase vulnerability by allowing wrongdoers to focus their code-breaking efforts on a single technology.

		<P>The only discussion of the U.S. government's favored solution, key escrow, comes in an unusual context -- certification of digital signatures.  For an American, this seems to be mixing two very distinct policy concerns.  It is true that digital signatures almost certainly require some kind of certification authority, i.e., some institution that will verify and stand behind the identities that go with digital signatures.  Key escrow in the context of signature certification seems to imply that certifying authorities will keep copies of each private key as well as each public key used for digital signatures.  

		<P>The policy reasons for considering this option are grounded in the underlying technology.  Public-key encryption may be used for two separate purposes.  A message can be encrypted by anyone using the certified and published key belonging to a particular individual, and it can only be decrypted by that individual.  Conversely, a message encrypted using the private key of that individual may be decrypted by anyone who has access to the published public key.  This method is obviously useless for privacy, but it is an effective digital signature, since the only person who could have encrypted such a message is the holder of the private key.  

		<P>Because the same key pair may be used for encryption as for signature, escrowing signature keys would also allow access to encrypted communications that use the same key pair. The problem with this approach is that it would also add a layer of insecurity to the entire digital signature structure, allowing those with access to the escrow system not just to decrypt but also to forge messages from registered users.  Since there is little law-enforcement reason for being able to conduct such forgeries, adding this layer of insecurity has been rejected in U.S. policy circles.  Instead, the U.S. seems to be moving toward a system in which digital signature standards are divorced from encryption-for-privacy  standards.  Whether the Japanese government intends to achieve authorized access to digitally encrypted messages through the certification authority is not yet known, but as the consequences of holding private signature keys begin to dawn on the private sector, this option seems unlikely to prove attractive.<P>

			<LI><I>Electronic payment study group</I>.  The third study group concerns electronic payment and digital cash.  Its report is due in March 1996.  It too will focus on standardization of cryptographic techniques.  It seems likely that the risks of such technology will be more prominent for this group, which is also charged with examining the tax, foreign exchange and credit creation issues arising from digital cash schemes.</UL><P>

		<B><LI><I>The Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI)</I>
</B>
		MITI has its own independent -- even competitive -- computer technology initiative.  It funds the Information-Technology Promotion Agency (IPA).  Within the IPA, there is a software technology center headed by Takashi Goto.

		<P>The IPA and MITI, like MPT, have concluded that cryptographic technology is important for Japan's competitiveness as the Internet grows in importance and as electronic commerce increases.  The IPA is spending about $320 million on research and development for the electronic commerce technology, including evaluation methods for cryptography.

		<P>While MITI formally supports discussions of cryptography policy on an international basis, the Clipper Chip was highly unpopular in Japan for a variety of reasons.  There's a strong antipathy to wiretaps among the Japanese people.  Wiretaps are lawful with a warrant, but remain controversial.  Therefore, the Clipper Chip's law enforcement rationale did not resonate in Japan.  The Chip's use of a classified algorithm and the lack of technical controls on police or government access were also seen as significant failings in the system, according to MITI sources.</OL>


<hr>
