<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Steptoe & Johnson LLP Karn Decision Summary</TITLE></HEAD>
<h2 align=center>Karn Decision Summary</h2>
<P>A federal district court in Washington, D.C. on March 22, 1996, dismissed a case brought by privacy activist Phil Karn challenging the State Department's refusal to allow him to export cryptography.  Our summary of the <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/karn.htm">decision</a> follows.

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson <font size=-2>LLP</font> web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>

<P>In February 1994, Karn applied for a license to export cryptographer Bruce Schneier's book Applied Cryptography. The State Department approved the license, but shortly thereafter denied Karn's request for a license to export a diskette which contained text files of different cryptographic algorithms that were printed in the book.  Karn filed suit, making two main arguments.  First, he argued that the State Department should have treated the diskette as in the public domain and therefore not subject to regulation as a defense article on the U.S. Munitions List, and that its failure to do so was arbitrary and therefore violated the Administrative Procedures Act.  Second, Karn argued that by prohibiting his export of the diskette, the State Department had imposed a prior restraint on his right to free speech in violation of the First and  Amendment to the Constitution.

<P>The court rejected both of Karn's arguments.  The court found that Karn's argument that the State Department should not have regulated the diskette as a defense article was barred by a provision of the Arms Export Control Act (AECA), 22 U.S.C. Section 2778(h).  That section provides that the President's "designation" of items as defense articles shall not be subject to judicial review.   The court found it was reasonable to interpret the term "designation" to refer not only to the listing of broad categories of defense articles on the Munitions List, but also to the decision that a particular item is contained within one of the listed categories.  The court reasoned that it was appropriate to interpret the term "designation" broadly in light of Congress' intent in enacting the AECA to give the President discretion to control the export of those items the Executive Branch considers to be defense articles.  Moreover, the court noted an anomaly would result if Karn's position prevailed, in that the Export Administration Act precludes judicial review of the Commerce Department's determination that an item is a dual-use commodity: the court stated that "it would be strange indeed if Congress precluded judicial review of the determination that an item has merely a potential for military use (i.e. subject to the commodity control list), but permitted review of the determination that an item was in fact a defense article (e.g. subject to the munitions list)."  Accordingly, the court found that Karn's challenge to the State Department's regulation of the diskette as a defense article was barred by statute, and the court did not reach the merits of Karn's argument that the diskette was in the public domain and therefore not subject to regulation as a defense article.

<P>With regard to Karn's First Amendment argument, the court first noted that the AECA's bar on judicial review did not apply to Karn's constitutional challenge.  The court then found that under past First Amendment cases, the standard to be applied in reviewing the State Department's action depended on the purpose of the action, namely whether the State Department's action was aimed at regulating the content of Karn's speech ("content-based") or was taken for other reasons ("content-neutral").   The difference is important because content-based regulations are presumptively invalid, while content-neutral regulations are legitimate if certain criteria are met.  The court found that the State Department's decision to bar the export of the diskette was content-neutral, stating that "[t]he defendants are not regulating the export of the diskette because of the comments and or source code, but instead are regulating because of the belief that the combination of encryption source code on machine readable media will make it easier for foreign intelligence sources to encode their communication."  Finally, the court held that the State Department's action met the criteria for content-neutral regulations, finding that the State Department's action was within its constitutional authority, that the government had an important interest in regulating the export of cryptography, and that the restriction was "narrowly tailored" to this government interest.  The court refused to address Karn's argument that the restriction was not "narrowly tailored" in that the regulated encryption was either widely available in other countries or could be broken by the National Security Agency, reasoning that to address Karn's argument on the merits would embroil the court in sensitive foreign policy issues that involved fundamentally political decisions.

<P>Karn and his supporters are likely to appeal the court's decision.  However, until an appeals court considers these issues, the lower court's decision will provide the legal framework under which exporters of encryption must operate.  Given the court's rejection of Karn's arguments, in terms that indicate a broad willingness to defer to Executive decisionmaking in this area, the State Department is likely to rely on this decision as supporting its legal authority to regulate encryption exports as it deems necessary.


