<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT04-B38-197</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA079-000540-B027-334</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.steptoe.com:80/337683a.htm 198.240.72.75 19970124171043 text/html 8402
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Fri, 24 Jan 1997 17:10:23 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.2
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Wed, 13 Nov 1996 20:29:39 GMT
Content-length: 8226
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>337683</TITLE>
  
</HEAD>
<Body>
<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and 
circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web 
page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  
Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely 
to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<P>
<hr>
<p>
<Center><B><FONT SIZE=4>Hearing of the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations</FONT></B></Center>
<P>
<P>
		On June 25, the Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations held a hearing
on computer network security which addressed vulnerability of both government and private sector 
networks.  Senator Sam Nunn was the only senator present at the meeting.  Subcommittee staffers 
Harold Damelin (Chief Counsel, Staff Director) and Daniel Gelber (Chief Counsel, Minority Staff 
Director), also attended the hearing.  The witnesses included John Deutch (Director, CIA), Peter 
Neumann (SRI International), and four representatives from the RAND Corp. (Roger Molander, Robert 
Anderson, Andy Riddile, and Peter Wilson). 
<P>
<P>		The next hearing is scheduled on July 16 to discuss how the executive branch 
intends to respond to cyberspace security threats.  Deputy Attorney General Jamie Gorelick and 
Deputy Secretary of Defense John White will be witnesses for the next hearing.
<P>
<H4><B><U>Likelihood of Cyber-Attacks</U></B></H4>

<P>		Nunn agreed with all witnesses that coordinated attacks on cyberspace are 
inevitable and will threaten national and economic security.  They concurred that the relatively easy 
access to tools and knowledge necessary to conduct cyber-attacks would allow even a small group 
of individuals to pose a serious security threat.  They predicted that both government and private 
computer systems are likely targets of cyber-attacks.
<P>
<H4><B><U>Cyber-Attack Response Center</U></B></H4>

<P>		There was an agreement that securing cyberspace should be a very high 
priority of the U.S. government.  Deutch gave the following list of actions that intelligence organizations 
are currently taking or plan to take:
<P>
<P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>improve collection activities that are designed to uncover evidence of foreign intent to attack U.S. computer systems;
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>work closely with the FBI and Department of Justice on computer security issues;
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>forge working relationships with the private sector, including U.S. corporations and academic institutions;
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>devote additional resources to computer security threat analysis;
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>create a new government intelligence center at the National Security Agency to deal with cyberspace security; and,
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>finish a comprehensive report on cyberspace security by December 1, 1996.  
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<P>		Among the above six items mentioned by Deutch, Nunn seemed to be most 
interested in the plan to establish a new government intelligence center.  Deutch testified that the 
center should focus its efforts on developing tools to deal with cyberspace security and on sharing 
such tools with the private sector.  He also said that he hopes to open the center in the next two to 
four years.
<P>
<P>		Additionally, Nunn identified a need for a 24-hour real-time crisis response center 
to help the private sector combat cyber-attacks.  Deutch testified that such a center, if established, 
should be under a direction of the Department of Justice and separate from the center that he plans to 
establish.  Nunn and the other witnesses, however, seemed to support establishing one center to handle 
all cyberspace security issues in order to facilitate closer cooperation among intelligence, law 
enforcement, and the private sector.  Given the unwillingness of private companies to share information 
on cyber-attacks, several witnesses suggested implementing confidentiality procedures for the reporting 
of cyber-attacks.
<P>
<H4><B><U>Government-Funded Public Awareness Campaign</U></B></H4>

<P>		Nunn, Neumann, and the RAND representatives agreed that the private sector has 
failed to secure cyberspace.  Nunn asked all witnesses whether an electronic &quot;Pearl Harbor&quot; 
was necessary before the country takes cyberspace security seriously, for which nobody gave a definite 
answer.  
<P>
<P>		Nunn seemed to advocate the increased use of government resources to educate 
the public on cyberspace security threats.  He showed interests in creating an organization like the 
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention to conduct a public awareness campaign. 
<P>
<H4><B><U>Private Sector Insurance</U></B></H4>

<P>		Nunn asked Neumann and the RAND representatives whether the insurance 
industry could play a role in increasing cyberspace security.  None of them were aware of insurance 
that covers a third-party liabilities arising out of cyber-attacks.  Nunn suggested that if such insurance 
were available, insurance contracts could require private companies to put more resources into 
computer security.
<P>
<H4><B><U>Protection of Essential Services</U></B></H4>

<P>		Nunn expressed an interest in Anderson's proposed &quot;Minimum Essential 
Information Infrastructure&quot; (MEII) plan, in which minimum essential services are identified and 
are placed under a higher security standard.  The goal of MEII plan is to secure a subset of cyberspace 
so that &quot;essential services&quot; can survive cyber-attacks.  Anderson's definition of 
&quot;essential services&quot; seemed to include private-sector services such as financial, utility, 
and transportation services.  Anderson testified that a further study is necessary to define what 
&quot;essential services&quot; are. 
<P>
<H4><B><U>Encryption Export Controls</U></B></H4>

<P>		Neumann testified that the use of cryptography technology would help increase 
cyberspace security and that the U.S. government should remove the regulation on the export of 
cryptography technology.  Nunn did not comment on this recommendation.
<P>
<H4><B><U>Liability Legislation</U></B></H4>

<P>		There was an exchange between Nunn and the Rand representatives on 
legislation that would limit liabilities of private companies for damages caused by internal security 
tests.  Nunn agreed with the Rand representatives that internal security tests conducted by the Defense 
Information Systems Agency have shown that such tests are useful in identifying security holes.  
The Rand representatives testified that private companies seemed unwilling to conduct internal security 
tests due to fear of potentially large liabilities that might arise out of damages caused by such tests.  
Nunn seemed to agree with the Rand representatives that legislation that limits liabilities could 
encourage private companies to conduct self-attacks on their systems.

<P></blockquote><P><hr><P>Copyright 1996 Steptoe & Johnson LLP <blockquote><P>
