<H4>Resident Attorneys</H4>
<P>All attorneys resident in the Phoenix Office are admitted to practice before the Supreme Court of Arizona and various federal courts, except as otherwise noted. Admission to practice in other states or the District of Columbia is noted individually.
<H4>Partners</H4>
<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/katz.htm">Lawrence A. Katz</a> received his undergraduate degree from Harvard University in 1964 and his J.D. degree from the Boston College Law School in 1967. He served as the Editor-in-Chief of the <I>Boston College Law Review</I> and was awarded membership in the Order of the Coif. He is a past Chairman of the Labor Law Section of the State Bar of Arizona, a past member of the Board of Directors of the Arizona Affirmative Action Association, a charter member of the National Banking Industry Labor Law Committee, and a member of the Labor Lawyers Advisory Committee/CUE of the National Association of Manufacturers. Larry's practice focuses on labor relations issues, employment discrimination law, wrongful discharge claims, and related litigation. He is also admitted in New York. Direct Line: (602) 257-5211.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/meyerson.htm">Bruce E. Meyerson</a> received his undergraduate degree in 1968 from Arizona State University and his law degree in 1972 from Georgetown University, where he was an editor of the <I>Georgetown University Law Journal</I>.   He is a former Judge of the Arizona Court of Appeals, General Counsel of Arizona State University, and Executive Director of the Arizona Center for Law in the Public Interest. Bruce has a diversified civil and appellate litigation practice which emphasizes employment law. He also practices in the areas of education law and public utility law. He is the co-editor of the State Bar of Arizona manual on court-awarded attorneys' fees. Bruce regularly serves as a mediator and arbitrator.

<p>His professional activities in the field of alternative dispute resolution include serving as: Chair, Arizona State Bar Committee on Alternative Dispute Resolution, 1985-87; Chair, Arizona Commission on the Courts, ADR Task Force, 1989-90; Chair, Arizona Supreme Court Alternative Dispute Resolution Advisory Committee, 1991-95; Chair, Dispute Resolution Committee of the ABA Section of Business Law, 1992-95; and Council Member, ABA Section of Dispute Resolution, 1993-95. He is a co-editor of <I>A Drafter's Guide to Alternative Dispute Resolution</I> (1991), published by the American Bar Association.

<p>Bruce is an adjunct professor of law at Arizona State University College of Law, where he teaches Arbitration. He is also a visiting professor at the Institute for Dispute Resolution at Pepperdine University School of Law, where he teaches Negotiation and Settlement Advocacy. Bruce is a member of the Center for Public Resources At-Large Panel of Distinguished Neutrals. Direct Line: (602) 257-5229.

<p><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/burke.htm">Francis J. Burke, Jr.</a> received his undergraduate degree from Cornell University, graduating <I>magna cum laude</I> in Economics in 1972, and his law degree from Harvard Law School in 1975. He is Chair of the ABA Litigation Section's Committee on Corporate Counsel. He has served as Co-Editor of <I>The Corporate Litigator</I> (ABA Press 1989), Co-Chair of the ABA 1991 and 1993 National Institutes on Corporate Litigation, Co-Chair of the Committee on Corporate Counsel's 1992 Mid-Winter Meeting, and a panelist and moderator of many ABA programs on corporate litigation topics.

<p>Frank's practice emphasizes complex litigation, including securities, professional malpractice, racketeering, antitrust, business tort, corporate, environmental, and white collar crime litigation. He 
is also admitted in California, Colorado, and Washington. Direct Line: (602) 257-5227.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/dale.htm">Barry J. Dale</a> received his undergraduate degree from Rice University, <I>magna cum laude</I>, in 1975, and his law degree from Harvard Law School, <I>cum laude</I>, in 1978. His practice includes construction law and corporate, commercial, finance, real estate, and natural resource transactions. His construction law practice includes the representation of owners, general contractors, and suppliers. He represents both borrowers and lenders in agribusiness and real estate loans, equipment and other asset-based financings, and unsecured loans. He represents entrepreneurs in the creation
and operation of businesses, and sellers and buyers in business asset and stock acquisitions. Barry's real estate practice includes representing buyers and sellers of improved and unimproved property, and landlords and tenants in commercial lease matters. He also handles transactions involving the exchange of water rights, including assignments of Central Arizona Project allocations. Direct Line:  (602) 257-5213.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/bodney.htm">David J. Bodney</a> received his undergraduate degree from Yale College where he graduated <I>cum laude</I> in 1976, and his joint law and masters degrees from the University of Virginia in 1979 (J.D./M.A., Foreign Affairs). He served as Senior Editor of the <I>Virginia Journal of International Law</I>, after working on Capitol Hill as a legislative aide to Sen. John V. Tunney.

<p>In 1989 and 1990, he served as President of the Arizona Center for Law in the Public Interest, and has co-authored <I>The Annual Survey of the Arizona Law of Defamation</I> published by the Libel Defense Resource Center. David's practice focuses on media and constitutional law, including defamation and other First Amendment litigation, as well as on employment, environmental, natural resources, and Indian law. Direct Line: (602) 257-5212.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/bienst.htm">Floyd P. Bienstock</a> received his undergraduate degree from Rutgers University where he graduated with distinction in 1976, and his law degree from the University of Arizona where he graduated with distinction in 1980. He served as the Executive Editor of the <I>Arizona Law Review</I> in 1979 and 1980 and was a member of the National Moot Court Team in 1979. He has served as Chair of the Trial Practice Section of the State Bar of Arizona. Floyd's practice principally involves complex commercial litigation with an emphasis on contract, business tort, employment, and environmental matters. Direct Line: (602) 257-5210.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/selden.htm">David A. Selden</a> received his undergraduate degree from George Washington University in 1973, a masters degree from George Washington University in 1976, and his law degree from Georgetown University where he graduated <I>magna cum laude</I> in 1982 and
was an editor of <I>The Tax Lawyer</I>. While in Washington he also served as a Congressional staff member for more than ten years. He is Chairman of the Employee Relations Committee of the Arizona Chamber of Commerce, and is a member of the Editorial Review Board of the <I>Arizona Labor Letter</I> and the Board of Editors of the <I>Arizona Employment Law Handbook</I>, published by the State Bar of Arizona. Dave's practice concentrates on labor and employment law issues, as well as other administrative and litigation matters. Direct Line: (602) 257-5214.


<H4>Associates</H4>

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/cooperb.htm">Bennett Evan Cooper</a> received his undergraduate degree from Harvard College, <I>magna cum laude</I> in Government, in 1983, and his law degree from Harvard Law School, <I>cum laude</I>, in 1986. While there he was Executive Editor of the <I>Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy</I>, President of the Harvard Society for Law and Public Policy, and a winner of the Ames Moot Court Competition. He then served as a law clerk to the Honorable Alex Kozinski of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit in 1987 and 1988. From 1989 to 1994 he was Chair of the Intellectual Property Section of the State Bar of Arizona.

<p>Ben is a founding officer and director of Arizona Volunteer Lawyers for the Arts, Inc. and a member of the International Trademark Association. His practice focuses on appellate advocacy and trademark, trade dress, copyright, and trade secret protection, including counseling, registration, licensing, and litigation. He has been involved in a wide variety of antitrust, securities, unfair competition, defamation, and other complex litigation. He is also admitted in California. Direct Line: (602) 257-5217.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/goebel.htm">Monica L. Goebel</a> received her undergraduate degree in Criminal Justice and Public Administration from Grand Canyon University where she graduated <I>magna cum laude</I> in 1985, and her law degree from Arizona State University College of Law where she graduated <I>magna cum laude</I> in 1988. She served as Articles Editor of the <I>Arizona State Law Journal</I> and was awarded membership in the Order of the Coif. She was a law clerk to Chief Justice Frank X. Gordon, Jr. of the Supreme Court of Arizona in 1988 and 1989. Monica is a member of the Executive Council of the State Bar of Arizona's Employment and Labor Section. Her practice concentrates on employment discrimination law, labor relations issues, wrongful discharge claims, and related litigation.  Direct Line: (602) 257-5218.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/judiscak.htm">Kevin M. Judiscak</a> received his undergraduate degree from the University of Colorado where he graduated <I>summa cum laude</I> in 1985, and his law degree from the University of Notre Dame where he graduated <I>magna cum laude</I> in 1989. While there he was a member of the <I>University of Notre Dame Law Review</I>.

