<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Financial Services Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>Financial Services Practice</CENTER></H2>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has a diverse financial services practice designed to meet the needs of
our domestic and international institutional and individual
clients in the evolving financial services marketplace.  We
represent commercial banks, thrift institutions, credit unions,
holding companies, their officers and directors, and
individuals controlling, affiliated with or conducting
transactions with such financial institutions.  We have
represented Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) and
Resolution Trust Corporation (RTC) in a wide range of matters
pertaining to failed and failing financial institutions and to
their portfolios of loans and real estate. 

<P>The matters we handle for these clients are as varied as the
clients themselves and fall into several types of matters:
formation, acquisition and changes in control of financial
institutions; regulatory and enforcement matters; commercial
financing and workout matters; litigation; legislative matters;
and specialized representations in the financial services area.

<h4><CENTER>Formations, Acquisitions and Changes In Control</CENTER></h4>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has advised domestic and international clients
regarding the organization of new financial institutions and
holding companies, assisted with charter applications and
advised clients regarding changes in control of financial
institutions and regarding mergers and acquisitions of healthy
as well as failing or failed financial institutions.  In
addition, we have advised national and regional securities firms
and other financial institution clients regarding trust company
powers, the trust company chartering process in various
jurisdictions and related issues.  This transactional work has
encompassed drafting basic documentation for such transactions,
preparing regulatory submissions and providing tax analyses and
opinions regarding such transactions.  

<h4><CENTER>Regulatory and Enforcement Matters</CENTER></h4>

<H4><CENTER>Regulatory Matters</CENTER></H4>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represents financial
organizations before federal and state regulatory agencies
regarding a variety of matters that arise under governing
supervisory requirements.  Such representations involve both
matters requiring regulatory approvals and those limited to
interpretive issues.

<P>We have, for example, advised depository institution and holding
company clients regarding a wide range of interpretive and
operational issues such as: 
<ul><LI>federal limitations on affiliate transactions such as the
purchase and sale of mortgage loans; <P>
<LI>community reinvestment and related obligations;<P>
<LI>international investment matters; <P>
<LI>interstate banking issues; <P>
<LI>Glass-Steagall Act and related securities law issues;  <P>

<LI>capital distribution and dividend issues;  <P>
<LI>the development of capital plans and the issuance of
securities to achieve plan objectives; <P>
<LI>lending limitations;<P>
<LI>consumer credit issues; <P>
<LI>credit card operations;<P>
<LI>the effects of the Historic Preservation Act on the
development of a financial institution's main office and branch
network;<P>
<LI>government contracting issues; and<P>
<LI>the responsibilities and potential liabilities of officers and
directors.</ul>


<P>In addition, the firm has advised clients considering expansion
of their products and services and assisted them in seeking
approval to offer such new products and services.  Our
representations in this area have included: 
<ul><LI>representing a financial institution in the formation and
operation of several financial institution mutual funds;<P>
<LI>representing a client regarding the establishment of a
multiple-partner electronic funds transfer system, a
representation that required obtaining the approval of four
federal depository institution regulatory agencies; 	<P>
<LI>advising a client regarding the development of an automatic
payment system; <P>
<LI>advising a bank holding company client in connection with its
application to offer data processing services through a new
subsidiary; <P>
<LI>counselling another client concerning the establishment of a
travel services program to be  offered through national and
state banks; and <P>
<LI>assisting a savings institution client in obtaining
regulatory approval to implement a pension advisory and
administrative service.</ul>

<P>These regulatory representations often have involved working
with both local or regional offices of various state and federal
regulatory agencies and with agency headquarters in Washington. 

<H4><CENTER>Enforcement Matters</CENTER> </H4>
Steptoe & Johnson LLP has represented and advised both depository institutions and individuals associated
with them as officers, directors or controlling persons in a
variety of supervisory and enforcement matters.  These matters
have ranged from informal enforcement proceedings, to more
formal written agreements and memoranda of understanding, to
cease and desist actions initiated by federal and state
agencies.  The firm has successfully represented clients in
connection with the early termination of formal enforcement
actions.  In handling these enforcement matters we have
represented clients before each of the federal bank and thrift
institution regulatory agencies.

<h4><CENTER>Commercial Financing and Workout Matters</CENTER></h4>
<H4><CENTER>Commercial Financing Transactions</CENTER></H4>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP's
transactional practice in the financial institutions area
includes representations of domestic and foreign lenders and
borrowers in connection with a broad range of sophisticated
financial transactions.  Our work in this area has involved
structured financings, sales of loan portfolios and
securitization of assets as well as traditional commercial and
real estate-related lending including project financing,
equipment financing, international financing, nonstandard
collateral financing, agricultural financing, construction
financing, real estate financing and leveraged sale-leaseback
transactions.   

<P>For example, the firm has:
<ul><LI>structured the refinancing by rural electric utilities of $1.7
billion in long-term, fixed-rate Federal Financing Bank loans
with private loans guaranteed by the United States, a project
which involved our establishing special-purpose grantor trusts
to hold notes and issue freely transferable certificates of
beneficial interest suitable for sale to public investors;<P>
<LI>represented a Canadian corporation in the negotiation and
drafting of the loan and security documents associated with
the extension of a US$140 million revolving line of credit from
an international consortium of banks led by Citicorp USA and
Creditanstalt of Austria;<P>
<LI>represented the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development in connection with its financing of an enhanced digital
telecommunications system for the City of Moscow, reportedly the
first limited recourse project financing under the newly-enacted
Russian Law on Mortgages, the second project financing in the
territory of the former Soviet Union, and the first such project
financing following the division of the Union into its
constituent parts;<P>
<LI>advised an international lending agency in connection with its
guarantee of a loan by a consortium of U.S. and Western European
banks to finance a housing project developed by the Government
of the Ivory Coast;<P>
<LI>represented a U.S. manufacturer in the negotiation of a $135
million purchase facility from an international consortium of
banks as part of a refinancing transaction; <P>
<LI>represented a major power cooperative; <P>
<LI>acted as lead counsel for the debt participants in a
$623,000,000 leveraged lease financing of a North Dakota
lignite-fired, steam electric facility;<P>
<LI>acted as lead counsel for the debt participants in the
$185,000,000 financing of a coal-fired steam electric generating
station in Indiana; <P>
<LI>represented a major U.S. conservation group in structuring
debt-for-nature swaps to purchase tracts of virgin rain forest
throughout Latin America;  <P>
<LI>represented various international airlines in the
negotiation and drafting of documents associated with
tax-advantaged lease financing transactions;<P>
<LI>represented a major cable television company in negotiating
and documenting its construction and permanent financing
agreements for the development and construction of its corporate
headquarters in an industrial park in Washington, D.C.; and<P>
<LI>represented one of the largest Japanese construction companies
in the formation of its single purpose U.S. subsidiary and in
documenting that subsidiary's participation in a joint venture
and its financing for the acquisition, development and
construction of a $50,000,000 million mixed-use condominium
development in the District of Columbia.</ul>

<H4><CENTER>Creditor/Debtor Relations; Workout Matters</CENTER></H4>
<P>We have substantial
experience and expertise in creditor/debtor relations, in
reorganizations and workouts, especially those involving debtors
engaged in the development of real estate, and in bankruptcy
litigation.  Our practice in this area has encompassed the
entire gamut of functions within and outside of proceedings,
including our representation of the Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corporation in the largest bankruptcy filed in l985 and in the massive LTV bankruptcy.  



<P>The firm's attorneys are often involved in the capstone of
bankruptcy negotiation -- the reorganization plan -- including
some extremely complex plans in major reorganizations, and
Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have broad experience in rendering
advice and in structuring transactions in the course of
bankruptcy proceedings.  In addition, Steptoe & Johnson LLP has
represented some of the nation's largest lenders, and FDIC and
RTC, in pursuing the borrowers and guarantors of billions of
dollars in connection with troubled real estate projects.  



<P>Such representations within and outside proceedings include, for
example, matters in which the firm:
<ul><LI>represented a major money center bank in the restructuring of
$130 million in indebtedness of a real estate developer/guarantor, a restructuring that involved, among other matters, restructuring of loans, deeds in lieu, assumptions of loans by
new buyers; <P>

<LI>represented a major money center bank in a $500 million
Chapter 11 proceeding, at that time the largest bankruptcy ever
of a Washington, D.C. real estate developer/guarantor;<P>

<LI>represented major and smaller financial institutions in
pursuing claims in bankruptcy against defaulted
debtors/guarantors in chapter proceedings and against former and
current tenants of properties owned by those institutions; <P>
<LI>represented FDIC and RTC as receiver for a number of failed
institutions in connection with various aspects of the workout
or restructuring of debt of various defaulted borrowers and
guarantors, including representation of FDIC in connection with
the debt restructuring outside of a chapter proceeding of the
$100,000,000 indebtedness of a defaulted borrower/guarantor; <P>
<LI>represented the principal creditor in the negotiation of a
$3.5 billion settlement agreement for our client in the LTV
reorganization; and<P>
<LI>represented a substantial claimant in the $600 million
reorganization of 341 affiliated real estate limited
partnerships and obtained significant concessions for its client
and similarly situated claimants in the plan of reorganization. </ul>

<h4><CENTER>Litigation Practice</CENTER></h4>

<P>We have represented clients in a wide variety of litigation
involving financial institutions, their officers, directors,
shareholders and those doing business with them.  For example,
we have: 

<ul><LI>represented lenders in defense of a variety of lender
liability claims and counterclaims, including a case involving
defense of a lawsuit in which investors in a project as to which
a financial institution was the construction lender sued the
promoter and financial institution for securities fraud, common
law fraud, RICO and similar claims when the project failed;<P>
<LI>represented a bank holding company in emergency litigation
against the District of Columbia to prevent it from blocking the
merger between the holding company's commercial bank and a
District of Columbia bank;<P>
<LI>represented plaintiffs in a $10,000,000 state law fraud action
against a state bank, a case involving litigation in the federal
and bankruptcy courts of the Commonwealth of Virginia and the
District of Columbia;<P>
<LI>represented a financial institution in the defense of a class
action alleging securities fraud in the context of the financial
institution holding company's acquisition of another holding
company;    <P>
<LI>represented a variety of lenders in collection actions in
federal and state courts; and<P>
<LI>represented financial institution clients in matters involving allegations of bank fraud and allegations of violations of the False Claims Act and similar legal theories.</ul>



<P>And, as described below, our financial services representations
have included extensive litigation experience on behalf of FDIC
and RTC, both pursuing its claims against those involved with
financial institutions and defending it as receiver in
litigation brought against it by creditors of failed financial
institutions and others.  A number of these cases have involved
novel and complex issues of first impression. 

<h4><CENTER>Legislative Matters</CENTER></h4>

<P>As participants in a regulated industry, Steptoe & Johnson LLP's
financial institution clients must remain alert to relevant
actions taken by the U.S. Congress and the federal regulatory
agencies.  Congress has been active in recent years enacting
legislation affecting the structure and financial stability of
the financial system, and we have been actively involved in
representing financial institutions and other interested parties
in connection with such legislation.   

<P>The firm has assisted clients in preparing written statements
for testimony before congressional committees and has drafted
statutory language with supporting explanations in connection
with the representation of such clients. We have advised
clients, for example, regarding the effects of legislation on: 
<ul><LI>bank securities and insurance activities; <P>
<LI>community reinvestment and related obligations; <P>
<LI>the status of limited purpose trust companies under the Bank
Holding Company Act; <P>
<LI>the use of specific intangible assets under statutory capital
standards; <P>
<LI>deposit insurance premium assessments;<P>

<LI>tax attributes of financial institutions; <P>
<LI>international regulatory standards; and<P>

<LI>statutory provisions governing government loan programs.  </ul>

<P>In addition to such specific representations, we routinely
monitor congressional and federal agency activities in the
financial services area for a number of clients, helping keep
them abreast of legislative issues and initiatives in the
financial services area and advising them about actions that may
affect their operations. 

<h4><CENTER>Specialized Representations in the Financial Services Area</CENTER></h4>

<H4><CENTER>Representation of FDIC and RTC</CENTER></H4>

<P>In recent years we have
represented Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation and Resolution
Trust Corporation in a broad spectrum of legal work.  Among
other matters, we have advised FDIC and RTC as receiver of
various failed institutions on a variety of issues such as the
exercise of their powers as receiver and their administration of
the claims process.  We have advised them regarding such
specialized issues as their disposition of stock and
stock-secured assets in the portfolios of failed institutions,
theirdisposition of a failed institution's portfolio of
so-called Qualified Financial Contracts, their collection on
assets involving debtors in bankruptcy proceedings and various
industrial revenue bond matters.  

<P>We have represented RTC in a wide range of corporate,
contracting, transactional and other matters.  For example, we
have: 
<ul><LI>advised and represented RTC with respect to its asset
management arrangements with SAMDA contractors;<P>
<LI>advised RTC regarding its policies and procedures in the
procurement of other third-party services; <P>
<LI>represented RTC with respect to contractor suspension and
debarment issues;  <P>
<LI>represented RTC, and prepared its December 1990 Report to
Congress, regarding the so-called Southwest Plan 1988
FSLIC-Assisted Transactions; and<P>
<LI>represented FDIC/RTC in negotiations and documentation of
transactions involving their formation of several innovative
private/public sector limited partnerships and the acquisition
by those partnerships of portfolios of loans and REO with
market values of $450 million and $1.28 billion respectively. </ul>

<P>In addition to the foregoing counseling and transactional work
for FDIC and RTC, we have extensive litigation experience on
behalf of FDIC and RTC, both pursuing their claims against
debtors and others involved with financial institutions and
defending them in litigation brought against them in their
capacity as receiver of failed institutions, including lender
liability theory claims.  We represented FDIC as receiver for
The National Bank of Washington in a wide array of litigation,
including the landmark Cafritz litigation which tested for the
first time, and established, FDIC's powers under the "Crime
Control Act of 1990" to freeze a debtor's assets pending the
outcome of litigation on the merits.  

<H4><CENTER>Privatization Activities</CENTER></H4>
<P>The firm has extensive experience in
representing clients in matters involving the privatization of
matters previously performed by government entities.  Among
other privatization matters, we have advised foreign
governments on issues pertaining to modifications of their
banking laws and regulations in the context of privatization
efforts.  For example, the firm has:
<ul><LI>Advised the Government of Kenya, at the request of the World
Bank, on the modifications to its laws which are necessary to
carry out a program of privatization and economic reform.  The
firm's advice took the form of adetailed evaluation of economic
legislation and recommendations for changes.  <P>
<LI>Advised the Government of Tanzania, in conjunction with the
World Bank, on modifications to its banking laws which are
necessary to carry out a program of privatization and economic
reform.</ul>

<P>Other Specialized Financial Services Representations.  Finally,
the firm has handled a wide array of other representations
relating directly or indirectly to financial institutions,
including, for example, matters involving: 
<ul><LI><I>Banking Arrangements in Russia and Eastern Europe</I>:  We have
advised private sector clients regarding banking arrangements
and various other financial issues pertaining to doing business
in Russia and Eastern Europe;<p>
<LI><I>National Treatment Issues</I>:  We have advised the embassy of a
major western nation regarding U.S. laws affecting its financial
institutions engaged in business in the United States and have
advised other financial institution clients on national
treatment issues;<P>
<LI><I>Employment Law Issues</I>:  We have represented financial
institutions in a variety of employment law matters, including,
among others, claims of unlawful discrimination, reductions in
force, compliance with the requirements of the Americans with
Disabilities Act; and<P>
<LI><I>ERISA</I>:  We have advised financial institutions acting as
fiduciaries, plan advisors and in other capacities in connection
with various benefit plans on the requirements of ERISA.  </ul>

<H4><CENTER>Staffing of Representations in the Financial Services Area</CENTER></H4>
  
<P>The selection of Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys who participate in
our diverse financial services practice depends upon the
requirements of the particular representation.  In addition to
the areas of expertise described above, we draw, as appropriate
in particular representations, on the specialized skills of the
firm's experts in other fields relevant to our financial
services representations, such as securities law, corporate, tax
and white-collar expertise.  <p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>
