<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Environmental Law Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>Environmental Law Practice</CENTER></H2>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has a broad-based practice in the area of environmental law,
encompassing many sub-specialties in this diverse field.  Our
environmental practice group is widely recognized as a leader
among major private firms.  The principal areas in which our
environmental lawyers practice are outlined below.

<h4><CENTER>Site Remediation and Cost Allocation</CENTER></h4>

<P>Remediation of contaminated sites and facilities raises some of
the most complex and difficult issues for environmental lawyers
and their clients.  Problem areas include responding to
regulators, negotiating enforcement documents, negotiating or
litigating cost allocation and recovery claims, working with
consultants and regulators to develop efficient, cost effective
remediation approaches, and identifying other parties with whom
to share the burden of remediation and negotiating or litigating
an acceptable allocation.  

<P>Steptoe's environmental practice has a long record of successful
work in this challenging field.  We represent parties that are
alleged to have owned, sent waste to, or hauled waste to,
locations that are now contaminated.  Our clients include
industrial, transportation, oil and chemical companies;
municipalities; and real estate owners.  Steptoe attorneys are
experienced in connection with CERCLA (Superfund), RCRA and
analogous state programs in a large number of jurisdictions,
including Arizona, California, Connecticut, the District of
Columbia, Massachusetts, Montana, New Jersey, North Dakota,
Oregon, Virginia and Washington.  Many of these sites include
private cost allocation actions in addition to site remediation
issues. 

<h4><CENTER>Operating Facility Issues:  RCRA, The Clean Water Act</CENTER></h4>

<P>Steptoe's environmental practice group also provides ongoing
compliance advice to clients in the industrial and
transportation sectors.  We regularly work with clients on
federal and state hazardous waste compliance issues, including
waste classification, and RCRA permit requirements and disposal
requirements.  Steptoe lawyers also provide practical advice on
Clean Water Act permitting and enforcement issues.  We regularly
advise on NPDES and indirect discharge permits, and appear
before water regulatory agencies in several states.  The firm
also has much experience in working on wetlands issues with
federal and state regulatory agencies.  

<h4><CENTER>Toxic Substances Control Act</CENTER></h4>

<P>Steptoe also has an active practice under the Toxic Substances
Control Act (TSCA).  We frequently provide TSCA compliance
advice, and regularly handle administrative enforcement
proceedings before the EPA.  In resolving enforcement matters,
we focus on assisting our clients to come into compliance and
assist in providing the information necessary to ensure that
ongoing compliance takes place.

<h4><CENTER>Medical Waste and Medical Devices</CENTER></h4>

<P>Over the past few years, regulation of medical waste has become
an increasingly important issue to OSHA, FDA and EPA.  Steptoe &
Johnson LLP has been in the forefront of this emerging area of
regulation.  We represent registrants of pesticide
products intended to disinfect or sanitize health care
facilities and medical wastes.  We have advised clients on the
trial federal Medical Waste Tracking Program, as well as medical
waste regulation on the state level.  Currently, we are active
in the regulation of medical waste at the federal level and in
many states have established relationships with local counsel
who regularly provide advice on state and local compliance
issues.

<h4><CENTER>Occupational Safety and Health</CENTER></h4>

<P>Steptoe has an active practice under the Occupational Safety and
Health Act and analogous state programs.  We provide compliance
advice to a number of employers in manufacturing, construction
and service industries.  We also handle a range of enforcement
matters.  Steptoe lawyers recently won a substantial victory in
a trial before an OSHA administrative law judge, and now are
defending that victory before the Occupational Safety and Health
Review Commission.  Our compliance and enforcement practices
cover a wide range of substantive issues, from toxic agent
exposure to lifting standards and the issues raised by OSHA
under the so-called General Duty Clause.

<h4><CENTER>Toxic Tort Defense</CENTER></h4>

<P>Steptoe's toxic tort defense specialists represent chemical
manufacturers and users throughout the nation. This group has
successfully defended many cases, from ones involving chemical
exposures (e.g., mercury, arsenic), to alleged noise-induced
hearing loss.  We have been particularly active in defense of
personal injury and property damage claims allegedly caused by
exposure to pesticides, including successfully establishing
federal preemption of state tort claims under FIFRA.  Our toxic
tort defense practice is nationwide, with recent or current cases
in state and federal courts from Hawaii to New Jersey.

<h4><CENTER>Defense of Environmental Criminal Matters</CENTER></h4>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has a national practice in defense of white
collar criminal matters generally, and environmental crimes in
particular.  Steptoe attorneys include former federal
prosecutors from a wide variety of backgrounds, including the
Department of Justice's Environmental Crimes Section, other
Sections and U.S. Attorney's offices.  Steptoe attorneys defend
both corporate and individual clients against alleged
environmental, health and safety-related criminal matters, at
both the state and federal levels. 

<h4><CENTER>National Environmental Policy Act</CENTER></h4>

<P>The firm has extensive experience in working with NEPA, both in
assisting clients in compliance and in assessing the adequacy of
environmental impact statements.

<h4><CENTER>Natural Resources Law</CENTER></h4>

<P>Both the D.C. and Phoenix offices have experience dealing with
the environmental aspects of legal questions involving mining
(both deep and strip mining), mineral leasing (oil, gas,
geothermal), forestry, grazing, land exchanges (federal, state
and private), water rights, and wildlife law (including
particularly the Endangered Species Act and Marine Mammal
Protection Act).

<h4><CENTER>Environmental Audits, Acquisitions and Divestitures</CENTER></h4>

<P>The firm arranges and participates in environmental audits for
clients related to property or corporate acquisitions and
divestitures.  We frequently perform the environmental portion
of preacquisition due diligence reviews, and have much
experience drafting transactional documents to clearly define
environmental responsibility.

<h4><CENTER>Energy Projects</CENTER></h4>

<P>The environmental practice group works together with the firm's
energy practice group on the environmental aspects of energy
projects (power plants, pipelines, etc.).

<h4><CENTER>International Environmental Practice</CENTER>
</h4>

<P>Together with lawyers from the firm's international practice
group, including the Moscow office, Steptoe environmental
lawyers frequently advise on and work with both international
environmental law (NAFTA, etc.), and national environmental law
abroad (Europe, the Far East, Latin America).  The practice
group also assists the firm's large international trade practice
on environmental matters involving funding sources like the
World Bank, USAID, and the various U.S. interregional banks.  We
also provide advice to clients on environmental trade questions
arising under the GATT.

<h4><CENTER>Congressional and Administrative Agency Representation</CENTER></h4>

<P>The environmental practice group has long experience in
representing clients on environmental matters before Congress
and administrative agencies, both in the process of assisting in
the developing of legislation and in formulating its regulatory
implementation.  We currently are active on the Superfund and
FIFRA bills pending in Congress, and in the past have been
active on other issues, such as the recent amendments to the
Clean Air Act.



<HR>

<P>The foregoing discussion highlights the most active areas of
Steptoe & Johnson LLP's environmental practice.  These descriptions
provide an overview of our firm's capabilities.  We also handle
environmental issues in a number of sub-specialties and will be
pleased to provide additional information on request.<p>
<p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>

