<HEAD>
<TITLE>C.I.S. Institutional Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>


<H2><CENTER>Representation of Institutional Investors in Russia and the Commonwealth of Independent States (&quot;CIS&quot;)</CENTER></H2>
<CENTER><B>Scope of Work<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Since Steptoe &amp; Johnson opened its Moscow affiliate office in 1990, we have been at the forefront of developments in debt and equity financing, and related securities law issues, in Russia and the CIS.  In early 1994, we expanded our CIS operations to Almaty, Kazakstan as well.  The following synopsis focuses on our experience counseling institutional investors on a wide range of investment activities in Russia and the CIS.<P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson represents investment funds, investment fund managers, and investment advisors, as well as other venture capital investors.  Our attorneys are well versed in the corporate and tax environments in which institutional investors operate in the CIS and around the world.  We advise our clients regarding appropriate structures and procedures for debt and equity financing in the CIS in a manner that provides them the maximum benefit under Russian (and other nations') currency, securities, tax, and other laws.  Our attorneys have structured and negotiated a broad array of debt and equity financing terms including various forms of debt security (mortgages, stock and asset pledges, cash collateral accounts, etc.) and a variety of stock rights (preferred stock, put and call rights, preemptive rights, antidilution provisions, voting rights and agreements and registration rights) --all standard questions faced by venture capital investors.  All of our work for client investments has involved careful review of CIS securities and corporate laws for applicable restrictions and requirements.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Case Highlights<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>In particular, Steptoe &amp; Johnson has:<P>
<P>
-	Advised a multilateral lending institution in connection with its investments in a series of investment funds designed to invest in Ukraine, as well as the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, and the Slovak Republic.<P>
<P>
-	Represented the Kirghiz State Property Committee in the establishment of a $15 million, World Bank-supported lending institution (to bypass the Kirghiz banking system) for the provision of debt (and later equity) financing to privatizing enterprises. <P>
<P>
-	Drafted an investment advisory agreement on behalf of a U.S. adviser overseeing investments in Russia. <P>
<P>
-	Represented a venture capital fund in the initial stages of negotiations with a major Russian bank regarding the establishment of offshore funds that would invest Russian and foreign money in Russian securities. <P>
<P>
-	Assisted a private U.S. investment fund in establishing Russian and offshore investment vehicles for direct equity investments in the Russian timber industry.<P>
<P>
-	Established a venture capital fund's joint-stock company with a Russian investment company for investment in the Russian securities market. <P>
<P>
-	Advised an OPIC-guaranteed investment fund regarding its first investment in Russia, a $25 million purchase of the shares of a Russian oil company.  Special attention was paid to securing OPIC's interests. <P>
<P>
-	Negotiated a U.S. investment fund's $1 million investment in a Russian service company developing a system of irradiating timber to be exported from Russia to the U.S.<P>
<P>
-	Served as chief legal counsel to a U.S. Government-sponsored investment fund in its successful bid for a minority share of a major Moscow brokerage firm. <P>
<P>
-	Facilitated a $3 million equity<B> </B>investment by a private U.S. investment fund in a Russian manufacturer of electron vacuum tubes. <P>
<P>
-	Negotiated on behalf of a private U.S. investment fund a $1.8 million loan to a joint venture between a major St. Petersburg and a U.S. manufacturer of engines, established to produce engine components for export. <P>
<P>
-	Assisted a major U.S. Government-sponsored investment fund in negotiating several debt and equity investments in the food processing, textile, consumer products and publishing industries, including structuring the transactions, due diligence, document preparation and registrations. 	<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Related Experience in Central Europe &amp; Globally:<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>-	Negotiated and documented a Luxembourg investment fund focusing on investments in Bulgaria on behalf of two multilateral lending institutions. <P>
<P>
-	Participated in the planning of U.S. public offerings of foreign-issued equity and debt securities, and structured exchange offers between foreign holders of debt securities of a domestic issuer and U.S. holders of equity securities of a foreign issuer.<P>
<P>
-	Structured, negotiated and documented the acquisition by our foreign client, in a deal valued at over $200 million, of a technology business from a major U.S. transportation corporation. <P>
<P>
-	Structured, documented and/or advised with respect to numerous offshore investment funds focusing on U.S. investments.	<P>
<P>
-	Worked with several large financial institutions in connection with their development of tax-advantaged, cross-border financial products. <P>
<P>
-	Structured, negotiated, and documented cross-border transactions (including acquisitions, dispositions, restructurings, and financings) to maximize tax benefits and minimize tax risks.  (Several clients)<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Representative Clients<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Amadeus GmH (a consortium including Lufthansa, SAS, Iberia and Air France) <P>
<P>
Central Asian-American Enterprise Fund<P>
<P>
Croesus Capital Management<P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Enterprise Fund<P>
<P>
International Finance Corporation<P>
<P>
PaineWebber Russia Partners Fund<P>
<P>
Rothschild Emerging Markets Fund	
