<html><head><title>Stanley Smilack</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Stanley Smilack</h2>
<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.us.net/~steptoe/taxprac.htm">Taxation</a></center></blockquote>
<hr>

<P>Stanley Smilack's practice centers on the taxation of the
operations of multinational corporations and investments across
national borders.  He has worked extensively on the establishment
of joint ventures in Russia, Kazakstan, and other members of the
Commonwealth of Independent States, as well as in Europe, Asia,
Latin America and the United States.  He has also planned
strategies to maximize the availability of foreign tax credits
for activities carried on abroad, and to minimize the current
taxation of United States shareholders of foreign corporations.</P>

<P>Mr. Smilack has been substantially involved in intercompany
pricing issues, the acquisition of interests in foreign firms by
United States entities, and the acquisition of interests in
United States firms by foreign and domestic entities.  In
addition, he has handled Competent Authority proceedings.  </P>

<P>Mr. Smilack has also dealt extensively with the taxation of
financial products and commodities transactions.  He regularly
deals with excise tax matters relating to petroleum products and
chemicals.</P>

<P>Before becoming of counsel to Steptoe & Johnson LLP, Mr. Smilack
was in private practice in New York and Washington, 1973-84 and
was Tax Counsel, Salomon Inc, 1984-88.  He is a member of the
American Bar Association, the Tax Committee of the National
Foreign Trade Council, and the International Tax Policy Task
Force of the United States Chamber of Commerce.

<P><UL><LI>University of Michigan J.D., cum laude, 1973<BR>
<LI>Massachusetts Institute of Technology S.B. 1970</UL>
