<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Morgan D. Hodgson Bio</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</H3><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>
Morgan D. Hodgson</H2>

<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/emplyben.htm">Employment Law</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/apellate.htm">General Litigation </a><P></center></blockquote>




<P>Morgan Hodgson's practice focuses on a number of areas related to litigation, with a particular focus on employment law matters.  Ms. Hodgson's employment law practice includes representation of employers in all types of employment-related litigation in federal and state courts, at both the trial and appellate levels. 
In the equal employment field, her cases have included both individual and class actions and have  involved age, sex, race, disability, religion and national origin discrimination claims and reverse discrimination suits.  Ms. Hodgson's practice also includes representation of employers in whistleblower litigation, both before the United States Department of Labor and in federal court.  Ms. Hodgson also advises clients on employment-related issues including compliance with EEO and affirmative action
requirements, force reduction programs, unjust dismissal law, sexual harassment, employee handbooks, disability discrimination issues, early retirement programs, immigration law compliance, and employee relations matters.  She writes and speaks frequently on employment issues.  In other related areas Ms. Hodgson has represented clients in litigation involving claims of wrongful termination, retaliatory discharge, employee privacy, interference with contractual relations,  use of trade secrets, defamation, other contract and tort claims, and False Claims Act litigation.

<P>Before joining Steptoe, Ms. Hodgson was a trial attorney in the Bureau of Consumer Protection, Federal Trade Commission, 1973-75, and Assistant to the Director of the Bureau of Consumer Protection, FTC, 1975-76.

<P><DIR><LI> Stanford University J.D. 1973
<LI> Radcliffe College B.A. cum laude, 1969</DIR>
