<HEAD>
<TITLE>C.I.S./Intellectual Property  Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>


<H2><CENTER>Intellectual Property Protection Capability in Russia and the CIS</CENTER></H2>
<P>Our CIS IP group includes, among others:<P>
<P>
<B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/ward.htm>Maureen Ward</a></B>, a Steptoe &amp; Johnson partner with decades of IP experience who has worked on numerous technology licensing agreements in the CIS.<P>
<P>
<B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/solton.htm>Michael Solton</a></B>, a senior Russian attorney based at Steptoe &amp; Johnson's offices in Washington who has worked closely with the RF Copyright Office for over five years.<P>
<P>
<B>Olga Bezrukova</B>, a certified Russian patent and trademark attorney, based in SJI's Moscow office, who brings with her a network of patent and trademark attorneys located in all of the major nations of the CIS. (Prior to joining SJI, Ms. Bezrukova served as Director of the Patent and License Center of the Russian Science Foundation, an agency engaged in patent and trademark work.)  <P>
<P>
<B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/carey.htm>Sarah Carey</a></B>, the senior partner responsible for Steptoe &amp; Johnson's CIS practice group, has worked extensively in the area of IP, assisting many major US corporations in negotiating contracts for the transfer or acquisition of technology, and in verifying the title of CIS partners to technology that they claim to control.<P>
<P>
These attorneys receive strong support from the members of Steptoe &amp; Johnson's Washington based IP group (see next page), who are available to represent Russian enterprises seeking to protect, acquire, or engage in defensive actions against patents and other IP in the US.<P>
<P>
The collective experience of our CIS IP group includes:  <P>
<P>
-	Filing and prosecuting hundreds of trademarks and patents, as well as negotiating and drafting license agreements related to trademarks and patents, in Russia, Ukraine, Belarus, Kazakstan, Georgia and other CIS countries.<P>
<P>
-	Completing due diligence on numerous technologies and other forms of  IP that Russian companies have sought to transfer to Western partners or to capitalize in US-Russian joint stock companies.<P>
<P>
-	Negotiating and documenting transfers of technologies and technical data from Russian enterprises (including those previously in the defense sector) to Western partners and from Western companies to newly created Russian companies.<P>
<P>
-	Assisting Russia-based joint ventures and other enterprises in securing declassification of previously classified technology (developed under Ministry of Defense sponsorship), and in obtaining export permits and other necessary governmental approvals.<P>
<P>
Specific transactions include:  <P>
<P>
-	Negotiating and documenting the license of Russian-enhanced oil recovery technology to a US client and the patenting of the technology in the US.<P>
<P>
-	Representing a major US high tech company in the filing of its trademarks and in the prosecution of  trademark infringement disputes with Russian companies.<P>
<P>
-	Assisting in negotiating and documenting the transfer by a US company of technology and technical data to a Russian joint venture producing environmental control systems for aircraft.<P>
<P>
-	Negotiating the terms governing the distribution of Russian software and databases within the US.<P>
<P>
-	Assisting in the purchase and marketing of Soviet patents by and for a US high tech company.<P>
<P>
-	Serving as outside counsel regarding IP licenses in many other joint ventures, including those in the automotive, agricultural equipment, oil field equipment, telecommunications equipment, and other industries.<P>
<P>
-	Assisting in establishing a joint venture to modify US simulation technology for use in training the operators of Soviet-designed nuclear and coal fired electrical plants.<P>
<P>
-	Analyzing the trademark status of a major Russian mass media company in connection with its potential acquisition by an outside investor. <P>
<P>
-	Conducting lobbying effort before the RF Government and the Duma for copyright protection on behalf of major US trade association. <P>
<P>
-	Assisting a US publisher in acquiring and protecting copyright to Russian scientific journals. <P>
<P>
Our CIS IP group works closely with Steptoe &amp; Johnson's Washington-based IP group. This group  practices IP law for a broad range of corporate clients, including data encryption, software, defense, computer technologies, optical disc, and other industries. The Washington IP group's expertise includes litigation, licensing and in-depth counseling on patent, copyright, mask work, trademark, trade dress, trade secret, and related antitrust issues, as well as the special issues that arise in the protection and dissemination of computer software, computer network services, and other high-tech products.  Steptoe &amp; Johnson's intellectual property attorneys also provide services for the prosecution of patent applications and the securing of copyright, trademark, trade secret, and mask work rights.<P>
<P>
The Washington IP group's areas of substantive expertise include:  <P>
<P>
-	Patent, trademark, trade secret, copyright, unfair competition, false advertising, and computer performance litigation, including actions in the international context, actions in the US judiciary, proceedings in the US International Trade Commission, and private arbitrations and mediations.<P>
<P>
-	Covenants not to compete, non-disclosure agreements, and intellectual property agreements in the employer-employee, contractor, and joint venture contexts.<P>
<P>
-	Antitrust and other complex litigation.<P>
<P>
Provided below are descriptions of some of the key members of the Washington IP group:<P>
<P><center><B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/frei.htm">Frederick Frei</a></B></center>
<P>Mr. Frei has worked for over two decades in litigating on behalf of and counseling both plaintiffs and defendants in the areas of patents, trademarks, copyrights and trade secrets.  In addition, he has been widely published in the field of intellectual property law and has served as an Examiner in the US Patent and Trademark Office.<P>
<P><center><B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sulzer.htm">Stephen Sulzer</a></B></center>
<P>Mr. Sulzer specializes in the representation of foreign and domestic clients in patent, antitrust and unfair competition litigation in the Federal Courts and before the US International Trade Commission.  He serves as chief litigator in all phases of litigation, and has extensive trial experience before trial judges, administrative law judges and in appellate proceedings.<P>
<P><center><B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/rinkerma.htm>Gary Rinkerman</B></a></center>
<P>Mr. Rinkerman has extensive litigation experience in the judiciary, the US International Trade Commission, and in arbitration and mediation proceedings.  He has also handled all aspects of intellectual property acquisition, licensing and enforcement, including drafting and negotiation of patent, trademark, mask work, copyright, and trade secret agreements among private parties and in transactions involving the US Government.<P>
<P><center><B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/huang.htm">Stuart Huang</a></B></center>
<P>Mr. Huang has practiced before the US Patent and Trademark Office and has experience in patent applications, amendments, petitions, appeals, reexaminations, reissues, and Patent Cooperation Treaty international) practice.  He also has experience in licensing and other transactions involving intellectual property.<P>
