<HEAD>
<TITLE>Steptoe & Johnson LLP/C.I.S. Trade and Investment
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>


<H2><CENTER>Steptoe & Johnson LLP's C.I.S. Trade and Investment Practice</CENTER></H2>
<hr>
<blockquote><ul><li><a href="#cis">Commonwealth of Independent States ("C.I.S.") Trade and Investment</a><P><li><a href="#priv">Privatization</a><P><li><a href="#gov">Government Assistance and Public Education</a><P><li><a href="#struc">The Structure of the Practice</a><P><li><a href="#mem">Members of the C.I.S. Trade and Investment Practice Group</a><P><li><a href="#prac">Related Practice Areas</a><P><li><a href="#aff">Steptoe & Johnson LLP Affiliates</a><P><li><a href="#consult">C.I.S. Consultants</a></ul></blockquote>
<hr>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP is one of Washington, D.C.'s oldest and largest full-service law firms.  Our attorneys provide advice and representation to private and government clients in all fields of law, including corporate transactions, tax, international trade and finance, environmental protection, intellectual property protection, general litigation (including international arbitration), telecommunications, transportation, energy, maritime, antitrust, labor and pension matters.

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP currently has four lawyers in <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/almaty.htm">Almaty, Kazakstan</a> and 12 lawyers in Moscow, Russia supported by 200 attorneys in its Washington, D.C. headquarters, as well as a number of specialists and paralegals.  The firm maintains also an office in <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/phoenix.htm">Phoenix, Arizona </a>.

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has an exceptionally strong international commercial practice generally, and in the former Soviet Union particularly.  Our attorneys annually handle a broad range of trade and investment matters for numerous U.S. and foreign clients in all regions of the former Soviet Union.

 <h4 align=center><a name="cis">Commonwealth of Independent States ("C.I.S.") Trade and Investment</a></h4>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has long been at the forefront of legal and business developments in C.I.S. trade and investment.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP was one of the first U.S. law firms to establish a presence in Moscow, and it's affiliate there has doubled its practice in Russia each of the four years that it has been there.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys collectively bring decades of experience to their work in Russia and the former Soviet Union.  Several of our partners were actively involved in major trade and investment projects during the detente period of the late 1970s; and, since the early days of perestroika, Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have participated, through representation of Western (and, more recently, Russian) companies, in the definition of all phases of Russia's new private sector.  This involvement has included assistance to Russian policy-makers in developing the legal framework required for the transition to a market economy as well as extensive involvement in the structuring of new business forms and the creation of a broad range of new private companies.  

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has helped negotiate and draft sales, distribution, supplier, technology transfer, production sharing and countertrade agreements -- to name a few.  

<P>The firm advises on the establishment of representative offices, branches and subsidiaries and assists U.S. companies in the negotiation of joint activities with C.I.S. partners in the form of cooperation agreements, jointly owned companies, or direct investment in privatizing enterprises.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have helped plan, negotiate and structure hundreds of joint ventures and other Western investments in Russia and other nations of the C.I.S., including Azerbaijan, Belarus, Georgia, Kazakstan and Ukraine.  The firm also assists clients in obtaining financing or guaranties from international lending organizations ("ILO") and other financial institutions.

<P>Whatever the client's goals, Steptoe & Johnson LLP's C.I.S. Trade and Investment practice provides a full analysis of all relevant legal issues affecting those goals -- including questions arising under corporate, securities, tax, intellectual property, privatization, antitrust, currency control and labor laws, in order to provide the client with the most advantageous trade or investment structure possible.  The firm's lawyers also assist clients and the C.I.S. companies in which they invest to comply with the growing body of regulatory law in the energy, telecommunications and other sectors.  And, where appropriate, Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys provide representation to clients in dispute resolution proceedings, including local litigation and international arbitration.<a href="#begin"> <font size=-2>[return to top of document]</font></a>
<hr>
 <h4 align=center><a name="priv">Privatization</a></h4>
<P>Since 1991, Steptoe & Johnson LLP has also been active in the development and implementation of C.I.S. privatization policies and has provided counsel to companies, both U.S. and C.I.S., regarding the privatization process.  Our attorneys have represented dozens of U.S. companies that are investing in privatized Russian companies or buying assets previously owned by state enterprises.  The firm has also been retained by several major high-tech Russian enterprises to provide counsel regarding their restructuring options with a view to attracting foreign investment. <a href="#begin"><font size=-2>[Return to top of document]</font></a>
<hr>
 <h4 align=center><a name="gov">Government Assistance and Public Education</a></h4>

<P>Enhancing the firm's privatization practice, Steptoe & Johnson LLP actively participates in U.S. government and ILO-sponsored programs.  The firm was awarded a three-year contract by the U.S. Agency for International Development ("AID") to assist the nations of the C.I.S. in their various privatization efforts, including assistance in discrete privatizations in key industrial sectors.  Projects under the AID contract include the privatization of the Port of Murmansk (drafting a new Seaport Authority charter and designing the stock distribution plan for ten newly privatized joint stock companies) and the drafting of implementing regulations and procedures for the Kazak and Russian Antimonopoly Committees.

<P>Similarly, Steptoe & Johnson LLP prepared a corporate governance manual for the International Finance Corporation to be distributed to the management and shareholders of newly privatized companies in Russia, and a book for the European Commission entitled, "Doing Business with the USA," for use by foreign persons.

<P>Public education is another key facet of Steptoe & Johnson LLP's C.I.S. practice.  The firm sponsors a quarterly "Roundtable" on U.S.-C.I.S. trade and investment issues to brief U.S. companies on legal and economic developments.  Our attorneys also conduct seminars on an annual basis in the C.I.S. on issues of central concern to the emerging private sector.  And, Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys publish and lecture widely on C.I.S. commercial law and policy.<a href="#begin"> <font size=-2>[return to top of document]</font></a>
<hr>
 <h4 align=center><a name="struc">The Structure of the Practice</a></h4>

<P>The core of the C.I.S. Trade and Investment practice consists of six Russian speaking attorneys in Washington, D.C., and eight attorneys (U.S. and C.I.S.) in Moscow as well as two in Almaty practicing through the firm's affiliates.  The group is also assisted by area specialists and various consultants (also English/Russian speaking).  Steptoe & Johnson LLP's U.S. and C.I.S. operations are unique in that the firm's non-Russian speaking specialists in intellectual property, tax, finance, environmental protection law and other disciplines (see "Related Practice Areas" below) work as an integrated team with the D.C.-, Moscow- and Almaty-based specialists in C.I.S. law.  This integration is enhanced by a comprehensive communications system, involving satellite phone and fax links and electronic mail.  

<P>The C.I.S. Trade and Investment practice maintains extensive collections of laws for all of the C.I.S. nations in which it is active.  The firm also maintains a network of legal consultants who provide access to key government officials, assist in obtaining political support for client projects and confirm the latest legal and regulatory developments in the C.I.S. nations where Steptoe & Johnson LLP does not currently have offices, but has active client matters.<a href="#begin"> <font size=-2>[return to top of document]</font></a>
<hr>
 <h4 align=center><a name="mem">Members of the C.I.S. Trade and Investment Practice Group</a></h4>
 <h4 align=center>Washington, D.C. Office</H4>

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/carey.htm">Sarah Carey</a> chairs the firm's C.I.S. Practice.  Ms. Carey has practiced law for over 30 years, focusing primarily on corporate and regulatory law, largely in an international context.  Her practice over the past ten years has concentrated on the negotiation and structuring of trade and investment transactions in the countries of the former Soviet Union, including, since 1986, the creation of hundreds of joint ventures and other forms of foreign investment.  Ms. Carey has also been active since 1991 in counselling both Russian enterprises and U.S. companies partnering with such enterprises regarding privatization and restructuring alternatives under Russian law.  Ms. Carey, who speaks Russian, was recently named by President Clinton to serve on the first board of the Russian-American Enterprise Fund; she was also named to the board of the Eurasia Foundation, which was created by Congress to further market reforms in the C.I.S.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/charles.htm">Marina Charles</a> is a corporate attorney specializing in commercial transactions, and investment and securities law issues.  Ms. Charles, who speaks fluent Russian, advises clients with respect to general corporate issues and issues raised by the C.I.S. legal and regulatory framework in connection with their negotiation of joint ventures in a wide range of industries.  Ms. Charles also assists clients in the establishment of business presences in the C.I.S. and in the negotiation of commercial contracts with C.I.S. parties.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/samuelia.htm">Thomas Samuelian</a>, who is fluent in both Russian and Armenian, is an associate in the firm's Washington, D.C. office.  His practice includes CIS transactions, international arbitration, international project finance, intellectual property, Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, and customs law.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/abbey.htm">Michael Abbey</a> is an international trade and antitrust associate.  His practice focuses on C.I.S. transactions, U.S. and European Union antitrust/competition regulation, comparative international law, GATT-related issues and bilateral investment treaties.  In addition to his involvement in U.S. antitrust litigation, Mr. Abbey has provided legal advice on antimonopoly issues in connection with foreign investment in the former Soviet Union.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/solton.htm">Michael Solton</a> is a senior Russian attorney currently based in the Washington, D.C. office.  He is an expert on intellectual property rights and has been actively involved in the privatization of Russian enterprises.  Prior to joining Steptoe & Johnson International in 1991, Mr. Solton was General Manager and General Counsel for the Russian-American joint venture Interperiodica, where he specialized in copyright and corporate law.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/shenk.htm">Maury Shenk</a>, who speaks Russian, is an international and antitrust associate.  His practice involves a variety of international matters, including Russian law, trade litigation, other administrative litigation, export controls, and public international law.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/wack.htm">David Wack</a>, a staff attorney with the firm, advises clients on matters of C.I.S. law and practice.  Mr. Wack, who speaks Russian, also manages the firm's East-West law library.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/phillips.htm">Anne Phillips</a> is Manager of C.I.S. Operations and Development for the firm.  In addition to her practice management responsibilities, Ms. Phillips serves as C.I.S trade advisor, performing policy and market entry analysis for the firm's clients and assistive in securing sources of public financing for their trade and investment activity in the C.I.S. Before coming to Steptoe & Johnson LLP, Ms. Phillips was the Executive Director of Hedrick Smith Productions, where she assisted in the production of the PBS documentaries, "Inside Gorbachev's USSR" and "Challenge to America."  Ms. Phillips, who speaks Russian, completed an M.A. in Soviet Studies and International Economics at Johns Hopkins SAIS.  
<a href="#begin"> <font size=-2>[return to top of document]</font></a>
<hr><h4 align=center><a name="prac">Related Practice Areas</a></h4>

 <h4 align=center>Washington, D.C.</H4>

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/leigh.htm">Monroe Leigh</a>, a specialist on public international law and international trade law, is a former Legal Adviser of the Department of State.  He has been a member of the Permanent Court of Arbitration and the Advisory Committee of the Restatement of the Foreign Relations Law of the United States, and now serves on the USTR Advisory Committee on International Investment (INPAC). 

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/ward.htm">Maureen Ward's</a> practice centers on the protection and licensing of intellectual property, with special emphasis on computer systems and software, trademarks, patent licensing, and publication of literary works.  She has worked on a number of East-West trade transactions involving the transfer of intellectual property, including a joint venture to modify U.S. simulation technology for use in training the operators of Soviet-designed nuclear and coal fired electrical plants; a joint venture to produce and distribute personal computers and software; a joint venture relating to in-flight communications systems; and arrangements to distribute Soviet software and databases within the U.S.  She also works with the firm's Russian colleagues in coordinating lobbying efforts by clients in support of improved intellectual property laws in Russia and other members of the C.I.S. 

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/smilack.htm">Stanley Smilack</a>, whose practice centers primarily on the taxation of the operations of multinational corporations and investments across national borders, is involved in the establishment of joint ventures in the C.I.S., Europe, Asia, Latin America and the U.S.  His practice at the firm includes work in connection with the availability of foreign tax credits for activities carried on abroad, the taxation of U.S. shareholders of foreign corporations, intercompany pricing, the acquisition of interests in foreign firms by U.S. entities and the acquisition of interests in U.S. firms by foreign and domestic entities.  He has also worked on a number of investment funds focusing on investments in East European companies.
<a href="#begin"> <font size=-2>[return to top of document]</font></a>
<hr> <h4 align=center><a name="aff">Steptoe & Johnson LLP Affiliates</a></h4>

<H4 align=center>In Moscow</H4>

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/white.htm">Walter H. White, Jr.</a> is a partner in Steptoe & Johnson LLP and Managing Director of Steptoe & Johnson International, Moscow, where his work consists of multinational securities transactions and international business law issues.  Mr. White has represented U.S., Canadian and European clients in developing business activities in Central Europe and the C.I.S. and has advised governments of the C.I.S. on economic development issues and legislation.  Mr. White was appointed by President Clinton to the Board of the Central Asian-American Enterprise Fund and also is a member of the Council on Foreign Relations in New York, New York.  In the North American Securities Administrators Association, he has served as Chair of the International Corporation Finance Committee, and as Vice Chair of its Corporation Finance Section.  He was a member of the SEC Task Force on the U.S. Canadian Multijurisdictional Disclosure System.  Mr. White served as Commissioner of Securities for the State of Wisconsin from February 1988 until January 1991.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/bregman.htm">Randy Bregman</a> is a partner of Steptoe & Johnson LLP and has worked in the area of U.S.-Soviet law and commerce for over 20 years and has an extensive network of relationships throughout the C.I.S. and Eastern Europe.  Mr. Bregman frequently meets with Russian government officials to obtain authoritative clarification of emerging legislation in commercial areas and international transaction activity.  He has also headed start-up efforts for several Fortune 500 firms in Russia.  Recent projects have included providing advice for a major multi-national pharmaceutical company pursuing groundbreaking projects in Russia and ongoing operational counsel for a large oil joint venture.  

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/kovaleva.htm">Tatiana Kovaleva</a>, a senior Russian attorney, is a specialist in Russian tax and commercial law and a professor of Moscow State University Law School.  Dr. Kovaleva has counselled numerous U.S. and European companies on the structuring of their investments as well as on negotiating strategies.  Dr. Kovaleva is widely regarded as a leading expert on Russian energy regulatory law.  Before coming to the firm's affiliate, she spent one year conducting research in the U.S. at Harvard University Law School.  

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/kaldina.htm">Marina Kaldina</a>, a Russian attorney with the firm's Moscow affiliate, specializes in structuring and developing corporate forms for foreign and Russian businesses.  In addition to her civil law training at Sverdlovsk Law Institute, Ms. Kaldina completed a special course on American Law that was conducted under the auspices of Emory University Law School. 

<P>Olga Bezrukova is a specialist in intellectual property as a registered agent in the Russian Federation.  Ms. Bezrukova defended her dissertation at Moscow State University in 1989.  Before coming to Steptoe & Johnson LLP, she served as Director of the Center of Economics and Patent Consultants, as well as a research associate at the Institute of the USA and Canada, Russian Academies of Science, and a seminar lecturer at the Institute of Industry, Property and Inventions of the Russian Patent Registry.

<P>Tatiana Orlovskaya is a specialist in Russian labor law and serves as senior legal researcher in Steptoe & Johnson LLP's Moscow affiliate.  Ms. Orlovskaya has worked extensively in the field of Russian/Soviet law since completing her J.D. equivalent at Moscow State University.

<H4 align=center>In Almaty</H4>

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/altynbae.htm">Gulzhan Altynbaeva</a>, a citizen of Kazakstan, is a corporate attorney with the firm's Almaty affiliate.  Her practice has focused primarily on privatization and the growing body of commercial law associated with trade and investment in Kazakstan, Russia and the C.I.S.  Ms. Altynbaeva recently served as lead counsel on a AID project for the privatization of the Port of Murmansk.  Prior to joining the firm's affiliates, she served as legal counsel to the Kazak Cultural Fund and focused on labor law and commercial law matters.  She also served at lecturer at the Kazak Polytechnic Institute, where she focused on Soviet patent law.  In addition to completing a J.D. and post-graduate work in Russia, Ms. Altynbaeva completed an LL.M. at the University of Illinois in 1993. 

<P>Kairat Serikpaev, a citizen of Kazakstan, is the senior legal assistant with the firm's Almaty affiliate, specializing in accreditations and registrations of foreign companies in Kazakstan.  Mr. Serikpaev completed his J.D. equivalent at Sverdlovsk Law Institute in 1989.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/titkov.htm">Alexander Titkov</a> is an associate with the firm's Almaty affiliate.  He specializes in international law, the civil law of the states of the C.I.S., and U.S. civil and tax law.  Mr. Titkov recently completed work on a USAID Mass Privatization project in Kazakstan, where he advised on a wide range of company formation, privatization and securities registration issues.  He is a graduate of Kiev State University International Law Department and completed an LL.M. in 1994 at John Marshall Law School.  Mr. Titkov speaks both Russian and Ukrainian.  <a href="#begin"><font size=-2>[Return to beginning of document]</font></a>

<hr><h4 align=center><a name="consult">C.I.S. Consultants</a></h4>

 <h4 align=center>Ukraine</H4>

<P>Evgeny Kubko is the senior partner in Salkom Ltd., a leading Ukrainian law firm.  He is a specialist in commercial law and the regulation of the banking and finance sectors.  As counsel to the Ukrainian Parliament, Mr. Kubko is actively involved in drafting the new body of commercial laws accompanying Ukraine's transition to a market economy.


 <h4 align=center>Kirghiz Republic</H4>

<P>Samuel Mashansky, Associate Professor of Commercial Law at Kirghizstan State University, provides consulting services for the firm in Kirghizstan.  Professor Mashansky has advised the Kirghiz Parliament on property law issues and has served as the director of various state agencies.  He recently participated in the firm's AID technical assistance work in Bishkek, providing counsel with respect to the reform of commercial law and other issues related to the transition to a market economy.<a href="#begin"> <font size=-2>[Return to top of document]</font></a>
<hr>
