<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Environmental Law Practice:  Site Remediation and Cost Allocation Supplement
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2>
<CENTER>Environmental Law Practice:</CENTER></h2>
<H2><CENTER>Site Remediation and Cost Allocation Supplement</CENTER></H2>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have been active on federal Superfund issues since the passage of the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act (CERCLA) in 1980.  Currently, Steptoe attorneys are handling matters under CERCLA, RCRA and analogous state programs
governing site remediation and cost allocation in a number of jurisdictions, including Arizona, California, Connecticut, the District of Columbia, Massachusetts, Montana, New Jersey, North Dakota, Oregon, Virginia and Washington.  This wide range of experience provides Steptoe with the expertise to devise sound, creative approaches to remediation and related cost allocation issues in almost any setting.  We work with our clients to bring the knowledge we have gained at sites all around the nation to bear on the client's specific situation(s).

<P>Among our current and recent Superfund representations are the
following:
<ul><LI>Negotiating voluntary clean up programs with state regulatory
agencies for manufacturing facilities in California, New Jersey
and Montana, and for a former waste disposal facility in
Virginia.<P>
<LI>Working out an understanding with EPA to allow construction of
a new building to take place on a federal Superfund site.<P>
<LI>Working with consultants to convince state regulators that the
risk from a contaminated facility should be addressed through
containment, rather than other alternatives.<P>
<LI>Convincing EPA to add additional PRP's to a federal Superfund
site before consent decree negotiations.	<P>
<LI>Winning a victory for a large group of municipalities in
private cost recovery litigation arising out of the Murtha site
in Connecticut.  Steptoe attorneys successfully argued that
sending municipal solid waste to a landfill is not by itself a
sufficient basis to impose liability under Superfund.<P>
<LI>Serving as Court Appointed Liaison Counsel for a group of over
150 third-party defendants and also representing 25 parties in
private cost allocation litigation surrounding the SCP-Carlstadt
Superfund Site in New Jersey.  Our firm also represents a group
of 30 de minimis contributors to the site seeking a settlement
with the other members of the cooperating PRP Group and with
EPA.  <P>
<LI>Achieving settlement in a complex private cost recovery action
involving a site near Washington National Airport.  Representing
the plaintiff landowner, we brought an action against the
operator of a scrap yard and the approximately 25 waste
generators seeking response costs.</ul>


<P>Steptoe also is heavily involved on the legislative side of
Superfund matters.  Steptoe lawyers worked with the
Environmental Law Institute to prepare The Superfund Desk Book,
the first major publication to assess the impact of the
Superfund Amendments and Reauthorization Act (SARA).  Since that
time, Steptoe has been in close touch with Superfund legislative
developments at the federal level and in states, such as
California and New Jersey, which are of particular interest to
our clients.  We currently are representing a major industry
association in connection with the Superfund Reauthorization
bill.<p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/environ.htm">Environmental Law Practice Area Description</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>

</DOC>
