<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Appellate and Supreme Court Practice

</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>



<H2><Center>Appellate and Supreme Court Practice</center></H2>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has represented clients on numerous occasions in the U.S. Supreme Court and federal courts of appeals throughout the country.

<P>Because the firm's litigation practice frequently involves cutting-edge issues leading to appellate litigation, virtually all Steptoe & Johnson LLP litigators are experienced in appellate work.  In addition to appeals arising from cases in which Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys con-ducted the trial court proceedings, the firm's litigators often handle cases brought to the firm at the appellate or Supreme Court stage.  

<P>Unlike some other firms with substantial appellate practices, however, Steptoe & Johnson LLP does not compartmentalize its appellate practitioners by placing them in a department separate from the rest of the firm.  The firm believes that its appellate clients benefit from working with litigators who also have trial experience, and that its clients with matters at the trial level often benefit from having the perspective of a litigator with appellate experience.


<h4><center>Supreme Court Litigation</center></h4>

<P>Practice before the U.S. Supreme Court, particularly at the stage of petitioning for certiorari, involves distinctive rules and procedures.  A command of the relevant substantive law is therefore only a threshold requirement in dealing with the Court.  A number of partners at our firm have considerable Supreme Court experience, both as former Supreme Court clerks and as veteran Supreme Court practitioners.

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys routinely handle cases brought to the firm following a loss in a federal court of appeals or a state supreme court.  The firm's Supreme Court specialists are often asked to provide advice on petitioning for certiorari and other aspects of Supreme Court practice.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have also served as counsel or co-counsel in numerous cases for clients filing briefs amicus curiae in support of petitions for certiorari or on the merits.

<P>On a number of Supreme Court matters, we have collaborated with trial counsel in presenting a case to the Court.  We have found that this collaboration often provides enhanced representation for the client.  Typically, each set of counsel will have somewhat different insights and experiences to contribute to the case.

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have briefed and argued all sorts of cases before the Supreme Court.  In recent years, challenges to state laws affecting multi-state corporations on constitutional and federal pre-emption grounds and tax cases have been especially prominent in the firm's Supreme Court practice.  The constitutional challenges have invoked the commerce clause and the equal protection clause to challenge discrimination against out-of-state companies on state and local laws; the tax cases involved such diverse issues as state insurance premium taxation, federal statutory limitations on state taxation, corporate tax issues, and ERISA preemption matters.  


<h4><center>Biographies of Key Appellate Litigators</center></h4>


<H4><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/nolan.htm">John E. Nolan, Jr.</a></center></H4>

<P>Born Minneapolis, Minnesota, 1927:  J.D. Georgetown University; Associate Editor, Georgetown Law Journal; B.S. United States Naval Academy; Law Clerk to Justice Tom C. Clark; Administrative Assistant to Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy (1963-64); Executive Committee, National Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights Under Law (1976-present).

<P>Recent cases include <i>Mass Mutual v. Collins</i> (S. Ct. 1991); <i>Pilot Life v. Dedeaux</i> (S. Ct. 1987); <i>Mass Mutual v. Russell</I> (S. Ct. 1986); <I>Nixon v. Fitzgerald</I> (S. Ct. 1981); <I>Harlow & Butterfield v. Fitzgerald</I> (S. Ct. 1981). 

<H4><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/christia.htm">Betty Jo Christian</a></center></H4>

<P>Born Temple, Texas, 1936:  LL.B. University of Texas (summa cum laude); Articles Editor, Texas Law Review; Order of the Coif; B.A. University of Texas (summa cum laude); Phi Beta Kappa; Law Clerk to Chief Justice Robert W. Calvert, Supreme Court of Texas; Commissioner, Interstate Commerce Commission (1976-79); Vice Chairman, Interstate Commerce Commission (1978); Chairman, Transportation Committee of ABA Administrative Law Section; Chairman, Council Member, Railroad Committee of ABA Public Utility Section; Senior Conference Fellow, Administrative Conference of the United States; D.C. Circuit Conference Advisory Council.

