<html><HEAD>
<TITLE>Overloading the FCC</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body><H2 align=center>Overloading the FCC</H2><P>
<CENTER><I>By <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/mamlet.htm">Alfred Mamlet</a></I><p> This article appeared in the February 19, 1996<br> issue of the <I>Legal Times</I> under <I>Opinion and Commentary</I></CENTER>

<hr>
<P><CENTER><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review of the needs and circumstances of an individual client.  This and other documents on the Steptoe & Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.  Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest. </I></CENTER><P>
<hr>



<P>At the Feb. 8 signing ceremony for the Telecommunications Reform Act of 1996, President Bill Clinton and Senate Commerce Committee Chairman Larry Pressler (R-S.D.) both praised the legislation as a deregulatory measure that would reduce governmental oversight of the telecommunications industry. While the legislation does reduce many regulatory barriers to entry into several critical telecommunications markets, however, it also simultaneously and significantly increases the regulatory role of the Federal Communications Commission.

<P>Ever since Judge Harold Greene of the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia effectively assumed regulatory control of significant portions of telecommunications policy through his administration in the early 1980s of the American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. consent decree in <I>United States</I> v. <I>AT&amp;T</I>, 555 F. Supp. 226 (D.D.C. 1982), Congress has been considering how to wrest dominance of telecommunications policy from the judiciary. The 1996 act marks the culmination of this decade-long legislative effort.


<h4 align=center>RAZING WALLS</h4>


<P>The act removes barriers to four major telecommunications markets: the long distance and manufacturing markets (by overriding terms of the AT&amp;T consent decree that prohibited the seven regional Bell operating companies,Baby Bells,from entering these markets); the local telephone market (by pre-empting state and local regulatory barriers); and the video market (by removing statutory barriers to Baby Bell entry that Congress itself had erected).

<P>At the same time, the new law ensures that the FCC will continue to have four essential tasks for years to come. First, the commission will play a significant &quot;gatekeeper&quot; role by regulating entry into some sectors. For example, the FCC will decide the crucial question of when the regional Bell operating companies will be permitted to originate long distance service inside their own territory. (For example, when can Bell Atlantic
provide long distance service to its customers in Virginia?) The FCC will judge Baby Bell applications for every state (except Alaska and Hawaii, which have no Baby Bells) on the basis of (1) whether the Baby Bell faces a facilities-based competitor; (2) whether the Baby Bell has met an intricate 14-point checklist for opening up the local market to competition; and (3) whether Baby Bell entry meets the amorphous &quot;public interest&quot; test.


<P>Second, and most important, the FCC will continue to operate as &quot;rule-maker,&quot; establishing the rules of the road for the newly competitive markets. The 1996 act commands the commission to conduct rule-makings on about 80 topics. These include: <P>

<blockquote>Regulations on local competition that must cover interconnections, reciprocal compensation for terminating local calls, resale, number portability (which permits a customer to keep the same phone number when switching local carriers), and access to rights-of-way and placement of competitor's equipment in facilities owned by Baby Bells; Creation (in conjunction with a joint board of the FCC and state utility commissioners, and a consumer advocate) of a new program for universal service that includes (1) expansion of the program to subsidize &quot;advanced telecommunications and information services&quot;; (2) establishment of a new funding mechanism providing discounted access for public schools, libraries, and health care institutions; and (3) designation of carriers eligible for federal support;

<p>Regulations for &quot;open video systems,&quot; which will allow video programming using common carrier regulatory principles instead of traditional cable regulation; and 

<p>Regulations for incumbent local exchange companies to share infrastructure with new entrants.</blockquote>


<P>Third, the FCC increasingly will be called on to play &quot;traffic cop&quot; in newly competitive markets. New entrants will inevitably claim that incumbent powerhouses are unfairly using their market power to squelch competition. For example, new entrants into the local exchange market are likely to contend that RBOCs are not opening up their local networks quickly enough to competitors. Similarly, new entrants in the video market may argue that cable TV companies that control a significant amount of content,such as TCI and Time-Warner [a
Legal Times' affiliate],are not making that content available on a nondiscriminatory basis. These complaints will lead to calls to revise the rules of the road and to take specific remedial action against some companies. The commission will be increasingly asked to sharpen the line between legitimate competitive advantages and unfair practices.


<P>Fourth, the FCC will continue to be the &quot;megadeal magistrate&quot; for the many transactions that will be stimulated by the act. For example, FCC approval will be needed for transfers of radio licenses, as well as for major foreign investments in companies holding radio licenses. Such transactions are likely to increase under the new act. Indeed, the recent Disney/ABC and Westinghouse/CBS transactions anticipated the legislative changes increasing the number of broadcast stations that can be under common ownership. Similarly, foreign investment is growing as U.S. carriers seek capital to position themselves for increased competition in the market sectors opened up by the 1996 act. The MCI/British Telephone and Sprint/France
Telecom/Deutsche Telekom transactions are evidence of this trend. More transactions on a similar scale,many requiring FCC review and approval,are likely as other companies strive to provide one-stop shopping for consumers' communications, information, and entertainment needs.

<h4 align=center>STRAIN ON RESOURCES</h4>

<P>The new regulatory responsibilities imposed by the 1996 act will put a major strain on commission resources. Virtually every one of the 80 mandated rule-makings has a congressional deadline. Many of the rule-makings must be completed within six months; almost all are to be finalized within two years. Indeed,
these and other time limits demonstrate that the battle between lawmakers who intended the telecommunications act to function primarily as a means of deregulating the industry and those who
wished to bolster FCC authority in order to protect consumers and companies without market power has not been resolved.

<P>For example, Congress has allotted only 90 days to consider an RBOC's application to originate long distance service from within its own territories. Yet, these reviews (and there will be one for every state the Baby Bells serve) must include a proceeding to obtain comments from interested companies and the public. It is inevitable that this will prove to be a lightning rod for attracting Baby Bell competitors complaining that insufficient steps have been taken to open up the local market to competition.

<P>Similarly, in reviewing these applications, the FCC is required to consult with state utility commissions on whether the Baby Bell has satisfied the 14-point competitive checklist for opening up the local market. The FCC also must give &quot;substantial weight&quot; to the views of the Department of Justice.


<P>A proceeding of this magnitude normally would take the commission at least one year. A timetable of 90 days precludes an exacting review, apparently, a deliberate choice by Congress.



<P>Ninety days, however, is a leisurely pace compared to the timetable for FCC consideration of local telephone company applications to provide video services through an &quot;open video system.&quot; To qualify as an open video system provider, which allows a company to avoid numerous traditional cable TV
regulatory requirements, a telephone company must certify that it meets an eight-point checklist. The FCC is given all of 10 days to pass on such a telephone company application.

<P>In addition to denying the FCC the time needed for careful analysis, some in Congress are determined to deregulate by starving the commission of necessary resources. Many commissioners and staff members have already begun working seven days a week just to plan the implementation of the act. At the same time, Congress has allowed the commission's budgetary fate to remain uncertain. The FCC is operating at a reduced funding level, and its financing beyond March is in doubt.

<h4  align=center>GOVERNMENT'S BEST BARGAIN</h4>

<P>This move to cripple the FCC certainly cannot be justified on fiscal grounds. The commission is the best bargain in government, raising more than $15 billion in revenues in the last year through spectrum auctions, more money than any other federal agency except the Internal Revenue Service.



<P>If Congress wants the FCC to discharge its important gatekeeper, rule-maker, traffic cop, and megadeal magistrate responsibilities in a manner that promotes competition and protects the public, then it should provide the commission with sufficient resources to complete the telecommunications reform task started in the 1996 act. A decision to deny these funds will be an unfortunate attempt to obtain deregulatory goals not
realized in the 1996 law through the appropriations process.       

<hr>
