<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR)
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR)</CENTER></H2>

<P>Over the past few years, Steptoe & Johnson LLP has successfully concluded some of its most important litigation by switching to alternative dispute resolution (ADR).  These cases have included a major antitrust suit in the railroad industry and litigation over royalties to be paid by a major Alaska North Slope oil producer to the State of Alaska.  In these examples and others, we have specially tailored ADR procedures to wind up ongoing litigation on terms that clients thought to their great advantage.  As usual with ADR, these settlements have involved major savings to the client in time and expense.  We have also drafted ADR clauses for settlement agreements and contracts to provide quick and less expensive means of solving disputes arising under such agreements.

<P>More recently, partners in the firm have served as mediators or arbitrators in cases involving professional football franchises, communications satellites, and major retail and real estate holdings.  In one instance, multiple lawsuits in three jurisdictions were settled in a mediation of three and one-half months.


<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/bouknigh.htm">Lon Bouknight</a>, <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/green.htm">Doug Green</a>, and <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/patterso.htm">Errol Patterson</a> represented Public Service Electric & Gas Company in a suit against another utility that was settled for $131,000,000 through an ADR process which included a mini-trial presided over by former Deputy Attorney General Harold Tyler.

<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/nolan.htm">John Nolan</a> was the mediator for those parts of the Haft family litigation that have settled and has served as either mediator or arbitrator in a number of other noteworthy cases.  

<P>We find that our clients' interests are best served by maintaining an ADR capability separate from our litigation group.  We screen all new litigation matters for ADR potential and work closely with the litigation team when some alternative to litigation becomes a possibility.

<P>The firm has been an active participant in the CPR Institute for Dispute Resolution since its founding.  <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/nolan.htm">John Nolan</a>, <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/jordan.htm">Bob Jordan</a> and <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/meyerson.htm">Bruce Meyerson</a> are among the members of the Center for Public Resources' panels of "Distinguished Neutrals" and all are proponents of ADR in the national bar.  Several of our largest corporate clients have been leaders in the development of ADR, and we continue to work closely with them as the field develops.
<p><p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>
