<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>W. George Grandison Bio</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</H3><H2 ALIGN=CENTER>
W. George Grandison</H2>

<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/intlctm2.htm">International Trade and Customs</a></center></blockquote>


<P>George Grandison's practice centers on the regulation of international trade andinvestment.  In international trade litigation, he has handled major cases under the antidumping and countervailing duty laws, Section 301, and Section 22 of the Agricultural Adjustment Act, before the Department of Commerce,
the International Trade Commission, the Court of International Trade and Binational Panels established under the U.S. Canada Free Trade Agreement.  In the Customs area, he advises clients on classification, valuation, country of origin, marking, and other related issues.  He also represents clients in civil and criminal customs enforcement and penalty matters.  His cases have involved agricultural and forestry products including sugar, wheat and lumber and manufactured products, including steel, oil platforms,
heavy electrical equipment, chemicals, optical fiber, commuter aircraft and high technology products and materials.  Mr. Grandison has written and lectured on legal topics relating to international trade, customs law, export controls and international procurement.
<P>Following service as an infantry officer and law school, Mr. Grandison was an attorney in the International Affairs Division, Office of the Judge Advocate General, Department of the Army, 1972-76.  He was a member of the U.S. Delegation to the Diplomatic Conference on Reaffirmation and Development of International Humanitarian Law in Armed Conflict, Geneva, Switzerland, 1975-76.
<P> He is a member of the District of Columbia and Connecticut bars, the American Society of
International Law, the International Bar Association and the American Bar Association. 

<P><DIR><LI> Yale University J.D. 1972 
<LI>United States Military Academy B.S. 1966 </DIR>


