<html><head><title>Anne Phillips</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Anne Phillips</h2>


<blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/cistrade.htm">Manager CIS Operations & Development</a></CENTER></blockquote>
<hr>
<P>As Steptoe & Johnson LLP's Manager of CIS Operations & Development, Anne Phillips specializes in trade and investment with Russia and the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), performing policy and market entry analysis for the firm and clients. Ms. Phillips also assists clients in securing public and private sector insurance and financing (U.S. Government, World Bank, EBRD, among others) for investments in the CIS.  Complimenting her analytical and finance work, she promotes and conducts widespread business development for the firm and clients and manages the professional operations of Steptoe & Johnson LLP's Washington office and CIS affiliates (Moscow and Almaty).

<P>Prior to joining Steptoe & Johnson LLP in 1992, Ms. Phillips was Executive Director of Hedrick Smith Productions (1990-1992), where she managed commercial operations and coordinated all of the research for the company's first PBS documentary, "Challenge to America (airdate May 1993)." Through a series of case studies, the documentary examines the social and economic challenge from Asia and Japan and a united Europe, and competitive strategist for the U.S. strategies in the coming century.  As Executive Director, Ms. Phillips managed project staffing, budgeting and fundraising.  

<P>From 1989-1990, Ms. Phillips was Research Director for Hedrick Smith, then a senior fellow of the Johns Hopkins University Foreign Policy Institute.  In this capacity, she coordinated all of the research for the PBS documentary, "Inside Gorbachev's USSR," as well as for Hedrick Smith's best-seller, The New Russians.

<P>In addition, Ms. Phillips, who speaks Russian, has worked as an independent consultant, accompanying American congressional and trade delegations to the former Soviet Union.

<P>Ms. Phillips completed an M.A. in Soviet Studies and International Economics at The Johns Hopkins University School of Advanced International Studies (1988).  Her field research paper, The Law on the State Enterprise (Association): A Case of Soviet Legal Reform, examined the status of property rights
under Mikhail Gorbachev's economic reform program, and the importance of the legal reform which underlay the more visible and frequently analyzed economic reform program.  While attending graduate school, she also worked as a research assistant to Dr. Bruce Parrott, Chairman of the SAIS Soviet
Studies Department, and conducted primary research on the development of civilian-military relations under Gorbachev. In addition, Ms. Phillips was research assistant to Dr. Carol Rae Hansen with whom she organized a series of four roundtables on U.S.-Soviet trade issues and analyzed the U.S. policy of
differentiation toward Eastern Europe (for a Council on Foreign Relations project).  Ms. Phillips attended the SAIS Bologna Center in Bologna, Italy during her first year of graduate school.

<P>Ms. Phillips received a B.A. with commendations of excellence from Reed College (1981), where she majored in Political Science.  In her senior year, she completed and defended a thesis, "The University of California v. Bakke: Equality of Opportunity vs. Equality of Results."  Ms. Phillips completed post-graduate work in French literature at the University of Paris-Sorbonne (1981-82).

<p><hr><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/cistrade.htm">CIS Trade</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorneys</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
