<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Antitrust and Trade Regulation Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>


<H2><CENTER>Antitrust and Trade Regulation Practice</CENTER></H2>
<P>The antitrust practice at Steptoe & Johnson LLP has been a mainstay since the firm's inception.  Calling upon the experience of a large and diverse number of talented lawyers over the years, Steptoe's antitrust group remains committed to the highest level of competence and currency in serving the demands of its antitrust clients.  We provide a full scope antitrust and trade regulation practice, including such areas as traditional business counseling; complex litigation and jury trials; acquisition representation and related transactional services; white collar crime; specialization in various statutory antitrust exemptions; trade association counseling; state antitrust enforcement; and, consumer protection, unfair trade practices and business tort matters.  Steptoe's antitrust lawyers provide this array of substantive areas of expertise both in domestic U.S. and international contexts.

<P>The firm has also built substantial expertise on an industry-specific basis, including virtually every segment and level of the U.S. and global economy -- from the production tier (e.g., steel, automobiles, petroleum production and refining, food processing, defense systems and electronics), through distributive services (e.g., wholesale distribution of groceries, hospital supplies, pharmaceutical products, consumer electronics and various other industrial and consumer goods), to traditional and specialty retailing (e.g., supermarkets, drug store chains, tire and auto parts stores and other specialty retailers).  In addition, our antitrust practice has long included substantial representations in the insurance, telecommunications and transportation industries.

<P>In each instance, and over time, our client specific work includes one or more of the following areas of expertise:

<P><I>Antitrust Business Counseling.</I>  Antitrust business counseling with a corporate client may include, for example: acquisition planning and execution; evaluation of competitive aspects of distribution and supply arrangements, joint ventures and strategic alliances; technology licensing; franchisor-franchisee relations; management of government enforcement investigations; monitoring of proposed federal legislation affecting competitive positions in the U.S. and abroad; advice relating to trade association activities; and, development of antitrust compliance programs.

<P><I>Complex Antitrust Litigation and Class Actions</I>.  Antitrust litigation invariably is complex, often involving multiple cases, parties and judicial districts.  This, in turn, can require multi-district coordination and experience before the Federal Judicial Panel for Multi-district Litigation.  In addition, private cases are often brought on behalf of an entire class of plaintiffs, allegedly injured by the anticompetitive conduct of defendants.  These cases can present aggregate damage exposure in the hundreds of millions of dollars.  Steptoe antitrust litigators have substantial experience with such litigation.  Currently, we are representing a major insurance company in <I>In re Insurance Antitrust Litigation</I>, MDL 767, a treble damages case brought by nineteen state attorney generals.  Steptoe antitrust litigators also represent the world's largest aquaculture farm cooperative in <I>In re Catfish Antitrust Litigation</I>, MDL 928, a treble damages class action brought by a nationwide class of direct purchasers of processed farm-raised catfish products.
<P><I>Criminal Antitrust. </I> The Steptoe & Johnson LLP antitrust group has wide experience representing both corporations and individuals throughout the country in connection with Sherman Act felony investigations.  Our extensive federal grand jury experience includes all pre- and post-indictment phases of criminal antitrust proceedings, as well as the federal, state and private treble damages actions that typically follow a criminal charge.  We also have in-depth experience handling civil fraud actions and administrative suspension and debarment proceedings, which frequently arise when the federal government itself claims to have incurred damages as a result of antitrust violations.
<P><I>Federal Trade Commission and Department of Justice, Antitrust Division Matters</I>.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys appear before the Federal Trade Commission, the Antitrust Division of the Department of Justice and their staffs of attorneys and economists on a regular basis.  The firm's Justice Department practice centers on merger-antitrust (Hart-Scott-Rodino Premerger Notification and follow-on investigations) and criminal grand jury investigations conducted by the Division.  A number of Steptoe partners served as FTC officials prior to joining the firm.  These attorneys direct defenses of FTC investigations and adjudications originating both in the FTC's Bureau of Competition (involving traditional antitrust enforcement issues such as competitive evaluation of proposed mergers) and its Bureau of Consumer Protection (including matters such as deceptive advertising claims and other marketing practices directly relating to possible consumer injuries).  Steptoe's FTC and DOJ practices include representation before the headquarter offices in Washington and at regional offices from Seattle to Atlanta.
<P><I>State Antitrust and Trade Regulation Litigation.</I>  Most states have antitrust and trade regulation statutes patterned after the federal Sherman, Clayton and Federal Trade Commission Acts.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP antitrust litigators actively participate in the defense of such matters in numerous states, both as lead counsel and, on occasion, on a consultative basis with local litigation and corporate counsel.
<P><I>International Antitrust.</I>  Steptoe's antitrust group intersects with the firm's large International Law and Trade Group to produce a truly global antitrust practice.  Serving off-shore clients with U.S. interests, as well as domestic firms with multi-national concerns, Steptoe's antitrust attorneys provide the same range of antitrust business counseling outlined above in the international context.  This includes active involvement in transactions and practices subject to the jurisdiction of such entities as the European Economic Commission and the Japan Fair Trade Commission.  Steptoe's international antitrust merger and acquisition practice also includes Exxon-Florio Act filings and practice before the U.S. Commerce Department in connection with foreign acquisition of U.S. assets.

<P>These Steptoe & Johnson LLP partners, with the support of the firm's associate lawyers, paralegals and law clerks, currently direct the practice of the Antitrust Group:

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/fleishma.htm">Robert Fleishman</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Lexington, Kentucky, 1945:  J.D. Michigan Law School (cum laude) 1972; B.A. University of Kentucky (cum laude) 1967, Phi Beta Kappa and Departmental Honors in Philosophy; Trial Attorney, Bureau of Competition, Federal Trade Commission, 1973-74; Attorney Advisor to Federal Trade Commissioner Elizabeth Dole, 1974-75; currently leader of Steptoe's Antitrust Practice Group.

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/graubert.htm">John Graubert</a></CENTER>

<P>Born New York, New York, 1956:  J.D. Georgetown University 1981, Articles & Notes Editor, American Criminal Law Review; B.A. Williams College (cum laude) 1978; law clerk, Judge J. MacDonald Ingraham of the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit, 1981-82.


<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/horning.htm">Mark Horning</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Detroit, Michigan, 1947:  J.D. Yale University 1974; B.A. Yale University 1968.


<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/jordan.htm">Robert Jordan III</a></CENTER>
<P>Born South Boston, Virginia, 1936:  J.D. Harvard Law School (magna cum laude) 1961, Editor, Harvard Law Review; S.B. Massachusetts Institute of Technology 1958; Officer, United States Army (1961-63); Special Assistant for Civil Rights, Office of the Secretary of Defense (1964-65); Executive Assistant for Enforcement, Office of the Secretary of the Treasury (1965-67); Deputy General Counsel, Department of the Army (1967); General Counsel of the Army and Special Assistant to the  Secretary of the Army for Civil Functions (1967-71); Chair, Legal Ethics Committee, District of Columbia Bar (1978-81); President, District of Columbia Bar (1987-88); Chairman, Executive Committee, Steptoe & Johnson (1989-90).

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/labovitz.htm">John Labovitz</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Washington, D.C., 1943:  J.D. University of Chicago (with honors) 1969, Editor-in-Chief, University of Chicago Law Review; A.B. Brown University (summa cum laude) 1965.

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/larocca.htm">Anthony LaRocca</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan, 1955:  J.D. Harvard Law School (magna cum laude) 1984, Editor, Recent Developments, Harvard International Law Journal; A.B. University of Michigan (high distinction) 1977.

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/malet.htm">Philip Malet</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, 1955:  J.D. George Washington University (with high honors) 1979; B.S.E.E. University of Pennsylvania (cum laude) 1975; Federal Communications Commission, Review Board, 1979-80; Electronics Engineer, FCC.

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/mcnamara.htm">Ellen McNamara</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Brooklyn, New York, 1950:  J.D. University of Virginia 1975, Managing Board (Notes Editor), Virginia Law Review, Order of the Coif; B.A. Douglass College -- Rutgers University (with honors) 1972, Phi Beta Kappa; Contributing Author, Antitrust Trial Evidence Manual, (ABA Antitrust Section, 1991).

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/plaine.htm">Daniel Plaine</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Washington, D.C., 1943:  J.D. Yale University 1970; LL.B. International Law Cambridge University 1967, Marshall Scholar; B.A. Williams College (magna cum laude) 1965, Phi Beta Kappa.

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/porter.htm">Richard Porter</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Fitchburg, Massachusetts, 1942:  J.D. Georgetown University 1967, Georgetown Law Review; B.S.B.A. Georgetown University (cum laude) 1964; Legislative Assistant, Senator Edward Kennedy; Legal Assistant to General Counsel of the Army.

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/roll.htm">David Roll</a></CENTER>
<P>Born Pontiac, Michigan, 1940:  J.D. University of Michigan 1964; B.A. Amherst College (cum laude) 1962; Assistant Director, Bureau of Competition, General Litigation, Federal Trade Commission (1972-75); Council Member, ABA Antitrust Section; Chair, Clayton and Robinson Patman Act Committees of ABA Antitrust Section; Author and Editor, The FTC as an Antitrust Enforcement Agency:  Its Structure, Powers and Procedures.


<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/walsh.htm">Timothy Walsh</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Dallas, Texas, 1952:  J.D. Yale University 1977; A.B. Stanford University (with distinction) 1974.

<P><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/whiting.htm">Richard Whiting</a></CENTER>

<P>Born Cambridge, Massachusetts, 1922:  A.B. Dartmouth College (cum laude) 1944; LL.B. Yale University 1949; Chairman, ABA Antitrust Section (1984-85); Adjunct Professor, Vermont School of Law.
