<html><head><title>Olin L. Wethington Bio</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Olin L. Wethington</h2>
<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/intltrad.htm">International Corporate and Finance Transactions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/intltrad.htm">International Trade Regulation</a></center></blockquote>
<hr>



<P>Olin Wethington's practice focuses on international corporate and
finance transactions, particularly related to emerging markets in
Latin America, the states of the former Soviet Union, and Asia. 
His practice is also directed to financial firms requiring
regulatory advice in the United States and assistance in accessing
foreign financial markets.  Mr. Wethington returned to Steptoe &
Johnson LLP in March 1993, after having served as Assistant
Secretary for International Affairs at the U.S. Department of the
Treasury and as Special Assistant to the President at the White
House. </P>

<P>As Assistant Secretary at the Treasury, Mr. Wethington worked to
encourage economic and financial market reform in developing
countries and strengthening of the private sector.  He managed U.S.
participation in the multilateral development banks, including the
World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development, and served on the Board of
Directors of the U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corporation.
</P>
<P>Mr. Wethington also has been deeply involved in U.S.-Latin American
affairs.  At the White House, he was the chief policy official
responsible for coordinating the development of President Bush's
Enterprise for the Americas Initiative (EAI).  After moving to the
Treasury in 1991, he had responsibility for implementing the debt
reduction and investment sector elements of the Initiative, which
were carried out with over a dozen Latin American countries.  He
was closely involved in the Treasury's support of commercial bank
Brady deals in Latin America.  Mr. Wethington was the chief U.S.
negotiator on the financial services chapter of the North American
Free Trade Agreement.</P>

<P>At the Treasury, Mr. Wethington worked on behalf of the
Administration's effort to support economic reform in the states of
the former Soviet Union.  He played a significant role in the U.S.-
led multilateral aid package for Russia in April 1992, was a strong
advocate of expanded technical assistance to Russia to encourage
privatization, and sought to expand Western participation in the
Russian energy sector.  Mr. Wethington is also involved in Steptoe
& Johnson LLP's Russia-related practice, which includes the firm's
affiliate, Steptoe & Johnson International, one of the most
experienced American-affiliate law offices in Moscow.
</P>
<P>At both the White House and the Treasury, Mr. Wethington had
significant responsibilities with respect to U.S. trade and
economic policy toward Asia.  At the Treasury, he was one of the
Administration's lead negotiators on the U.S.-Japan Structural
Impediments Initiative and was responsible for the U.S.-Korea
financial policy talks, the exchange rate discussions with China
and Taiwan, and various financial policy and market access issues
with Japan.</P>
<P></p>
<DIR><L1>Harvard Law School J.D., 1977<BR>
<L1>Columbia University Ph.D. candidate, 1974<BR>
<L1>University of Pennsylvania M.A., 1971
B.A., 1971
Phi Beta Kappa</DIR>
