<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Employee Benefits Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>Employee Benefits Practice</CENTER></H2>

<P>In the employee benefits area, the  firm has developed a significant practice which covers the
full range of legal issues arising under ERISA, the Internal
Revenue Code, and related laws.  Our clients include corporate,
Taft-Hartley and public plans themselves, as well as their
fiduciaries.  We also serve as counsel to the Association of
Private Pension and Welfare Plans ("APPWP"), the largest
association of private plans, plan sponsors, and consultants in
the United States.  In addition, we represent, on a regular
basis, a wide variety of employer sponsors of corporate and
single employer plans (including several members of the Fortune
100), plan participants and beneficiaries, and insurance
companies, investment advisors, trustees, custodians,
recordkeepers and other services providers to employee benefit
plans.


<P>In connection with these representations, Steptoe & Johnson LLP
provides its clients a full range of advisory services.  The
firm regularly renders advice on such matters as benefits
planning, plan qualification, structuring nonqualified deferred
compensation, plan mergers and terminations, workforce
restruct-urings, fiduciary responsibility, prohibited
transactions, investment policies, withdrawal
liability,legislative developments and compliance with ERISA,
the Internal Revenue Code and other regulatory statutes.  We
prepare plan documents, as well as requests for advisory
opinions, rulings, and exemptive relief from the Department of
Labor, Internal Revenue Service ("IRS") and Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corporation ("PBGC") and regularly appear before those
agencies on behalf of our clients.  We also are frequent
participants in the legislative process, most often in our
capacity as counsel to the APPWP but for other clients as well,
and thus play a role in formulating policy on employee benefit
issues.  Moreover, we are active in the regulatory process,
providing input in structuring new regulations and changing
existing regulations.  We often work with the Treasury
Department and the IRS in attempting to structure workable rules
for implementation of legislative measures, or to modify
existing regulations to accommodate new workplace structures or
new technologies.

<P>Our ability to provide advice and assistance is enhanced by the
fact that, unlike many firms in the employee benefit plan field,
we have an active ERISA litigation practice.  In this area, the
firm has litigated cases involving issues from the most mundane
to the most significant and complex under ERISA and related
statutes.  For example, we successfully represented major
insurance companies before the United States Supreme Court in two
landmark cases involving the scope of remedies under ERISA and
ERISA's preemption of state law:  <U>Massachusetts Mutual Life v. Russell</U>, 473 U.S. 134 (1985) (holding that
punitive and extra-contractual damages generally unavailable
under ERISA); <U>Pilot Life v. Dedeaux</U>, 481 U.S.
41 (1987) (holding that ERISA preempts the state tort of "bad
faith" in the benefits area and provides the exclusive means for
redressing benefit claim matters). 

<P>The firm furthermore represented the PBGC in connection with the
multi-hundred million dollar claims it asserted in the LTV
bankruptcy.  In connection therewith, we assisted the PBGC with
the litigation and ultimate settlement of these claims in the
bankruptcy proceeding.  We also represented the defendant
pension plans in a complex, multi-party action brought by the
Department of Labor and two participant classes that involved
significant investment-related issues under ERISA's fiduciary
responsibility provisions.  In addition, we recently
successfully represented the law firm of Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen
& Katz before the U.S. Tax Court in a major test case brought by
the Internal Revenue Service, involving the actuarial funding
assumptions used for the Wachtell partners' pension plans and,
ultimately, the deductibility of their plan contributions. 
Furthermore, we are currently representing the administrative
committee of an ESOP in an action brought by the Department of
Labor challenging the financial aspects of an employee buy-out
and merger of two companies. 

<P>Other significant cases that the firm has handled have involved
such matters as fiduciary responsibility, prohibited
transactions, retiree medical obligations, and ERISA's
preemption of state law.  This substantial litigation experience
not only assures our clients effective representation in the
event of court action, but also enables us to bring practical
considerations to bear, particularly with respect to the
avoidance of potential liability and exposure, in providing
advice and counsel on planning matters.

<P>The following Steptoe & Johnson LLP partners and of counsel, with
the support of the firm's associate lawyers, paralegals and law
clerks, currently direct the practice of the Employee Benefits
Group:

<h4><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/rhodes.htm">Theodore E. Rhodes</a></CENTER></h4>

<P>Born Los Angeles, California, 1943: LL.M. New York University 1969, Editor, Tax Law Review; J.D.
Hastings College of Law 1968; B.S. Oregon State University 1965;
Attorney Advisor, Office of the Tax Legislative Counsel,
Department of the Treasury, 1973-76; Consultant to
Administrator, Pension and Welfare Benefit Programs, Department
of Labor, 1976-77; general counsel tothe Association of Private
Pension and Welfare Plans; former Chair, Employee Benefits
Committee, ABA Tax Section; currently leader of Steptoe's
Employee Benefits Practice Group.

<h4><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/ondrasik.htm">Paul J. Ondrasik Jr.</a></CENTER></h4>

<P>Born Palmerton, Pennsylvania, 1950: J.D. University of Virginia 1975, Notes Editor, Virginia Law
Review, Order of the Coif; A.B. Princeton University
(Distinction in American Civilization) 1972; law clerk, Chief
Judge Collins J. Seitz, United States Court of Appeals for the
Third Circuit, 1975-76; law clerk, Chief Justice Warren E.
Burger, United States Supreme Court, 1976-77; principal ERISA
attorney in Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Company v.
Russell, and Pilot Life Insurance Company v. Dedeaux before the
United States Supreme Court; Advisory Director, International
Foundation of Employee Benefit Plans.

<h4><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/nussdorf.htm">Melanie F. Nussdorf</a></CENTER></h4>

<P>Born Buffalo, New York, 1949: J.D. New York University 1973; B.A. University of Pennsylvania
1970; Assistant Counsel, Equal Pay and Age Discrimination,
1973-77, and Executive Assistant to Solicitor of Labor, 1977-81,
Office of the Solicitor, Department of Labor; Special Counsel,
Office of the General Counsel, Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corporation, 1981-84.

<h4><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/kohn.htm">Ellen Kohn</a></CENTER></h4>

