<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>J. A. BOUKNIGHT, JR. BIOGRAPHY</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><H3 ALIGN=center>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP</H3><H3 ALIGN=CENTER>J. A. Bouknight, Jr.</H3>
<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/ferc.htm">Energy Law</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/antitrst.htm">Antitrust Law</a> | 
Major Litigation</center></blockquote>

<P>Lon Bouknight is a senior partner in the Washington, D.C. law
firm of Steptoe & Johnson LLP.  He received a B.A. in History
from Wofford College in 1965 and a J.D. degree from Duke
University in 1968.  He has practiced in the electric power and
related fields since 1968.</P>  <P>Mr. Bouknight represents electric
power clients in the full range of regulatory, commercial, and
antitrust matters affecting the industry.  This includes practice
before the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, other federal
agencies, and state commissions, as well as counselling clients
on the transition taking place in the electric power industry. 
It also includes participation in the development of, and
regulatory proceedings pertaining to, power sales and
transmission service contracts and arrangements for joint
ownership and coordination of generation and transmission
facilities.  Mr. Bouknight's experience includes:  Acting as lead
counsel in FERC and antitrust proceedings for the approval of the
proposed mergers of (i) Entergy and Gulf States Utilities, (ii)
Northeast Utilities and Public Service Company of New Hampshire,
and (iii) Southern California Edison Company and San Diego Gas &
Electric Company. Acting as lead counsel for several electric
utilities in proceedings before the FERC concerning the rates,
terms and conditions, and competitive impacts of complex power
supply and transmission service agreements.  Acting as lead
counsel in complex commercial litigation concerning the
construction and operation of electric generating facilities.
Participation in the defense of large electric utilities in
antitrust proceedings in the federal courts and before federal
agencies.  Counseling of electric utilities and independent power
producers concerning positioning themselves for the transition to
a more competitive bulk power market. Counseling of electric
utilities with respect to developing and administering contracts
with qualifying procedures and independent power producers.  He
has been active in the Public Utility Law Section of the American
Bar Association, having served as Chairman of the Section's
Antitrust Committee, and in the Federal Energy Bar Association,
of which he has served as a member of the Board of Directors. 
Mr. Bouknight has authored a number of published articles and
lectured extensively on electric power subjects.</P>

