<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/International Arbitration Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>


<H2><CENTER>International Arbitration Practice</CENTER></H2>



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has a long history of involvement in dispute resolution and
international arbitration on behalf of U.S. and foreign clients.

<P>The firm's excellent reputation for providing service in
international trade and business transactions, its strong
litigation capability, and its expertise on numerous public
international law issues (particularly sovereign immunity, act
of state doctrine, and investment protection) have together
allowed Steptoe to remain one of the premier firms for handling
international commercial disputes.



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have a wide range of experience
before the principal arbitral forums of the world, as advisors,
counsel and members of the arbitrator rosters.  These include
proceedings under the United Nations' UNCITRAL Rules,
party-designed "ad hoc" rules, as well as various
internationally recognized arbitration centers, including the
American Arbitration Association, the International Chamber of
Commerce, the U.S.-Iran Claims Tribunal, the Foreign Trade
Arbitration Commission, the Permanent Court of Arbitration in
the Hague, the Court of Arbitration of the Russian Federation,
the Stockholm Chamber of Commerce, the International Centre for
the Settlement of Investment Disputes, and the U.S.-Canada
Bi-National Free Trade Agreement Panels.



<P>The firm's expertise stems back to the early 1960s, when it was
active in assisting U.S. clients to pursue claims against the
Cuban government after the expropriation of investments by the
Castro regime.  <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/leigh.htm">Monroe Leigh</a>, a former Legal Adviser in the U.S.
State Department, and currently a senior partner in the
international group, was one of the chief architects of the
Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act, the principal U.S. legislation
for pursuing claims against foreign governments.



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP was deeply involved in a number of
arbitrations before the U.S.-Iran Claims Tribunal, located in
the Hague.  The firm successfully represented a large number of
U.S. companies in pursuing contract and investment claims
against the Iranian government.  A number of current partners
were responsible for pursuing the largest private commercial
claim before this Tribunal -- the Oil Consortium Claim,
involving many of the major U.S. petroleum companies and
complicated issues of liability and damage valuation.



<P>The firm's clients in international arbitration matters have
ranged from small companies and individuals to major energy,
banking, construction, defense, and supply companies operating
around the world.  A few additional representative cases include:
<DIR><LI>A major U.S. oil company in an arbitration against the
Government of Libya;
<LI>A large U.S. construction company in an ad hoc UNCITRAL
arbitration against the Egyptian government;<P>
<LI>A producer of medical equipment in connection with settling an
arbitral dispute with the World Bank involving a transaction in
the Russian Federation; <P>

<LI>The Canadian forest industry in a U.S.-Canada binational
proceeding against U.S. lumber manufacturers;<P>
<LI>A major Russian petroleum producer in an ad hoc UNCITRAL
arbitration in Sweden involving a German machinery manufacturer; <P>

<LI>Numerous U.S. energy, engineering and consumer products
companies in connection with filing claims with the U.N. Claims
Commission for damages arising from the Persian Gulf Conflict;<P>
<LI>A political subdivision and ethnic community in connection
with a high-level dispute concerning sovereignty over an island; and<P>
<LI>A major multi-national refiner and chemical producer in
obtaining resolution of its claims for expropriated property
against the Government of Vietnam.</DIR>



<P>The arbitrations handled by Steptoe & Johnson LLP have involved a
full range of complex international and commercial issues,
including nationalization, creeping expropriation, boundary
disputes, governmental breach of contracts, the proper standard
of valuation and compensation, fraudulent credit documents,
non-payment or non-delivery of goods, wrongful death, and
foreign publishing rights.  



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has also advised clients, including U.S.
government agencies and negotiators, on issues ancillary to
international investment protection and dispute resolution.  A
few of the more salient areas where Steptoe's expertise has been
sought out and utilized are:  foreign sovereign immunity and
waivers; enforcement of foreign arbitral and judicial awards;
the law of expropriation and valuation; exhaustion of local
remedies; immunity from suit of international organizations; and
organization and standards of conduct for international arbitral
tribunals.



<P>The firm provides to its clients a comprehensive range of
dispute resolution support, including organizing and marshalling
documentary and testimonial evidence, working with experts and
witnesses, crafting legal arguments based on relevant national
and international law, presentations at hearings, negotiation
and assistance with settlements, and the execution and
enforcement of arbitral awards.



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have written articles, presented
seminars, and published treatises in the area of international
arbitration.  Among the publications are a book-length series of
articles comprehensively analyzing the application of UNCITRAL
Arbitration Rules, a succession of annual reports on the cases
of the Moscow Foreign Trade Arbitration Commission, a treatise
on international economic arbitration, and numerous articles. 
Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have lectured and presented papers
at U.S. and European universities, as well as for the American
Arbitration Association, the Institute of Transnational
Arbitration, and the Moscow Conference on Law and Economic
Relations.



<P>The firm's philosophy and approach in assisting clients is to
develop strategies and methods to avoid disputes at the outset,
and to vigorously represent clients when disputes become
unavoidable.  The firm can assist clients in devising
contractual mechanisms to avoid disputes or to encourage
effective mediation or conciliation prior to arbitration.  Our
experience with actual arbitrations has provided a practical
perspective on how to structure an arbitration agreement in
order to be enforceable and beneficial to the client.  Careful
planning is required to deal with such issues as
unenforceability of an arbitration clause or award, foreign
sovereign immunity defenses, inconsistent local law, and harmful
choice of law.  When pursuing claims on behalf of clients, the
firm's professionals work closely and cooperatively with
in-house counsel and client representatives to achieve the
maximum satisfaction in a cost-efficient manner.


<P>The following Steptoe & Johnson LLP attorneys have had significant
experience representing clients with respect to international
arbitrations.



<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/leigh.htm">Monroe Leigh</a>, Legal Adviser of the Department of State from 1975
to 1977, has directed the presentation of a large number of
arbitration claims on behalf of major multinational companies. 
He has served, at the request of the appointing authority under
the UNCITRAL Rules, as a party-appointed arbitrator in a dispute
arising out of an alleged expropriation and contract breach by a
West African government.  From 1975 to 1980 he was a standing
member of the Permanent Court of Arbitration in The Hague.



<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/baker.htm">Stewart Baker's</a> practice covers international arbitration,
international trade and appellate litigation.  He has handled
the arbitration of claims exceeding one billion dollars.  He is
an organizer of the arbitration programs of the Institute for
Transnational Arbitration and has lectured throughout the world
on arbitration topics.  He is the author of a book on the
UNICITRAL arbitration rules.



<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/olmstead.htm">Cecil J. Olmstead</a> advises with respect to international law and
international trade and investment matters and is a leading
expert in the field of international arbitration.  He has been
involved with numerous arbitrations particularly involving the
nationalization of U.S. oil company development operations in
foreign countries.



<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/hochberg.htm">Sheldon E. Hochberg's</a> arbitration experience includes
representation of a major U.S. oil company in extensive
arbitration with Libya over several years.  This arbitration
involved claims of several million dollars and counterclaims
exceeding one billion.  He has also been involved in other major
international arbitrations involving the oil industry.



<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/krauland.htm">Edward J. Krauland</a> has represented clients in arbitrations
involving a foreign government's breach of military procurement
contracts and expropriation of a U.S. food products company's
foreign affiliate.  He recently represented a Russian petroleum
producer in arbitral proceedings against a German machine
manufacturer.  Mr. Krauland has also represented U.S. clients in
American Arbitration Association proceedings and frequently advises
clients on dispute resolution issues in contractual and
investment transactions.



<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/novick.htm">Robert Novick</a> has represented multinational companies in
complex arbitrations before the Iran-U.S. Claims Tribunal.  The
primary issues included questions of nationalization,
government breach of international contracts, the proper
valuation of expropriated assets, and sovereign immunity.  He
actively participated in preparation of the claims for Iran's
nationalization of oil concessions and counterclaims arising out
of oil company operations in Iran.  He has published on the
subject of sovereign immunity.



<P><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/moran.htm">Mark Moran</a> has assisted in representing petroleum companies in
arbitration proceedings in the Hague.  He has represented a
major U.S. construction company in ad hoc arbitration against a
foreign government under the UNCITRAL rules.  Recently, Mr.
Moran has successfully pursued multiple appeals to the
U.S.-Canada binational panel on a trade dispute involving the
Canadian softwood lumber industry.<p><p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>
