<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/International Transactional Practice Appendix
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>International Transactional Practice Appendix</CENTER></H2>



<P>The following are a sampling of international business transactions in which the firm has
been involved:



<blockquote><i><B><CENTER>Capital Financing Transactions</CENTER></B></i>
<P>The firm represented the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development in connection with its financing of an enhanced digital
telecommunications system for the City of Moscow.  This was
reported to be the first limited recourse project financing
under the newly-enacted Russian Law on Mortgages.  It was the
second project financing in the territory of the former Soviet
Union and the first such project financing since the split of
the Union into its constituent parts.
<P>The firm represented a Canadian corporation in the negotiation
and drafting of the loan and security documents associated with
the extension of a US$140 million revolving line of credit from
an international consortium of banks led by Citicorp USA and
Creditanstalt of Austria.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represented the National Bank for
Cooperatives ("CoBank") in its successful presentation to the
U.S. Commodity Credit Corporation persuading it to make payment
under the U.S. Government's guarantees of certain international
letters of credit in an aggregate principal amount exceeding $75
million.  The Bank had paid U.S. grain exporters for shipments
of grain to the Republic of Iraq on the strength of a note from
Iraq, secured by the Iraqi state bank and guaranteed by the
United States under the Department of Agriculture's export
promotion programs.  The Gulf War prevented payment and the
United States had, for certain technical reasons associated with
the law of international letters of credit, hesitated to make
payment on the guarantees.
<P>The firm has provided advice to Czech Government ministries in
connection with potential project financing matters with
respect to construction of electric infrastructure.
<P>The firm advised an international lending agency in connection
with its guarantee of a loan by a consortium of U.S. and Western
European banks to finance a housing project developed by the
Government of the Ivory Coast.
<P>The firm has represented United States developers in
connection with a certain prospective electrical power project.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represented The Nature Conservancy, a
major U.S. conservation group, in structuring debt-for-nature
swaps to purchase tracts of virgin rain forest throughout Latin
America.  Under the program, management of the purchased tracts
was turned over to local environmental groups.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has represented a major U.S. railroad
company in transactions in connection with the cross-border
leasing of railcars.  These representations have involved
significant tax issues as well as corporate leveraged leasing
issues.
<P>The firm has represented various international airlines in the
negotiation of and drafting of documents associated with
tax-advantaged lease financing transactions.</blockquote>



<blockquote><i><B><CENTER>Acquisitions and Other Investments</CENTER></B></i>
<P>The firm has represented Haka Oy, a major Finnish construction
company, in connection with various actual and potential
investments in the United States.  These have included a project to
construct a downtown mall in an American city, the development
of a major condominium and apartment project in Louisville,
Kentucky financed by the Finnish Export Bank with a guarantee
from the company, the acquisition of a major minority interest
in an American construction and construction management company,
and the negotiation ofconstruction contracts for projects in the
United States.
<P>The firm represented a major Swiss corporation in its
acquisition of a significant minority interest in a leading
international supplier of satellite transmission and
distribution services.  Under the terms of the share purchase
agreement, the Swiss were able to secure special voting rights
and assurance of representation on the Board of Directors.
<P>The firm represented Swissair Air Transport Group in its
strategic alliance with Delta Air Lines.  The transaction
essentially consisted of Swissair's acquisition of $194 million
of the stock of Delta Air Lines and Delta's simultaneous
acquisition of $90 million of Swissair stock, together with related
agreements for the coordination of international schedules and
servicing arrangements.
<P>The firm has advised a major railroad company in connection
with possible strategic partnerships with railroad concerns
around the globe.  This representation has involved
consideration of cross-ownership of stock and mutual service
agreements.
<P>The firm provided representation to a major Canadian utility in connection with
its $76 million investment in an American NYSE company and in
connection with the U.S. financialaspects of its $700 million
sale of two business divisions.
<P>The firm represented Telefonica, S.A., the principal Spanish
telecommunications company, in its acquisition of the Puerto
Rican long distance carrier company.  Steptoe has continued
representation of each company in various matters, particularly
FCC regulatory matters.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represented a major Canadian utility in its
conclusion of strategic investments in the United States heating
and cooling unit manufacturing concerns.
<P>The firm has represented Brazil's leading manufacturer of
agricultural implements in connection with its acquisitions of
several United States companies that manufacturer complementary
product lines.  The transactions involved financing from a
number of Jersey Island trusts.
<P>The firm has represented a Cayman Islands corporation in
structuring its investments in certain United States
pharmaceutical concerns.  This representation has involved,
inter alia, structuring the investment so as to protect the
client from "controlling person" liability under the U.S.
Employee Retirement Income Security Act.

<P>The firm has represented Seikagaku Corporation, a Japanese
pharmaceuticals manufacturer, in its acquisition of a U.S.
company that owned the patent for certain enzymes necessary for the development of drugs to alleviate pain caused
by spinal disc dysfunctions.
<P>The firm has represented IRIDIUM, Inc. before the FCC in its
efforts to develop a global telecommunications system centered
around a fleet of over 70 low orbit satellites.  The
representation has also involved the conduct of due diligence in
connection with the sale of interests in IRIDIUM to strategic
users and telecommunications companies throughout the globe.
<P>The firm provided representation to Cook Industries, a U.S. agricultural
commodities company, in its acquisition of the assets of a
United Kingdom firm in a complementary industry, including real
estate and major equipment facilities in the U.K.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represented an Australian software
manufacturer in its acquisition of a U.S. company with a
complementary product line.  The transaction involved a
negotiation for the purchase of assets as well as the
negotiation of employment agreements for the principals of the
United States concern.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represented Montedison, S.A., an Italian
conglomerate in its proposed acquisition of a major supplier to
the U.S. Department of Defense.  In addition to its
transactional aspects, the representation involved significant
advice concerning national security regulations governing the
acquisition of U.S. government contractors by foreign-controlled
entities.
<P>The firm has represented a manufacturer of components for
military aircraft engines in its acquisition by a multinational
conglomerate.  This has involved consideration of national
security and government contract regulations.
<P>The firm has rendered assistance to a major U.D. defense
contractor in obtaining U.S. government clearances for a
significant foreign stock purchase.</blockquote>

<blockquote><B><i><CENTER>Manufacturing Joint Venture, and Other Operating Agreements</CENTER></i></B>
<P>The firm is representing a U.S. biochemical company in its
negotiations to enter into a co-manufacturing agreement with
Bayer, A.G., one of Germany's largest chemical companies, to
manufacture a patented chemical product in Germany and to market
it throughout the Eastern Hemisphere.
<P>The firm is representing Gulf Canada, a Canadian petroleum
company, in a joint venture to explore and produce petroleum
from Komi Province in Russia.  The project will entail
construction of production, refining, and transportation
facilities.
<P>The firm is representing Teijin Chemical Company, a major
Japanese chemical company, in connection with the negotiation
and drafting of a series of long-term supply and joint venture
agreements with Amoco Chemical Company.  Under the agreements, Amoco would construct a manufacturing facility for a new
chemical component and Teijin would create a manufacturing
facility to use that component in a new, thinner type of video
film.  Teijin would also create a worldwide distribution and
marketing system for the new end-product.
<P>The firm is representing Burlington Northern, a major U.S.
railroad carrier, in the negotiation and drafting of various
agreements to form a joint venture with Grupo Protexa of Mexico.
 The joint venture would establish a train and sea link to
transport points in the U.S. grain belt to Mexico City, where it
would be processed into food products.
<P>The firm represented the interests of the major creditor of
Wheeling-Pittsburgh Corporation, a U.S. steel manufacturer in
bankruptcy, in a joint venture between Wheeling-Pittsburgh and a
Japanese steel company to create a state of the art
manufacturing facility for specialized steel products.
<P>The firm represented Teijin Chemical Company of Japan in the
drafting and negotiation of a series of agreements with The
DuPont Company whereby the parties established a Luxembourg
joint venture to manufacture and market a new type of video
cassette film.  The venture involved the construction of a
manufacturing facility in Luxembourg and the creation of a
distribution and marketing network.
<P>The firm represented a U.S. manufacturing company in the
negotiation and drafting of a long-term nitrate supply and
transportation agreement with a Chilean state-owned mining
company.  The innovative resolution of currency risk and
sovereign immunity issues was of great import in the arrangement.
<P>The firm represented a major international construction
company in a joint venture with an American company to retrofit
Russian railroad tank cars and tankwagons with heating systems
that would facilitate the transportation of liquid products
during the Russian winter.  Apart from technical and
intellectual property issues, the representation has involved
negotiations with international public financing sources.
<P>The firm represented a U.S. chemical company in its
acquisition of 40% of the ownership of a Spanish chemical
manufacturer. Under the terms of a related co-manufacturing
agreement, the parties agreed to expand the capacity of an
existing chemical plant near Barcelona, Spain to produce a
chemical component which is the intellectual property of the
American company.
<P>The firm has represented Los Alamos Technology, Inc. in its
role as prime contractor for the remediation of the health and
environmental damage in the Chernobyl region caused by the 1986
Chernobyl nuclear accident.  This has involved negotiations with
many local and international subcontractors as well as with the
local governmental authorities.
<P>The firm was counsel to a major Brazillian construction and
engineering company in its construction of buildings and
associated infrastructure in Libya.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has represented a French medical device
company in its attempt to introduce into the United States
market a machine that removes fat from patients for aesthetic
purposes without surgical procedures.  This representation has
involved FDA aspects as well as distribution and intellectual
property issues.
<P>The firm has represented a U.S. chemical company in connection
with the creation of its network of distribution agreements
throughout Europe.  This has involved the coordination of U.S.
and EC law with respect to intellectual property and competition
law concerns.
<P>The firm is representing a major U.S. oil company in its
efforts to resume petroleum and natural gas production in
Vietnam.  In addition to representing the client on corporate
transactional matters, the firm is providing advice on certain
federal regulatory issues related the ability of U.S. firms to
conduct business in Vietnam.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has prepared the transactional documents and
assisted in negotiations for several major U.S. or international
companies entering in joint ventures or investing in Eastern
Europe, including Kodak, Honeywell, Merck, the World Bank and
the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
<P>The firm has represented major Russian industrial and defense
concerns in connection with their structuring of privatization
plans and of various joint ventures. </blockquote>

<blockquote><B><i><CENTER>Privatizations</CENTER></i></B>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has represented two major Russian defense
concerns in the process of conversion into non-military product
lines and privatization.  These representations have included
bringing those concerns in contact with prospective investors
from the U.S., assisting in negotiations with them, and advising them on the legal structure of the planned privatization.
<P>At the request of the World Bank, Steptoe & Johnson LLP advised
the Government of Kenya on the modifications to its laws which
are necessary to carry out a program of privatization and
economic reform.  The firm's advice took the form of a detailed
evaluation of economic legislation and recommendations for
changes.  This advice was of particular importance to the
country, because the community of donor countries had
conditioned further financial aid to the country on satisfactory
measures of reform.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP was retained by the agency of the Australian
government that was responsible for selecting a
telecommunications consortium to buy AUSSAT, a hitherto
state-owned satellite company.  After privatization, AUSSAT
would be licensed to compete with Telecom/OTC, the state-owned
telephone company.  The firm drafted certain transactional
documents in connection with the purchase of AUSSAT and provided advice
on the formation of an interconnection policy to govern the
relationship between AUSSAT and Telecom/OTC.
<P>For the government of Tanzania, the firm has developed a
series of comprehensive reports for recommending modifications
to that nation's company, securities and bankruptcy laws.  The
representation focused on changes that would facilitate
privatization of Tanzanian government assets.
<P>The firm has acted as counsel to Fondo de Inveriones, the
privatization agency of Venezuela, in connection with the
privatization of the telephone company, CANTV.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has given advice on issues connected with or
arising from privatizations in several other Latin American and
Caribbean countries, including Columbia (privatization of the
electric energy sector), the Dominican Republic (advice to
Tricom, the new private telephone company competing with the
former monopolist).
<P>The firm advised British Steel on structuring its
privatization so as to ensure compliance with U.S. law on
unfair trade practices.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP provided counsel to the Government of
Argentina on alternative vehicles for restructuring the
Argentine telecommunications sector.  The firm also participated
in a World Bank-sponsored team which worked on the framework of
a regulatory structure to oversee the sector structure
ultimately adopted by the Government.
<P>The firm has represented United States private interests in
their potential investments in previously Soviet
state-controlled businesses such as airport restaurants,
telecommunications services, and port modernization.  In
addition, Steptoe represented U.S. private interests seeking to
invest in the Nahodka Free Trade Zone in defining the terms of
their participation in the Zone, in coordination with local and
national governmental entities.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP was retained by the Compania de Telefonos de
Chile to assist in post-privatization issues which arose just
prior to the economic decline of the Australian entrepreneur who
initially purchased the company from the Government.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP was counsel to a Crown corporation of the
Federal Government of Canada in connection with its
privatization of a uranium manufacturing enterprise.
<P>The firm assisted the Government of Poland in the
privatization of its cellular telephone system.  Recently, the
firm's lawyers advised the Government of Poland on an informal
basis on privatization issues as they prepare additional
legislation to move toward a restructuring of basic services.
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP was retained by Telefonos de Mexico
("TELMEX") to advise on certain aspects of that telephone
company's current privatization.  Our recent advice is legal and
strategic and deals with the legal and regulatory restrictions
of certain U.S. companies in the purchase of foreign telephone companies.
<P>The firm was counsel to the Government of Latvia in connection
with the creation of its national privatization program.</blockquote>
