<html><head><title>Gary J. Rinkerman</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Gary J. Rinkerman</h2>
<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/intellip.htm">Intellectual Property</a></center></blockquote>
<hr>



<P>Gary Rinkerman specializes in the acquisition, protection, licensing and enforcement of intellectual
property rights in domestic and international contexts, as well as antitrust, unfair competition,
business torts, international trade, and private and government contract matters.  Mr. Rinkerman's
experience includes licensing activities in a broad range of technological areas and litigation in the
judiciary and at the United States International Trade Commission, where Mr. Rinkerman has
litigated, e.g., large-scale patent, copyright, trade secret and unfair competition matters.  Mr.
Rinkerman's experience also includes alternative dispute resolution, including arbitration and
mediation.
</P>
<P>Mr. Rinkerman has served as in-house counsel to a major international corporation and as a Senior
Investigative Attorney at the  United States International Trade Commission's Office of Unfair Import
Investigations.  Among his other professional activities is a ten-year term as Editor-in-Chief for the
Computer Law Reporter, an internationally circulated journal devoted to domestic and international
legal issues related to computer technologies.
</P>
<P>Mr. Rinkerman has handled cases involving such diverse issues as the copyrightability of object
code, patent infringement and licensing issues in the areas of optical disc technologies, and
intellectual property ownership issues arising in the course of employer-employee relationships and
government sponsored activities.
</P>
<P>Mr. Rinkerman has authored numerous articles on intellectual property, licensing, and international
trade matters.  He has also lectured extensively in the United States and abroad on matters within
his areas of expertise.
</P>

<p></p><ul><li>Georgetown University
  J.D., 1980
  Nathan Burkan Memorial Award
  ("Moral Rights" of Authors in
  Europe and the United States)
<br>
<li>Rutgers University
