<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Corporate/Securities Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>Corporate/Securities Practice</CENTER></H2>

</B></I>Steptoe &amp; Johnson has an active practice in all areas of corporate/securities transactions, litigation and counseling.  The discussion below highlights particular areas of the firm's corporate/securities practice and summarizes certain recent representations.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Securities Offerings<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Steptoe &amp; Johnson represents issuers, underwriters and investors in public offerings and private placements of securities issued by corporations, partnerships, trusts, pooled investment funds, options funds and other investment vehicles. The firm's recent representations include a $270 million equity offering and a $200 million debt offering on behalf of Burlington Northern, Inc.; an $83 million initial public offering of common stock by BET Holdings, Inc., the parent of Black Entertainment Television; a $140 million public offering of senior secured notes by Inter-City Products Corporation (USA); and a $25 million public offering of common stock by Hooper-Holmes, Inc. <P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Acquisitions, Mergers <P>
and Restructurings<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Steptoe &amp; Johnson represents both purchasers and sellers in stock and asset acquisitions.  The firm recently represented Plaid Holdings Corp. in its acquisition of the men's tailored clothing business of Crystal Brands, Inc. for $50 million; Swissair in its $194 million acquisition of Delta Airlines stock; Haka Oy, a major Finnish construction company, in the acquisition of a major minority interest in a U.S. construction company; Seikaguku Corporation, a Japanese pharmaceuticals manufacturer, in its acquisition of a U.S. company; and Troy Chemical Corporation in its acquisition of 40% of the stock of a Spanish chemical manufacturer.  <P>
<P>
The firm has also represented Inter-City Products as SEC counsel in its sale of two business divisions for $700 million; Advanced Technology, Inc. in its acquisition by Emhart Corporation for $140 million; Computer Entry Systems Corporation in its acquisition by BancTec, Inc. for $42 million; Program Resources, Inc. in its acquisition by Dyncorp; Scitec, Inc. in its acquisition by TRW, Inc.; and CNW Corporation as ICC and special corporate counsel in its acquisition by Blackstone Group for $3.5 billion. <P>
<P>
The firm also counsels corporations involved in recapitalizations, stock repurchase and self-tender offers, exchange offers, reverse mergers, asset dispositions and debt restructuring.  The firm assisted Burlington Northern in a $130 million exchange offer and consent solicitation and a $34 million debt-for-debt swap, and represented Inter-City Products Corporation (USA) in the negotiation of a $135 million purchase facility from an international consortium of banks as part of a refinancing transaction.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Commercial Financing<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Steptoe &amp; Johnson represents lenders, borrowers and other participants in commercial financing transactions.  The firm provides advice in project financing, equipment financing, international financing, nonstandard collateral financing, agricultural financing, construction financing, real estate financing, leveraged sale-leaseback transactions and interest and usury issues.  <P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson frequently represents parties in the financing of electric power generation and other utility facilities through venture capital as well as taxable and tax-exempt revenue bond offerings and the refinancing and restructuring of long-term utility debt through registered public securities offerings and private placements.  For example, Steptoe &amp; Johnson structured the refinancing by rural electric utilities of $1.7 billion in long-term, fixed-rate Federal Financing Bank loans with private loans guaranteed by the United States.<P>
<P>
The firm also has a special expertise in the leveraged leasing area, including the sale and leaseback of electric generating facilities, transportation facilities, computer equipment, and construction, manufacturing and business equipment.  Two recent representations include the sale-leaseback of a $625 million lignite-fired, steam electric unit and the sale-leaseback of a $190 million partial interest in a coal-fired steam electric generating station.<P>
<P>
The firm has also represented several publicly - owned venture capital companies that provide financing to new and emerging companies throughout the United States.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Joint Ventures<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Steptoe &amp; Johnson is actively involved in assisting U.S. and foreign clients to establish joint ventures. For example, the firm has represented Kodak, Honeywell, Merck, the World Bank and the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development in connection with joint ventures or investments in Eastern Europe, and has represented Teijin Chemical Company (Japan) in the negotiation of joint venture agreements with U.S. chemical companies.  The firm also represents U.S. and foreign clients entering into manufacturing, supply, distribution and operating agreements.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Securities Litigation<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Steptoe &amp; Johnson litigates securities cases in federal and state courts nationwide. <P>
<P>
The firm has an active securities fraud litigation practice, and has represented defendants in several major consolidated securities fraud class actions, including the Drexel Burnham litigation and the Bolar Pharmaceutical litigation in New York.  The firm currently represents a major bank holding company in a class action brought by a former shareholder of an acquired bank.<P>
<P>
The firm has also represented clients in litigation involving such issues as lender liability and enforcement of stock conversion rights and represents the litigation committee of the board of directors of a publicly traded company in several shareholder derivative actions. <P>
<P>
The firm has developed a special expertise in representing lawyers and law firms accused of negligent or intentional participation in frauds relating to securities offerings, ranging from private placements of limited partnership interests to public municipal bond offerings.  <P>
<P>
Finally, Steptoe &amp; Johnson counsels and represents takeover targets,<P>
shareholder groups, prospective acquirors and independent directors in proxy contests and battles for corporate control, developing and executing both offensive and defensive measures.  <P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Securities and Exchange <P>
Commission Proceedings<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Steptoe &amp; Johnson defends companies and individuals in SEC investigations, civil enforcement actions and administrative proceedings relating to alleged breaches of the federal securities laws.  The firm has recently represented NYSE companies in SEC investigations relating to adequacy of corporate disclosures and accounting issues, corporate officers accused of financial fraud and insider trading, and investors who were allegedly &quot;tippees&quot; of inside information regarding material corporate events. The firm also represents clients in NASD enforcement proceedings.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Internal Corporate Investigations<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>The firm conducts internal investigations on behalf of corporations regarding potential financial fraud and/or self-dealing by corporate officers and advises corporations regarding related federal securities law disclosure obligations.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>White-Collar Practice<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Because securities fraud litigation and SEC proceedings may have criminal implications, one of Steptoe &amp; Johnson's special advantages in these areas is our strong expertise in white-collar crime.  A former federal prosecutor heads the firm's white-collar practice.  He has substantial experience in defending corporations and individuals in white-collar criminal investigations involving securities and RICO allegations.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Financial Institutions<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>The firm is actively involved in the financial institutions area.  The firm assists clients with mergers, acquisitions and changes in control of financial institutions and counsels financial institutions and their officers and directors in regulatory compliance and enforcement matters.  The firm has served as counsel to Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation and Resolution Trust Corporation on a wide range of counseling and transactional matters and represented both FDIC and RTC in litigation.  The firm represented RTC in connection with formation of several private/governmental partnerships and their acquisition of $1.28 billion and $450 million portfolios of real estate and real estate related loans. <P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Counseling<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>The firm advises clients on a broad range of corporate/securities issues, including all aspects of compliance with federal and state securities laws and state corporate laws.  Recent issues the firm has addressed include resales of restricted securities, disclosure of material corporate events, fiduciary obligations of directors, insider reporting obligations under Section 16 of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, and proxy requirements relating to executive compensation and shareholder communications.  The firm has expertise under all federal securities statutes, including the Investment Company Act and the Investment Advisers Act.  The firm also negotiates, prepares and reviews all types of corporate and commercial contracts.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Arbitration<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>The firm conducts an active practice in the area of arbitration of securities transactions.  We represent broker-dealers against claims brought by their customers in binding NASD arbitration proceedings, and several of our partners have served as arbitrators in proceedings for the NASD, the American Arbitration Association and the Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Corporate/Securities Partners<P>
</CENTER><P>
</B>Steptoe &amp; Johnson has a strong group of partners with substantial experience in the corporate/ securities area.  Several of these partners have previously served in various capacities at the Securities and Exchange Commission. <P>
<P>

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/cobb.htm">Calvin Cobb</a></center>

<P>Mr. Cobb, the firm's most senior corporate/securities partner, has represented clients in a broad range of corporate and securities transactions, including mergers and acquisitions and public and private sales of securities.  He also frequently serves as counsel in corporate and securities adversary proceedings (trial and appellate litigation, arbitration, SEC administrative), including, for example, hostile takeovers, proxy contests, securities fraud, broker/dealer and investment company compliance cases, and corporate reorganizations.  Mr. Cobb received a B.S. degree with distinction from the United
States Naval Academy and a LL.B from Georgetown University, where he served as leading articles editor of the Georgetown Law Journal.

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/mclaughl.htm">Robert E. McLaughlin</a></center>

<P>MR. McLaughlin has extensive experience in securities regulation and general corporate matters, including mergers, acquisitions, financings and venture capital and real estate transactions.  Before coming to Steptoe & Johnson LLP, Mr.
McLaughlin served first as a financial analyst and later as an Attorney Adviser in the Division of Corporate Finance at the SEC.  He also serves as a public arbitrator for the NASD.  He is a member of the Small Business Committee of the ABA's Section of Corporation, Banking and Business Law and currently serves as
Chairman of its Subcommittee on Financing.  He is also a member of the Board of Directors of Attorney Liability Assurance Society(Bermuda), Ltd, a lawyer-owned professional liability insurance company, and serves as Chairman of its Investments Committee.  Mr. McLaughlin received a B.S. from Iowa State University and a J.D. from Georgetown University.  

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/quinn.htm">Terence P. Quinn</a></center>
<P>Mr. Quinn's practice encompasses securities offerings, venture capital financing, mergers and acquisitions, corporate restructuring and business planning.  Mr. Quinn worked at the SEC for seven years before coming to Steptoe & Johnson LLP, serving in his last year at the Commission as Branch Chief in the Division of Corporation Finance.  Mr. Quinn received a B.S. from Iowa State University and a J.D. from American University.

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/collins.htm">John T. Collins</a></center>

<P>Mr. Collins counsels depository institutions, securities firms and insurance companies on regulatory, enforcement and structural issues.  Before joining Steptoe & Johnson LLP, Mr. Collins served as General Counsel to the U.S. Senate Banking Committee, a senior attorney in the Legal Division of the Federal Reserve Board, and a staff attorney in the Division of
Market Regulation of the SEC.  Mr. Collins received a B.A. from Holy Cross, and a J.D. and LL.M. in taxation from Georgetown University.

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/d'alelio.htm">Ellen d'Alelio</a></center>

<P>Ms. d'Alelio specializes in transactions and litigation involving financial services, commercial real estate and related corporate law matters.  She counsels financial institutions and their officers and directors in regulatory compliance and enforcement matters, and assists clients with acquisitions, and changes in control of financial institutions.  She has represented both FDIC and RTC in transactions and litigation.  Ms. d'Alelio received a B.A. from St. Mary's College magna cum laude and studied in France as a Fulbright Scholar after college.  She earned an M.A. from New York University and a J.D. from Harvard University.

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/weingart.htm">Reid M. Weingarten</a></center>

<P>Mr. Weingarten's representations include complex criminal matters at the pre-trial, trial and post-trial stages, including cases involving RICO, bank fraud, bribery, government procurement fraud, tax and securities matters.  In addition, Mr. Weingarten has served as Chief Counsel of the Senate "October Surprise" investigation and as a Deputy Independent Counsel in the Iran-Contra investigation.  Before coming to Steptoe & Johnson LLP, Mr. Weingarten was a prosecutor in the Public Integrity Section of the Department of Justice.  Mr. Weingarten received a
B.S. from Cornell University and a J.D. from Dickinson Law School.

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/martin.htm">William L. Martin II</a></center>

<P>Mr. Martin practices principally in the areas of securities litigation and SEC enforcement.  Mr. Martin served as a staff attorney and later as Special Counsel in the SEC's Division of Enforcement.  Mr. Martin received a B.A. summa cum laude from the University of New Mexico, an M.B.A. from Stanford University, and a J.D. from Georgetown University.

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/agusti.htm">Filiberto Agusti</a></center>

<P>Mr. Agusti represents major business lenders, equity investors, and other participants in complex commercial financing transactions.  These have included project financing and leveraged leasing of electric generating stations and other substantial facilities, U.S. government guaranteed refinancings, loan asset-backed public debt offerings, corporate acquisition financing, and international venture financing.  He has also negotiated agreements in several nationally significant workouts and reorganizations.  Mr. Agusti received a B.A. summa cum laude from the University of Illinois and a J.D. from Harvard University, where he served as an editor of the Harvard Law
Review.

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/koegel.htm">J. William Koegel</a></center>

<P>Mr. Koegel's practice centers on the litigation of complex cases.  His cases have involved business torts, breach of contract, the Uniform Commercial Code, civil securities fraud, RICO, directors' and officers' liability, employment discrimination, libel & slander and professional malpractice. He has experience in a variety of criminal investigations, and
has represented clients in Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, government procurement fraud, securities, tax and bank fraud, Ethics in Government Act, criminal environmental bribery, and criminal antitrust matters.  Mr. Koegel received a B.A. cum laude from Northwestern University and a J.D. cum laude from Boston College Law School, where he served as an editor of the Boston College Law Review.

<P><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/kitchen.htm">Erik L. Kitchen</a></center>

<P>Mr. Kitchen represents clients in civil securities lawsuits, SEC enforcement proceedings, internal corporate investigations, and acquisitions and other corporate transactions.  Mr. Kitchen also counsels clients on a broad range of securities, corporate and Foreign Corrupt Practices Act (FCPA) issues. Mr. Kitchen received a B.A. <U>magna cum laude</U> from Princeton University and a J.D. <U>cum laude</U> from Harvard University.<P>
<P><Center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/katz.htm><B>Scott H. Katzman </B></a></center>
<P>Mr. Katz specializes in complex corporate finance, public finance, and commercial transactions.  These transactions include public and private debt and equity offerings, project financings, lease financings, municipal securities offerings, refinancings of government guaranteed debt, and asset-backed financings.  Mr. Katzman provides general corporate and commercial advice to numerous corporations. He also provides advice in restructuring troubled real estate loans and complex settlements in the bankruptcy context. Mr. Katzman received a B.S. from Cornell University and a J.D. from Columbia University, where he served as an editor of the <U>Columbia Journal of Law and Social Problems</U>.<P>
