<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/International Trade and Customs Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>International Trade and Customs Practice</CENTER></H2>



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has more than 35 attorneys working full-time in the international
area.  The firm represents both domestic and foreign clients. 
Many of the firm's attorneys have held senior positions in the
Executive Branch including the Departments of State, Commerce,
Justice, Treasury and Defense.  Others have served as advisors
on trade issues to various Federal agencies and to Congressional
Committees.  The main areas of the firm's trade expertise are
outlined below.





<h4><CENTER>Trade and Customs Cases Before the Executive Branch Agencies and
Judicial Trade Litigation</CENTER></h4>


<P>For more than four decades, Steptoe & Johnson LLP has represented
both domestic and foreign clients in all major forms of trade
litigation and administrative investigations.  These cases
involve investigations and litigation before the Treasury
Department, the U.S. Customs Service, the U.S. Commerce
Department, the International Trade Commission and the U.S.
Trade Representative's Office.  They also have included grand
jury investigations and judicial appeals to the U.S. Court of
International Trade, the Federal Circuit Court of Appeals, and
bi-national panels under the Canada-United States Free Trade
Agreement.  Below is a summary of the firm's practice in the
last five years.



<H4><CENTER>Antidumping/Countervailing Duty Cases</CENTER></H4>
<P>The firm has represented
both foreign and domestic clients in over 90 antidumping and
countervailing duty cases.



<H4><CENTER>Section 201 (Escape Clause) and 301 Cases</CENTER></H4>
<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP
has been involved in over half of the Section 201 cases filed
with the International Trade Commission.  The firm has
represented and advised clients in connection with more than a
dozen Section 301 cases.



<H4><CENTER>Customs Cases</CENTER></H4>
<P>The firm has represented numerous companies and
industries before the Customs Service and the Treasury
Department in matters involving a wide variety of issues such as
classification, country of origin and duty preference programs
and Section 592 penalty investigations.  



<H4><CENTER>Litigation Before the U.S. Court of International Trade and
Federal Circuit Court of Appeals</CENTER></H4>
<P>The firm regularly represents
clients in appeals from antidumping and countervailing duty
cases before these two courts.



<H4><CENTER>Import-Related Antitrust Action</CENTER></H4>
<P>The firm has represented
clients in both civil and criminal investigations of alleged
price-fixing of imports. 



<h4><CENTER>Customs Matters</CENTER></h4>



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has advised a wide range of domestic and
foreign clients regarding compliance with the increasingly
complex Customs regulatory regime.  Steptoe & Johnson LLP also has
represented such clients before the U.S. Customs Service and the
Treasury Department on a variety of matters, including:
<DIR><LI>Administrative rulings, protests and judicial review of Customs actions<P>
<LI>Customs Modernization Act, Customs compliance and Customs audits<P>
<LI>Classification under the Harmonized Tariff System<P>
<LI>Valuation -- assists, nondutiable charges, basis for valuation <P>
<LI>Country of origin -- substantial transformation<P>
<LI>Duty preference programs<P>
<LI>NAFTA<P>
<LI>Generalized System of Preferences<P>

<LI>Caribbean Basin Initiative<P>
<LI>American goods returned<P>
<LI>Marking requirements<P>
<LI>Fines and penalties -- 1592 investigations and prior disclosures<P>
<LI>Customs seizures<P>
<LI>Customs administration of quotas and AD/CVD orders<P>
<LI>Foreign trade zones and temporary in bond importations<P>

<LI>Drawback</DIR>





<h4><CENTER>Export Matters</CENTER></h4>



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represents clients in a wide range of matters
concerning the regulatory environment affecting U.S. exports and
negotiates and arranges commercial transactions.


<P>The following are major export-related matters the firm has
recently been involved in:
<DIR><LI>amendments to the Export Administration Act;<P>
<LI>advice and assistance to companies in obtaining licenses for
the export and re-export of goods, services and technology;<P>
<LI>advice concerning the jurisdictional reach of U.S. export
control laws;<P>
<LI>representation in connection with compliance and enforcement
of export control and anti-boycott laws;<P>
<LI>advice on structuring internal corporate operations to
ensure compliance with export control requirements; and<P>
<LI>representation and advice to companies on compliance with U.S.
sanctions issued under the Trading with the Enemy Act and IEEPA</DIR>




<h4><CENTER>Development of Trade Strategies for Operating Effectively in the
U.S. Domestic and Foreign Markets</CENTER></h4>



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP has advised a wide range of foreign and
domestic clients on how to cope with the increasingly complex
regulatory, legislative, political and legal environment in the
United States and overseas.  In this connection, Steptoe &
Johnson LLP has provided the  following kinds of services:
<DIR><LI>counseling on the regulatory requirements in the trade,
customs and investment areas;<P>
<LI>formulating corporate and marketing strategies for dealing
with international competition and succeeding in international
markets;<P>
<LI>developing legislative strategies for dealing with trade,
customs and investment matters;<P>
<LI>developing strategies for seeking to affect Executive Branch
decisions regarding trade, customs and investment;<P>
<LI>advising clients on negotiating strategies with respect to
international agreements, including the GATT multilateral trade
negotiations, the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement, the NAFTA,
bi-lateral investment treaties (BITs) and negotiations on market
issues, investment subsidies and intellectual property;<P>
<LI>representing clients in connection with the negotiation and
notification of trade and investment treaties;<P>
<LI>representing clients concerned with UNCTAD and OECD codes of
conduct;<P>
<LI>representing clients concerned with bilateral trade
negotiations concerning a variety of sectors and countries; and<P>
<LI>advising on application of law affecting investment both in
the United States and abroad and on the transfer of technology.</DIR>



<h4><CENTER>Representation Regarding Trade Policy Issues and Legislation
Before the Executive Branch and the Congress</CENTER></h4>


<P>A major part of Steptoe & Johnson LLP's international practice
concerns advice and representation on international matters
involving the Executive Branch, trade agencies, or the Congress. 
This activity includes advice on pending legal and political
issues, efforts to influence policy and legislation on behalf of
client interests, and, in some instances, simply monitoring, on
an ongoing basis, recent developments in particular areas of
trade.



<P>The firm has represented clients recently in connection with the
following legislation:
<DIR><LI>Export Administration Act<P>
<LI>Export Trading Company Act<P>
<LI>Foreign Corrupt Practices Act<P>
<LI>Foreign Sales Corporation Act<P>
<LI>The Trade Acts of 1979, 1984 and 1988<P>
<LI>The Canada-U.S. Free Trade Agreement Implementation Act<P>
<LI>NAFTA Implementation Act</DIR>



<P>In addition, we have provided advice to agricultural, chemical,
paper and natural resource companies in connection with
legislative proposals affecting trade.  We have also recently
advised companies on legislative proposals for change in the
non-market economy provisions of the antidumping and
countervailing duty laws.





<h4><CENTER>Negotiation of International Commercial and Investment Arrangements</CENTER></h4>



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP represents both domestic and foreign clients
in negotiating major commercial and investment transactions.  In
this context, we represent private parties in negotiating and
drafting contractual terms and advising on the legal and
commercial environment.  More specifically, we have been engaged
in negotiating the following:
<DIR><LI>international commercial sales contracts;<P>
<LI>acquisition, merger and investment arrangements involving
foreign parties;<P>
<LI>licensing arrangements between United States and foreign
parties involving transfer of various intellectual property
rights;<P>
<LI>formation of United States-foreign joint ventures;<P>
<LI>technology transfer agreements; and<P>
<LI>transactions in Russia through firm's Moscow Office.</dir>



<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP provides legal advice to serve the entire
range of needs of clients doing business in or located in the
United States.  Our expertise includes, among other areas,
taxation, labor and employment law, immigration law, government contracts, corporate and securities law, and federal and state regulation.


<H4>
<CENTER>Countertrade</CENTER></H4>
<P>Representation of companies in countertrade
arrangements, including advice regarding the implications of
such arrangements under U.S. trade law.



<H4><CENTER>Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act</CENTER></H4>
<P>Representation of various
interests in federal courts concerning suits involving foreign
sovereign entities.



<H4><CENTER>Foreign Corrupt Practices Act</CENTER></H4>
<P>Advice concerning compliance
programs for companies operating abroad and subject to the FCPA. 



<H4><CENTER>P.L. 480</CENTER></H4>
<P>Advice to clients re compliance with the terms of
P.L. 480 in the export of grain shipments.



<H4><CENTER>Export of Defense Articles</CENTER></H4>
<P>Assistance to companies seeking to
export high technology equipment governed by the Munitions
Control Regulations and other export control regimes.



<H4><CENTER>Petroleum</CENTER></H4>
<P>Advice on establishing, maintaining, and terminating
petroleum development contracts in oil exporting countries.





<H4><CENTER>Actions Under Foreign Trade Laws</CENTER></H4>
<P>Representation of U.S.
companies or their foreign subsidiaries in proceedings under the
trade laws of various foreign countries.<p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>
