<HTML><TITLE>Steptoe & Johnson LLP/Technology Practice</TITLE>
<BODY>

<H3><CENTER>Steptoe &amp; Johnson LLP </H3>
<H2>Technology Practice </H2>
</CENTER>As an outgrowth of Steptoe &amp; Johnson's cutting-edge practice in the fields of computer technology, telecommunications, and financial services, and extensive experience with intellectual property, antitrust, and corporate law issues, our firm has developed a thriving practice counselling innovative high-technology companies on all aspects of their operations.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Digital Commerce</B> <P>
</CENTER><P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson represents leading financial services and information services firms on all legal matters relating to their new services. The firm has counselled these service providers on potential liability to customers, cooperation with law enforcement, and the wide array of general commercial and intellectual property matters that arise when a new service is introduced.<P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson has developed both legal and technical expertise in data encryption technology, the application of which is considered essential to providing reliable and confidential communications over the Global Information Infrastructure (GII). The firm has counselled companies providing encryption and electronic payment services on regulatory, legislative, and corporate contractual matters.<P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson also represents clients in the procurement, licensing, and enforcement of patents relating to many facets of digitally-encoded optical disc technology. The firm's patent attorneys provide these clients with a full range of intellectual property services, including preparation and prosecution of patent applications, appellate and interference practice before the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office, preparation of patent validity, enforceability, and infringement opinions, preparation of licensing agreements, counselling on potential antitrust issues related to the prosecution and licensing of patents and the maintenance of patent portfolios, and initiation and defense of litigation in the federal courts and before the U.S. International Trade Commission.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Computer Law<P>
</CENTER></B> <P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson has represented computer hardware and software companies on a range of commercial and regulatory matters. The firm's lawyers have drafted and negotiated complex software development and distribution agreements, as well as standard and specialized vendor and end-user agreements for software firms in the financial, communications, and data processing industries. Steptoe &amp; Johnson has also frequently drafted technology license agreements for U.S. high technology companies forming joint ventures with foreign partners.<P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson has extensive experience in the area of government contracts related to computer technology. The firm's attorneys have drafted and negotiated computer- related Cooperative Research and Development Agreements (&quot;CRADAs&quot;) and work for other represented government contractors providing computer equipment and services to the U.S. government.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Telecommunications<P>
</CENTER></B> <P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson's communications practice is in the forefront of the rapid evolution of new technologies, services, investment strategies, and ideas. Steptoe &amp; Johnson attorneys represent major telecommunications companies in the developing areas of personal wireless communications, low earth orbit mobile satellite services, direct broadcast satellite services, and fiber optic cable systems. Steptoe also regularly advises clients on complicated legal and policy issues arising from the development of the GII. Steptoe &amp; Johnson recently has begun to advise electric utilities on a range of communications issues, as these companies develop strategies for entering the communications market. <P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson has extensive experience representing clients in international telecommunications matters. Our experience includes the entry of foreign- owned carriers into the U.S. communications market; privatization of government-owned telecommunications entities; international trade issues involving communications services and equipment; access into foreign telecommunications markets and efforts to influence the structure of foreign and international telecommunications markets. Steptoe &amp; Johnson regularly advises clients on issues relating to telecommunications investment and regulations in foreign countries as well as regulation of telecommunications by international organizations.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/finserv.htm>Financial Services</a></B> <P>
</CENTER><P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson has a diverse financial services practice designed to meet the needs of clients in the evolving financial services marketplace. Our attorneys represent financial institutions and other participants in the industry on regulatory, legislative, corporate and transactional matters, as well as in litigation. We are well versed in electronic commerce generally and in &quot;cyberbanking&quot; matters such as stored value cards, smart cards, digital cash and on-line banking, and have represented clients in the areas of electronic fund transfers, financial data processing systems, electronic banking and payment system issues, and system security and data encryption matters.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/intellip.htm">Intellectual Property</a></B> <P>
</CENTER><P>
A team of Steptoe &amp; Johnson attorneys specializes in the practice of intellectual property law for a broad range of general corporate clients, as well as clients in the defense, computer, optical disc, and data encryption technology industries. Steptoe &amp; Johnson's expertise includes litigation and in-depth counselling on patent, copyright, trademark, trade dress, trade secret, and associated antitrust issues, as well as the special issues that arise in the protection and dissemination of computer software, computer network services, and other high-tech products. Also available is the prosecution of patent, copyright, and trademark applications, as well as representation and support in licensing of those intellectual properties. Steptoe &amp; Johnson attorneys assist in identifying intellectual property and exploiting it through creative agreements, and represent clients in infringement and other litigation in judicial, administrative, and alternative dispute resolution proceedings.<P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson lawyers have drafted and negotiated a wide range of licenses for patented and unpatented technologies, other types of technology transfers, and service arrangements. Our lawyers are experienced in negotiating license agreements between private companies and the U.S. government and its affiliated research laboratories.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/corpsecu.htm">General Corporate</a></B> <P>
</CENTER><P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson has an active practice in all areas of corporate transactions, litigation and counseling.<P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson has represented issuers, underwriters and investors in public offerings and private placements of securities issued by high-technology corporations. The firm's recent representations include an initial public offering of common stock by a major cable entertainment company. <P>
<P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson also has an active practice in the mergers and acquisition of high technology companies. The firm has represented Advanced Technology, Inc. in its acquisition by Emhart Corporation; Computer Entry Systems Corporation in its acquisition by BancTec, Inc.; Program Resources, Inc. in its acquisition by Dyncorp; and Scitec, Inc. in its acquisition by TRW, Inc. <P>
<P>
<CENTER><B><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/taxprac.htm">Taxation</a></B> <P>
</CENTER><P>
In the course of rendering the services recounted above, the firm has provided clients with tax advice concerning the most advantageous ways to structure investments and business operations. With respect to international activities, this has included establishing Foreign Sales Corporations, deferring current taxation of income, and maximizing the availability of foreign tax credits. We have helped structure license agreements, joint ventures, and other technology transfer arrangements to minimize U.S. and foreign tax burdens. Our tax specialists keep closely abreast of developments in Washington so as to advise clients of the tax, legislative and regulatory climate that may affect their transactions.<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Practice Group Profiles</B> <P>
</CENTER><P>
<B>Stewart Baker</B> , former General Counsel of the National Security Agency, has an international practice that includes counseling high technology companies on commercial and government relations matters. He has extensive experience with export controls imposed on various high-technology products that incorporate encryption. Mr. Baker has frequently testified before Senate and House committees on issues relating to encryption, international trade, foreign affairs and national security.<P>
<P>
<B>Phil Malet</B> has an active practice in communications law. He has represented domestic and international satellite providers, including low-earth orbit satellite systems, undersea fiber optic cable companies, cellular radio operators and manufacturers, corporate telecommunications users, pay telephone companies, and broadcast licensees. Mr. Malet has advised cable companies and municipalities on regulatory matters affecting cable television, and has negotiated major construction contracts for cable systems and programmers. In addition, he advises companies on developments in U.S. telecommunications policy. <P>
<P>
<B>Alfred Mamlet's</B> practice centers on communications, computer and litigation matters. His practice includes advising international and domestic telephone, cable, and satellite companies. Mr. Mamlet regularly counsels clients on contractual, intellectual property, privacy and liability issues. He currently chairs the National Information Infrastructure Committee of the American Bar Association's Science and Technology Section.<P>
<P>
<B>Ellen d'Alelio's</B> financial institutions practice encompasses transactions, regulatory matters and litigation involving banking organizations. As technological advances have transformed banking operations and commerce, she has devoted an increasing part of her practice to electronic banking matters. She serves on the editorial board of THE ELECTRONIC BANKING LAW AND COMMERCE REPORT as well as on a number of professional and bar association committees dealing with the commercial, regulatory, and technological issues affecting electronic banking products, services and operations. She speaks and writes regularly on the application of federal and state law to emerging electronic banking developments.<P>
<P>
<B>John Collins</B> counsels banking and other financial organizations on regulatory, structural and legislative issues. He has advised and represented clients in connection with bank applications and acquisition transactions, Federal bank agency rulings, legislative amendments and the application of banking laws to payment system matters and electronic cash technologies. Mr. Collins has taught a banking law course at Georgetown Law School for a number of years. He speaks regularly on banking issues and is a member of bar committees involved in developing standards and guidance in electronic banking matters.<P>
<P>
<B>Maureen Ward's</B> practice centers on the protection and licensing of intellectual property, with special emphasis on computer systems and software, trademarks, technology licensing, literary publication contracts and television production contracts. Ms. Ward also litigates intellectual property infringement and other types of business disputes and provides product liability counseling. <P>
<P>
<B>Frederick Frei</B> has a broad range of experience in litigation, licensing, and counseling clients in the areas of patents, trademarks, copyrights, trade secrets and antitrust and trade regulation. He has represented clients 
</DOC>
