<HTML><TITLE>Steptoe & Johnson LLP/Transportation (Railroad)</TITLE>
<BODY>

<P>
<CENTER><B><H3>                                                                                                                                         <P>
	Steptoe &amp; Johnson LLP
</H3></B></CENTER><P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER></B><h2>Railroad Transportation<P>
</H2></B></CENTER><P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson has a distinguished practice in the area of railroad transportation.  Led by Betty Jo Christian, former Vice-Chairman of the Interstate Commerce Commission and Edmund Burke, former Executive Vice President Law and Government Affairs of Burlington Northern Railroad, a multi-talented team of Steptoe transportation lawyers regularly represents or counsels major railroads, regional and short-line carriers, start-up carriers, shippers, ports, state governments and other transportation players.  We practice extensively before the Surface Transportation Board, the Department of Transportation, federal district courts and courts of appeals, state appellate courts and the Supreme Court.  Steptoe attorneys have been prominently involved in many of the agency and court proceedings that have shaped the railroad industry since the Staggers Act of 1980.  Our expertise spans such areas of transportation law as economic and rate regulation, contract litigation and arbitration, antitrust, railway labor and employer liability matters, safety and drug testing.   Our clients prize our knowledge of the industry's economic and competitive characteristics.  This knowledge has enabled us to obtain favorable results for our clients in regulatory and other contexts involving complex economic issues.<P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Economic Regulation<P>
</CENTER></B><P>
<B><I>Rail transactions</I>.</B>  Our experience runs through the entire range of transactions requiring Board approval -- from mergers or consolidations between major railroads through short line sales to abandonment and construction projects.  We recently represented Burlington Northern in its successful effort to obtain the approval of the former Interstate Commerce Commission for its consolidation with Santa Fe -- the largest railroad transaction ever to have been approved by the Commission.  We guided BN through a multi-month merger proceeding that involved thousands of pages of economic testimony and dozens of protesting parties.  In that process, we successfully opposed most of the requests made by those parties for the imposition of burdensome conditions on the transaction.  We have also participated in most other significant rail merger proceedings of recent years, such as the acquisitions by Union Pacific of Chicago &amp; North Western (in 1995) and Missouri-Kansas-Texas (in 1988).  In the latter proceeding, we helped a short-line railroad obtain a major concession from the merger applicants.  In 1989, we obtained Commission exemption for the acquisition of CNW by Blackstone Capital Partners, after CNW had fought off one of the few hostile takeover attempts in the history of the industry.<P>
<P>
<B><I>Short lines.</B></I>  We have been active in the vibrant area of short line sales.  We have participated in major line sale programs, such as the sale of substantial parts of Illinois Central's network in the 1980s.  More recently, we have participated in the regulatory review of the Alameda Corridor transit project. We have made new law in the area of trackage rights that accompany a line sale and have developed specialized expertise in the area of labor protection, where the law has changed dramatically with the ICC Termination Act of 1995. We regularly advise short-line railroads on the structure of line sales, leases, trackage and operating agreements.<P>
<P>
<B><I>Trackage compensation.</B></I>  We have a thorough understanding of the complex methods for determining the rental due for the use of one railroad's tracks by another railroad.  We have advised several clients, including most recently a state-owned entity leasing its line to a major railroad, on these complex methods.<P>
<P>
<B><I>Line construction and abandonment.</B></I>  We have obtained approval for several construction projects and assisted in the process of environmental review necessary for these projects.  We have made new law on the question of a railroad's authority to build a line that crosses another rail line.  We have represented both shippers and railroads in abandonment proceedings.  Recently, we vigorously contested on behalf of a shipper the abandonment of a rail line that provided the only rail service to a major plant in Maine.  This made possible a negotiated solution that preserved rail service to the plant.  <P>
<P>
<B><I>Rate proceedings.</B></I>  We have participated in most major rate proceedings since the Staggers Act and are currently representing 26 rail carriers in a multiple-defendant rate proceeding before the STB.  Through those proceedings, we have gained a firm command of the intricacies of the market dominance concept that triggers STB rate reasonableness jurisdiction and the extremely complicated constrained market pricing standard and &quot;stand-alone cost&quot; methodology that is used by the Board to evaluate rate reasonableness.  We successfully challenged the Commission's use of a rate standard other than constrained market pricing in a major case before the court of appeals, and also successfully challenged the authority of the ICC or STB to order a railroad to publish a tariff prior to a shipper's actual need for the transportation.  <P>
<P>
<B><I>Rulemaking Proceedings.</B></I>  We have taken a leading role in representing the railroad industry in numerous agency rulemaking proceedings, such as those involving car hire rules and rate reasonableness standards.  Our in-depth knowledge of the industry and our familiarity with ICC and STB policy are particularly valuable to clients in this type of policy-making context.  <P>
<P>
<B><I>The ICC Termination Act of 1995.</B></I>  We have pioneered the analysis of the many important changes brought about by the 1995 ICCTA.  Attorneys in our Transportation Group prepared an overview and section-by-section analysis of the ICCTA which was distributed by a major transportation organization to all of its members, and we have been actively involved in speaking and writing about the new statute.  In addition to counseling clients on the implications of the new Act for railroad activities and the structure of rail transactions, we recently obtained a landmark decision from a state appellate court ruling that all state regulation of matters such as agency closings have been preempted by the new federal law.  <P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Safety Regulation<P>
</CENTER></B><P>
Steptoe attorneys have an in-depth understanding of the safety requirements imposed by the Federal Railroad Administration and regularly counsel start-up carriers with respect to compliance with FRA requirements.  We have also been actively involved in litigation concerning the preemptive effect of FRA regulations with respect to state laws in such areas as caboose requirements, walkway regulations, and grade crossing protection.  <P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Contract Disputes<P>
</CENTER></B><P>
We have represented railroads in numerous contract disputes with shippers before federal and state courts and arbitration panels.  Because of our in-depth knowledge of rate matters, we have developed a special expertise in disputes relating to rate contracts between railroads and shippers.  Recently we obtained a favorable decision in a suit brought by a utility involving the interpretation of a provision of a rate contract in which hundreds of millions of dollars were at stake.  We successfully persuaded a jury that the utility had failed to prove its case with respect to its major claims, and obtained an appellate reversal on the one issue in which the jury had found in favor of the utility, resulting in a total victory for the railroad.  <P>
<P>
We have also developed significant expertise in the interpretation of leases and other agreements between railroads, including the background of arcane provisions of various 19th century agreements.  We have successfully represented smaller railroads in arbitration proceedings involving the interpretation of century-old agreements.  We have also represented railroads in negotiations with respect to the renewal of such agreements upon their expiration.  <P>
<P>
The expertise we have acquired in contract litigation and arbitration is also valuable to our clients in the negotiation context.  We regularly assist both carriers and shippers in drafting contract provisions, trackage rights agreements, leases, operating agreements, settlement agreements and similar documents. <P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Railway Labor Act<P>
</CENTER></B><P>
Our attorneys have substantial experience in interpreting, applying and litigating the Railway Labor Act.  We have handled a broad range of RLA issues, including representation and bargaining issues, grievance handling and arbitrations, injunctions and strikes.  We have also been involved in the front-line issues in the rapid evolution of the industry since deregulation, including employee drug testing, secondary strikes, and bargaining and representation issues arising from acquisitions and rail line sales.  Our attorneys regularly provide advice on the labor aspects of proposed transactions and management programs, including labor protection issues arising under the former Interstate Commerce Act and the ICC Termination Act.  <P>
<P>
<P>
<CENTER><B>Trial, Appellate and Supreme Court Litigation</B><P>
</CENTER><P>
Steptoe &amp; Johnson's attorneys have litigated a wide range of rail-related issues in the state and federal courts, including antitrust, complex contract claims, constitutional challenges to state legislation, Indian law issues, federal preemption issues, statutory interpretation issues, and RICO defense. Well known for our specialization in appellate matters, we have participated in a number of recent Supreme Court cases involving rail issues, including state taxation of railroads, state venue laws, creation of short-line carriers, and regulation of employee drug use.
<HR>
<P>
