<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Electric Power Practice
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>Electric Power Practice</CENTER></H2>

<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP's electric power lawyers represent a number of major electric utility
companies in a wide range of subject areas, and also assist the
owners and financiers of non-utility generators of electricity.

<P>The firm represents its clients in all aspects of practice
before the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC"),
including transmission, power contract, and rate matters and
merger approvals. It represents a number of electric utilities
in rate and other ongoing regulatory matters before the FERC,
and is involved in rate and other regulatory matters before
state regulatory commissions.  Attorneys in the firm's electric
power group served as FERC and antitrust counsel to the
applicant (i.e., acquiring) utilities in the three most recent
contested merger hearings before the FERC (including Entergy's
recently completed acquisition of Gulf States Utilities Co.). 

<P>The firm's electric power lawyers assist clients in the
negotiation and approval of contracts for large wholesale power
and transmission service sales and in development of the
contractual documents that serve as the basis for development
and financing of joint generation and transmission ventures.

<P>The firm provides antitrust advice and representation to firms
in the electric power, natural gas, andnuclear energy
industries, including participation in antitrust litigation in
the federal courts and in matters, including merger clearances
under the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act, before the Federal Trade
Commission and the Antitrust Division of the U.S. Department of
Justice.  This includes assistance with merger and acquisition
and diversification issues, as well as transmission and
wholesale power issues.  Senior lawyers in the group also have
assisted clients in commercial negotiations and disputes, and
assumed the lead role in complex commercial litigation.


<P>Steptoe & Johnson LLP assists utilities, non-utility generators,
and financiers of electric power projects in regulatory and
contract matters arising out of non-utility generation projects.
 These include regulatory matters under the Public Utilities
Regulatory Policies Act, the Public Utility Holding Company Act
("PUHCA"), and the newly enacted National Energy Policy Act. 
The firm also advises electric power clients more generally
concerning regulatory matters arising under PUHCA.

<P>The electric power practice is led by <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/bouknigh.htm">J.A. ("Lon") Bouknight, Jr.</a> Other senior partners are <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/green.htm">Douglas G. Green</a> and <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/raskin.htm">David B. Raskin</a>.  <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/vasile.htm">James B. Vasile</a> heads up the firm's non-utility
generation and hydroelectric power practices. Major clients
include:  Florida Power & Light Co., Southern California Edison
Co., Entergy, Potomac Electric Power Co., Public Service Electric & Gas Co., Carolina Power & Light Co.,
ESI Energy, Inc., and Idaho Power Co.<p>
<p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>
