<HEAD>
<TITLE>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP/Government Contracts Practice

</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H3><CENTER>STEPTOE & JOHNSON LLP
</CENTER></H3>

<H2><CENTER>Government Contracts Practice</CENTER>
</H2>

<P>Our contracts clients cover a  broad spectrum:  aerospace and defense, engineering and
construction, ADP and communications, commercial products and
services, research and development, natural resources, and
consulting services.  We advise domestic and foreign profit,
nonprofit and governmental organizations.

<P>Lawyers in this practice area are experienced in all types of
litigation, including bid protests, claims, appeals,
subcontractor disputes, fraud proceedings, Freedom of
Information Act, and Trade Secrets Act actions.  Recent matters
litigated include:
<dir><LI>Representing a major electronics company in a series of bid
protests filed in the U.S. Court of Federal Claims and U.S.
District Courts;<P>

<LI>Representing aerospace, electronics, construction, medical and
service contractors in numerous General Accounting Office and
agency bid protests;<P>

<LI>Representing a large insurance company in a series of bid
protests at the General Services Board of Contract Appeals;<P>


<LI>Representing a leading aerospace company in several Freedom of
Information Act and Trade Secrets Act injunctive actions in U.S.
District Court;<P>

<LI>Representing another major aerospace company in a petition for
certiorari to the U.S. Supreme Court challenging the
constitutionality of the qui tam provisions;<P>


<LI>Representing a qui tam defendant accused of improperly billing
the government for services; and<P>

<LI>Representing numerous clients in contract and subcontract
disputes before boards of contract appeals, the U.S. Court of
Federal Claims, and U.S. District Courts.</dir>


<P>We counsel our contractor clients on a full range of issues,
including cost accounting, defective pricing, anti-deficiency,
leases, procurement integrity, ethics, foreign commercial and
military sales, licensing and data transfers, antitrust,
national security, teaming, joint ventures, and procurement
reform.  Recent examples of counseling engagements include:

<dir><LI>Advising a leading aerospace company with regard to a
termination settlement proposal arising out of a partial
termination of a major space program;<P>
<LI>Advising a major electronics company concerning cost
accounting, cost allowability, Truth in Negotiations, internal
investigation and ethics issues;<P>
<LI>Developing and evaluating corporate codes of conduct,
procurement integrity compliance and training programs;<P>
<LI>Advising insurance companies concerning aspects of financing
construction of housing to be leased to the government;<P>
<LI>Advising a government-owned corporation on various government
contracting issues, including implementation of federal
acquisition laws and regulations; and<P>
<LI>Advising a number of companies on suspension, debarment and
False Claims Act issues.</dir>

<P>Frequently, our government contract efforts call upon attorneys
from other practice areas, such as white-collar, antitrust and
international.  Recent engagements of this type include:
<dir><LI>Representing companies and individuals in Inspector General
and Justice Department investigations and prosecutions of
alleged product substitution, labor mischarging, Multiple Award
Schedule pricing, and other false claims;<P>
<LI>Advising major aerospace companies on foreign military sales
requirements and compliance procedures;<P>
<LI>Representing foreign corporate investors in Defense
Investigative Service investigations and proceedings to
terminate facility security clearances;<P>
<LI>Advising domestic and foreign companies on the application of
the Exon-Florio amendment;<P>
<LI>Representing clients in defense of Justice Department
investigations of illicit payments;<P>
<LI>Advising a major electronics company on issues arising out of
a proposed teaming arrangement and assisting on questions raised
by the Justice Department;<P>
<LI>Advising several clients on the acquisition and divestiture of
business units that were performing government contracts; and <P>
<LI>Advising and representing clients on privatizations.</dir>


<P>The leader of our government contracts group, Robert D. Wallick,
has practiced in this field for over thirty years.  He recently
was one of only three private practitioners on the Advisory
Panel on Streamlining and Codifying Acquisition Laws.  This
"Section 800" Panel's comprehensive recommendations for legal
reform have been substantially enacted into law as the Federal
Acquisition Streamlining Act of 1994 (Pub. L. No. 103-355).  Our
government contracts group also includes:
<dir><LI><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/barletta.htm">Thomas P. Barletta</a>, who recently completed three years as
Chair of the Accounting and Cost and Pricing Committee of the
ABA's Section of Public Contract Law.<P>
<LI><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/fennell.htm">Stephen A. Fennell</a>, who is Vice Chair of the Construction
Dispute Resolution Committee of the ABA's Section of Public
Contract Law.<P>
<LI><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/howe.htm">Jerald S. Howe, Jr.</a>, who is the current President of the
Federal Circuit Bar Association and a Director of the Washington
Space Business Roundtable.<P>
<LI><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/krauland.htm">Edward J. Krauland</a>, whose practice includes a combination of
government contracts and international law/trade issues.<P>
<LI><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/mcnamara.htm">Ellen M. McNamara</a>, whose practice includes a combination of
government contracts and antitrust issues.<P>
<LI><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sauls.htm">Daniel C. Sauls</a>, whose practice includes large construction
and dredging claims throughout the country, bid protests, and
related matters in the government contracts area.<P>
<LI><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/schneide.htm">Martin D. Schneiderman</a>, who served in the Air Force Office of
the General Counsel prior to joining the firm.<P>
<LI><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/wellingt.htm">Peter L. Wellington</a>, who is a member of the Council of the
ABA's Section of Public Contract Law and a past Chair of the
Section's Procurement Fraud Committee.<p><p><blockquote><CENTER><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Areas Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorney Bios</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></CENTER></body></html>
