content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 2.0">
<title>j17</title>
</head>

<body>
<Center>January 21, 1997</Center>



<Center><H3>STEPTOE &amp; JOHNSON LLP</H3>

<H3>DAILY TAX LEGISLATIVE UPDATE</H3></Center>
<HR></P>

<CENTER><P><I>No legal analysis is complete without a particularized review
of the needs and circumstances of an individual client. This and other
documents on the Steptoe &amp; Johnson LLP web page are not to be treated
or relied upon as legal advice or as creating a lawyer-client relationship.
Most materials are not updated, but are maintained on the page because
they are nonetheless likely to be of continuing interest.</I></P></CENTER>

<P>
<HR></P>
<P></P>
<I><B></B>The following briefly summarizes today's news items in the area of tax legislation:</I> 
<P>
<P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>Senate Republican leaders held a news conference today to announce their top legislative priorities.  Included on 
the list is a balanced budget constitutional amendment and a five-year $163 billion tax cut package that includes capital gains
 relief and a $500-per-child tax credit.
</UL>
</UL>
<P></P>
<UL>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>At a separate news conference held today, Senate Minority Leader Thomas Daschle (D-SD) said he believes the Republican
 package contains too large of a tax cut.
</UL>
</UL>
</UL>
<P></P>
<UL>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>President Clinton has already indicated his opposition to a balanced budget amendment.
</UL>
</UL>
</UL>
<P></P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>On January 17, a staff attorney the Joint Committee on Taxation (JCT) speaking at a conference predicted that comprehensive
 tax system reforms would not be addressed by Congress this year.  Rather, the staff attorney predicted that passing a balanced
 budget and addressing tax simplification would be top priorities for Congress.
</UL>
</UL>
<P></P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan, in testimony before the Senate Budget Committee today, said he believes 
that the capital gains tax should be eliminated, because it is a poor means of raising revenue.  He also indicated that he has
 concerns about a balanced budget constitutional amendment.
</UL>
</UL>
<P></P>
<UL>
<UL>
<LI>On January 17, economists told the Joint Committee on Taxation (JCT) that using dynamic scoring to estimate the revenue
 effect of tax legislation is not practical at this time.  They reported that the method, also called macroeconomic modeling, is not 
yet adequately developed.
</UL>
</UL>
<P></P>
<P>
<HR></P>

