<html><head><title>Bruce E. Meyerson</title></head><body><h3 align=center>Steptoe & Johnson LLP</h3><h2 align=center>Bruce E. Meyerson</h2>
<blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/alternat.htm">Alternative Dispute Resolution</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/apellate.htm">Appellate Litigation</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/emplyben.htm">Employment Law</a><BR><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/elecpwer.htm">Utility Law</a> | Education Law</center></blockquote>
<hr>


<P>Bruce Meyerson joined the firm in 1995 following several distinguished legal careers.  After graduating from the Georgetown University Law Center in 1972, Bruce began his law practice as the Executive Director of a public interest law firm in Phoenix, where he litigated numerous, cutting-edge public interest issues.  Three cases which he filed ultimately went to the United States Supreme Court.<P>

<P>

At age 35, he was the youngest person to be appointed by Governor Bruce Babbitt to the Arizona Court of Appeals, where he served for almost five years.  While on the court, he successfully spearheaded major projects to reduce appellate delay.  When he &quot;retired&quot; from the court, he became General Counsel for Arizona State University.<P>

Bruce's practice is as diverse as his background and experience.  Although his principal area of practice is in employment litigation and counselling, he works extensively in the areas of education law and utility law.  Drawing upon his experience as an appellate judge, Bruce is leading the efforts of the Phoenix office to expand its appellate practice.<P>

Bruce has substantial experience in alternative dispute resolution as a mediator, arbitrator, trainer, and designer of ADR systems.  As a  state and national leader in the dispute resolution field, Bruce has taught negotiation at Pepperdine University, and arbitration and alternative dispute resolution at Arizona State University.  He has chaired the American Bar Association Section of Business Law Committee on Dispute Resolution and presently chairs the Arizona Supreme Court ADR Advisory Committee.<P>

<P><UL><LI>Georgetown University J.D. 1972 Editor, <U>Georgetown University Law Journal</U><br>
<LI>Arizona State University B.S. 1968</UL> <hr>
<p><blockquote><center><a href="http://www.steptoe.com/sjbios.htm">Attorneys</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/pgatoc.htm">Practice Area Descriptions</a> | <a href="http://www.steptoe.com/welcome.htm">Home Page</a></center></body></html>

