<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Elan Corporation plc</TITLE></HEAD>
<body background="images/paper1.gif"><P>
<A HREF="index.html"><img border=0 SRC="images/elnmain.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=75 ISMAP USEMAP="index.html"></A><P>
<IMG SRC="images/charstat.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=47><P>
<UL><FONT COLOR="03056B"><FONT SIZE=3><b>Dear Shareholders,</b><BR>

<P>
When I reported to shareholders last May I referred to the opportunities open to Elan in the coming year against the changing industry background. For me it was also a significant personal moment in that for the first time in the Company's history I was reporting to you as a non-executive chairman rather than the Company's chief executive. I am therefore pleased to report that substantial progress has been made towards achieving our objectives over the past twelve months. I would like to give proper credit to the management team under Donal Geaney's leadership which is applying itself to building the business of Elan for the medium to long term. I am very confident that they will continue to do so with great skill, enthusiasm and energy.
<P>
During the past year we have established a number of key strategic objectives. It has long been our desire to be the world leader in drug delivery technology and to be the preferred industry partner in the provision of drug delivery services. Through our broad platform of technologies, our collaborative alliances and range of marketed products I believe this objective has been accomplished. It has also been our desire to establish Elan as a fully integrated pharmaceutical company in one market niche. By full integration, we mean from drug discovery through sales and marketing. Our own development activities have led us to diseases of the central nervous system where a company such as Elan can make a significant impact and compete on the same basis as larger pharmaceutical companies. The acquisition of Athena Neurosciences, Inc. which we announced on 18 March, 1996 will assist us in achieving that objective. This is perhaps one of the single most important steps ever taken for our Company and I very much look forward to the contribution which Athena's management and research and marketing personnel will make to the enlarged group. Athena's chief executive John Groom, who has over 35 years experience in the pharmaceutical industry, will become the chief operating officer of the enlarged group. I look forward to the contribution that he will undoubtedly make to building Elan for the future. The completion of this merger will represent the fulfilment of our "Mind to Market" strategy.
<P>
The results for the year, summarised in the financial highlights on page one, represent a significant achievement by our management and staff. The growth in net income per share from $1.90 to $2.38 was particularly gratifying.
<P>
It is my responsibility as chairman to ensure the board implements appropriate procedures for corporate governance. When I became non-executive chairman I undertook a review of the structure of the board, its committees and its relationship with  management. It is my objective that our corporate governance procedures comply with best practice in Ireland. 
<P>
In addition, I initiated a review of the composition of the board to ensure that it reflects the range and skills that a Company of Elan's size requires. I was particularly pleased to welcome to the board of directors four new appointments since my last report. Mr. David Bethune who was president of the Lederle Laboratories division of the American Cyanamid Company joined the board in July 1995 and brings a substantial experience in the sale and marketing of pharmaceutical products. In February 1996 Mr. Laurence G. Crowley, the deputy governor of the Bank of Ireland and executive chairman of the Graduate Business School, University College, Dublin became a non-executive director. In March 1996, Dr. Alan R. Gillespie a partner in Goldman, Sachs & Co. and its head of UK/Irish investment banking division and Mr. Richard Thornburgh a former attorney general of the United States of America and governor of the State of Pennsylvania became non-executive directors. These appointments bring considerable governmental, business and other relevant experience to our board of directors. I look forward to their contribution to our Company as it develops.
<P>
At the Annual General Meeting, Mr. Charles Greyston a director of the Company since 1985 will retire from the board of directors. Mr. Greyston has made a remarkable contribution to the development of Elan serving throughout that period as chairman of the audit committee. His independence of mind, integrity and wide business experience will be much missed by the board.
<P>
It is with regret that I record the death on 15 March last of Mr. Andrew Casey who served as our Company secretary. In Elan's formative years, Mr. Casey's contribution was instrumental in establishing the basis for future growth. Although much debilitated by a long-term illness, Mr. Casey's interest in and commitment to Elan never faltered.
<P>
For me, last year has been a period of considerable change. Having founded Elan and led it through its first 25 years I have had  the privilege of implementing Elan's first executive succession in handing its management and direction over to Donal Geaney and his management team. They have done an excellent job for the Company and for its shareholders and have my full support. I must also acknowledge the contribution of our employees and partners throughout the world to the continuing success of our Company. Finally to you our shareholders I thank you for your continuing support. My objective with respect to enhancing shareholder value has been to ensure that the interests of management and shareholders are united for a common purpose. I believe our record of achievement is a validation of that approach.
<P>
<P>
<P>
<B>Donald E. Panoz,</B><BR></I>Chairman</I></UL><P>
<P>
