<DOCHDR>
http://www.elan.ie:80/ceostatement.html 194.125.133.25 19970113212327 text/html 13154
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 21:23:27 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 21-Jun-96 10:43:14 GMT
Content-length: 12970
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Elan Corporation plc</TITLE></HEAD>
<body background="images/paper1.gif"><P>
<A HREF="anrep.html"><img border=0 SRC="images/elnmain.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=75 ISMAP USEMAP="anrep.html"></A><P>
<IMG SRC="images/pressie.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=47><P>
<UL><FONT COLOR="03056B"><FONT SIZE=3>The fundamental review of our corporate strategy which was initiated in January 1995 when I became chief executive officer has yielded important and exciting results. Over this period the pharmaceutical industry has and will continue to experience major change. From Elan's perspective, it is my responsibility to ensure that we anticipate and adapt to these changes rather than allow these changes to sweep Elan along in their wake.
<P>
The two most significant corporate events in 1996 were the approval and launch of NaprelanÅ and the selection of its marketing partner and the announcement on 18 March, 1996 of the signature of a definitive merger agreement with Athena Neurosciences, Inc., a San Francisco based bio-pharmaceutical company. I will explore our reasoning behind this acquisition later in the statement.
<P>
In July 1995 I announced our agreement with the Wyeth-Ayerst division of American Home Products for the marketing of our once-daily Naprelan. Naprelan is a unique long-acting non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug ("NSAID") indicated for the treatment of arthritis and analgesia. It has a superior side-effect profile to all other long-acting NSAIDs and I believe its approval and launch in 1996 represents a major medical advance in the treatment of arthritis and pain management, generally. We have had a significant business relationship with American Home Products and their commitment to Naprelan as the lead product in their arthritis specialisation strategy is a major opportunity for Elan.
<P>
The watchword in pharmaceutical production is quality and adherence to current good manufacturing practices ("cGMP"). In July 1995, we received a Warning Letter from the US Food and Drug Administration ("FDA") referencing our approach to cGMP at our Athlone, Ireland  facility in 1993 and 1994. On receipt of this letter, I initiated a review of our manufacturing operations, established an independent regulatory compliance function and subjected all of our manufacturing facilities to independent regulatory audit. A further FDA inspection of the Athlone facility in October 1995 resulted in the lifting of the Warning Letter. I would like to place on record my thanks to officials of the FDA for their support, interest and assistance during a very difficult period for Elan. Adherence to cGMP is a continuing process to which I and the management of Elan are fully committed. It is my intention that all of our facilities will continue to operate to the highest standards of quality assurance and regulatory compliance.
<P>
Manufacturing operations have come through a period of growth as we scaled up our facilities to produce Naprelan and other newly approved products. Manufacturing employment increased at our Athlone facility from 125 employees to 275 employees by 31 March, 1996. There was a substantial increase in manufacturing facilities in Athlone which have also been upgraded to comply with the highest standards of environmental protection. We are planning to extend our US manufacturing facilities at Gainesville, Georgia to provide for anticipated product approvals in 1998 and 1999.
<P>
The continued success of Cardizem&reg; CD (once-daily diltiazem) and Verelan&reg; (once-daily Verapamil) in the United States market and their equivalent products elsewhere in the world make a significant contribution to our revenue and profitability. These products were the foundation of our early success and underline the value of drug delivery technology in enhancing the clinical and medical advantages of these drugs. In Japan, the originator of the diltiazem molecule, Tanabe, has just launched Herbesser&reg; HP (a high potency once-daily formulation of diltiazem). This will enhance the market opportunity in Japan for our marketing partner. Also this year, Mitsubishi successfully launched Theodur&reg; Sprinkle which represents the second product utilising our PharmaZome&reg; technology that has been commercialised. The third product utilising this technology, Erythelan&reg; (a twice-daily formulation of erythromycin) will be launched in the United Kingdom this year, marketed by Elan Pharma Limited, our marketing affiliate and hopefully later this year by Adams Laboratories, a division of Medeva plc, in the United States of America.
<P>
Our marketing affiliates, in general, recorded a satisfactory year of trading and profitability. In the United Kingdom and Ireland, Elan Pharma Limited acquired the marketing rights to Ponstan&reg; from Parke-Davis and I am pleased to report that this product is now increasing in revenue and profitability. In Taiwan, the Philippines and the Far Eastern market generally our products continued to grow satisfactorily and occupy the leading market position in a number of important market niches. In Spain, I anticipate that a number of new product launches this year will further the growth of Vita Elan Farma. In China, we expect to commence the launch of Elan developed products later this year. In all, these marketing affiliates are an important part of our future commercialisation strategy and they will be enhanced by the acquisition of Athena Neurosciences and its pipeline of products in development.
<P>
Research and development has been the cornerstone of our success. Research is primarily directed at the development of new drug delivery technologies and is conducted at our research facilities in Dublin, Ireland and Yavne, Israel. In Ireland the principal focus is on the development of new oral delivery technologies particularly in the area of bio-technology, large molecule and immunotherapeutic drugs. In Israel the primary focus is on the transcutaneous, pulmonary and iontophoretic delivery of drugs. Our research in these fields is designed to address the delivery requirements of the newer drugs which are generally administered by intra-veneous or sub-cutaneous means.
<P>
Our development activities are largely centered at our second site in Ireland at Athlone (where our principal manufacturing centre is based). Our research and development projects span pre-clinical evaluation of new technologies, pharmacokinetic and clinical determination of a range of novel dosage forms through process transfer, full validation and regulatory filings. For calendar 1996 we expect up to six regulatory filings with the FDA and a further 70 worldwide. The most important products in the near-term development pipeline include Neurelan&reg; (for the symptomatic treatment of multiple sclerosis);  Morphelan&reg; (once-daily morphine sulphate primarily for pain management); Verelan PM (a chronotherapeutic formulation of once-daily verapamil); Captelan&reg; (a once-daily formulation of captopril); EL 530/532 (for the treatment of certain types of cancer);  and once-daily nifedipine. 
I envisage that these products will provide the basis for the future growth of our drug delivery business.
<P>
We have also expanded our research and development through a number of research collaborative ventures. These include:
<P>
<ul><b>Dura Pharmaceuticals, Inc.</b>  Pulmonary delivery of proteins and peptides</ul>
<P>
<ul><b>Ethical Holdings, plc</b>  Solid oral dosage and transdermal delivery</ul>
<P>
<ul><b>Emisphere Technologies, Inc.</b>  Delivery of large molecular drugs</ul>
<P>
<ul><b>Cytogen Corporation</b>  Access to combinatorial library</ul>
<P>
These relationships expand our technology platform and the range of services that we can provide our clients. In the cases of Dura, Ethical and Emisphere we are shareholders at generally the 5 to 10 per cent level. These shareholdings enable us to enhance the value of our collaborations with these companies.
One of our primary objectives is to be the preferred industry provider of drug delivery services. I am therefore pleased to report that during fiscal 1996 we signed 33 agreements with 28 industry partners. In addition, we are developing fifteen complex generic products for five clients utilising the Abbreviated New Drug Application procedures of the FDA.
<P>
For 1996, our success as a Company will be determined by the successful launch and roll-out of Naprelan;  the continued performance of Cardizem CD and Verelan;  our continued success in attracting licencing and research revenues; and the completion of the acquisition, integration and achievement of the transaction benefits and synergies with respect to Athena Neurosciences, Inc. It is this transaction which I would now like to discuss.
<P>
As I mentioned at the start of this statement, shortly after becoming chief executive I undertook a comprehensive review of our corporate strategy. The timing was opportune and enabled the Company to critically review its positioning and future opportunities. The conclusions of this review were as follows:
<P>
(i)	Elan should continue to be a leading provider and developer of drug delivery technologies;
(ii)	our products would have demonstrable clinical and medical advantages;
(iii)	where appropriate, we would enhance our technology platform through strategic alliances and collaborative arrangements; and
(iv)	we would review the opportunity for Elan to access a market niche where our capability would include drug discovery through sales and marketing in North America.
<P>
The outcome of this review resulted in the conclusion that while the products in our pipeline would sustain our growth in the short to medium term it would be desirable to build critical mass in a market niche through an acquisition. We determined that diseases of the central nervous system ("CNS") were our preferred area because (i) although the neurology community was relatively small, it was influential in terms of total number of prescriptions for CNS products written by general practitioners and others and (ii) the area contained many disease conditions which are currently untreatable and where our drug delivery technologies could add significant value. In early 1996 we initiated discussions with Athena Neurosciences, Inc. (where in March 1995 we had concluded a research and development arrangement and purchased a $12 million convertible security) to further review collaborative opportunities. During these discussions, we agreed that a merger of our two businesses would provide the best available opportunity to achieve our mutual objectives. These discussions were concluded through the signature of a definitive merger agreement on 18 March, 1996. It is, in my view, the most significant transaction in our corporate history and will give Elan, for the first time, world-class drug discovery research and an influential position in the sales and marketing of CNS products to the US neurology community. When the acquisition closes Elan will be organised through three divisions:
<P>
<ul><b>Elan Technologies</b>  Drug delivery development licencing and world-wide manufacturing<P>
<b>Elan Pharma</b>  World-wide sales and marketing of Elan and ultimately Athena developed products<P>
<b>Athena Therapeutics</b>  Drug discovery research and development of CNS products</ul>
<P>
I am pleased that John Groom, the president and chief executive officer of Athena, will become the chief operating officer of Elan. In contrast to many recent transactions of this nature in the pharmaceutical industry the transaction benefits will be derived from "upsizing" the combined organisation rather than "downsizing" through plant closures and redundancies.
<P>
Elan was founded based on the vision of Donald Panoz who was among the first to see the clinical and medical benefits of improved drug absorption. Its fulfilment was achieved through many different contributions over our first twenty five years. However we must now position Elan for the 21st century. I believe that much has been achieved over the last year. In particular, the approval of Naprelan and the Athena transaction represent critical milestones in our future development. It is and will remain our strategy to expand our business through exploitation of the product pipeline, extensions to our  marketing infrastructure and, where appropriate, product acquisitions. We will remain committed to our world leadership position in drug delivery and to being the preferred industry partner.
<P>
I would like to thank our shareholders and employees for their support, interest and commitment over the past twelve months. I look forward with confidence to 1996.<P>
<BR Clear=All>
<IMG SRC="images/donal.jpg" WIDTH=142 HEIGHT=255><P>
<P>
<b>Donal J. Geaney,</b><br></I>President & Chief Executive Officer</i></ul>
<P>
