<HEAD><TITLE>Elan Corporation plc</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="../images/paper1.gif"><P>
<A HREF="index.html"><img border=0 SRC="../images/elnmain.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=75 ISMAP USEMAP="index.html"></A><P>
<IMG SRC="../images/press.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=47><P>
<UL><FONT COLOR="03056B"><FONT SIZE=4><ul><ul><h2>FDA Grants Approvable Status for Elan's Diastat&reg; Product</h2></ul></ul><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<b>DUBLIN, IRELAND, (December 4, 1996): Elan Corporation, plc ("Elan") (NYSE:ELN) announced today that its wholly-owned subsidiary, Athena Neurosciences, Inc. ("Athena"), received from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration ("FDA") an approvable letter for Diastat&reg; (diazepam rectal gel).</b><P>

Diastat is a new proprietary gel formulation of diazepam and is approvable for rectal administration in the management of selected, refractory, epileptic patients, on stable regimens of anti-epileptic drugs, who require intermittent use of diazepam to control bouts of increased seizure activity.  The conditions for approval include reaching agreement on labelling proposed by the FDA, including appropriate guidance for the use of Diastat, and the submission of a current safety update.<P>

The Peripheral and Central Nervous System Drugs Advisory Committee convened by the FDA unanimously recommended  approval of the New Drug Application ("NDA") for Diastat on November 15, 1996 and the labelling proposed to the company by the FDA is consistent with the committee's recommendation.  The FDA has previously granted the company Orphan Drug designation for Diastat, providing seven years of marketing exclusivity from new drug approval for an indication previously defined as acute repetitive seizures.   Elan plans to review the indication language proposed by the FDA with the Office of Orphan Products Development to retain the company's Orphan Drug designation.<P>

Although most of the 2.5 million patients with epilepsy in the United States are controlled with daily medication, a subset of patients with severe epilepsy may suffer from a cluster of prolonged, acute seizures that, if not treated quickly, may lead to brain damage, other injury or death.
<P>
"When approved, Diastat will offer the convenience of at-home administration to help control increased seizure activity, thereby enabling patients and families to avoid visits to the emergency room and the economic and emotional costs related to those visits", said Jan Wallace, M.D., Athena's vice president of clinical and regulatory affairs.  "Diastat can provide the ability to manage this severe epileptic condition at home for the thousands of affected patients and their family members".
<P>
Elan chief executive officer, Donal Geaney, commented that, "The approvable status of Diastat is welcome news, particularly since it comes only days after the marketing approval of Zanaflex&reg; (tizanidine hydrochloride), a product indicated for the management of increased muscle tone associated with spasticity, a condition affecting the central nervous system.  Diastat's approvable FDA status underscores the company's growing neurological product line and furthers Elan's presence as a significant contributor to the neurology community".
<P>
Elan Corporation, plc is a leading worldwide drug delivery company with innovative drug absorption technologies designed to improve patient care in a cost-effective manner.  Its principal research and manufacturing facilities are in Ireland, and through its subsidiaries in the United States and Israel.  Athena Neurosciences, Inc., a wholly-owned subsidiary of Elan, discovers, develops and markets product to be used primarily for the treatment and diagnosis of central nervous system diseases and disorders.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Except for historical information, the statements made in this press release contain certain forward-looking statements that involve a number of risks and uncertainties, including final governmental approval, product demand, market acceptance and pricing of Diastat, as well as the other risks detailed from time to time in the SEC reports filed by Elan, including its report on Form 20-F for the year ended March, 31, 1996 as amended November 1996.</FONT><P>
<P><BR><P>
