<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Elan Corporation plc</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="../images/paper1.gif"><P>
<A HREF="index.html"><img border=0 SRC="../images/elnmain.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=75 ISMAP USEMAP="index.html"></A><P>
<IMG SRC="../images/press.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=47><P>
<UL><FONT COLOR="03056B"><FONT SIZE=4><ul><ul><h2>Elan and Cytogen create cancer product company
</h2></ul></ul><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<h3><i>Targon Corporation To Combine Core Competencies To Achieve Accelerated Drug Development and Commercialisation Programs.</i></h3><P>
<b>PRINCETON, N.J., September 26, 1996 -- Elan Corporation, plc (NYSE:ELN) and CYTOGEN Corporation (NSADAQ:CYTO) announced today that they have entered into an agreement creating a new U.S. based company to focus exclusively on the rapid development, registration, manufacturing and commercialisation of differentiated oncology products.   The agreement calls for the establishment of Targon Corporation, which will initially be a wholly-owned subsidiary of CYTOGEN.   Elan, which has made a $20 million investment in CYTOGEN (consisting of $5 million in common stock and $15 million in a new Series A convertible preferred stock, the proceeds of which will initially capitalise Targon), will have the right to have equal ownership with CYTOGEN in the new company.</b><P>

Targon will utilise Elan's and CYTOGEN's demonstrated competencies in drug development and manufacturing in order to accelerate its global registration of oncology products.  Products for the new company will be accessed from the two principal sources: (1) Elan's and CYTOGEN's existing pipelines and (2) the in-licensing of additional late stage oncology products.   All new products to be developed by Targon will benefit from Elan's expertise in drug delivery and enhanced formulation, and CYTOGEN's strength in the clinical development and registration of cancer products.<P>

 "The new company creates a unique combination of competencies and provides an effective and efficient development channel for differentiated oncology products", said Michael Sember, Elan's Vice President of Planning, Investments and Development, who will serve as Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of Targon.<P>

At the outset, Targon will have five products in its research pipeline:<P>

<UL><i>EL530 and EL532,</i> for the treatment of solid and hematologic tumours.   These agents inhibit the growth of cells from a wide range of cancers.  This mechanism of action differs from traditional treatment approaches that are dependent on killing cancer cells rather than limiting their growth.  Currently, Phase II clinical trials are being directed by the National Cancer Institute.<P>

<i>Prostatec,</i> for use in detecting the extent and location of prostate cancer.   This diagnostic is a second generation version of CYTOGEN's ProtaScint prostate cancer diagnostic, which has been sanctioned by an FDA advisory committee and is currently under FDA review.  Oncotec, a diagnostic imaging agent for the detection of breast cancer based on OncoScint CR/OV, which has been cleared by FDA for use in detecting colorectal and ovarian cancers.   These two products, which have the potential to reduce cancer diagnostic costs and provide timelier results than available tests, are undergoing IND preparations.<P>

<i>PSMA Technology </i>(Prostate Specific Membrane Antigen), a unique approach to identifying prostate cancer in the blood.  Antibody and gene therapy products based on PSMA offer diagnostic and therapeutic applications in prostate cancer.</UL><P>

"Targon's singular focus on the oncology market enhances the company's ability to bring oncology products to market, and to do so quickly," said Donal J. Geaney, Chief Executive Officer and President of Elan.  "By combining the strengths of Elan and CYTOGEN we have created a dynamic new company with focussed strengths and exceptional capabilities in the oncology sector."<P>

"Our agreement with Elan confirms our commitment to growth through alliances and strengthens our leadership position in the development, registration and manufacturing of differentiated cancer products," said Thomas J. McKearn, CYTOGEN's President, Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the Board.   "Our ongoing alliance with Elan concerning the Genetic Diversity Library technology has been extremely productive.  I am confident that this second alliance will further advance CYTOGEN's objective to build its business and create sustainable stockholder value."<P>

According to the American Cancer Society, the estimated number of cancer cases diagnosed annually in the United States (excluding certain skin cancers) increased from approximately 782,000 in 1980 to approximately 1.2 million in 1994, an increase of 53%.  This increase is attributable to a number of factors, including a growing and ageing population.  As a result, more than eight million Americans have been diagnosed with cancer.   It is expected that these trends will continue and that the number of cancer patients, and the demand for oncology services, will continue to increase.<P>

The oncology pharmaceutical market is predicted by industry experts to grow to an estimated $11 billion by the year 2002 and represents one of the fastest growing segments in the pharmaceutical industry.<P>

Elan Corporation, plc is a leading world-wide drug delivery and biopharmaceutical company.   Its innovative drug absorption technologies are designed to improve patient care in a cost effective manner.   Its Athena Neuroscience subsidiary discovers, develops and markets products to be used by neurologists for the treatment and diagnosis of neurological disorders.   Elan's principal research and manufacturing facilities are in Ireland, the United States and Israel.  Elan's shares trade on the New York, London and Dublin Stock Exchanges.<P>

CYTOGEN is a biopharmaceutical company engaged in the development, manufacture and commercialisation of products for the targeted delivery of diagnostics and therapeutic substances directly to disease sites.   CYTOGEN has demonstrated its ability to evolve novel technology from early discovery through clinical development, regulatory approval and commercial-scale biologic manufacturing, and is focused on leveraging these core capabilities to expand and build a profitable business.<P>

Attached is a fact sheet which provides additional information on Targon, its management, its products and the financial structure involved in the formation of this new company.<P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<h6>Except for the historical information contained herein, the matters discussed in this press release contain forward looking statements that involve risks and uncertainties, including the timing and outcome of FDA approval of products and the other risks detailed from time to time in Elan's and CYTOGEN's SEC reports, including Elan's Form 20-F for the fiscal year ended March 31, 1996 and CYTOGEN's Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 1995.</h6><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<h2>Targon Corporation Fact Sheet</h2><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>

<h3>The Company</h3>
Targon Corporation will commence business with immediate access to the core competencies of Elan and CYTOGEN, and will specialise in expedited drug development programs for differentiated oncology products.<P>

Targon Corporation is established initially as a wholly-owned subsidiary of CYTOGEN and, at Elan's option, may be owned by Elan and CYTOGEN.<P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<h3>The Management</h3>
The new Company will have a Board of Directors that includes equal representation from Elan and CYTOGEN, as well as representation from the management of the new company and from the industry.<P>

Upon election of the Board of Directors, Michael Sember, Elan's Vice President of Planning, Investments and Development, will serve as Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the new company.<P>

Robert Maguire CYTOGEN's Vice President of Medical Affairs, will serve as the new company's  Executive President and Chief Scientific Officer.<P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<h3>The Products.</h3>
Targon Corporation will have rights to five products:  EL530 and EL532 from Elan; Prostatec, Oncotec and PSMA Technology from CYTOGEN.   Additional products will be accessed through the in-licensing of late stage oncology products that can benefit from Elan's drug delivery and enhanced formulation expertise and CYTOGEN's proven strengths in the clinical development and registration of cancer products.<P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<h3>The Financial Structure</h3>
In connection with the formation of the new company, CYTOGEN completed a sale of registered Common Stock to Elan for $5 million, the proceeds of which formed CYTOGEN's cash contribution to the new company . In addition,the proceeds of a $15 million Series A convertible preferred stock sale to Elan will be used to fund the new company.  The new company will use $10 million of such proceeds to acquire certain products from Advanced Therapeutics Systems Ltd.<P>

The CYTOGEN Series A convertible preferred stock purchased by Elan may, at Elan's option, be either exchanged for one-half of CYTOGEN's interest in the new company or converted into shares of CYTOGEN's common stock.<P>

If Elan exchanges the Series A convertible preferred stock for ownership in the new company then Elan will additionally receive a warrant to purchase up to 1 million shares of CYTOGEN common stock with exercise price (based on the time of exercise) from between $8.40 per share to $14 over time.<P>

If Elan converts the CYTOGEN Series A convertible preferred stock into CYTOGEN common stock, a maximum of 1,785,715 shares of CYTOGEN common stock (reduced over time) would be issuable, depending on when the conversion occurs.   If Elan exercises its conversion right, CYTOGEN will retain full ownership of the new company.<P>
<P><BR><P>
<P><P>
<P>
