<HEAD><TITLE>Elan Corporation plc</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="../images/paper1.gif"><P>
<A HREF="index.html"><img border=0 SRC="../images/elnmain.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=75 ISMAP USEMAP="index.html"></A><P>
<IMG SRC="../images/press.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=47><P>
<UL><FONT COLOR="03056B"><FONT SIZE=4><ul><ul><h2>Elan Corporation, plc announces net income increase of 51%</h2></ul></ul><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<b>DUBLIN, IRELAND,  July 23, 1996:  Elan Corporation, plc (NYSE: ELN) today announced net income for the quarter ended June 30, 1996 of $27,982,000 and earnings per share of $0.68 compared with net income of $18,588,000 and earnings per share of $0.52 in the three months ended June 30, 1995, increases of 51% and 30% respectively.</b><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
Total revenues for the first quarter were $67,620,000, an increase of 39% from $48,691,000 in the first quarter of the previous year.  Revenue from product sales rose 50% to $33,301,000 from $22,186,000 for the quarter, largely reflecting the launch of Naprelan&reg; in the United States in April  1996.<P>

Royalties and fees in the quarter were $22,155,000, up from $17,503,000 in the first quarter of last year.  Licence and option fees reflected 6 new agreements entered into during the quarter and revenue from agreements where milestone payments were earned in the quarter.<P>

Research revenues rose to $12,164,000 for the quarter, from $9,002,000 in the first quarter of fiscal 1996.  Research revenues included $10,596,000 received from Advanced Therapeutic 
 Systems, Limited, up from $6,391,000, reflecting the high level of payments for external work done on behalf of ATS in the quarter.<P>

The gross margin declined reflecting, primarily,  the significant increase in funded research projects for which no milestone payments were achieved, and the early stages of production and the large quantities of samples of Naprelan ".<P>

Unfunded research and development expenditures declined to $5,511,000 from $6,608,000 in the first quarter of the previous year  reflecting the launch of products over the preceding 12 months.<P>

Interest and other income grew by 64% to $7,006,000 from $4,265,000 reflecting primarily the higher levels of cash and cash equivalents on the balance sheet in the current quarter compared to the previous year.<P>

Elan's President and Chief Executive Officer, Donal Geaney, in reviewing the performance for the quarter, commented that "this was an extremely important quarter in the long-term development of Elan.  The approval of the merger with Athena Neurosciences during the quarter, and the completion of the merger on July 1, 1996, brings a new breadth and depth to Elan in terms of management, existing products, research and product pipeline and marketing skills.  The results to June 30 do not, of course, reflect in any way the effect or benefits of the merger.  The results of Athena will be consolidated from July 1".<P>

 Mr. Geaney further commented "the launch of Naprelan in the United States in April by our licensing partner, American Home Products Corporation was a major event for the company.  Naprelan continues to build market share and is well placed to become a major product in its category.  The progress of Cardizem CD and Verelan is also very satisfactory in difficult market conditions.  We are excited about the opportunities for our products in the Far East, particularly in Japan.  I am optimistic about the challenges and prospects facing the enlarged Elan Corporation.  The combination of our leading edge position in research into diseases of the central nervous system and our position as preferred industry partner for drug delivery technologies supported by a strong cash flow and balance sheet leaves Elan well positioned to maximise future opportunities". <P>

As previously announced,  Elan has changed its reporting currency from Irish pounds to U.S. dollars with effect from April 1, 1996 and has also changed its reporting year end from March 31 to December 31.<P>

Elan Corporation, plc is a leading world-wide drug delivery and biopharmaceutical company.  Its innovative drug absorption technologies are designed to improve patient care in a cost effective manner.  Its Athena Neuroscience Division discovers, develops and markets products to be used by neurologists for the treatment and diagnosis of neurological disorders.  Its principal research and manufacturing facilities are in Ireland, the United States and Israel.<P>
