<HEAD><TITLE>Elan Corporation plc</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="../images/paper1.gif"><P>
<A HREF="index.html"><img border=0 SRC="../images/elnmain.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=75 ISMAP USEMAP="index.html"></A><P>
<IMG SRC="../images/press.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=47><P>
<UL><FONT COLOR="03056B"><FONT SIZE=4><ul><ul><h2>Elan Corporation, plc licences Carbatrol<SUP><SMALL>TM</SMALL></SUP> from Pharmavene, Inc through Athena Neurosciences, Inc and announces completion of Phase II clinical study for BOTB<SUP><SMALL>TM</SMALL></SUP> in patients with Cervical Dystonia</h2></ul></ul><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<b>Dublin, Ireland (July 9, 1996):  Elan Corporation, plc (NYSE: ELN) ("ELAN") announced today that its wholly-owned subsidiary, Athena Neurosciences, Inc. ("Athena") has completed an agreement with Pharmavene, Inc. ("Pharmavene"), a private company based in Rockville, Maryland, to license worldwide rights to Carbatrol<SUP><SMALL>TM</SMALL></SUP>, a sustained-release capsule formulation of the extensively used anti-epileptic medication carbamazepine.</b><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
Pharmavene's New Drug Application for Carbatrol was submitted to the Food and Drug Administration ("FDA") on April 3, 1996 and was accepted for substantive review on June 1, 1996.<P>

Carbatrol is a specially formulated capsule using Pharmavene's proprietary technology.  Carbatrol permits carbamazepine to be administered in a twice-a-day dosage regimen, compared to the conventional administration in tablet form of three to four doses per day.  Carbamazepine is one of the principal medications used to control the incidence of epileptic seizures and has been approved in the United States for treatment of this condition for over twenty years.  The FDA recently approved for marketing a two-a-day tablet formulation of carbamazepine called Tegretol&reg; XR.<P>

Mr. John Groom, Elan's chief operating officer commented, "To achieve the full therapeutic benefit of carbamazepine and its protective effect in seizures, it is important that patients 
 maintain appropriate, stable blood levels of the drug throughout the day.  This usually requires tablets to be taken three to four times per day.  We believe Pharmavene's clinical and technical data for Carbatrol demonstrates that their twice daily formulation is able to provide equivalent blood levels of carbamazepine to conventional tablet administration.  Many breakthrough seizures in epileptic patients can be attributed to missed or forgotten doses of their medication, and simplification of the dosage, especially the elimination of the need of a mid-day dose, offers true clinical benefits in compliance as well as patient convenience."<P>

Financial terms of the worldwide license were not announced but contain an upfront payment, a milestone payment on FDA approval, and royalty payments to Pharmavene.  Elan, Athena and Pharmavene will collaborate to pursue the regulatory, technical and other steps necessary to prepare for the planned introduction of Carbatrol.<P>

Elan also announced today the successful completion by Athena of a multi-center, double-blind, placebo-controlled Phase II safety, tolerability, dose-selection and efficacy study of BotB<SUP><SMALL>TM</SMALL></SUP> (Botulinum Toxin Type B) in patients with cervical dystonia (spasmodic torticollis).  Cervical dystonia is a severe condition of abnormal muscle tone and movement that can result in severe, painful abnormalities of posture or inability to flex and relax affected neck and shoulder muscles.<P>

Results from this study, involving 122 patients with cervical dystonia, revealed statistically significant clinical improvement in patients treated with a single injection of BotB, as compared to the placebo-treated patients.  In responding patients, a dose-related duration of effect was achieved lasting at the two highest doses for 3-4 months in some patients.  No unexpected, clinically significant or serious drug-related adverse events were reported for any of the doses tested.  Detailed results of this study will be reported via a satellite symposium of the American Neurological Association's Annual Meeting - The Third International Dystonia Symposium in Miami, Florida on October 9-11, 1996.<P>

Commenting on the results, Dr. Jan Wallace, Athena's vice president for clinical and regulatory affairs said, "We believe that the results of this Phase II study underscore the efficacy of BotB in the treatment of patients with cervical dystonia.  The data from this and earlier studies will enable us to select the appropriate BotB dose for following pivotal Phase III studies, which, subject to FDA review, we hope to commence later this year."<P>

Elan's chief executive officer, Donal Geaney commented, "I am pleased that we are able to announce the first product and research news following our acquisition of Athena.  These products, when approved, will expand our growing portfolio of directly marketed products and are the first steps in our program to exploit the strengths of the enlarged Elan."<P>

Elan Corporation, plc is a leading worldwide drug delivery company with innovative drug absorption technologies designed to improve patient care in a cost-effective manner.  Its principal research and manufacturing facilities are in Ireland, the United States and Israel.  Athena Neurosciences, Inc., a wholly-owned subsidiary of Elan, discovers, develops and market products to be used primarily by neurologists for the treatment and diagnosis of neurological disorders.<P>
<P>
<P><P>
