<HEAD><TITLE>Elan Corporation plc</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body background="../images/paper1.gif"><P>
<A HREF="index.html"><img border=0 SRC="../images/elnmain.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=75 ISMAP USEMAP="index.html"></A><P>
<IMG SRC="../images/press.gif" WIDTH=525 HEIGHT=47><P>
<UL><FONT COLOR="03056B"><FONT SIZE=4><ul><ul><h2>Elan Corporation, plc and Athena Neurosciences, Inc. to merge.</h2></ul></ul><P>
<BR Clear=All><P>
<b>Creates the largest integrated drug delivery company with discovery, development, marketing and manufacturing capabilities<P>
New York (March 18, 1996) -- Elan Corporation, plc (NYSE: ELN) ("Elan") and Athena Neurosciences, Inc. (NASDAQ: ATHN) ("Athena"), announced today that they have signed a definitive merger agreement whereby Athena will become a wholly-owned subsidiary of Elan.</b><P>
<BR Clear=All>
<BR Clear=All><P>
Under the terms of the agreement, Athena's shareholders will receive 0.2956 Elan American Depositary Shares for each Common Share of Athena they own at the time the transaction closes.   Based on the closing price of Elan on March 15, 1996 of $61.25, the agreement values Athena at $18.25 per share.  In the all-share transaction, 9.74 million new Elan shares will be issued for the currently outstanding Athena shares.  The merger will be accounted for as a purchase and has been structured as a tax-free transaction for United States tax purposes.  The merger is expected to be completed by early Summer, subject to the approval of the shareholders of Elan and Athena, and the receipt of requisite regulatory approvals.  The transaction is expected to have a dilutive impact on Elan's earnings in 1996 but should be accretive to earnings in 1997 and thereafter.<P>
Following the merger, Elan will be an integrated drug delivery and bio-pharmaceutical company with expanded capabilities in the discovery, development and marketing of treatments for CNS diseases and disorders supporting its existing strengths in drug delivery.<P>
"This merger advances our mind-to-market strategy by adding research, marketing, sales and distribution capabilities to Elan's expertise in drug delivery and development.  With Athena's complementary skills, we will now be able to employ AthenaÌs infrastructure to market products directly to providers," said Donal J. Geaney, president and chief executive officer of Elan.<P>
"We will be adding pioneering research in the CNS area to our existing multiple sclerosis program.  Additionally, we will be better positioned to capitalize on the market opportunities created by the continued consolidation of the pharmaceutical industry as well as broaden our relationships with our drug delivery clients," Mr. Geaney continued.<P>
To Elan's expertise in formulating, testing, registering and manufacturing products, Athena adds experience in drug discovery and biotechnology as well as strong marketing and distribution to neurologists.  Together, these resources comprise all elements necessary to bring innovative products to market.<P>
After the merger Elan will have strong scientific infrastructure in neurological research with marketed products for the treatment of epilepsy and ParkinsonÌs disease; products in development for multiple sclerosis, epilepsy, neuromuscular disorders and Parkinson's disease;  and potential products in discovery for the treatment and prevention of AlzheimerÌs disease and multiple sclerosis.  In addition, Athena has a diagnostic subsidiary which has recently introduced a series of testing services for the diagnosis of AlzheimerÌs disease.<P>
Elan will increase its access to neurologists in the United States through Athena's top five recognised neurology marketing force of 42 specialists in pharmaceutical sales and 12 in diagnostic services.  As a result, Elan will be able to leverage Athena's market presence potentially to introduce its own products such as Neurelan&reg (fampridine), a new treatment for multiple sclerosis currently undergoing clinical trials.  The merger also benefits Elan by enhancing its existing operations, creating new opportunities for growth and reshaping Elan's revenue mix so that a greater proportion of its revenue is based on the marketing of a strong pipeline of products.<P>
John Groom, currently president and chief executive officer of Athena will be joining Elan's existing management team, led by chief executive officer Donal J. Geaney.  Mr. Groom will serve as chief operating officer of Elan and will also continue to manage Athena.  Dennis J. Selkoe, M.D., Athena co-founder and Harvard University professor of neurology, and Mr. Groom will join the Elan board of directors.<P>
When the merger is completed, Elan will principally comprise three operating divisions, reporting to Mr. Groom:<P>
<b>Elan Technologies</b>, which will focus on the development and application of advanced drug delivery systems;<P>
<b>Elan Pharma</b>, which will conduct the company's U.S. non-neurological sales and marketing efforts and Elan's joint ventures worldwide; and<P>
<b>Athena</b>, which will continue to discover, develop and market therapeutic agents for the diagnosis and treatment of central neurological diseases and disorders.<P>
In addition, the nutrition/diagnostic division of Elan and the diagnostics division of Athena will continue as separate operating units.<P>
"This merger provides Athena the opportunity to expand our business worldwide and optimize our neurology focus through Elan's drug delivery systems, manufacturing capabilities and financial resources," said Mr. Groom.  "These vital assets will allow us to accelerate our efforts in scientific research to identify new compounds that treat neurological diseases.  Since the inception of Athena, we have focused our discovery efforts on building a leading position in the area of Alzheimer's disease.  The merger provides added opportunity for Elan's shareholders to share in the potential success of these efforts and for Athena shareholders to participate in the continued success of Elan's strong presence in drug delivery."<P>
Both Elan and Athena have had recent success in gaining regulatory clearances.  In the last two months, Elan received United States Food and Drug Administration ("FDA") clearance to market Naprelan&reg (naproxen sodium), an anti-arthritic treatment and Athena obtained contingent approval from the FDA for Zanaflex&reg (tizanidine hydrochloride), a potential new treatment for spasticity resulting from multiple sclerosis and spinal cord injury.<P>
Athena was founded in 1986 to discover, develop and market products to be used primarily by neurologists for the treatment and diagnosis of neurological diseases and disorders.<P>
Elan's chairman Donald E. Panoz commenting on the transaction said: "On behalf of the Board, I welcome Dr. Selkoe and Mr. Groom as members of our board of directors and look forward to the merger and the benefits it will create for Elan and Athena shareholders."<P>
Elan is a leading world-wide drug delivery company with innovative drug absorption technologies designed to improve patient care in a cost-effective manner.  Its principal research and manufacturing facilities are in Ireland, Israel and the United States.  Elan is best known for developing the advanced drug delivery technology used in Cardizem SR&reg (diltiazem hydrochloride), Cardizem CD&reg (diltiazem hydrochloride), and Verelan&reg (verapamil hydrochloride) -- all anti-hypertensive treatments.<P>
Except for historical information, this press release contains certain forward-looking statements that involve a number of risks and uncertainties.  In addition to the matters described in this press release, the success of integration of operations, the degree of dilution, the success of product approvals and marketing opportunities for each companyÌs products, and the success in discovery research as well as the risk factors listed from time to time in Elan and Athena's SEC reports may affect the actual results achieved by Elan and Athena.  Elan and Athena disclaim any intent or obligation to update these forward-looking statements.<P>
<P><P>
