<ul><ul><h3>Transactions with Directors</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
Refer to note 28 of the attached financial statements.
<ul><ul><h3>Significant Share Holdings</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
As of 31 March, 1996, Ardsley Partners, William Blair &amp; Co.,
Provident Investment Counselling, Putnam Investment Management
and AIM Advisors, Inc. own 1,710,000 shares, 1,529,000 shares,
1,507,000 shares, 1,414,000 shares and 1,408,000 shares, respectively.
Save for these interests and those referred to under Directors'
Interests above, the Company is not aware of any person who, directly
or indirectly, holds 3% or more of the issued share capital of
the Company.
<ul><ul><h3>Corporate Governance</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
The Company is committed to the highest standard of corporate
governance and compliance with best practice in Ireland. The Company
complies with all of the provisions of the Cadbury Code of Best
Practice save for the disclosure of the remuneration of the directors
which is disclosed in accordance with the Companies Act 1963 to
1990 and in compliance with the regulations of the Irish Stock
Exchange. Refer to pages 52 to 55 of this report for further information
relating to corporate governance.
<ul><ul><h3>Statement of Directors' Responsibilities</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
Company law requires the directors to prepare financial statements
for each financial year which give a true and fair view of the
state of affairs of the Company and of the profit or loss for
that period. In preparing those financial statements, the directors
are required to and have:
<P>
<ul><ul>selected suitable accounting policies and applied them
consistently
<P>
made judgements and estimates that are reasonable and prudent
<P>
prepared the financial statements on the going concern
basis
</ul></ul>
<P>
The directors are responsible for keeping proper books of account
which disclose with reasonable accuracy at any time the financial
position of the Company and which enable them to ensure that the
financial statements comply with the Companies Acts 1963 to 1990
and all regulations to be construed as one with those Acts. They
have general responsibility for taking such steps as are reasonably
open to them to safeguard the assets of the Company and to prevent
and detect fraud and other irregularities. 
<ul><ul><h3>Material Contracts</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
There were no material contracts in relation to the business of
the Company in which any director of the Company had an interest
during the year ended 31 March, 1996.
<ul><ul><h3>Tax Status</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
As far as the directors are aware, the Company is not a close
company as defined by the Corporation Tax Act 1976.
<ul><ul><h3>Service Contracts</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
There are no service contracts in existence between any of the
directors and the Company.
<ul><ul><h3>Subsidiary Companies</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
Information relating to significant subsidiary undertakings is
set out in note 37 to the financial statements.
<ul><ul><h3>Auditors</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
On 1 January, 1996 the Auditors changed the name under which they
practice to KPMG and, accordingly, they will sign their report
in their new name. In accordance with Section 160(2) of the Companies
Act, 1963 the Auditors, KPMG, Chartered Accountants, will continue
in office.<BR>
