<HEAD>

<TITLE>Reconciliation between Irish and US Accounting Principles</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<body background="images/paper1.gif" text="#03056b"><p>
<a href="index.html"><img border=0 src="images/elnmain.gif" width=525 height=75 ismap usemap="index.html"></a><p>
<ul>
<ul><ul><h2>Reconciliation between Irish and US Accounting Principles</h2></ul></ul>


<P>
The financial statements of the Company set out on pages 25 to
50 have been prepared in accordance with generally accepted accounting
principles applicable in Ireland (&igrave;Irish GAAP&icirc;) which
differ in certain significant respects from those applicable in
the US (&igrave;US GAAP&icirc;). The significant material differences
as they apply to the Companys financial statements are
as follows:
<ul><ul><h3>(a) Financial fixed assets</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
Under Irish GAAP financial fixed assets are stated at cost less
provision for permanent diminution in value. Under US GAAP in
accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting Standard No.
115 &igrave;Accounting for Certain Investments in Debt and Equity
Securities&icirc; certain financial fixed assets of the Company
would be classified as available for sale and reported at fair
value with unrealised gains and losses being excluded from earnings
and reported in a separate component of shareholders equity
(net of tax).
<ul><ul><h3>(b) Financial statement format</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
Under US GAAP the format of the financial statements and certain
note disclosures differ from those under Irish GAAP. The Company
will be preparing a US Securities and Exchange Commission Form
20-F annual report in accordance with US GAAP which will be available
on request to all shareholders on or about 30 June, 1996.
<P>
The following is a summary of the material adjustments to profit
and shareholders equity which would be required had the
financial statements been prepared in accordance with US GAAP:<p>
<strong></i>(i) Earnings per share</em></strong>

<P>
Refer to note 21 of these financial statements for details of
the basis of calculation under both Irish and US GAAP.<p>
</i>(ii) Effect on profit/(loss) for the years ended 31 March,</em>
1994, 1995 and 1996</strong>

<P>
Nil effect for the years ended 31 March, 1994, 1995 and 1996.<p>
</i>(iii) Effect on shareholders equity at 31 March,</strong></em>


 
<TABLE>

<TR><TD width=600></TD><TD width=78 align=right>1995</TD><TD width=72 align=right>1996</TD><TD width=78 align=right>1996</TD></TR>

<TR><TD width=600></TD>
<TD width=78 align=right>IR&#163;000s</TD>
<TD width=72 align=right>IR&#163;000s</TD>
<TD width=78 align=right>US$000s</TD></TR>
<tr><td colspan=4><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
<tr>
<td width=600>Shareholders equity as stated under Irish GAAP</td>
<td width=78 align=right>184,430</td><td width=72 align=right>314,385</td><td width= 78 align=right>494,213</td></tr>

<tr><td colspan=4>
US GAAP adjustment:  </td></tr>
<tr><td width=600>
Financial fixed assets</td><td width=78 align=right>-</td><td width=72 align=right> 8,545</td> <td width=78 align=right>13,433</td></tr>
<tr><td width=600></td><td colspan=3><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
<tr><td width=600>
Shareholders equity as stated under US GAAP</td><td width=78 align=right> 184,430</td><td width=72 align=right> 322,930</td><td width=78 align=right>507,646</td></tr>
<tr><td width=600></td><td colspan=3><hr noshade size=2 noshade></td></tr></table>
