<hTML>

<hEAD>

<TITLE>Corporate Governance</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="images/paper1.gif" TEXT="#03056b"><p>
<a href="index.html"><img border=0 src="images/elnmain.gif" width=525 height=75 ismap usemap="index.html"></a><p>
<p>
<img src="images/finstat.gif" width=525 height=47>
<ul><ul><ul>
<h2>Corporate Governance</h2>
<br><br><h3>Policies</H3></ul></ul>

<P>
Elan is committed to the highest standard of corporate governance
and compliance with best practice in Ireland. The Company complies
with all of the provisions of the Cadbury Code of Best Practice
save for the disclosure of the remuneration of the directors which
is disclosed in accordance with the Companies Act 1963 to 1990
and in compliance with the regulations of the Irish Stock Exchange.
<P>
The role of chairman and chief executive are separate and the
board includes ten non-executive directors who constitute a clear
majority of the board. The board regularly reviews the respective
responsibilities of the board, its committees and of management.
The board has reserved certain matters to its exclusive jurisdiction,
thereby maintaining its control of the company and its future
direction. All directors are appointed by the board, as nominated
by its organisation and compensation committee, and subsequently
re-appointed by the shareholders. No director has a service contract.
Procedures are in place where directors, in furtherance of their
duties, take independent professional advice if necessary, at
the Company's expense.
<ul><ul><br><br><h3>Committees of the Board</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
The board has delegated authority over certain areas of the Company's
activities to three committees as more fully explained below.
In addition, a scientific advisory committee provides senior management
with an independent overview of the Company's research
and development activities.
<ul><ul><br><br><h3>Executive</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
The executive committee exercises the management authority of
the board during the interval between board meetings.
<br>
<ul><ul>
D.E. Panoz, Chairman 
<br>
J. Balog
<br>
D.J. Geaney
<br>
T.G. Lynch
<br><br><h3>Audit</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
The audit committee, composed entirely of non-executive directors,
helps the board oversee the Company's accounting and reporting
practices. The audit committee periodically reviews the effectiveness
of the system of internal control. It monitors the adequacy of
internal accounting practices, procedures and controls, and reviews
all significant changes in accounting policies. It also addresses
all issues raised and recommendations made by the external auditors.
<P>
<ul><ul>C. Greyston, Chairman
<br>
B.E. Boushel</ul></ul>
<ul><ul><br><br><h3>Organisation and Compensation</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
The organisation and compensation committee, composed entirely
of non-executive directors, reviews the compensation philosophy
and policies of the Company with respect to executive compensation,
fringe benefits and other compensation matters. The committee
also considers nominations to the board of directors and makes
recommendations thereon, as appropriate. The committee also administers
the Company's stock option plans and determines the compensation
of the chief executive officer.
<P>
<ul><ul>D.E. Panoz, Chairman
<br>
B.E. Boushel
<br>
K. McIntyre</ul></ul>
<ul><ul><br><br><h3>Scientific Advisory</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
The scientific advisory committee advises the senior management
on scientific matters that include major internal projects, interaction
with academic and other outside research organisations, and the
acquisition of technologies and products.
<P>
<ul><ul>H.C. Ansel, PhD., Chairman
<br>

J.G. Devane, PhD.
<br>
D.J. Geaney
<br>
R.M. Kartzinel, M.D., PhD.
<br>
J.R. Koepke M.D.
<br>
J. Loscalzo M.D., PhD.
<br>
D.H. Mason M.D.
<br>
K. McIntyre M.D.</ul></ul>
<P>
Dr. Loscalzo is Distinguished Professor of Medicine and Biochemistry
at Boston University School of Medicine and Director of the Whitaker
Cardiovascular Institute. Dr. Koepke retired in 1994 from Duke
University where he was Professor of Pathology and an Associate
Professor of Medicine. Biographical details of other members of
the committee are included elsewhere in this report.
<ul><ul><br><br><h3>Internal Control</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
The board of directors has overall responsibility for the Company's
system of internal financial control. Management is responsible
for the planning and implementation of the system of internal
financial control and ensuring that these controls apply throughout
the Company. The audit committee reviews the quarterly and annual
financial statements and the nature and scope of the external
audit. Any significant findings, audit or accounting issues or
other business risks are reported by the committee to the board
of directors.

<P>
The system of internal financial control is designed to provide
reasonable, but not absolute, assurance against material misstatement
or loss.
<P>
The Company's system is designed to provide the directors
with reasonable assurance that physical and financial assets are
safeguarded, transactions are authorised and recorded properly
and material irregularities are either prevented or will be detected
with the minimum of delay.
<P>
The organisation structure of the Company under the day to day
direction of its chief executive is clear. Defined lines of responsibility
and delegation of authority have been established within which
the Company's activities can be planned, executed, controlled
and monitored to achieve the strategic objectives which the board
have adopted for the Company.
<P>
The Company has a comprehensive system for reporting financial
results to the board. This includes a budgeting system with an
annual budget approved by the board. The board compare actual
results with budgeted results regularly. Management accounts are
prepared on a timely basis. They include profit and loss account,
balance sheet, cash flow and capital expenditure reporting together
with an analysis of the performance of key operating divisions
and subsidiaries.
<ul><ul><br><br><h3>Going Concern</h3></ul></ul>

<P>
The directors, having made enquiries, believe that the Company
has adequate resources to continue in operational existence for
the foreseeable future and that it is appropriate to continue
to adopt the going concern basis of preparing the financial statements.
