(1993), the manufacturer violated the lemon law statute where the new motor
vehicle was out of service because of repairs for 30 days during initial three
months of ownership and failure to repair the pickup resulted from lack of
repair parts.  The Michigan Court of Appeals emphasized that there is a strong
presumption that a reasonable number of repair attempts have been made and that
this presumption is irrebuttable absent delay in repairs due to war, invasion,
strike, fire, flood or other natural disaster, conditions which are explicitly
provided in the statute.  Id.</P>
